<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-FINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES SAY THEY'RE MORE THAN ONE-MAN SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
BUFFALO _ Dixon Ward was upset. Speaking after his team's Game 3
victory over Toronto in the Eastern Conference finals, the Buffalo
Sabres winger was saying how his team was more than a one-man show;
more than Dominik and the 20 Dwarfs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This team has the reputation of being an average team with a
great goalie,'' he said, blaming the Buffalo media for perpetuating
that reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres' image as a roster full of grinders fortunate to have
world-class goalie Dominik Hasek behind them has stuck. As a
Toronto Star columnist put it: ``The Sabres are a whole bunch of
fast guys with medium skill coming at you all night, with the Brian
Holzingers barely distinguishable from the Curtis Browns or the
Dixon Wards or the Geoff Sandersons.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Sabres have shown anything in their remarkable run to
the Stanley Cup Finals, it's that their overall talent has been
greatly underestimated. How else to explain their playoff-best 12-3
record?
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres say they've won three consecutive playoff series
thanks to teamwide scoring balance, improved play by key veterans
and the emergence of several young players, as well as the
goaltending of Hasek. Still, they said that The Dominator hasn't
had to be as brilliant in this postseason because of the improved
play of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different guys have stepped up every night,'' defenseman James
Patrick said. ``There's a lot of depth here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got speed up front and we're starting to get size up
front,'' winger Rob Ray said. ``It's a bunch of guys that are 10-20
goal scorers, except for \R40-goal scorer Miroslav Satan\S. I would
rather have that than three or four big scorers.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, there was little reason to expect a Sabres
sojourn to the Finals. After posting a 22-12-7 record in the first
half of the regular season, Buffalo stumbled home with a
second-half mark of 15-16-10.
</P>
<P>
   But key March trades that netted veterans Joe Juneau, Stu Barnes
and Rhett Warrener bolstered the club as did the improved play of
young defenseman Jay McKee, which strengthened Buffalo along the
blue line. Offensive-minded forwards began to check and
defensive-minded players began to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the last six weeks of the season we played as well
as a team defensively as any team in the league,'' head coach Lindy
Ruff said. ``The one thing any team needs in this league is to play
well at your own end. So there were a lot of good signs; we just
weren't getting much up on the board. Suddenly, offensively, a
couple guys broke out.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have broken out in the postseason are defenseman
Jason Woolley, the Sabres' top scorer in the playoffs with 13
points, forwards Curtis Brown and Ward, who lead in goals with
seven and six, respectively, and center Michael Peca, who has added
firepower to his sterling defensive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of talent. I'm amazed,'' said Juneau, who came
over from Washington in March. ``I didn't really know Buffalo when
I played against them. We knew there was a lack of experience when
we played them last year \Rin the Eastern Conference final\S. But
these kids learned so much last year. Some of the key guys are 23,
24-years-old, and they're playing like 30-year-old veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo players say their biggest star, Hasek, has been as good
as he has needed to be, but that he hasn't been a one-man team in
the playoffs because that hasn't been necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played good, which has allowed him to play well,'' Ray
said. ``There were a couple games in the Ottawa \Rfirst-round\S
series where if we didn't have him, we might not be to this point.
But in the Toronto series, he really wasn't called upon to play
great because we were able to contain them up front. But one hand
washes the other.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Sabres, Ray said, ``It's not just one person. It's
everybody.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
