<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4759 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHERIFF-AZR &LR;      06-06 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHERIFF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH JAIL STORE MARKUPS, SPENT PROFITS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sheriff Joe Arpaio rakes in a profit of nearly $3
million a year by charging high markups to Maricopa County inmates
for phone calls and jail commissary goods, money that is supposed
to pay for inmates' ``education and welfare'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Arpaio is spending much of the money to help run and build
his jails, including expansion of the sheriff's much-touted Tent
City housing, an examination of records by ``The Arizona Republic''
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio's spending practices are under review by the state
Auditor General's Office. And an inmate-rights group maintains that
the 6,500 inmates aren't being provided sufficient job training,
drug rehabilitation and other programs that could dissuade them
from lives of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate advocates also complain that it's unfair for Arpaio to
levy big markups, such as $1.50 for an 80-cent bottle of shampoo,
or $36 for a $16.99 radio, to inmates awaiting trial who are too
poor to make bail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Arpaio maintains that the inmate fund is being used correctly
and that he saves the taxpayers money.
</P>
<P>
   Past reviews by state and county auditors and budget managers
support the sheriff's spending practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have experts that take care of these matters. The operation
seems to be appropriate as to how we're using these funds. But I
don't go around counting dollars and cents,'' the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the $3 million in annual profits entrusted to the sheriff
from the inmate ``Special Services Fund,'' at least $920,000 was
recently spent in areas that critics say should be covered by the
sheriff's general operations budget.
</P>
<P>
   For example, $820,000 of the inmates' fund is spent each year to
screen and classify detainees when they arrive at the jails. And at
least $100,000 was spent recently for concrete, steel fencing and
utilities to create a Tent City wing for juveniles sentenced as
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Hamm, the head of Middle Ground, a prison-reform group,
says the classification of inmates is a basic constitutional
requirement and should be funded out of the jail operation budget,
not from the inmates' fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine how they can charge inmates for this,''
she said. ``If it isn't illegal, it smells to high heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officials maintain that the use of the money for
classification legitimately helps the inmates' welfare by ensuring
that they are placed in the most appropriate jail facilities to
ensure their health, comfort and safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a child molester, you don't want to be in a cell
with the wrong guys,'' said Glenn Christenson, the sheriff's budget
chief.
</P>
<P>
   Classification director Rick Bailey added that qualified,
college-educated personnel screen every inmate booked into the
jails. Each inmate is checked for psychological needs and
eligibility for inmate education and counseling programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could classify them by shoe size,'' Bailey said,
emphasizing the thoroughness of the classification efforts. ``This
goes above and beyond most jails in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sheriff's officials contend that the Tent City for
juveniles, dubbed ``pup tents,'' is part of an overall program of
education and job training.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of keeping inmates in Maricopa County jails is
among the lowest in the nation and only a fraction of the cost of
jails in other large metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   But paying for classification out of the inmates' fund is being
questioned by state auditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making sure the dangerous prisoners are separated from the
non-dangerous prisoners, is that for the welfare and benefit of the
inmates?'' state financial audit director Dennis Mattheisen asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to take a real strong stand when you've got these
vague statutes.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the law governing the inmates' fund is the word
``may.'' The law says that the fund ``may be used for the education
and welfare of inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   That could mean the sheriff has authority to spend the money
only on inmates' education and welfare. Or it could be read that
the sheriff has permission to do just that, and also to spend it on
anything else he believes is proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell for sure what it means,'' Arizona State
University law Professor Paul Bender said. ``But in order to give
the statute some meaning, you have to interpret it to mean what he
should do with the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender said the law appears to mean that the money is for
``extra things'' beyond food and housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the sheriff uses the money to build jails, that would seem
wrong to me,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Dipping into the inmate welfare account for jail operations
might not be so objectionable if more education and welfare
programs were provided, activist Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia jails, which house a similar number of inmates as
Maricopa County's, provided drug-related programs to 2,600 inmates
in 1997, according to the Criminal Justice Institute, of
Middletown, Conn., a national consulting group that tracks data on
prisons and jails.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the group found that Maricopa County jails, which
hold 1,000 more prisoners than Philadelphia's, provided
drug-related programs that year to just 180 inmates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In all, Maricopa County sheriff's officials say they spend more
than $1.5 million each year on various inmate education programs,
including library, religious and legal services. In addition, the
Sheriff's Office used the inmates' funds for computers, books,
pencils and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Thelda Williams, who heads inmate programs for Arpaio, said
participation in inmate programs ranges from as few as two inmates
being tutored in a literacy program to as many as 3,500 who weekly
attend religious services.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance in other inmate programs, she said, varies from the
500 inmates who attend Alcoholics Anonymous meetings to the 80
enrolled in the jail's ``intensive'' substance abuse program. The
jails offer a dozen other education and self-help programs,
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamm said she believes these programs are inadequate and
simply provide the sheriff with cover for a ``gargantuan petty cash
fund.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason they're doing any programs at all is they'd
(otherwise) be totally caught with their hands in the cookie jar,''
she said. ``It should raise the red flag for any auditor.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law governing jail canteen funds, county supervisors
can order audits every two years. No such audit has been done since
1990. But Fulton Brock, chairman of the Maricopa County Board of
Supervisors, is considering one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to evaluate that (the need for an audit),'' Brock
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to how the money is being spent, an audit might look
at the prices being charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is gouging, it probably would be something we'd want
to look at more closely,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Most jail inmates are citizens who haven't been convicted of a
crime and are too poor to bail themselves out while they await
trial, or they are convicts sentenced to less than a year's
imprisonment for misdemeanors and lesser felonies such as drug
abuse, burglary and drunken driving. Those sentenced to longer
terms are transferred to state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   But, in jail, if inmates want virtually anything beyond a bunk
and toilet, they have to pay the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Jail inmates must use the sheriff's collect-call telephone
system, at $1.65 per local call, because no other calls are allowed
out of the jail.
</P>
<P>
   And they must buy all but the most basic sanitation items at the
jail canteens. The Sheriff's Office also sells them things like
candy and over-the-counter medications for up to twice the cost. To
prevent contraband, families are forbidden to send anything into
the jails.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Hare, who is living on Social Security and recovering
from a stroke, regularly goes to the Madison Street Jail to deposit
money into a friend's account while he awaits trial for auto theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it stinks,'' Hare said. ``I have $65 a month after I
pay rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, she said, her contributions are taken from her friend's
canteen account to pay a monthly charge of $30 per inmate for jail
food. Since charges for food were imposed in August, canteen sales
have plunged more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff responded in January with a price increase, even
though suppliers had recently reduced the cost of most canteen
items, according to financial reports obtained by ``The Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' said Matthew Hansen, 22, as he pulled a
palm-size radio from his pocket while leaving the Madison Street
Jail. The Gilbert man said he had just served six months for
driving under the influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost $30,'' he said. ``You could get it on the outside for
$8.''
</P>
<P>
   The canteen price of a portable radio with earphones is $36. The
Sheriff's Office pays $16.99 per set. Cheaper ones don't work deep
in the concrete jails.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen did not complain about the 75-cent canteen charge for
candy bars or the $1.50 price of a 16-ounce bottle of generic
shampoo, even when told that the sheriff pays only 33 cents for the
candy and 80 cents for the shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about normal,'' Hansen said of the prices for most
products.
</P>
<P>
   Budget director Christenson contends that canteen prices are not
out of line. They are adjusted yearly to fall somewhere in the
range of prices charged at convenience, grocery and discount
stores, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hansen's mother, Paula, said her son's jail stay was costly.
She made deposits regularly to his account.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked, so he had money,'' she said. ``It's gone now.'' &QL; 
Mike McCloy may be reached at (602) 444-8111 or at
mike.mccloy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
