<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-06 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL DAY IN AND DAY OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The folks at the VA hospital want to know why a news writer is
wandering around the place when Memorial Day is nearly a week past
and the extra flags have been taken down outside the building and
the TV trucks that fill up the parking lot once a year are long
since gone.
</P>
<P>
   It had to do with my old man's dog tags, I say.
</P>
<P>
   My boy, who's 7, asked me if he could wear them on Memorial Day,
``because Pap Pap was in the Army and this is the day for
remembering Army men.'' So I said OK.
</P>
<P>
   The tinny World War II tags dangled around his neck all day,
with him pointing them out to grocery store baggers and coffee shop
patrons and a clerk at the video store and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of the day, he took them off and set them down
and hasn't mentioned them since, which is how most of us treat
veterans, as a curiosity, for one day a year.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that right?
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside me in a small office in the VA hospital,
listening, is Louise Ellis, a woman of proper Southern upbringing
who'd never think of telling the gentleman in her presence that
he's full of it. Not directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well my goodness, no,'' she says, her Mississippi accent
hanging like perfume on the words. ``We have over 1,000 volunteers
here. They aren't all as crazy as I am, coming in most every day.
But, they love it. If you stay home you may have a beautiful yard
and pretty flowers, but who is that helping?'' &QL; 
`I go where I'm needed' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On this day, as on most days, Mrs. Ellis arrived at the Carl T.
Hayden Veterans Affairs Medical Center shortly before 5 a.m. She
opens the offices in the hospital's gastrointestinal department,
where most of her volunteer hours are spent, then gets to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on I may do some typing,'' she says. ``But you never
know from day to day what you'll end up doing. I go where I'm
needed. I've probably been hired and fired more than anybody in the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise began volunteering at the VA hospital in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, B.C., was a patient at the time, and Louise decided
to help the nurses. After B.C. died, Louise stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   And on.
</P>
<P>
   And on.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of March, she'd accumulated a total of 38,179
volunteer hours. Which is roughly 1,583 days. Which is four years
and four months worth. Of 24-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gracious,'' Louise says. ``All that does is prove I'm old.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course, that's not at all what it proves. It proves there
are people out there better than you and I, more generous, more
committed, and one of them is Louise Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   She actually took a few months off from volunteering recently,
but only because she fell and broke her kneecap in three places.
She came back with wire still holding the bone together, a little
slower but no less determined.
</P>
<P>
   Walking with her along a hallway, nurses and doctors stop to say
hello, along with a fellow who once helped her plant flowers
outside the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave a bouquet to every lady in the place, remember?'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why yes,'' she answers, hugging him. &QL; 
The human touch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the ward where she spends most of her time, Dr. Francisco
Ramirez says, ``We have to do more and more things faster. We have
computers. Everything is fast. Sometimes, we lose the human touch.
Volunteers like Louise remind us about that. About the human
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   She often sits with patients during medical procedures, holding
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that what we're supposed to all do for one another?''
she says. ``Besides, I get a lot more out of it than the veterans
do. Anybody would.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been thousands of them over the years. They're part
of her family, now, like her two daughters and her relatives living
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, to Louise, there's really no such thing as Memorial
Day. A person who never forgets doesn't need a reminder. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
