<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, June 6. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHERIFF (Phoenix) _ Sheriff Joe Arpaio rakes in a profit of nearly
$3 million a year by charging high markups to Maricopa County
inmates for phone calls and jail commissary goods, money that is
supposed to pay for inmates' ``education and welfare'' programs.
But Arpaio is spending much of the money to help run and build his
jails, including expansion of the sheriff's much-touted Tent City
housing, an examination of records by ``The Arizona Republic''
shows. Arpaio's spending practices are under review by the state
Auditor General's Office. And an inmate-rights group maintains that
the 6,500 inmates aren't being provided sufficient job training,
drug rehabilitation and other programs that could dissuade them
from lives of crime. Story by MIKE McCLOY. Will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHURCH (Phoenix) _ It was a church born of turmoil in the
mid-1920s, made up of Hispanic Catholics who had tired of racism
and being forced to sit in the basement of St. Mary's for services.
Now, Immaculate Heart of Mary Church in central Phoenix is at
loggerheads with the Catholic hierarchy once again, saying that the
language and cultural needs of its predominantly immigrant,
Spanish-speaking parishioners are being slighted. At issue is the
decision by the Phoenix diocese to combine Immaculate Heart's huge
congregation with that of St. Anthony Church and a smaller mission
church under the stewardship of one Spanish-speaking priest, Father
Saul Madrid. It's a move admittedly of desperation, said Father
Prudencio Rodriguez, vicar for the Phoenix diocese Hispanic
ministry. Rodriguez said that the diocese, which has more than 100
parishes and missions, has only about 20 priests who are fluent in
Spanish. BY MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) Louise Ellis began volunteering at the VA
hospital in 1973. By the end of March, she'd accumulated a total of
38,179 volunteer hours. Which is four years and four months worth.
Of 24-hour days. `'Gracious,'' Louise says. ``All that does is
prove I'm old.'' No. It proves there are people out there better
than you and I, and one of them is Louise Ellis. That's why, to
Louise, there's really no such thing as Memorial Day. A person who
never forgets doesn't need a reminder. By E.J. MONTINI Story will
move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
