<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SAVING RED SOX THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BRAVES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   Usually after nailing down a save _ and there have been many
over the past two years _ Tom Gordon looks to the heavens in praise
of God. Saturday, he couldn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   The unfamiliar scene saw Gordon walking off the mound with his
head down after a 6-5 Braves win before 32,793 at Fenway Park as
the Red Sox' first-place lead over the Yankees in the American
League East dropped to a half-game.
</P>
<P>
   As astonishing as it was to watch Pedro Martinez dominate the
Braves Friday night, there was no greater surprise to the fandom
than Gordon squandering a one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been able to do anything different,'' said
Gordon, whose streak of 54 straight saves, a major league record,
ended. ``I think the last couple of times out I was getting behind
the hitters and I was trying to avoid that. I probably threw too
many strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning hit, a scorching two-out grounder down the
left-field line in the ninth by catcher Javy Lopez, was a case in
point. Lopez had been having a tough day _ 0 for 4 with a double
play and two strikeouts. He had been retired on curveballs from Sox
starter Brian Rose and Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   So Gordon threw the curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he was supposed to,'' said pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan. ``He threw the right pitch. He had very good stuff. This
is a team of excellent professional hitters on the Braves. They're
a fine club.''
</P>
<P>
   What hurt was not being able to beat Greg Maddux, the four-time
Cy Young Award winner, when they had such a good chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough pitcher, a great pitcher,'' said Brian Daubach of
Maddux, who won his first game since April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach gave the Sox the lead in a wild eighth inning, when the
Braves threw the ball around.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman (2 for 4) reached on a bloop single to center, and
after John Valentin struck out, Maddux tossed a wild pitch.
Offerman ended up on third when Perez's throw sailed over Bret
Boone's glove at second.
</P>
<P>
   On the next pitch, Daubach delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept coming at (Maddux), but he does a great job of mixing
his pitches and keeping you off balance,'' said Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 4-2, against Maddux after Brian Jordan hit a Rose
changeup for a three-run homer in the fifth, the Sox tied it at 4
by scoring twice in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback began when Valentin stroked his second hit, a
single to center, with one out. He advanced to third on Daubach's
second hit, a double to right on which Jordan made a navigational
error, taking a strange route to a ball he had a chance of
catching.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Randall Simon made a nice diving grab of Nomar
Garciaparra's wicked grounder near the bag, which scored Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux thought he had Troy O'Leary struck out on a 2-2 pitch,
but plate umpire Tim Tschida did not call the low pitch a strike,
giving O'Leary life. He singled past Maddux into center to score
the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good-hitting ballclub,'' said Maddux. ``They don't
have too many guys who go up there and hack. They try to (take)
what the pitcher gives them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose left after five innings with a career-high six strikeouts,
issuing four walks and giving up four hits. He retired the first
two batters of the fifth and was sailing along until Bret Boone
singled off the wall and Chipper Jones walked. That brought
Kerrigan out for a chat. Then Jordan hit a low fastball 410 feet
over the screen in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose got some key outs for us,'' said manager Jimy Williams.
``I thought he pitched real good. He really battled.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose was replaced by Lowe, who pitched three scoreless innings
and was outstanding with men on base.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan hit an RBI single in the first, but Rose prevented
further damage by inducing Javy Lopez into a 5-4-3 double play.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra singled and stole his seventh base in the second
inning and scored on Jason Varitek's two-out triple to the
triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Presented a similar two-out opportunity, Darren Lewis failed to
get the go-ahead run in, watching a third strike on the outside
corner.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, there was an unusual feat against Maddux: the Sox
scored a two-out run. Valentin doubled off the wall and scored on
Daubach's wall single, giving the Sox a 2-1 lead. Daubach, however,
was gunned down at second by left fielder Ryan Klesko.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
