<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKM-PROVIDENCEBRUINS-     06-06 2186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKM-PROVIDENCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MINOR MIRACLE IN PROVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 BRUINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ They had just struggled to a 4-4 tie with Saint
John after a 2-4 start to the season, and now the Providence Bruins
were experiencing one of the perks of American Hockey League life:
a seven-hour bus grind, New Brunswick to Rhode Island, through a
godforsaken October night, from backwater to border to boondocks.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, this is quality time for the self-pitying; the only
thing darker than his surroundings is the minor leaguer's soul. He
spends such trips whining and bellyaching and cursing the
ignoramuses who somehow have failed to realize that he should at
this very moment be enjoying a catered midnight snack aboard a
National Hockey League charter flight.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no kvetching on this wilderness tour; in fact,
sitting at the front of the bus, head coach Peter Laviolette and
his assistant, Bill Armstrong, were startled by the noise in the
rear.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, a survivor of eight minor league seasons, turned to
Laviolette, a veteran of 12, and asked, ``You ever had a guitar
player on one of your buses?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me neither.''
</P>
<P>
   But when they looked behind them, they discovered this was no
hallucination. At the behest of teammates, Andre Savage, a
promising center and accomplished musician, had brought his
acoustic guitar on board. Also at the behest of teammates, he was
now performing an impromptu concert. Which quickly evolved into a
sing-along.
</P>
<P>
   Bon Jovi. Springsteen. Garth Brooks's ``I Got Friends In Low
Places.'' For the next four hours, the joyous cacophony echoed
through the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre did most of the singing because most of the guys didn't
know the verses and they'd just mumble along,'' recalls Armstrong.
``But they'd really go to town on the chorus.''
</P>
<P>
   And from the dissonance came a wondrous discovery: As a team,
these Bruins were in perfect harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a turning point, that was it,'' says former
University of New Hampshire center Eric Nickulas. ``After that, we
really started to jell.''
</P>
<P>
   The joyride hasn't stopped. Providence, the Boston Bruins' top
minor league affiliate, began the extended climax to its journey
with a 4-2 victory Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at the Civic Center against the
Rochester Americans in the opener of the best-of-seven Calder Cup
finals. For the uninitiated, that's the grail of the AHL, a trophy
that hasn't graced Rhode Island's capital since 1956, when the
Providence Reds claimed it on behalf of the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   This is not only the zenith of the Bruins' seven-year existence
here _ which ended a 15-year Providence AHL hiatus after the
Rangers pulled up roots _ it is also the culmination of a season
that long ago progressed from remarkable to astounding.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins led the league and set a club mark during the regular
season with 120 points, the product of a 56-16-4-4 record (the AHL
awards a point for overtime losses). Following that up with an 11-3
playoff run, they established an AHL record for combined victories
in a season _ just one of 38 league or team marks to their credit.
They boast the AHL's Most Valuable Player, center Randy Robitaille;
the two top-scoring defensemen, Brandon Smith (62 points) and Terry
Virtue (56); three first-team All-Stars, Robitaille, Smith, and
left wing Landon Wilson; a second-team All-Star, Virtue; a member
of the All-Rookie team, Savage; and the leading scorer in the
playoffs, Nickulas (19 points). They left the rest of the league in
their dust with a club-record 15-0-1 streak from Dec. 23 to Jan. 29
that included 11 straight victories.
</P>
<P>
   But what truly challenges the law of probability is that this is
the same core cast that last season fought its way to another club
record _ for fewest victories (19-49-5-7), a standard of ineptitude
that earned the Bruins their second straight last-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   There are differences, of course, some subtle, all vital. Most
prominent was the hiring of Laviolette _ a 34-year-old product of
Franklin, Mass., and Westfield State who owns the career record for
games played by a Providence Bruin _ to replace old-timer Tom
McVie. Last year's bewildered rookies are this year's mature
veterans. The team's savvy and psyche have been bolstered by the
addition of four former captains of AHL teams _ Smith, Virtue,
Steve Bancroft, and this year's leader, Dennis Vaske _ to the
defense, where they tutor former first-round draft pick Johnathan
Aitken, a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Says Laviolette, who was brought in after guiding the Wheeling
(W.Va.) Nailers to the East Coast Hockey League semifinals in his
first year as a coach, ``I think we have the perfect mix here with
our forwards, who are young, fast, and have tons of potential, and
if they make a mistake, the defensemen are there to bail them
out.''
</P>
<P>
   All those factors signal improvement. But a 70-point turnaround
in one season, the most dramatic in AHL history? Come on.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my wildest dreams,'' says team owner Ed Anderson, who
transplanted Boston's Maine Mariners AHL farm here in 1992, ``I
never saw this.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who in their most sadomasochistic nightmares could
have envisioned last year?
</P>
<P>
   Virtue and his wife were strolling along Bellevue Avenue,
admiring the Newport mansions, earlier this spring when a man
approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, aren't you Terry Virtue?'' the stranger asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``An hour down the road, somebody recognized me,'' says Virtue,
still marveling at the recollection. ``That's pretty nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he acknowledged any connection to the Providence Bruins last
year, he probably would have been mugged.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever right wing Aaron Downey, the league leader in penalty
minutes and winner of the team community service award the past two
seasons, goes to fill up his silver Chevy Blazer, he receives an
enthusiastic greeting and $10 of free gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year they wouldn't even talk to me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he's fortunate that they didn't smash his windshield
last year and charge him for the use of the sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who was promoted late in the season _ one of 15
Providence players who spent at least some time in the NHL in
1998-99 _ and was a key contributor in Boston's two playoff series,
was aboard the team charter after Boston was eliminated in Buffalo
last month. Wearing an ice pack on his separated left shoulder, a
souvenir of Stanley Cup combat, he approached assistant coach Bob
Francis and asked if he was supposed to return to Providence. Told
that he was, Wilson offered no complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they hadn't told me,'' he says, ``I probably would
have asked to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Given a similar order last year, he probably would have jumped
immediately off the plane without a parachute.
</P>
<P>
   As glorious as this season has been, that's how wretched last
year's experience was for Providence. The combination of
unsuspecting youth and discontented veterans bemoaning their
demotion created a poisonous environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a godawful year,'' recalls Armstrong, captain of the
'97-98 Bruins. ``It seemed like the harder you worked, the more you
buried yourself. I can remember driving down 95 with tears in my
eyes some nights. Some guys hated each other. There was some bad
blood there.''
</P>
<P>
   The venom was so pervasive that it even infected the corridors
of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take a lot of (expletive) from other mayors,'' says
flamboyant Providence Mayor Vincent ``Buddy'' Cianci, waving his
hand in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   But the penance may have served a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going through a year from hell like that is a learning
experience,'' says Boston assistant general manager Mike O'Connell.
``One thing you learn is that you never want to go through it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the Bruins brought in Laviolette, whom Anderson
has admired since his playing days, which included exactly 12 NHL
games with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a communicator,'' says the owner. ``I've always felt that
with his interpersonal skills, he would be successful regardless of
his career path.''
</P>
<P>
   That path has brought him full circle to the Civic Center, only
now as the boss. He professes to have no magic formula, but his
relationship with the players obviously has been essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our psychiatrist, our motivator, our playmaker,'' says
Downey. ``He's very hands-on. You can go in and talk to him about
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Laviolette is not is a petty bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sweat the small stuff,'' he says. ``Like if a guy is
wearing a mock turtleneck instead of a tie on the road. So what?
All I ask is that when you come to the rink, you do whatever is
necessary to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the alternative is intolerable to Laviolette, who
carries the buddy system only so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it clear that this was going to be a fresh start, that
he didn't care about last year, that all he was worried about was
winning,'' says Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took the returnees a while to rid their system of the
hangover from last season.
</P>
<P>
   While Armstrong observes, ``The good thing was that the kids who
came back all got along,'' newcomer Smith still noted some
reservations. At the start, the holdovers ``were still talking
about last year,'' he says. ``We didn't know what kind of team we
had. We knew we had the talent, but we didn't know how it would
come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Very nicely, as it turned out. After a sluggish 4-5-0-1 start,
the Bruins reeled off seven straight victories and didn't look
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``All championship teams have great chemistry,'' says goaltender
John Grahame, who posted a 37-9-1 record this season after being a
frequent victim of opposing fusillades during last year's debacle.
``It's not something you can force.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the campfire atmosphere on the bus from Saint John
proved to be genuine sentiment. The Bruins found out they actually
like one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a team here that's very dedicated, very focused on
each other,'' says former University of Maine right wing Peter
Ferraro, who spent most of the season in Boston before being
demoted March 15 _ and buying right into the harmonic convergence.
``It's the greatest group of guys I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   If that smacks of pure saccharine, Vaske, a 32-year-old former
New York Islander whose NHL days may well be behind him, thinks it
passed the litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys got called up,'' he says, ``everyone else was happy
for them. Everyone's goal is to get to the NHL, and we do whatever
we can to help the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The more immediate goal is the Calder Cup, which may seem a pale
facsimile of the Stanley Cup _ except to the people playing for it.
Wilson, who was part of the Colorado Avalanche's championship
entourage in the 1996 NHL playoffs (though he didn't suit up),
doesn't accept that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be any consolation prize,'' he says. ``It's a chance
to be a part of something you might never do again. It's something
we've been shooting for all year. And we'll know we won it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The city also is profiting from the turnaround. Chamber of
Commerce president James G. Hagan estimates that the Bruins'
economic impact on Providence conservatively is $10 million-$15
million, and that last year's on-ice recession meant 33 percent
less in the coffers.
</P>
<P>
   This year's increased success and prolonged season have been a
boon to business. Joe Peixoto, manager of a sports gathering spot
near the Civic Center, the Player's Corner Pub, notices
substantially more business in his restaurant and foot traffic in
the area on game nights. Ray Ruggieri, president of the team
booster club, has seen its ranks grow by some 16 percent this
season, during which the patrons made an unprecedented 13 bus trips
to follow the Bruins on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins drew an average of 7,191 fans per game during the
regular season, fourth in the league and an increase of almost
1,000 from last year. During the playoffs, the average has been a
league-leading 6,811 _ ``and that's starting from scratch,'' notes
team publicist Dave Goucher, ``because there is no season-ticket
carryover to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   That number is getting a boost during the finals, when the
Bruins figure to draw at least 10,000 per home game. Those who
can't get to the Civic Center will be able to tune in Calder Cup
play on New England Sports Network, and cyberfans can get the games
on the Internet (www.providencebruins.com). Even better, the
success and exposure bode well for next fall; Bruins marketing
director Randy Scott says that in contrast to last season, sponsor
solicitations ``are happy calls now.''
</P>
<P>
   There also are intangible benefits for this hardscrabble city on
the rebound. Almost $1 billion in new infrastructure is in place in
downtown Providence, and Cianci believes the success of the Bruins
enhances the spirit of revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a presence, gives us a place,'' he says. ``It's
good for the city's self-esteem. Everyone loves to be associated
with a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   It's music to their ears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-06 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST FINISHED, BUT END COULD HAVE BEEN WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The race and the Triple Crown were gone, but now
Bob Lewis was in for something far worse.
</P>
<P>
   A few strides past the finish line Saturday, Charismatic had
pulled up lame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable feeling of devastation,'' sighed the
gentlemanly owner. ``I just stood there and virtually froze.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bob and Beverly Lewis, their thoroughbreds are not just meal
tickets. They are, let's say, family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' Lewis said, ``this is the bad side of racing
you see on occasion. It does happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, Lewis's next-to-worst fear was realized. The
X-rays were back in very rapid fashion. His championship horse was
going to live. He just wasn't going to race again. The 1999 Belmont
Stakes would be Charismatic's final race. Put it down that a
would-be Triple Crown winner gave it a magnificent shot, finishing
third in the Belmont behind Lemon Drop Kid and Vision and Verse
despite sustaining a _ are you ready? _ ``lateral condylar fracture
of his left front leg,'' not to mention a ``little crack in his
sesamoid bone,'' both of which add up to the horse becoming an
instant retiree and assumed stud rather than the 12th colt to win a
Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   So there will be no Hollywood ending to this charming tale, a
story so enchanting it drew a record Belmont Park crowd of 85,818
on this truly spectacular spring afternoon. The public was quite
obviously drawn to the story of the two-time claimer who had won
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness under startlingly different
conditions. The public knew all about the kindly owners, whose good
spirits and generosity have been trumpeted by every media
organization for the past six weeks. And the public also was taken
with the reclamation story of jockey Chris Antley, who had battled
substance abuse and weight problems in order to earn a chance to
become a Triple Crown jockey.
</P>
<P>
   What the public should know now is that the jockey had become
very attached to that horse. Those were real, live tears rolling
down Antley's cheeks while he tended to the stricken animal. They
were a true team. Assuming that Antley's career is now back on the
proper track, he will always have this wonderful horse to thank.
</P>
<P>
   Antley's only postrace concern was the welfare of Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very sad thing,'' he explained. ``It was a very
emotional thing. An awful lot of emotion went through my body when
he pulled up after we passed the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Chris Antley. Any jockey would have felt the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time a horse injures itself, it hurts the rider.''
confirmed Pat Day, who was aboard Menifee. ``We love them. They
give their all for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley knew something was wrong at the eighth pole. Something.
What would have happened if Charismatic had stopped running, right
then and there? He'd probably be racing again; that's what. But
neither Charismatic nor any other championship horse was going to
stop just because he or she felt a twinge. In this regard,
thoroughbred horses are no different from humans. You play through
the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave everything he had,'' Antley said. ``He ran as hard as
he could, but he couldn't give the people what he wanted. He is an
athlete and he ran through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Antley felt what he described as a ``little dip'' at the
eighth pole, the race was going according to the plan concocted by
trainer D. Wayne Lukas and Antley. Charismatic was dueling
Silverbulletday. Charismatic was doing everything Antley was
asking. Antley had every reason to think he could win the race. ``I
was in a very confident position,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would he have won?'' inquired Antley. ``That's a very hard
prediction to make. But I was pleased and happy throughout the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened is part of the deal, pure and simple. It's even
happened to Bob Lewis before. He once had an Irish-bred horse named
Fatherland who was doing some great things when he went down at
Hollywood Park. That, too, said Lewis, was ``devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Having been down this two-thirds-of-a-Triple Crown road before
with Silver Charm only two years ago, Lewis was cautiously
optimistic, and no more. He knew better than to expect anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the race,'' Lewis said, ``Chris Antley looked me in the
eye and said, `Mr. Lewis, it's in God's hands now. If he wants us
to win, we'll win.' I said I could accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   What all this underscores is just how very difficult it is to
win these three particular races within five weeks in any given
year, and why those who win the first two legs get so pumped up
anticipating the Belmont. The Lewises may have had a saner outlook
than most people, but Lukas, for one, wasn't ashamed to admit how
antsy the whole thing was making him.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know that it just wasn't meant to be for Charismatic.
He's got a new role in life, effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought me a lot of joy,'' said Antley. ``It's been a great
road. It's too bad he couldn't give the general public what they
wanted. They won't see a Triple Crown this year. So, hopefully,
we'll see his babies running in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a great story, but there was no focus group to pass
judgment on the ending. There were no alternate takes. Charismatic
will race no more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
