<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONTSTAKES-BOS     06-06 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC LOSES INSPIRED BID 
</HEADLINE>
 STAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The Belmont Stakes is a test of champions that
traverses 1 1/2 miles. The Triple Crown is one that only the truest
of thoroughbred royalty can _ and should _ wear. It is horse
racing's most difficult feat, to be tested as a champion and only
then to wear the crown.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic, who many doubted through the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness, gave his all and then even more before coming up short
in his bid to become royalty. Alas, Charismatic broke down at the
wire Saturday, fracturing two bones in his left foreleg, as he
exerted his last ounce of will to win the race that would have made
him the first Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic never will race again.
</P>
<P>
   What was to be his greatest moment as a racehorse before the
largest crowd ever at Belmont Park, some 85,000 fans, turned out to
be his last moment as a competitor on a race track. ``He's through
as a racehorse,'' said Larry Bramlage, a track veterinarian. ``We
expect him to be fine as a stallion.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Selway, another veterinarian, said Charismatic would
undergo surgery Sunday &UR;  &LR; at an equine hospital near Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   As Charismatic, who briefly took the lead in the stretch from
the filly Silverbulletday, faltered in the final yards, Lemon Drop
Kid swooped by, as did Vision and Verse, two of the longer long
shots in the race. At the end of this 131st Belmont, it was the
29-1 Lemon Drop Kid who held off the 54-1 Vision and Verse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke down just after the wire,'' said a tearful Chris
Antley, Charismatic's jockey. ``It's sad that these things happen.
But he gave us a lot. He gave America a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Cleary, the chief examining veterinarian of the New York
Racing Association, described the injury as ``a lateral condylar
fracture of his left front leg. He is comfortable.'' But Cleary
added that it appears Charismatic ``is a surgical candidate.'' It
is not believed the injury is life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Within 2 minutes 27 4/5ths seconds, many of life's emotions _
both the highs and lows, the joys and distresses _ were
encapsulated for D. Wayne Lukas, Charismatic's trainer, and Bob and
Beverly Lewis, the colt's owners. The joy was growing as
Charismatic stalked Silverbulletday all the way down the endless
Belmont backstretch, and the joy was even brighter turning for home
as Charismatic took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Charismatic faltered near the 16th pole and the potential
for a Triple Crown was gone. But that was an athletic loss, a
racetrack defeat, painful because of its significance, but well
understood by all who ever led a horse onto a race track. But then
Charismatic took a bad step near the wire and, a 16th of a mile
past the finish line, Antley jumped off the colt and Charismatic
clearly was in distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, we're feeling pretty low,'' said Bob Lewis. ``We're
devastated by the thought that anything could be wrong with
Charismatic. Our only concern now is with Charismatic. We hope to
God he's going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises and Lukas ``accepted the accolades in Louisville and
Baltimore,'' Bob Lewis went on, ``and (Saturday) was one of those
things that happen. What happened is history. We have been in this
position to win the Triple Crown twice (also in 1997 with Silver
Charm) and if we are lucky enough we will try it again someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, aboard Silverbulletday, was dueling head to head
with Charismatic for more than half a mile and was surprised to see
that it was Charismatic, a closer, running early with the filly.
But Bailey also noticed that Charismatic was ``rank'' down the
backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   Antley, meanwhile, recalled that Charismatic ``had let up a
little bit at the eighth pole.'' At that point, he went on, ``I
rode just enough to hang on for third. Heading to the finish he
dipped underneath me and I could tell he was in pain. He gave
everything he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was devastated. Saturday was to be a rare moment of
triumph for both the colt and himself, as the trainer never has had
a Triple Crown winner despite numerous attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week long, we'd talked about how maintenance-free this
horse was and how durable he was,'' said Lukas. ``In racing, these
things happen and we have to deal with them. It's not an easy part
of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Santos, the jockey aboard the winner, Lemon Drop Kid, and
Scotty Schulhofer, his trainer, were aware of the injury to
Charismatic, the 8-5 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got our racetrack and we got a good clean trip,''
said Schulhofer, who also won the 1993 Belmont with Colonial
Affair. ``Jose gave him a great ride and Jose loves this horse.''
</P>
<P>
   In a little less than 2 1/2 minutes, 85,000 fans roared and
cheered. Until after the end, when racing's so-humbling nature once
again had humbled a would-be champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
