u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JONES-JOHNSON-BOS     06-06 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES UNIFIES LIGHT HEAVYWEIGHT TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ Roy Jones wasted little time wasting Reggie
Johnson Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Jones and Johnson sparred three times in Pensacola,
Fla., when Jones was a young professional and Johnson a top
middleweight contender. Saturday night was the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Each had since become a light heavyweight champion _ Jones
holding the World Boxing Council and World Boxing Association belts
_ and they had come to the Mississippi Coast Coliseum for one of
them to leave as the first undisputed light heavyweight champion in
14 years. Little more than a minute into the fight it was clear who
that was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Jones dropped Johnson with a lead right hand that the
International Boxing Federation champion never saw coming. That was
the beginning of a long night in which Johnson would lose his title
the hard way _ by being turned into a heavy bag by the faster and
more ferocious Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy bags are resilient pieces of equipment, and so was
Johnson, who though outclassed fought bravely and tenaciously for
12 rounds in the hope he might somehow catch lightning in a bottle.
But he didn't, more often catching a fist to the face.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, judges Paul Sita, Cova Jesus, and Chuck
Hassock all had the fight scored 120-106, meaning Jones had pitched
a shutout, an opinion held by the Globe's card as well as
heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good,'' said Holyfield from ringside, referring to Jones.
``Can't nobody touch him. He's not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't for Johnson either. Jones's hand speed advantage was
clear from the outset and he used it to drop Johnson in the first
round and cut him in the second. In the third, he nailed him with a
string of heavy combinations to the face that had Johnson leaning
back on the ropes with his gloves by his cheekbones.
</P>
<P>
   These defensive tactics didn't help, however, because Jones
countered a Johnson left hand with a left-right combination to the
button with eight seconds left in Round 3 that dropped Johnson dead
in his tracks. Somehow he got up again, but had the bell not
sounded when it did, he would have been finished right then.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Johnson (39-6-1) was rocked again in Round 4 but he
remained upright this time, his right eye was now leaking blood and
late in the round he took a stiff uppercut to the face that snapped
his head back and propelled him 5 feet backward.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth was more of the same, with the only moment of note
coming when Jones landed a combination that backed Johnson into the
ropes. Jones then dug a left to the body and when it landed,
Johnson covered up and Jones stepped into a clinch and hollered to
Michael Jordan, who was sitting at ringside. It was almost as if
Johnson wasn't there, which in point of fact he really wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has superior hand speed,'' Johnson said. ``I tried to time
him, but I wasn't able to. He does a lot of things wrong but his
hands make up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the ninth round, Jones (40-1, 33 KOs) had visibly slowed his
pace and although Johnson threw a few more punches, it was clear
that Jones was carrying Johnson to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he figured he had to save his strength to carry out his
extra belt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 0219EDT &QL; 
