</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF COMPLETES FRENCH REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A couple of very rare birds _ 29-year-old phoenixes _
were flitting about Stade Roland Garros Saturday, one in
nondescript baggy shorts, the other in a miniskirt.
</P>
<P>
   These phoenixes, sighted soaring from the crimson ashes of a
clay tennis court, were identified as two distinct breeds: Agassi
and Graf. Before an uproarious rain-spattered day at the French
Open had ended, both had reestablished faded careers.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-wounded and surgically carved _ yet ever-superb _ Steffi
Graf gave the sassy prodigy, Martina Hingis, a lesson in tennis and
style. Declaring, surprisingly, that it was her farewell to Paris,
Graf snatched away the championship after being pushed within 3
points of the abyss, pocketing her 22d major title, 4-5, 7-5, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have thought Graf was the reincarnation of Joan of Arc the
way the mob of 16,000 cheered her and lifted her as high as Gustave
Eiffel's nearby erector set tower. And that Hingis was a remake of
the haughty Marie Antoinette, as her gaucheries led the customers
to boo and whistle her to tears. If there has been a women's final
of such passionate clamor, I haven't seen it _ or one in which a
great player was nearly thrown out. Hingis came close, earning two
code-of-conduct violations, one short of ejection.
</P>
<P>
   The gifted Andre Agassi, seeming as busted-out as numerous
gamblers in his hometown, Las Vegas, had long been in the
wilderness, unable to attain a major final for four years. But now,
after blunting the thunder of the slugging Slovak, Dominic Hrbaty,
6-4, 7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 6-4, he's on the brink of crashing a select
sanctum. By beating another retread, No. 100 Andrei Medvedev, in
Sunday's final _ which he should _ Agassi would become the fifth
guy to hold all four majors (Australian, French, Wimbledon, US),
following in the sneaker steps of Fred Perry, Don Budge, Rod Laver,
and Roy Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   As good as Agassi and Hrbaty were in their suspenseful two-act
drama, doused by a deluge Friday evening with Agassi leading, 6-4,
7-6, 3-6, 1-2, but declining, they were merely a warmup gig for the
Graf-Hingis duel that turned emotions inside-out and Court Central
into Bedlam revisited.
</P>
<P>
   As Act 2 began, Agassi had to sock his way out of two break
points (15-40) to 2-2, and another to 3-3 with a stunner serve.
That seemed to convince Hrbaty, nicknamed ``Quasimodo'' because his
name means ``hunchback'' in Slovakian, that the bells were clanging
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bells of Notre Dame couldn't have been heard within the
stadium for much of the time during the rancorous clash of
generations: a matchup of sturm und drang, Granny Graf overturning
Childe Martina. It became a morality play for the audience stacked
into the sunny stadium after more rain had delayed the start by an
hour, and nearly a tragedy in their eyes as the argumentative
Hingis stepped to the line to serve for the lone major title that
has eluded her, leading, 6-4, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting on the chair at the change,'' Graf recalls, ``I
thought this is my last time to sit here. Kind of defeatist. But
then hearing my name'' _ the incessant chanting, ``STEF-FEE!
STEF-FEE!'' _ ``I decided not to worry. Just go for my shots, go
after it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And go after the kid who had heisted No. 1 from her, and said
Graf was over that well-known hill, she surely did. Hingis knocked
a forehand winner to 15-0, so close to victory she thought it was
over. ``I am the better player,'' the kid insisted afterward.
</P>
<P>
   How could she suspect at that carefree, contented moment she had
reached her afternoon zenith, and that Graf's rage to win a sixth
French (one behind Chris Evert's record), would sweep her away?
Graf would do it with those bludgeons that baptized her ``Fraulein
Forehand,'' sliced backhands causing Hingis to bend so low that ``I
got tired'' _ and a heart to make a lioness jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was against me, the crowd, the officials, the
umpire, the referee,'' Hingis complains. But mostly it was Graf.
Hingis's frequent moaning about line calls and appeals to umpire
Anne Ullrich disrupted the flow and won her massive disapproval.
Ullrich seemed exhausted herself, often coming down from her
highchair (following silly clay-court custom) to examine ball marks
at Hingis's insistence. But she slapped the intemperate kid with
one violation for breaking her racket in a pique, and the second
(and a point penalty) for invading Graf's court to point to an
alleged mark on the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we just play tennis, OK?'' Graf asked her in the third
set, confessing later that Hingis's deportment annoyed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wild, and I'm not even on the court,'' quipped John
McEnroe in the TV booth.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, last seen in a major final winning the US Open of 1996,
kept her cool throughout while applying the heat of her strokes and
superior athleticism, retrieving brilliantly, running the kid out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's young, she'll win it,'' Graf says. ``But for me, it was
my greatest victory. I came here without belief _ but the crowd
lifted me. At 1-0 in the third I knew the momentum was with me. She
got tight. Then at 3-0 I got tight and she almost caught me. It was
the craziest match. `Quit worrying,' I told myself. `Go for your
shots.' I did.''
</P>
<P>
   At match point, Hingis escaped momentarily with a playground
trick, an underhand serve. The crowd judged her underhanded, booing
and whistling fiercely. Graf says, ``It was a hell of a shot. She
won the point.'' But a pirouetting backhand drop and a bruising
forehand finished off the mad matinee. Both wept so profusely at
the conclusion that the grounds crew almost rolled out the tarp
again.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, France was Graf's once more, as it first was in
1987, when she was the kid tormenting an elder, another Martina
(Navratilova). And France may also be Agassi's Sunday as it wasn't
when he couldn't handle the 1990 and 1991 finals.
</P>
<P>
   For bird watchers, it was a great day for phoenixes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
