<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-BOS     06-06 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS WIN A WILD ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their situation remains one of utter improbability.
An eighth seed two wins from the NBA Finals? Their captain and
franchise conscience out for the playoffs? Their season already
once miraculously extended thanks to a fortuitous roll and now,
well, what do we say about this?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to New York, where anything can happen and usually does.
Even a game-winning 4-point play with 5.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks took a 2-1 lead in the Eastern Conference
finals Saturday with a wild 92-91 victory over the still-in-shock
Pacers. Larry Johnson gave this city its version of The Shot with a
desperation trey, one of his specialties du jour. He also was
fouled by Antonio Davis before the shot _ there was a very creative
interpretation of continuation by referee Jess Kersey _ and then
calmly made the free throw amid the pandemonium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a bad call,'' said Pacers coach Larry Bird. ``The way
I see it, I was disappointed he didn't get the free throws. But
that's part of it. He made a great play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks then stuffed the Pacers on Indiana's last possession
_ Reggie Miller was a spectator in that sequence and for much of
the game _ and Madison Square Garden erupted. Johnson was hugged by
Spike Lee as well as his teammates. The Knicks can take a 3-1 lead
with a victory at home Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball left my hand,'' said Johnson, recalling The
Shot, ``I wasn't thinking about anything. I had been trying to stay
focused, stay square and a get a good release.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4-point play gave New York its first lead since the previous
unorthodox trey from Johnson _ a 25-foot banker that he admitted
was lucky _ made it 75-71 with 10:49 to play. Indiana then
seemingly took over the see-saw game (16 ties and lead changes) by
putting together a 14-2 run, capped by a baseline pop from the
exhumed Rik Smits (25 points in 24 minutes). Indy still led by 8,
89-81, with 3:21 left after two Smits free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers then brought in Heathcliff Slocumb to close the
game. They managed only 2 more points the rest of the way _ a pair
of Mark Jackson free throws with 11.9 seconds left. The Pacers
missed shots. They turned it over. New York rallied behind Chris
Childs (9 points, 10 assists) and Marcus Camby (who was everywhere
with 21 points, 11 rebounds, and 2 blocks) before turning to
Johnson for the answered prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this game tough to swallow? I'm sure it will be,'' said
Miller, who finished with 12 points, none in the final 19 minutes.
``But we are a veteran team that understands we came here to get
one. We have another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Miller admitted, ``we've got to do a better job of
closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Knicks' magical run in the postseason continues. This
is a team that was dead three weeks ago, only to be revived by a
forgiving rim in Miami. It's a team trying to survive the loss of
Patrick Ewing (Achilles' tendon), who was Mr. Cheerleader Saturday
and will continue in that role indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   It's a team that has withstood inner turmoil and distractions
from above and beyond all season. It almost makes you wonder if
something else is at work.
</P>
<P>
   We can imagine Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy going over all the
options during his last timeout with 11.9 seconds to play and his
team down by 3, 91-88. We don't think he said, ``Go for the first
available 4-point play.'' He did want a quick 2 from Allan Houston
(15 points on 6 of 17) but that possibility was eliminated when
Jalen Rose tipped the inbounds pass. The ball ended up in Johnson's
hands and the rest is history _ if written with a decided New York
bent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
