<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCHALE HAS BEEN IN EWING'S SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kevin McHale saw what we all saw when he watched
Patrick Ewing limp up and down the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt me just to watch him,'' McHale said. ``I was saying,
`Look at him.' It was painful to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, quite familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is now officially gone from the postseason because of a
slight tear in his left Achilles' tendon. He tried to play through
the pain, but it no longer was practical. He thinks he has a few
years left, but he has no way of knowing whether he'll ever get
this close again to an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   McHale can relate. He already had three rings in 1987, but, as
he noted, ``Three doesn't mean a thing when you're going for the
fourth one. You forget about all the things in the past.'' During
those playoffs, it was discovered that he had a broken foot.
</P>
<P>
   He had two choices, much like Ewing. Also, like Ewing, he
continued to play. The break worsened as each series progressed
and, by the Finals, McHale was visibly limping. The difference? He
was only 29. Ewing is 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, all you are thinking is, how can I help the
team?'' said McHale. ``You want to play. You want to be a part of
something special. You don't want to give it up. The pain is all in
your brain and you just shut it off. You get accustomed to it. And
then, after the surgery, you say to yourself, `What was I
thinking?' ''
</P>
<P>
   McHale, amazingly, averaged 21.1 points and 9.2 rebounds in the
1987 playoffs. The break actually had come in March, when Larry
Nance stepped on his foot going for a rebound. It was not confirmed
until the first round of the playoffs against Chicago. He missed
only two of the Celtics' 23 games in that postseason. In the Finals
against the Lakers, he averaged 20.5 points and 9.0 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You figure you've overcome a lot already to get there,''
McHale said. ``There's something in you. It's such a small segment
of people that get to play in the NBA. It's the competitiveness. I
think that's what makes us different from other people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics lost the 1987 Finals in six games. McHale never made
it back that far; neither did Larry Bird. McHale clearly empathizes
with Ewing, who feels he is prolonging his career by not playing
rather than jeopardizing it by continuing to play.
</P>
<P>
   McHale had major foot surgery later that summer and admits he
was never quite the same. He now looks back on his decision 12
years ago with equal parts admiration and bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, you extend yourself and try to do it,'' he said.
``You make all these reasons to justify it, but in the end, it's
stupidity. It's like, `What was I thinking?' I look back and I
realize I've done some dumb things in my life. This was right up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cavaliers owner Gordon Gund made it clear last week that the
dismissal of Mike Fratello was not due to the team's boring style
of play. Well, that's only half right. Gund also met with players
after the season _ he does that every year _ and the message he got
was that it was time for a change. He also had done some polling of
season ticket-holders, who indicated they, too, found the Cavs
tedious to watch. Finally, attendance was at an 11-year low, and
with the Indians and Browns selling out every game, this was not
the time to have a boring product in Cleveland. Gund also knew it
would be suicidal to have Fratello return with one year left on his
contract (there was an option for 2000-01) so he pulled the plug.
Fratello said he was shocked, but his product was boring. He has
long insisted that he can coach an up-tempo, aesthetically pleasing
team, given the right personnel. Well, in his first year in
Atlanta, he had a young Dominique Wilkins, Dan Roundfield, Doc
Rivers, and Eddie Johnson and still finished last in the NBA in
scoring. In fact, in Fratello's 13 seasons as an NBA head coach,
his teams have finished among the top 10 in scoring only once (the
1988-89 Atlanta Hawks were ninth). The last three years, the Cavs
have been 28th, 29th, and 26th in scoring. The new head coach will,
in all likelihood, be the anti-Fratello, which means a player's
coach who probably is an ex-player. Dave Cowens comes immediately
to mind. Meanwhile, outgoing general manager Wayne Embry, who had
an on-again, off-again relationship with Fratello, will remain
active in the draft (Cleveland has two lottery choices) and will
tutor new GM Jim Paxson this season before becoming a consultant.
Embry is not unhappy about leaving, although, he, too, had to be
caught somewhat by surprise; 48 hours before the firing of Fratello
and the ascension of Paxson, Embry was on the phone with an Eastern
Conference general manager talking trades . . . Rivers, meanwhile,
was Orlando's first (and only) choice to succeed Chuck Daly and
also was in demand in New York, which was interested in him for
Ernie Grunfeld's post. He was interviewed Wednesday and Thursday by
Magic officials and hesitated to sign only because of a difference
on whether the fourth year would be guaranteed. Magic GM John
Gabriel said he ordinarily would be reticent about turning the team
over to someone who never had coached before, but not in this
instance. ``This guy is special,'' Gabriel said. ``I think there
are guys that are just ready. He's one. Of all the ex-players I've
been around, he's something.'' Look for Rivers to bring in Dave
Wohl as his top assistant . . . With Rivers in Orlando, that leaves
Washington, New Jersey, the Lakers, and Cleveland technically
without coaches. The latest name to surface in Washington is,
surprisingly, Isiah Thomas. Garfield Heard is also being mentioned.
Said Gabriel, ``Now that the money is good, you're going to see a
lot of ex-players getting interested in coaching.'' . . . The
Alamodome has been booked for a Baptist Youth Convention for the
weekend of June 25-26. That's only a conflict if both conference
finals end in five games. The director of the Alamodome, however,
is blaming the NBA and the lockout for the possible overlap . . .
The ever-secretive Jerry Krause, general manager of the Bulls, owns
the No. 1 pick in the draft. He ought to come out today and
announce whom he's taking _ because no one would believe him . . .
Everyone who's anyone _ at least in the coaching/general manager
world _ will be in Chicago this week for the annual predraft camp
Tuesday through Friday. No big-name draftees will be there, but the
Celtics could well find the 55th pick toiling away . . . Shaquille
O'Neal isn't alone in being swept four times in best-of-seven
series. However, since he entered the league, there have been eight
sweeps and he's been a part of half of them. In a quick run through
the NBA Guide, we found that the estimable Alton Lister also was on
teams that were swept four times (twice at Milwaukee and twice at
Seattle). Among those who've been swept three times are Paul
Mokeski, Earl Monroe, Wes Unseld, and Truck Robinson. Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar was swept three times while with the Lakers: 1977 (by
Portland), 1983 (by Philadelphia), and 1989 (by Detroit).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Rick Pitino said when asked what he was looking for
at the recently concluded free agent camp: ``We're looking for
Michael Curry-type players _ tough, hard-nosed guys that can score
as well.'' Well, guess who's a free agent? None other than Michael
Curry. So expect the Celtics to inquire about him, although Grant
Hill already is pushing the Pistons to reacquire Curry, who played
1 1/2 seasons in Detroit before signing with Milwaukee in July
1997. The Celtics are also interested in _ surprise, surprise _
Tony Delk. Another player they might take a look at is Lawrence
Funderburke, who got lost in the shuffle during the Kings' playoff
series with Utah but was a big part of their regular-season success
. . . McHale on Ron Mercer: ``The only way the Celtics should be
worried about re-signing him is if there are teams out there who
will pay him what they won't pay him. I don't see any teams out
there who will give him $71 million.'' The unknown here is whether
Mercer wants to stay in Boston and keep playing for Pitino. If he
wants to test the waters, the Celtics may feel they have to move
him; they are offering Mercer and Kenny Anderson in a package
around the league. But money should not be an object simply because
there won't be many teams, if any, able to offer Mercer big dough.
And who's to say it would be a place he'd want to go? If it's about
the money, Mercer's best bet is to stay in Boston. If it's
something else, the Celtics will have to move him . . . NBA teams
have been given an extra five days to extend qualifying offers to
their restricted free agents (the Celtics have one, Damon Jones).
Under normal circumstances, those offers have to be made between
the end of the season and July 1. But with the season ending so
late, the deadline has been pushed back to July 5 . . . The Pacers
could face a financial hit courtesy of Dale Davis. He can opt out
of his already exorbitant deal and, given the way he's playing,
who'd blame him? Then again, he has four years left at $26.18
million, numbers he'd have trouble getting on the open market. The
only way he'd get more would be to hold up the Pacers _ again _ or
do a sign-and-trade. Davis has some pretty good company in the
opt-out department. Also eligible to do so this summer are Shaq,
Vin Baker, Penny Hardaway, David Robinson, Isaiah Rider, and
Dikembe Mutombo. If Hardaway, Shaq, Robinson, and Mutombo were to
opt out, they would be forfeiting a combined $152 million. Shaq
alone is owed a staggering $81 million and change over the next
four years . . . McHale feels the Timberwolves will re-sign Joe
Smith, also a free agent. Smith took a one-year deal with Minnesota
and it worked out well for everyone. ``The only teams out there who
have money are the Clippers and Chicago'' _ and Toronto _ ``and Joe
has already been there,'' McHale said. ``We have a good
relationship and we've worked well together.'' The downside: Smith
is represented by Eric Fleisher, who also represents Kevin Garnett
. . . Don Chaney, who works alongside Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy,
talked at length last week about the pressures on his boss. Asked
about a comment he once made that the job was eating away at Van
Gundy, coupled with the ongoing management intrigue, Chaney said,
``Just being a coach, it happens that way. Although you know it's
there, and you try to block it out and put it on the back shelf,
it's still there. And sometimes it manifests itself in different
ways. I've had stomach pains and heart palpitations. I don't know
what he's going through internally. But I do know he's that he's
done a great job with this team, considering all the
circumstances.'' Asked if he encouraged Van Gundy to externalize
his feelings, Chaney said, ``Yeah, but he won't do it. Sometimes we
encourage him to do other things _ walk away from basketball for a
while, go out, find a hobby, do something. But he's a basketball
guy. Personally, I'd like to see him pick up a hobby, for his
career. Because he's going to have a great career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
