<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DETOUR ON ANDRETTI'S ROUTE 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before Championship Auto Racing Teams went its separate
way from Indianapolis Motor Speedway and the rival Indy Racing
League in 1996, Milwaukee was always the date on CART's schedule
that followed the Indianapolis 500. Sunday, Michael Andretti will
arrive in Milwaukee for the Miller Lite 225 FedEx CART race on the
heels of a Memorial Day weekend victory in the Motorola 300 at
Gateway International Speedway in Madison, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   While he savored that victory, which coincided with the 30th
anniversary of his father's one and only Indy 500 triumph, it was a
bittersweet moment for Andretti. Deep down, Andretti would have
preferred that it came at the fabled Brickyard, where Kenny Brack
was received in Victory Circle as the winner of the 83d Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the ongoing rift between CART and the IRL, whose
crown jewel event of its all-oval series is Indy, Andretti instead
celebrated on a small podium at Gateway, where he was joined by
runner-up Helio Castro-Neves and third-place finisher Dario
Franchitti.
</P>
<P>
   Another year. Another Indy 500 missed. Another opportunity lost
for Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said the 36-year-old son of racing
legend Mario Andretti. ``It could've been Indy today, who knows?
But that's just the way it is. It's another year we'll have to deal
with it and, hopefully, the powers that be will get it figured out
and next year this time we'll be running this race on another
weekend, I hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like I'm driving my best right now. I'm in my
prime and I don't want to miss being away from there for another
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, whose 38 victories make him the winningest active
driver in the CART series, expressed the fervent hope that, with
all the buzz last weekend about ongoing dialogue toward a possible
CART-IRL reconciliation, the sides would reach an accord and
reunite next year at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we were there now, you know?'' Andretti said. ``But
then again I hope we are there next year, but we'll have to wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, nodding toward Castro-Neves and Franchitti in the press
postrace conference, he added, ``I'm not sure that these guys have
ever really experienced it. They have to experience it. It's
special and we all want to experience it _ all of us there
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Andretti, Franchitti chimed in, ``I used to watch
this guy back at home in Scotland, watching the Indy 500, and he'd
be running away with the thing and then something would happen . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Andretti interrupted, a knowing smile creasing his
face, ``there's a lot of hard memories and I still feel like that
place owes me one. Hopefully, we'll be able to get back there and
be able to get one.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any reason Andretti still clung to hope for that
possibility, it was because of the emergence of NASCAR president
Bill France as a powerful advocate for peace between the warring
open-wheel series.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure,'' Andretti said. ``I'm hoping now with Bill France
being involved, and now owning a lot of tracks'' _ after the merger
of International Speedway Corp. and Penske Motorsports _ ``and
wanting our series to do a little better, hopefully, he'll be able
to get things worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a 1,100-mile marathon last Sunday, Sunday's MBNA Platinum
400 NASCAR Winston Cup race at Dover, Del., should seem like a walk
in the park for the indefatigable Tony Stewart, 28, who became the
first driver to complete both the Indy 500 (in Indianapolis) and
Coca-Cola 600 (in Charlotte, N.C.) on the same day. After finishing
ninth in the Indy 500, Stewart flew by private jet to Charlotte,
was taken by helicopter to Lowe's Motor Speedway, and finished
fourth after starting from the rear of the field. Amazingly,
Stewart even surged to the lead at Charlotte on Lap 67. But by the
time the race got down to the last 60-70 laps, an exhausted Stewart
was hanging on to finish. He might rethink his plans for Memorial
Day Weekend 2000. ``As much fun as I had, it wasn't fair to give
(the NASCAR team) 90 percent for the last few laps,'' said Stewart,
who had very little to eat that day (aside from two bagels and a
couple of Power Bars) and collapsed when he climbed out of his No.
20 Home Depot-sponsored Pontiac after the Winston Cup race. Asked
if he was thinking about pulling double duty again, Stewart said,
``I honestly don't know for sure, but most likely that's going to
be it (at Indy). It was definitely worth doing once. The crowd's
response at both places was the highlight of the day.'' . . . So
who had the most impressive run at Indy? Look no further than
rookie Robby McGehee. Overcome with grief after his crew chief,
Steve Fried, sustained serious injuries in a pit-row accident on
Lap 12, McGehee fought back emotions and pressed on to finish
fifth, good enough to win Rookie of the Year honors. ``The best
thing that could've happened was when they came on (the radio) and
said he was awake and he had given us the thumbs-up,'' McGehee
said. ``That meant everything to me. I would have traded my
Indianapolis 500 to hear that. That's when I went and kept my head
down and finished the race.'' Fried, who was admitted to Methodist
Hospital in critical condition with head, facial, and chest
injuries, showed signs of recovery the next day and was upgraded to
serious . . . Jack Roush was a big winner on Memorial Day Weekend.
The Winston Cup owner had Mark Martin win the Busch Grand National
race at Charlotte Sunday, then watched as the IRL Aurora engines he
built for car owner A.J. Foyt finished 1-3-6 in the Indy 500. By
the end of the night, Roush's cup had runneth over as he presided
over Jeff Burton's victory in the Coca-Cola 600 . . . And, finally,
leave it to Foyt to provide ABC television with the best line of
the Indy 500 when he attempted to express his elation over his
first triumph as a car owner. In his exuberance, Foyt gushed, ``I'm
so wonderful,'' when he probably meant to say, ``I feel so
wonderful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
