<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLOY CASE STILL ON PATRIOTS' DOCKET 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots have a contract proposal of
``more than four years'' from Lawyer Milloy's agent, Ray Anderson.
The deal would put Milloy among the top two or three highest-paid
safeties in the NFL, perhaps even make him No. 1. It would average
more than $4 million per year, including a huge signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The offer has been sitting in Foxborough for several weeks,
according to Anderson, as the Patriots scratch their heads trying
to figure out ways to get Milloy and Ty Law in the fold while
keeping the rest of the team intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyer wants to spend the rest of his career in New England,''
said Anderson. ``He's very fond of the Kraft family and he likes
the team and their chances of getting back to a Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wouldn't say whether Milloy was looking to be the
highest-paid safety, but he would like something to break before
the end of training camp so that Milloy won't be distracted when
the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played three years,'' said Anderson, ``and in that time
he's played in a Super Bowl and gone to a Pro Bowl. I'd say that's
pretty unique.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have options with Milloy. They could slap a
franchise label on him, making it difficult for another team to
sign him as an unrestricted free agent after this season. But they
have avoided franchise labels with their high-profile players,
feeling they cause resentment, and they're right.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy is a tough player who intimidates receivers going over
the middle, and the fear factor he creates is priceless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few players worth mentioning:
</P>
<P>
   --Scott Zolak: Why is it that so many ex-Patriots have to get in
a little shot at the old regime once they leave town? Zolak, now a
Jet, told the Newark Star-Ledger last week: ``It's great to be back
with Bill (Parcells). He's the only coach that really motivated me
over my eight years. He puts a little fire in you. He knows what
he's doing. He surrounds himself with good people. You see what
(quarterback coach) Dan Henning did with Vinny (Testaverde). The
last two years, with Bill and (quarterback coach) Chris Palmer
gone, we didn't have anyone teaching the fundamentals, all the
little aspects _ ball mechanics, footwork. I'm back to doing that
now and hopefully I'll get my control back and start being more
accurate with the ball.'' Without mentioning them, Zolak was
ripping Patriots QB coach Jack Reilly and former QB coach (now
tight ends coach) Carl Smith. Drew Bledsoe doesn't have a problem
with either one of them.
</P>
<P>
   --Carl Pickens: It may not be easy being a Bengal, but this
stuff about not showing up unless he's signed to a zillion-dollar
deal is ridiculous. Pickens is 29 years old and unquestionably an
excellent receiver, one who probably would have fit nicely in the
Dallas offense if a deal for Michael Irvin had come off last week.
But it didn't. Holding out at age 29 in a young man's business
isn't good business. The Bengals realize that, and they hope
Pickens will, too.
</P>
<P>
   --Barry Sanders: It's difficult to criticize one of the greatest
running backs of all time, but not returning phone calls from Lions
coach Bobby Ross, not showing up for one offseason workout, and not
muzzling his father (who said things about Ross and the Lions
organization that he can never take back) makes you wonder where
Sanders's priorities are.
</P>
<P>
   --Ryan Leaf: File him under ``Doesn't Get It.'' Leaf missed the
Chargers' voluntary workout last week to take part in the Cadillac
NFL Golf Classic in New Jersey. Leaf, whose QB rating was under 40
last season, already has little respect from his teammates and did
nothing last week to endear himself to them or new coach Mike
Riley. Jim Harbaugh, who is slated to be the Chargers' starter, was
there for the workout.
</P>
<P>
   --Terry Glenn: Having been a baseball and football beat writer
for the last 17 years, I find two players eerily similar: Glenn and
Jose Canseco. Both are enormously talented and have a tendency to
march to their own drummer. Both have trouble conforming to the
team concept, both are respectful of authority but tend to test its
limits, and both can carry their teams when not injured. Canseco is
well on his way to 500-plus home runs and perhaps the Hall of Fame,
though his career will be tainted by the perception that he didn't
get the most out of his ability. Glenn is headed in a similar
direction. Both players had their best years under authoritarians _
Canseco with Tony La Russa in 1988 and Glenn with Parcells in 1996
_ and both were happy never to play for them again.
</P>
<P>
   --Jamal Anderson: Falcons coach Dan Reeves is big on offseason
workouts, but Anderson doesn't show up for them. Anderson works out
on his own and apparently has been very successful doing it that
way. But Reeves is an old-school coach, and if there's one side
reason that he was shopping Anderson to the Patriots on draft day,
it was those differences. The sides still haven't reached agreement
on a new deal, even with the Falcons a comfortable $1.7 million
under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are finally doing what the Red Sox have done for
years, using former players to help with the development of young
talent. Former Patriots center Pete Brock was brought in recently
to help center Jason Andersen with his footwork and will work with
the centers in training camp at times. Brock, incidentally, is
president of the Patriots' new alumni association, a group that
will help the team promote various events and causes in the
community. Brock, who played for the Patriots from 1976-87, said,
``In the past we didn't feel a part of what was going on with the
organization. I'm very excited about our association and that the
players in this area can now feel they're still a part of the team
they once played for.'' Also on the alumni board is vice president
Steve Grogan, treasurer Halvor Hagen, and secretary Steve King.
Brock has representatives from each era in team history: Len St.
Jean from the '60s, Bill Lenkaitis from the '70s, Ronnie Lippett
from the '80s, and Brent Williams from the '90s . . . Sixteen-year
NFL center Jim Sweeney has seen a familiar face around Steelers
headquarters at Three Rivers Stadium for years: that of director of
football operations Tom Donahoe, who was Sweeney's football coach
at Seton LaSalle High School in Pittsburgh. ``He's been the same
since he was a junior in high school,'' said Donahoe. ``He's a lot
bigger now, probably meaner, at least on the field. But as far as
his character, personality, and work ethic, it has always been
excellent.'' . . . Former Patriots offensive line coach Paul
Boudreau, now in the same position with rival Miami, has been
hugely impressed with Syracuse and North Andover fullback Rob
Konrad in training camp. ``It looks like he's going to be an
excellent lead back,'' said Boudreau. ``I know Jimmy Johnson made
the comment that he's had Daryl Johnston in Dallas and that Rob can
do things even better than Moose, especially run the football. When
he learns his pass routes he's going to be a very effective H-back
guy.'' In camp, Boudreau will preside over 13 offensive linemen,
one more than the team's running back total. Another Miami
assistant said the Patriots shouldn't rush into signing a running
back off the next wave of cuts because at some point in camp the
Dolphins will likely let one loose. Karim Abdul-Jabbar could be the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Shula has been rumored to be joining the group seeking to
purchase the Jets. Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan and his
brother Larry were runners-up for the Cleveland Browns, and Shula
was part of their efforts there. Shula's interest in the Jets
wouldn't make much sense with Parcells running the show, unless
Parcells exercised a clause in his contract under which he could
leave without financial penalty. Shula and Parcells are friendly;
they did work out an Irving Fryar deal (New England to Miami) when
Parcells first arrived on the New England scene . . . Carolina
coach George Seifert had to be somewhat happy when the quarterback
he allocated to NFL Europe, Dameyune Craig, led the Scottish
Claymores to a 42-35 win over Frankfurt two weeks ago, throwing for
611 yards and completing 27 of 37 attempts with five touchdowns and
no interceptions. No NFL QB has ever thrown for that much yardage.
The record is Norm Van Brocklin's 554 yards on Sept. 28, 1951, for
the Rams. Craig, who leads NFL Europe with a 101.4 quarterback
rating and 15 touchdown passes, fell short of David Klingler's NCAA
record of 716 yards for Houston on Dec. 2, 1990, vs. Arizona State.
But where this gets Craig, a former Auburn star, is probably a big
fat nowhere. He is behind Steve Beuerlein, Jeff Lewis, and Steve
Bono on the Panthers' depth chart . . . Just ask Steve DeOssie
about the wonderful world of long-snapping. Another living legend
in that line of work is Dan Turk, who signed a one-year deal with
the Redskins to return for his 15th season. Turk will turn 37 this
month. He was drafted by the Steelers in 1985 in the fourth round .
. . Zolak said Parcells was still a factor with Patriots players
when they faced the Jets. ``It's a respect factor,'' Zolak said.
``It's not a thing to get his approval, but you wanted to do well
and see what his reaction was. A lot of guys got caught up in that.
Plays would happen during the game and (guys) would look over to
the sidelines and see what Bill's reaction was.'' Great.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is getting smart and starting its own youth development
program for kids 12-14 who have never played tackle football. The
eight-week program began last year in New York, and its founder,
Rhode Island native Scott Lancaster, met with Patriots coach Pete
Carroll last week to begin efforts to get a Boston-area program
going by next year. Lancaster hopes to expand to 10 major cities.
The program is geared toward instruction, but Lancaster claims it's
fun instruction geared to the attention span of kids that age.
There is a similar program emphasizing coaching development . . .
One NFL owner, still a little skeptical about instant replay,
offered this scenario: ``What if it's at the end of a game and a
team has no timeouts and their final play of the game is challenged
and overturned and they lose based on a call that's been
reversed?'' It's true, instant replay will have its own set of new
problems that are likely to rear their head as the season goes on .
. . Heath Irwin didn't sign his tender offer, which doesn't mean
much. Chris Sullivan and Tedy Bruschi both signed their $934,000
contracts for next year, but Irwin was tendered at $429,000, which
is lower than he would have liked. His agent, Jack Mills, doesn't
see it as a protest. ``It's just a sign that we have a different
direction in mind,'' said Mills. ``We would have liked a two-year
deal.'' . . . Dale Carter, the fine cornerback who signed a
four-year, $22.8 million free agent deal with the Broncos, raised
some eyebrows when he missed the first day of minicamp. But he did
show up for the second day, and after a meeting with coach Mike
Shanahan, all was supposedly well . . . Shanahan, who faces serious
salary cap issues now that his players feel they're worth more
after winning two Super Bowls, offered defensive end Neil Smith the
choice of taking an incentive-filled contract or being released.
Another veteran, Packers receiver Robert Brooks, who is returning
from a herniated disc in his back, took a pay cut in his
renegotiation to stay with Green Bay, fearing that if he were let
loose he wouldn't get anywhere near the $700,000 he'll average,
with incentives that could get him close to $1.8 million a year.
The Packers now have enough cap room to sign their rookies and no
longer anticipate any cuts . . . Now that the gibberish about his
buying the Patriots has been proven erroneous, Houston businessman
Bob McNair has a legitimate shot at getting himself the next NFL
franchise because Los Angeles may not get its act together before
the Sept. 15 deadline it was given. McNair would have a
Hartfordesque stadium deal in Houston and big-time support from the
business community . . . With the shelf life of Patriot running
backs being what it is these days, will anyone break Sam
Cunningham's team rushing record of 5,453 yards? Curtis Martin, who
is fourth on the list, fell far short at 3,799.
</P>
</TEXT>
