<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES WANT TO BE PART OF PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The innocent bystanders in the International Olympic
Committee scandal _ the athletes _ were in full voice at last
week's initial meeting of the IOC 2000 reform commission in
Switzerland. They want not only 20 athletes (current or recently
retired) on the new version of the IOC, they also want two on the
powerful executive board.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not about the athletes, then what is it about?'' says
former Norwegian speedskater Johann Olav Koss, the 1994 triple gold
medalist.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes also want primary say about host cities instead of
having them picked by what former Algerian miler Hassiba Boulmerka
calls ``an institution of elderly men.''
</P>
<P>
   The reform commission, which will propose changes in everything
from site choices to member selection, will make its preliminary
report this month at the full IOC meeting in Seoul and its final
recommendations in December.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the frustrated Italians and Austrians, banned from
inviting the Lords to tour their bid cities, are planning cosmic
dog-and-pony shows at the IOC session, where the 2006 Winter Games
will be awarded. ``Virtual-visit'' videos, slick brochures, reams
of technical data, souvenir pins, and T-shirts _ but no first-class
plane tickets, calfskin luggage, Waterford crystal, or jeroboams of
champagne. ``It's difficult,'' shrugs Marco San Pietro, Turin's
international relations director. ``Practically everything is
forbidden.'' With the odds-on favorite being Sion, the Swiss resort
that is within commuting distance of IOC headquarters and was a
2002 also-ran, the other five contenders merely want to make the
two-city cut. ``Our goal is to get into the finals,'' says Olympic
downhill champion Franz Klammer, who is fronting Klagenfurt's
unprecedented three-country bid (Austria-Italy-Slovenia). ``It's
not over yet. We are still fighting.'' Under the new process, a
16-member panel (only 11 of them IOC members) will whittle the
field, which also includes Helsinki/Lillehammer, Zakopane (Poland),
and Poprad-Tatry (Slovakia) to two on June 18. Then the entire IOC
will pick the winner the next day . . . Those 1,400 boxes of
documents turned over to Congress by the Atlanta organizers show
that most of the same IOC bottom-feeders who were shaking down the
Salt Lake bidders were also looking for handouts or family junkets
in Georgia. Chief mendicant was the expelled Jean-Claude Ganga of
the Republic of Congo, who got more than $50,000 worth of favors,
including a soccer scoreboard, equipment, and uniforms and a couple
of enrollments at the pricey Bollettieri tennis camp in Florida.
Also on the freebie list were Western Samoa's Seuili Paul Wallwork
and Mali's Lamine Keita, who were booted out, and Finland's Pirjo
Haeggman, who resigned. The Atlanta folks, who insist that they
acted with ``integrity and honesty,'' also gave out 38 individual
gifts that exceeded the IOC's $200 limit, including a $940
carburetor kit to the man from Libya. Just Southern hospitality,
chief organizer Billy Payne shrugged. The Atlanta revelations are
another shot upside the head for IOC member Phil Coles of
Australia, who has already been censured for his Salt Lake City
escapades and was grilled for nearly three hours last week by a
peer panel about other alleged misdeeds. The Atlanta people say
that Coles brought two guests (one more than allowed) for a visit
that cost $13,000. No worries, mate, insisted Coles. ``These are
not my last few days,'' he declared . . . Spirited tiff between IOC
board members Richard Pound of Canada and Kevan Gosper of Australia
over whether president Juan Antonio Samaranch should resign before
his term ends in 2001. Pound has said several times that Samaranch
might consider stepping down early; Gosper called Pound's remarks
``rather unfortunate'' and ``unwelcome.'' ``It's a term, not a
sentence,'' countered Pound, who said that Samaranch is free to do
whatever he wants. The 78-year-old Samaranch, in place since 1980,
says he'll go right down to the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the US Figure Skating Association said ``too late''
to the sexual misconduct grievance against Richard Callaghan, filed
14 years after the (alleged) fact by former pupil and coaching
partner Craig Maurizi. Maurizi, who has just taken over as skating
director at the New England Sports Center in Marlborough, still has
a grievance pending with the Professional Skaters Association.
Callaghan, meanwhile, apparently has changed his mind about
retiring from elite-level coaching. He'll keep working with Todd
Eldredge, Angela Nikodinov, Erin Pearl, and Stacy Pensgen, plus
Canadian champ Jennifer Robinson. Pearl, who comes from
Scarborough, Maine, is reaping the perks that come with placing in
the top five at this year's Nationals: She'll go to Germany and
Japan next fall for Grand Prix events . . . Sunday's inaugural
Track &AMP; Field Association pro meet on Long Island (live on ESPN) is
a model for the spectator- and TV-friendly circuit that's designed
to breathe life into a sagging sport. Eight events per gender,
eight athletes per event, a tight two-hour program, and a $100,000
jackpot for the winner of a random event (the women's 100 hurdles
Sunday). The only thing lacking Sunday is the marquee duels in the
glamor events. Olympic champions Michael Johnson and Mike Marsh
both pulled out of the 200, and Gail Devers begged off her planned
matchup with Marion Jones in the 100 . . . Heroine's welcome for
paralyzed Chinese gymnast Sang Lan, who finally returned to Beijing
10 months after breaking her neck at the Goodwill Games on Long
Island. ``She's approached her problems like a superwoman,'' a
government official declared. ``She's the pride of all Chinese.'' .
. . No surprises among the first batch of US rowers qualifying for
this summer's world championships in Ontario: Scullers Jamie Koven
and Leslie Burns Rawley, lightweight sculler Sherri Kiklas, and the
lightweight double of Steve Tucker-Conal Groom all retained their
spots on the team. Second batch (men's and women's doubles and
men's lightweight quad) will be chosen this week in South Carolina.
Doubles favorites are Dan Protz-Phil Henry and Laurel Korholz-Jen
Dore. Not surprisingly, the American entries got hammered in last
weekend's World Cup opener in Belgium. Only the women's pair made
the final and Koven, the former world champ, was last in his semi.
Next regatta is in Vienna in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inauspicious season's start by the US men's volleyball team,
which was swept by the Canadians in its three-match tour above the
border and faces a bumpy road to Sydney. Next up is a tour of
Japan. The women, who haven't played since March because their
domestic tour with the Russians was canceled, are sparring with the
Dominican Republic this week . . . Yet another milestone for beach
volleyball player Karch Kiraly, who can match the career record for
victories (139) by winning the Dallas Open Sunday with Adam
Johnson. Kiraly's former partner (and present rival) Sinjin Smith
holds the mark . . . After missing an automatic Olympic berth by
losing to the host Canadians in the World Cup last weekend, the US
women's water polo team will have to wait until next spring for a
second chance. The Yanks, who'd beaten Canada in the prelims,
dropped the payoff match by two goals . . . So where is the
international bobsledding federation holding this year's congress?
In Jamaica, of course, where the only ice is in the Planter's
punch. Cool runnings, mon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
