<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      06-06 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY LEFT IN COLD BY OPEN'S STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ There was much hoopla made over the fact
that the 1999 Masters went off without Jack Nicklaus, who was
recovering from hip replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Very little has been made of the fact that the US Women's Open
is being played without Pat Bradley. The pride of Westford, Mass.,
has played every one since her debut in 1975 and she deserves to be
here. She would like to be here, too, but was not offered an
exemption by the US Golf Association Women's Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, as the third round was played out, Bradley couldn't
watch. ``I'm sitting here, basically in shock,'' she said from her
home. ``It does not seem right. I gave 25 years of my life to the
United States Women's Open and felt I deserved better treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   She is right.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is the only woman to win all four of her sport's major
championships and, at 48, she still competes fulltime. When she
received her entry form for this year's Open, Bradley wrote on it:
``Former Open winner (1981) and member of the Hall of Fame.'' It
was not a request for an exemption, but a reminder of who she was.
</P>
<P>
   What she got back was a tee time for a sectional qualifer in
Tennessee. Saddened, Bradley chose not to go through a qualifier.
As it turns out, she couldn't have, anyway, because the funeral for
her brother Richard, who died after a long battle with cancer, was
that same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down in my heart,'' said Bradley, ``I feel I should be
(at Old Waverly Golf Club). ``I don't think (the USGA Women's
Committee is) looking at the big picture. My record speaks for
itself. I feel I deserve recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Exemptions into this year's tournament went to Nancy Lopez and
Jane Geddes. No argument there. Bradley and Amy Alcott received
them last year, and ``I thanked them very, very much,'' said
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Capouch, chairman of the USGA Women's Committee, said
``when Bradley's name came up (for this year), we looked at her
place on the money list (she's currently 85th with $33,619 in 10
events) and felt it wasn't high enough. It was tough. She's a great
champion and a great friend of the USGA.''
</P>
<P>
   Capouch said she wrote Bradley, explaining the Women's
Committee's thought process. ``We usually give past champions an
exemption the first year (that their window of exemption expires),
and that was last year for Pat.'' Great champions, she said, will
often get a second exemption, though rarely back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine she will get another exemption,'' said Capouch.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that is the hypocrisy. Last year, Nicklaus was
given an exemption into the US Open at The Olympic Club, and at the
same time the USGA said he would be in the field in 1999 and 2000.
``Where is that for us?'' said Bradley, including the names of
Alcott and JoAnne Carner. They, too, are Hall of Famers, and
Bradley thinks deserving of at least offers to play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer: Rich Beem. The question: Why are so many golfers out
there plugging along, trying to make it in this impossible game?
</P>
<P>
   Brett Quigley has always known the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
players out there who have got the physical game. It's getting into
a position to allow yourself the chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beem last week manufactured one of the best stories pro golf has
witnessed in some time. The 28-year-old went wire-to-wire to win
the Kemper Open, earning $450,000 and a two-year exemption on the
PGA Tour. Not bad for a guy who not long ago was playing
small-change tournaments in New Mexico, a guy who had quit the game
at age 24 to sell car stereo equipment, a guy who had made just
four cuts and $24,590 in this, his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Call it whatever you want. Quigley said it proves a point:
``Golf is a simple game when you play it well.'' Beem, said
Quigley, obviously was good enough to get through Qualifying School
(he finished ninth to earn his card), and at Kemper he seized the
opportunity. While he receives not a nickel of Beem's prize money,
Quigley does get some sort of satisfaction because he, too, is
waiting for a break.
</P>
<P>
   The Barrington, R.I., native finished 128th on the money list,
but only the top 125 are fully exempt. Quigley fits in behind those
125, as well as the Tour School graduates and special-category
players such as former champions. The first half of the season is
when players are most active, so Quigley's chances have been few.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to sit back and watch,'' said Quigley. ``Then when
I do get out there, I'm trying too hard. I'm putting pressure on
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley has gotten into just eight of 22 tournaments, missing
five cuts, and earning just $76,910. There will be more chances, he
knows, in the second half of the season, but the truth is this: By
then he'll be looking up a money list at players tens of thousands
of dollars ahead of him. It'll be like trying to make up a six-shot
deficit on the back side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have weeks off,'' said Quigley, trying to look at
the bright side. ``I can get things in focus, step back, and tell
myself to not try too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He will carry that philosophy to the first tee Monday when he
plays in a 36-hole US Open sectional at Bear Lakes in West Palm
Beach, Fla. Perhaps he'll earn a trip to Pinehurst, perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may not be David Duval-Tiger Woods, but an intriguing rivalry
is shaping up on the LPGA Tour. Grace Park will turn professional
Monday and almost immediately will be compared to Se Ri Pak.
Whether it was coincidence or not, the Seoul natives were paired
Thursday and Friday at the US Women's Open, an engaging story for
the many Korean journalists here.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, a hero in her homeland at the tender age of 22, is the
defending champion, a money-making machine for IMG and Samsung, and
a powerfully built golfing talent.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Park, who is a few months beyond her 20th birthday but
carries herself like a veteran. Which, in a way, she is. A standout
on the American Junior Golf Association circuit, she has been
heralded in golf circles for quite a while, and there are those who
feel she will, in a very short time, become the premier player on
the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Do not think, however, that Park is cut from the same mold as
Pak. Park does not command as much attention in her homeland
because her parents sent her to Hawaii in 1991 and to Phoenix two
years later, which many in Korea resent. Park has been molded into
a golf phenom, a strong player who casually talks about her
300-yard drives and seems to notice nothing around her. She won
last summer's US Women's Amateur, smiled, then yawned. Same thing
with the recent NCAA championship, which she won.
</P>
<P>
   Nice, but just part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sources have reported that there is some resentment in the camps
of these young talents. Pak played her junior golf back home and
has received more attention in Korea, but her father is merely
wealthy. Park craves the attention, and her father, according to
sources, is wealthier than wealthy. ``Very, very expensive,'' he
said back at the 1997 US Women's Open when asked if he travels much
from Korea to visit his daughter. Not so expensive, however, that
he hasn't been able to make dozens of trips to the United States
each of the last eight years to watch his daughter develop.
</P>
<P>
   Soo Nam Park is very much in command of his daughter's career.
IMG need not apply, because father knows best. His daughter will
turn down sponsor's exemptions to LPGA Tour events and head right
to the Futures Tour and try to earn her card by being one of the
top three money-winners. Less glamour, of course, but Soo Nam has
determined that this is a business and it calls for a long-term
investment decision.
</P>
<P>
   Park should find the Futures Tour easy pickin's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olin Browne avoided US Open qualifying with his victory at the
MasterCard Colonial two weeks ago, a victory that was quite a
surprise. ``When I got to 8 under (in the final round), I looked up
and saw that Greg Kraft was 10 under,'' said Browne. ``I was trying
to get to 10 under then promptly made a bogey.'' Browne got it to 8
under and Kraft lost three strokes coming home. It was the second
win in a calendar year for Browne (he won at Hartford last July),
and that was deemed worthy of a special exemption by the USGA.
Browne still has a lot of friends over at The Country Club, where
he played his golf one summer, and there is no one in the sport who
commands his respect more than longtime TCC head pro Don Callahan.
``He stands for all that is great about golf,'' said Browne, who
has earned another spot into the season-opening Mercedes
Championship. He missed last year's event after having elbow
surgery . . . During his induction into the World Golf Hall of
Fame, Seve Ballesteros related a story to reporters that goes a
long way in explaining his greatness. Living on a golf course in
Spain, Ballesteros's children naturally have access to the game.
Does he teach them? ``No, no,'' said Ballesteros. Instead, he gives
his youngest son, Javier, one club, an 8-iron, and says, ``Go play.
Go learn.'' One day, Javier notices his friends carrying bags with
many clubs. Perplexed, he asks why. The kids tell him that's what
you are supposed to do, and Javier says, ``No. My father says one
is all you need.'' Growing up poor, Seve had just one club, a
3-iron, which is what he used to develop his incomparable
shot-making skills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
