<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOSS READY WITH HIS OWN CAPITAL IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Why does Ted Leonsis want to buy the Washington
Capitals?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I can,'' said the owner-to-be, the multimillionaire
executive with America On-Line.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League's club of club owners continues to
change, almost on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Bill Davidson formally took control of the Tampa
Bay Lightning. Art Williams bailed out of the Bolts in less than a
year. In a little more than two weeks _ although the league would
prefer it happen sooner _ bankruptcy court in Pittsburgh will
determine who gets control of the debt-ridden Penguins. EMC
co-founder Roger Marino had to head to the courtroom when the red
ink got too deep.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Leonsis, a 1973 graduate of Lowell High School and
former head of public relations for Wang Labs, dreaming the dream
of propping up the Capitals in D.C. and making them a performing
and marketing force in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real left-brain/right-brain thing,'' said Leonsis, a
'77 Georgetown graduate whose family moved from Brooklyn to Lowell
in the late '60s. ``The left brain is the fan's point of view,
going to the game, and all the fun of it. The right brain says,
`Hey, this is a business like anything else _ and you can make it
work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals are a quirky fit. Based in a nontraditional hockey
market, they moved out of Landover, Md., last season with the
opening of the state-of-the-art MCI Center in downtown D.C. They
have a frighteningly low season-ticket base, believed to be no more
than 4,000, or about one-third of what the league demands of an
expansion franchise before it opens its doors. In a league of 27
teams, they also ranked 24th in paid attendance this past season.
In short, there is work to do, lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only afraid of what I don't know,'' Leonsis said in a
telephone interview last week when reminded of his challenges in
taking over the Capitals. ``I know all that.''
</P>
<P>
   To revivify the franchise, said Leonsis, he'll take a
three-pronged approach, which he identifies as 1. cosmetic; 2.
systemic; 3. cultural.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetically, there will be a whole new look, he said, including
new ticket pricing, new players, new offense.
</P>
<P>
   Systemically, Leonsis wants to break down what he believes are
existing barriers between fans and players and between fans and
ownership. Capitals business, from now on, will be from a
``fans-first'' perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make it more a Disney experience,'' he said. ``When
you're at the game, you'll have the feeling that every single
person is there to make your life better.''
</P>
<P>
   Culturally _ as in the corporate-ownership culture _ the Leonsis
approach will be to keep adding value to the franchise, to look at
it as a long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
   Leonsis remembers the Bruins' heyday. His family moved to Lowell
in '69, the year before Bobby Orr and the Bruins won their first of
two Cups across three years. `` `Jesus Saves!' '' said Leonsis,
recalling a popular bumper sticker of the era. `` `And Esposito
scores on the rebound.' I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only days after arranging his deal to buy the Capitals, he came
to Boston as commencement speaker at Emerson College and made a
point of visiting the Vault to see the Bruins face the Sabres in
the playoffs. He'd like to see the same atmosphere and success in
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was screaming, and half the place was dressed up in
black-and-gold sweaters,'' said Leonsis. ``The Bruins haven't won
the Stanley Cup in, what, almost 30 years, yet the place was sold
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the 43-year-old Leonsis is energetic and confident.
Recent reports peg his wealth to be upward of $750 million. He is
everything the NHL wants, and certainly everything the Players'
Association loves _ a gregarious guy with bottomless pockets who
sees endless potential in the game. In hockey terms, he's ready to
take it for a skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Execution is everything,'' reminded Leonsis. ``We will be a
bolt of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The late spring cleaning on Long Island saw Trevor Linden get
shoveled last weekend to Montreal, where the Canadiens committed
$15 million over the next four years to the former Canucks star.
The Islanders picked up Montreal's first-round draft pick, No. 10
overall, in the exchange. In the last three months, the Islanders
have ditched Scott Lachance, Robert Reichel, Sergei Nemchinov, Ted
Donato, and Tommy Salo. What's happening here? Simple answer:
Follow the money. The owners want Mike Milbury to run a young,
cheap franchise _ perhaps the only way to keep the boat afloat
unless Nassau County comes across with financial aid for a new
arena. Next to go will be scoring star Ziggy Palffy, who last
season came to terms on a five-year pact worth some $25 million.
What kind of deal will it take to land Palffy? The Bruins would
have to give up a Joe Thornton (forget it) or a Sergei Samsonov
(possibility). San Jose would have to cough up Patrick Marleau (a
chance). And the Kings would have to give up Olli Jokinen or Aki
Berg . . . No one in Toronto expects Mike Smith to end up back in
the Leafs' front office next season. In the moments following the
loss to the Sabres last week, Toronto boss Ken Dryden refused to
address Smith's status, saying the time wasn't appropriate. The
fact that the situation has lingered this long is essentially a
decision in itself. Look for Smith to catch on next month as a key
player in another front office _ possibly Minnesota . . . A sign of
the times: In days past, it was a guarantee that press rooms across
North America would fall silent when ex-Bruin coach Don Cherry
appeared on the tube for his Coach's Corner segment. However, when
the Leafs faced the Sabres last Monday night in Toronto, virtually
no one in the press box turned to catch the Grape One wax on with
partner Ron McLean. Cherry's act has lasted nearly a
quarter-century, and it has been worth millions to him, but even
his fellow Canadians appear to have grown tired of his jingoism and
Eurobashing . . . Nearly seven years after the swap, whom would you
rather have, Eric Lindros or Peter Forsberg? No doubt that L'Enfant
Terrible has sold a lot of tickets on Broad Street, but the two
best players in the game today are Forsberg and Jaromir Jagr. And
to think, the Flyers gave up not only Forsberg but also Steve
Duchesne, Kerry Huffman, Mike Ricci, Ron Hextall, Chris Simon, a
pair of first-round picks and money. Lindros, by the way, agreed
last week to honor a handshake deal he made last year and will play
next season at $8.5 million. His father/agent, Carl Lindros, chose
not to talk about a long-term deal . . . Larry Robinson, back with
New Jersey as an assistant coach, will earn some $2 million in his
new five-year pact. The deal calls for the ex-Hab to be an
assistant coach for three years and then work as a club consultant
for two years, 2002-04 . . . Don't be surprised if the Oilers deal
away star forward Doug Weight this summer. He'll make $4.3 million
this season, which is about $6 million in Canadian funds. He's a
talent, but that's a little too rich for the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the financial morass in Pittsburgh became untangled
Friday when bankruptcy judge Bernard Markovitz invalidated the
longstanding lease agreement between the Penguins and SMG Inc.,
landord of the Igloo. The decision should prove a major boost to
the bid by ex-Penguins star Mario Lemieux to buy the team _
possibly as early as June 24. Under the Lemieux plan, Marino would
remain a limited partner (at a cost of some $2 million). It was
Marino's decision to stop paying Lemieux and then to turn to
bankruptcy court for protection that ultimately led, in part, to
Friday's court decision to break the club's onerous Igloo lease.
``Roger and Mario met in the same room, face to face, about three
weeks ago,'' said Marino's Boston-based attorney, Harry Manion.
``And in the end, they shook hands. Roger just told him, `Look,
Mario, I didn't want not to pay you _ but there was just no more
money.' And Mario was great, saying, `I understand now what you
were up against, and I'd like you to be part of the deal.' '' The
SMG lease, set to run into the year 2007, was costing the Penguins
$7 million a year. For $24 million in up-front money to ownership
five years ago, SMG already received $35 million and stood to make
about another $56 million. The likely scenario now is for SMG and
Lemieux's group to work out a new lease that would keep the
Penguins in the Igloo until a new downtown arena can be built _ a
three- to five-year proposition. League VP William Daly said in
court that 20 of the league's 26 teams lost money in the '97-98
season . . . The Blues owe ex-Bruin Geoff Courtnall some $7 million
over the next two seasons, making him a likely candidate to be
exposed in the expansion draft that will stock Atlanta. Meanwhile,
Thrashers GM Don Waddell knocked down rumors last week that he
might be interested in giving up his No. 2 pick in the amateur
draft to acquire Palffy from the Islanders. He would be tempted to
pay $5 million a year only for a goalie, said Waddell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Corey unexpectedly stepped down as the Canadiens'
president last week, only hours after the Habs dished away their
first-round pick for Linden. On the job for 17 years, Corey said he
wants to spend more time with his family. The prevailing opinion
around Montreal is that Corey was pushed out, following another
disappointing season. Who's next? Ex-GM Serge Savard is expected to
be on the short list. Ex-Hab Bob Gainey, now the Dallas GM, said
he's not interested. ``Who wants to make a 50-cent buck and then
get nailed by the media?'' said ex-Hab Guy Lafleur . . . Michael
Peca, the Sabres' grinding center/captain, made $1.475 million in
1998-99. No fewer than 175 NHLers made more. It's tough to think of
a seven-figure salary as a bargain, but Peca rates as a blue-light
special in today's game . . . Rich Scimone, agent for former Bruin
Craig Janney, confirmed late last week that Janney has informed the
Islanders that he must retire. According to Scimone, extensive
medical tests show that Janney has a blood clot in one leg that
makes it impossible for him to continue playing . . . Don't look
for Ranger blue liner Jeff Beukeboom, hindered by a late-season
concussion, to resume his career. Consequently, the blueshirts will
scour the free agent market to come up with a right-side defenseman
_ possibly Stephane Quintal _ to play with Brian Leetch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
