<HEADLINE>
GORDON STILL COUNTING HIS BLESSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GORDON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ I want you to try something. Go to a computer and try
to log on to the Internet 54 consecutive times without failing.
Chances are you won't be able to do it (unless you are Cal Ripken).
You might punch in the wrong password. The phone line might be
busy. Maybe you forgot to pay your bill. Could be anything. It's
hard to do something 54 times in a row without making a few
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blessing when you think about it,'' Tom Gordon was
saying Saturday at Fenway Park. ``I never really thought about it
that much until now. Fifty-four in a row. Man, that's a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday, Gordon had gone more than a year without
blowing a save. The last time he did it was April 14, 1998, in
Oakland. Fifty-four times since then he had trotted out of a
bullpen in Boston, New York, Chicago, or Cleveland and preserved a
Red Sox win. Gordon is the only man in major league history to take
a regular-season saves streak over 50. Jose Mesa had the record, a
distant 43.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Stephen King wrote the book, ``The Girl Who
Loved Tom Gordon,'' a New York Times bestseller. Gordon means
safety. More than that, Gordon means victory. But the Braves were
in town Saturday and they became ``The Team That Slugged Tom
Gordon.'' The pitcher trotted out of the bullpen in the ninth
inning, the Sox holding a 5-4 lead. More than 32,000 people
cheered. A few minutes later, they were quiet as Gordon reminded
them why he points to the sky after he completes a job: Up there,
he believes, there is a higher power while here, Gordon is just a
pitcher. A pitcher who is human.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon got the first two outs of the ninth. But he couldn't get
by Chipper Jones, who singled. He had two strikes on Brian Jordan
before he also singled. And when Javy Lopez doubled to left,
driving in two runs, Gordon immediately got perspective. ``I
thought, `Man, I just blew a save,' '' he said. Shortly after, he
thought of The Streak.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates didn't let him dismiss his accomplishment as
frivolous history. Pedro Martinez approached Gordon in the
clubhouse and asked him to sign a baseball that said ``Tom Gordon _
54 Saves.'' Gordon appreciated that. ``The way he's been
pitching,'' Gordon said of his teammate, ``I might have to ask him
for a ball that says `30 wins in a row.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans would have been surprised to hear some of Gordon's
words Saturday. The first surprising statement was that he doesn't
consider himself a dominant closer, despite the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't call myself a closer,'' said the man who has been on
the job for one full season and parts of two others. ``I still have
a lot to learn. I think I'm one of the better relievers.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he can't call himself a closer because he still isn't
sure of the save rules. He was in New York and saw a save go to
Mariano Rivera and couldn't figure out why it did, because it
didn't appear to be a save situation. He asked Tim Wakefield to
explain it to him. He said Wakefield eventually told him, ``Flash,
I can't explain it to you anymore; you're going to have to figure
it out yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon laughed when he told that story. He laughed and smiled a
lot Saturday. He said he was blessed to have the streak and that he
``appreciated all the good things that were said in the
newspaper.'' He thanked his teammates, the organization, and the
fans. Fifty-four times in a row meant something to him. Newspapers
don't run mistake-free articles 54 days in a row. Sometimes you
write a check without incident and, say, on the 53d try, you forget
to sign your name. You tell your girlfriend that you love her 49
times in a row and on the 50th time you slip up and say something
like, ``I love me.'' Mistakes happen often.
</P>
<P>
   On June 8 of last year, Gordon blew a sizable lead against the
Braves in a game the Sox lost. He didn't see any similarities
between that game and this one. ``I was all over the place then,''
he said of the game at Turner Field. Not only that, but he hadn't
pitched in 10 days. Saturday, he said he felt better than he had in
his previous four outings. Really, the streak could have ended last
Saturday in Cleveland. He entered the game with a two-run lead, a
man on, and no one out. He walked the bases loaded, got a double
play, walked another man and then got a strikeout. How did he get
out of that one?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a miracle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon talked to his younger brother, Anthony, a few days ago.
Anthony Gordon was drafted by the Brewers (he's a pitcher, too) in
1988. As the brothers talked, Anthony told his older brother:
``We'll consider you a real closer when you get to 60.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make it to 60, but he's real. As a starter, he said he
had to look for things to do in the four days he wasn't pitching.
Now, he can pitch more often and stay busy. He was busy Saturday,
but for the first time in a year, in the regular season, he didn't
do his job. How many of us can say that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he said of his run. The only thing that
compared to it was the day in 1986 the Kansas City Royals drafted
him. ``Well, now I've got to start a new streak,'' he said. ``I've
got to get to 60.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
