<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORTER, REVOLUTION PUT OUT FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution discovered a winning
combination Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. They switched to a 3-5-2 alignment,
returned Edwin Gorter to sweeper, and defeated the Chicago Fire,
2-0, for their first regulation-time home victory since last Sept.
19.
</P>
<P>
   The formation allowed the Revolution to field their
most-skillful players, and the result was more composure on the
ball, less predictability, and some better passing combinations.
Whatever the reason, the Revolution displayed the cohesiveness and
intangible traits of a successful team. And, they moved into to
fourth place with 11 points in 11 games in the Eastern Conference
of the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was also significant because it was accomplished
against the defending MLS Cup champions and before 21,313, the
largest home crowd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan McKinley set up the first goal with a sliding tackle on
Peter Nowak, then a penetrating dribble to the left side of the
penalty area. McKinley crossed for Joe-Max Moore, who converted his
first goal since May 1 and his first in the run of play since April
3. Moore, though, will miss the Revolution-Miami Fusion game next
Sunday to play for the US national team against Argentina in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tackle was lucky, and it was ideal because I got the ball
on my left foot,'' McKinley said. ``It was the finish (by Moore)
that made the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had been playing a 4-4-2 formation, but injuries
to Mike Burns (hamstring) and Richard Goulooze (knee) have caused
player-coach Walter Zenga to alter the defensive back line. But
this time, Zenga made a major change, returning Gorter to the
defense for the first time since last season. There were a couple
of miscommunications which led to Chicago chances, most of them
squandered by Ante Razov, but Gorter provided a calming effect and
even contributed to the first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, Gorter moved into the offense and took a pass
from Jair, who continued his run, drawing Chris Armas away from the
play. Gorter's left-footed shot was deflected by Fire goalie Zach
Thornton for a corner, and McKinley set up the goal as Chicago
attempted to clear.
</P>
<P>
   But Chicago's Eastern European Connection _ Nowak, Roman
Kosecki, Lubos Kubik, and Jerzy Podbrozny _ continued to be
dangerous. Kubik advanced into attack in the second half as Francis
Okaroh marshalled the defense, but the Revolution clinched the
victory on McKinley's 76th-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley converted a header off a precise pass from John Harkes,
similar to the goal they combined on last week against the
MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, in his third Revolution start, again added leadership to
the right side of midfield, and allowed Jair to move to central
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Gorter, who had played only one complete game
this season, cannot be underestimated, since he raised the
Revolution's technical level several notches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just numbers,'' Zenga said. ``What is important in
soccer is the application of the players, staying together. When a
team wins one game, the team is compact and balanced. If Chicago
had scored in the second half, the questions would be different.
The one thing that is important in soccer is winning. The next game
will be harder. Every week is a different story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
