u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROW-YALE-HARVARD-BOS &LR;      06-06 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROW-YALE-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE LEAVES CRIMSON ALL WET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. _ The bulldog had bite for only the second
time in 14 years, but it was accompanied by a loud and clear bark:
Yale crew is back in business.
</P>
<P>
   Yale's heavyweight varsity crew put on a courageous show of
power and poise here Saturday evening on the Thames River as it
defeated Harvard by 1 1/2 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   The Eli covered the torturous 4-mile course in 20 minutes 45
seconds. Harvard was clocked in 20:51.
</P>
<P>
   The races were delayed more than three hours because of heavy
winds and a stronger than usual tide.
</P>
<P>
   Torturous? Yes. These crews row 2,000-meter races all year. Four
miles is 6,400 meters and a hair. That's like a heavyweight having
to fight 50-plus rounds instead of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Yale had played the bridesmaid too often in recent years in this
historic race, held for the 134th time since 1852. Before Saturday,
Harvard had won 13 of the last 14 races and 34 of 40. Harvard now
leads the series, 81-53.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's varsity led by two seats after a mile as both boats
slugged it out. It was Harvard by two seconds after 2 1/2 miles, a
seat after 3 miles, and three seats after 3 1/4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Then Yale cranked it up with a power 20 and took a three-seat
lead in a flash. That was it. The knockout punch was landed.
Harvard was stunned and couldn't recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes!'' bellowed Yale captain Jim Needham from his No. 6 seat
at the finish line, almost under the Gold Star Bridge. ``We wanted
it badly, we trained hard, and we rowed well as a team. We had good
senior leadership and we gave each other strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Needham, from Larchmont, N.Y., was one of seven seniors in the
big boat. The only underclassmen were sophomore Scott Proper
(recently promoted from second varsity) in the No. 5 seat and
junior Jim Donahue of Shrewsbury, Mass., in the No. 4 seat.
</P>
<P>
   Five Elis evened their record against Harvard at 2-2. Needham,
stroke Alex Reid, No. 7 Mark McCusker, No. 2 Hans von Trotha, and
coxswain Steve Pritzker were in the 1996 Eli freshman boat that was
part of a Yale sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this,'' said Pritzker of Alexandria, Va. ``We
practiced hard down here the past three weeks and it all paid off.
It was tough losing to Harvard the past two years, and this makes
up for it. This is the last race for most of us and it's the one
we'll remember most the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Yale coach Dave Vogel: ``Everything fell together nicely.
Our guys wanted it badly, they worked very hard all season, and I'm
proud of them. They got into a nice rhythm early and stayed
together. They'll always remember this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's undefeated freshmen, who will row at Henley, England,
later this month, were terrific as expected as they notched their
ninth victory with ease. The Crimson, the top seed and winner of
the Eastern Sprints, took command early.
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson freshmen have won eight of nine contests by open
water.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard was timed in 10:36.97 and Yale in 10:47.14 for a 2
1/2-length margin.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard won the second varsity race in 16:17.4, while Yale was
clocked in 16:26.3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
