<HEADLINE>
COLEMAN MADE HISTORY FOR PAWTUCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On the day after, Michael Coleman wondered aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times,'' he asked, ``does a guy go 7 for 7 and hit
for the cycle?''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to verify, especially considering the murky way
in which minor league records were kept in the early part of this
century. But of the countless thousands who have played
professional baseball since 1900, the Pawtucket outfielder is the
first ever to go 7 for 7 while hitting for the cycle (home run,
triple, double, and single) in a game, according to minor league
historian Bill Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fantastic,'' Weiss said from his home in Northern
California. ``I've never heard of such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, batting leadoff for the PawSox Friday night, hit a
single in the first inning, a bases-empty home run in the second, a
two-run homer in the third, a two-run homer in the fourth, a single
in the fifth, and a double and triple in the seventh inning of
Pawtucket's 25-2 win over the Norfolk Mets at McCoy Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The single and the three home runs all came on first pitches,
evoking memories of Reggie Jackson hitting three home runs on
consecutive pitches against the Dodgers in Game 6 of the 1977 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit three home runs in a game except in Little
League, and there it's easy,'' Coleman said Saturday from the
team's hotel in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's exactly how he made it look Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to feeling easy,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Only one major leaguer has ever had seven hits in a nine-inning
game. That was Rennie Stennett of the Pirates, who had four
singles, two doubles, and a triple in a 22-0 win over the Chicago
Cubs at Wrigley Field Sept. 16, 1975. Cesar Gutierrez went 7 for 7
for the Tigers in a 12-inning game June 21, 1970, and Rocky
Colavito of the Tigers went 7 for 10 in a 22-inning game June 24,
1962.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman became the first minor leaguer with seven hits in a game
since Neifi Perez, now the shortstop for the Colorado Rockies, had
seven hits in a 13-inning game Aug. 25, 1996. He is the first minor
leaguer to have seven hits in a nine-inning game since ex-Sox
outfielder Lee Tinsley, playing for Calgary in the Pirates' system,
went 7 for 8 in a 23-12 win over Las Vegas June 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, a statistician for 50 years who now serves as historical
consultant for Howe Sportsdata, provider of minor league stats,
said there has been an instance of a player getting eight hits in a
minor league game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three guys went 8 for 8 in the same game for Corsicana in the
Texas League back in 1902,'' Weiss said. ``They won, 51-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of those players, Corsicana catcher Nig Clarke, is
reputed to have hit eight home runs against Texarkana in that game,
according to ``Baseball: Doubleheader Collection of Facts, Feats
and Firsts,'' a Sporting News publication.
</P>
<P>
   But Weiss said there is reason to be skeptical about those
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rather peculiar game,'' he said. ``It was a
regulation Texas League game, but it was not played in a Texas
League park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the pitcher for the other team went the distance. The
story goes that A, he was a relative of the club owner, and B, the
club owner was mad at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's in the book as a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke went on to play 506 games in the big leagues, all during
baseball's so-called dead-ball era. He hit a total of six home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Coleman's seven hits came against pitchers who have
been in the big leagues. His first single and home run came off
Richie Lewis, who played for the Orioles and Marlins, among others,
and his second single came off Greg McMichael, who has pitched for
the Braves and Mets. And Norfolk came into the game with the best
record in the International League.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman hit his second home run off Johan Lopez, the third off
Dan Pontes. His first home run went over the left-field bullpen,
the second landed on the berm beyond the fence in left-center, and
the third landed in the right-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The hits that completed his cycle, however, came against a
5-foot-7-inch infielder, Todd Haney, who pitched the seventh
inning, when the PawSox scored nine runs. The double went into the
left-field corner. So did the triple, taking a bounce away from the
left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   The McCoy Stadium crowd of more than 6,300, which also got to
see parts of Pedro Martinez's 16-strikeout game on the video
scoreboard, roared its approval when it was announced over the PA
that Coleman had hit for the cycle, an event that in the big
leagues is almost as rare as a no-hitter. Coming into this season,
players had hit for the cycle 199 times since 1900; there have been
197 nine-inning no-hitters in that same span.
</P>
<P>
   The PawSox didn't score in the eighth, thus falling a run short
of the team record for runs in a game. Their 29 hits were a team
record. Coleman, who drove in seven runs, set club records for hits
and total bases (19) while tying club records for home runs and
runs (6).
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed was Joe Depastino, the ninth hitter in the PawSox
order, who went 5 for 5 with a walk and also scored six runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he got a hit, I got a hit,'' Coleman said. ``I was
following him.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago this spring, Coleman, 23, was touted as Boston's
center fielder of the future after a big-league callup the previous
fall. But when he didn't make the team out of camp and was sent
back to the minors, he went into a funk, hitting just .253 with 14
home runs in 93 games, and was benched after refusing Dan
Duquette's orders to undergo counseling. He eventually relented and
did see a Providence-based psychiatrist, but when the Sox promoted
a rookie outfielder this spring, it was Trot Nixon, not Coleman,
who talked about possibly qutting baseball and playing college
football.
</P>
<P>
   But after recovering from a knee injury in camp, Coleman has
seen his average climb steadlily, and his attitude no longer
appears to be an issue. On May 16, he was batting .237. Since then,
he is batting .359 (28 for 78), raising his average 62 percentage
points to .299.
</P>
<P>
   That average went up 34 points after the 7-for-7 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making a lot of progress at the plate,'' Duquette said
Saturday. ``He's done all of the work everyone has asked him to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   If Coleman was hoping to revive the team's interest in him, he
couldn't have done it better had he worn a flashing neon sign to
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it did,'' he said sleepily Saturday, having gotten just
three hours' sleep before catching the team's 6:30 a.m. bus to the
airport for the trip to Buffalo. ``We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not ready for them, I'm ready for somebody. I've heard
some trade rumors. I guess we'll find out at the All-Star break.
But only they can make that call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
