<HEADLINE>
DID A STROKE OF BAD LUCK FORCE MILOSEVIC'S HAND?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS
EXCELLENT ARTICLE OFFERS A HELPFUL 200-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 550.
TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,000.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Not once during NATO's onslaught on Serbia did
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic appear in public. He did not
walk in the streets of Belgrade. He visited no hospitals and
addressed no troops.
</P>
<P>
   He was silent. And now, in the twilight zone between war and
economic disaster, he remains silent.
</P>
<P>
   He had prepared for the worst. According to those who claim to
know his financial arrangements, the Milosevic family fortune was
transferred out of Yugoslavia long before NATO commenced its
bombardment, moved via Cyprus and Lebanon to an account in the
Shanghai free zone with the help of the president's personal
banker, Borka Vucic, the head of the Yugoslav bankers association.
</P>
<P>
   And his decision to accept NATO's ``peace'' terms was made by
May 28, a week before the end of the war. That was the day Russian
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin arrived in Belgrade for 10 hours of talks
with Milosevic and left _ though his words were largely ignored at
the time _ ``very pleased'' with the results.
</P>
<P>
   The president had sent Mirko Mirjanovic, the Serbian prime
minister, to meet Chernomyrdin at Surcin airport and, in the car en
route to the Beli Dvor Palace, the former Russian prime minister
asked Mirjanovic why the Serbs were being ``stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister understood the question, but said: ``It's the
boss who is taking the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chernomyrdin mentioned the exchange to Milosevic, the
president was incensed and refused Mirjanovic permission to return
to the airport with the Russian envoy. But ``the boss'' had already
made his decision to accept NATO's demands _ provided NATO troops
would not be allowed to travel outside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one day after the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The
Hague had published its indictment against the Serbian leader.
</P>
<P>
   And he had, according to those who know him, suffered another
shock: a minor stroke three weeks ago that affected his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, videotape of the Chernomyrdin-Milosevic meeting on May
28 shows the Milosevic greeting his visitor with a right handshake
rather than his usual two-hand grip. His left arm hung by his side.
</P>
<P>
   He already knew, of course, that his country was being
pulverized into the 19th century. An economic study just finished
in Belgrade showed that by May 21, annual per capita income in
Serbia had fallen from $1,000 to $450 _ about equal to the wealth
of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Did Milosevic also fear that a NATO ground offensive might bring
Western troops all the way to Belgrade?
</P>
<P>
   An opposition editor in Belgrade is convinced that it was the
indictment from Louise Arbour, the U.N. war-crime prosecutor, that
persuaded Milosevic to end the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided he had no other choice. Either he would remain the
boss in Serbia and lose Kosovo, or there would be a ground
intervention and troops in Belgrade and he would be sent for trial
in The Hague,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had 24 hours to think it over. He knew NATO was approaching
the moment of decision on a ground offensive, and that meant the
occupation of the whole country and the end for him. He did what he
always does: he took the worst decision in the worst conditions.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (200-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 550) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But NATO never had the courage to invade Kosovo, let alone the
rest of Yugoslavia. Besides, Milosevic has been threatened with an
indictment before _ and his colleagues in Bosnia, General Ratko
Mladic and Radovan Karadzic, have escaped NATO's arrest teams for
more than two years in a land controlled by American, British and
French troops.
</P>
<P>
   And when Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari arrived on June 2
along with Chernomyrdin, Milosevic put on a show of statesmanship
for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   There were no lounge chairs and sofas; the delegations were seen
facing each other across a conference table with Milosevic flanked
by two of the other Serb leaders indicted by Arbour: the army chief
of staff, General Dragoljub Ojdanic, and the Serb president, Milan
Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   President Milosevic received his assurance that NATO troops
would be confined to Kosovo _ and that there would be no mention of
a ``will of the people'' mechanism to change the status of Kosovo
after three years (a key clause in the original Paris peace
agreement signed by the Kosovo Albanians).
</P>
<P>
   NATO could enter part of Serbia, but Serbia's claim to Kosovo
remained unchallenged. But would this be enough for Milosevic to
claim he had saved his nation from defeat? &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONCLUDES) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dragan Veselina, president of the Vojvodina Coalition in the
Serbian parliament and a professor of political economics, believes
there is no future for Serbia as long as Slobodan Milosevic remains
in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no peace in Serbia until Milosevic and his
government have gone,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Serbia will qualify for economic aid as long as
Milosevic is here. Milosevic and his government must go. But they
will not go willingly. Our population should be released from fear,
they should feel free and speak freely and organize freely.''
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that Yugoslav democrats will rise up to throw
Milosevic from power may well be vain.
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs, including Veselina, fear that right-wing
nationalists such as Vojislav Seselj, the deputy prime minister of
Serbia, leader of the Serbian Radical Party and the notorious White
Eagles militia, could take power, leaving Serbia in the hands of an
openly fascist government rather than the crypto-socialist
dictatorship of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Russians step in then to offer Milosevic sanctuary? A
Russian exile for Milosevic, while it would be anathema to NATO
countries, might be a price worth paying for Moscow's cooperation
in Kosovo and the willing participation of Russian troops in
Yugoslavia under a unified command.
</P>
<P>
   And from Russia, of course, President Milosevic could even
travel on to China, and to the city of Shanghai. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
