<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: HAVE YOU SEEN THESE HOT-OFF-THE-PRESS STORIES?...  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (These provocative, TIMELY ``separate buy'' articles on the
promising NATO-Milosevic peace pact _ FRESH FOR COMMENTARY PAGES _
are from the Independent of London, distributed by the New York
Times Syndicate.)  
  
 (To publish these articles, they must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Moved Saturday night, 5 June 1999): &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DID A STROKE OF BAD LUCK FORCE MILOSEVIC'S HAND? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, THE INDEPENDENT of LONDON &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Not once during NATO's onslaught on Serbia did
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic appear in public. He did not
walk in the streets of Belgrade. He visited no hospitals and
addressed no troops.
</P>
<P>
   He was silent. And now, in the twilight zone between war and
economic disaster, he remains silent. Why?... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Note 200-word optional trim at 550; total uncut is 1,000) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MILOSEVIC-STROKE?-FISK-550&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE MADE A DESERT AND CALLED IT PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pithy Editorial) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT of LONDON &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victory in Kosovo is being celebrated Sunday morning. The deal
struck with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic will end the
bombing and allow the process of rebuilding to begin.
</P>
<P>
   But the war isn't over yet. NATO has created a desert, and it
would be unwise to call it peace.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be unwise to talk of victory. For who has gained?
What has been won? There is nothing to rejoice at here.... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-HOLLOW-`VICTORY'-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moved Friday, 4 June 1999): &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `PEACE' WITH DISHONOR: WE'VE BETRAYED KOSOVARS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors!) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ So we've won the war, have we? That's what we are now
being told by our leaders.
</P>
<P>
   All that will be missing is the truth: that we never went to war
for the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   And we are on the point of betraying the Kosovo Albanians...
</P>
<P>
   In a world where crystal balls are always broken, I venture to
make a prediction about Kosovo which I sincerely hope will prove
wrong:
</P>
<P>
   - That in the days before NATO's troops arrive in Kosovo, the
KLA's new commander _ the infamous Agim Cecu who, as a Croatian
army general, ``ethnically cleansed'' 170,000 Serb civilians from
Krajina _ will ``cleanse'' the remaining Serbs from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ That the KLA will refuse to be ``demilitarized.''
</P>
<P>
   _ That in a few months' time _ at most a year _ NATO's enemies
will be the KLA, who will be raging against the West for abandoning
their hopes of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Then we shall remember how we thought we had won the war. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-KLA-JUDAS-KISS-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moved the following 12 stories Thursday, 3 June 1999): &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANGEROUS DAYS OF RECKONING AHEAD FOR YUGOSLAVIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ If Kosovo's future is now being decided in
Washington, London, Brussels and Moscow, what of the rest of Serbia
with its shattered factories and epic postwar unemployment, its
broken roads and pulverized bridges and bombed-out power stations
and refineries and railways?
</P>
<P>
   And what of the immediate future of Kosovo? Turned into a
wasteland by two-and-a-half months of pillage and bombs, its
electricity and water supply destroyed, its communications torn up,
its villages and towns burned, its fields contaminated with mines
and the dust of depleted uranium shells, what possible home can the
refugees return to?
</P>
<P>
   There will be those here who will ask these questions many times
in the coming weeks and months. They will want the answer from
President Slobodan Milosevic... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WHAT-FUTURE-KOSOVO?-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE FOUGHT A HALF-WAR. NOW WE HAVE ACHIEVED A HALF-PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANNE MCELVOY, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONDON _ It is fitting that the end to Kosovo's nightmare
should be heralded at an EU summit. It reminds us that this was a
European problem, albeit one that Europe proved unable to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most depressing spectacles of the last 10 weeks has
been that of European leaders, so solid in their support for
military action before the going got tough, so adept later at
turning spineless on ground troops and criticizing NATO's choice of
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Neither America nor Europe has very much to be proud of in all
this. We fought half a war. It would not be surprising if we were
rewarded with half a peace... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE 150-word optional trim at 600. Total uncut is 1,200.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-HALF-WAR-HALF-PEACE-600&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON'S `COWARD'S WAR' STRATEGY VINDICATED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MARY DEJEVSKY, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. has grown too weary of President Slobodan
Milosevic's promises to take his word at face value. But if initial
reports are borne out, and the Yugoslav parliament's vote suggests
for the first time in three months that they could be, nowhere will
the satisfaction be greater than at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton's war, often dismissed as a ``coward's
war'' and ridiculed as ``immaculate coercion,'' will have been
vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a ``coward's war,'' but it is perhaps the only sort of
war that a squeamish public will support. What is more, it has
worked... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE 225-word optional trim at 725. Total uncut is 1,025.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-COWARD'S-WAR-CLINTON-725&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BOMB-STREWN ROAD LEADS TO IMPERFECT PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW MARSHALL, STEPHEN CASTLE, PHIL REEVES &AMP; KATHERINE
BUTLER &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was as British Prime Minister Tony Blair posed for the
``family photo'' with European leaders at Thursday's summit in
Cologne, that the news came through from Belgrade that the Serbs
had finally caved in.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-two days earlier in Berlin, the last time the fifteen
men had gathered together, the news was equally dramatic: it was
March 24 and the skies over Serbia were darkening with the shadows
of NATO's bombing squadrons.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in Cologne wanted to speak too soon or display
triumphalism but inside the summit the confident mood quickly took
hold.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic track had finally won the day, albeit with the
help of NATO's overwhelming military superiority. But if diplomacy
has indeed won out it has been a tortuous road... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE 225-word optional trim at 500. Total uncut is 1,325.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-POTHOLES-TO-PEACE-500&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERMS OF `THE DEAL' LEAVE ROOM FOR MANEUVER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MARCUS TANNER, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The deal struck Thursday between the two peace envoys and
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic deals a huge blow to Serbia,
but as analysis of the text shows, it also provides room for
maneuver and parts of it will allow the Yugoslav president to
proclaim a victory of sorts to his people.
</P>
<P>
   Let's dissect the fine print... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SLIPPERY-PEACE-LANGUAGE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MAKE OR BREAK DAY FOR PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RUPERT CORNWELL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top representatives of the West and Russia sat down with Serbian
President Slobodan Milosevic Thursday night for talks that probably
offer a last _ but far from guaranteed _ chance of a peaceful
solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic day for Yugoslavia,'' Martti Ahtisaari, the
Finnish president, declared as he arrived in Belgrade following
frantic diplomacy efforts in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   The ball is now in Milosevic's court... &QL;
</P>
