<P>
   &UR; CLINTON CAN'T SALUTE BUT HE SURE COMMANDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MARY DEJEVSKY, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton has had an ambivalent relationship
with the military since his first presidential campaign, when
documents suggested he dodged the Vietnam draft.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely looks comfortable addressing military audiences and
his salute still looks unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   Perversely, however, his lack of experience may have given him
something to prove, and he has resorted to force more than any
recent president _ helped by the end of the Cold War, which removed
the risk of precipitating a superpower conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Transformed into advocates of limited force, the likes of Bill
Clinton have resurrected the just war, a concept their anti-war
campaigning qualifies them uniquely to embrace... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (325 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ARTFUL-DODGER-CLINTON-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES TOO WEARY TO CELEBRATE, TOO SCARED TO RETURN HOME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PHIL DAVISON, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KUKES, ALBANIA _ They were still far too traumatized to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   As the word spread slowly that their homeland may soon be at
peace, the Kosovo refugees living in tents, on the back of tractor
trailers or in the humble homes of Albanians here reacted quietly
and skeptically.
</P>
<P>
   They are under no illusions as to what they expect to find if
they return: a Dante's inferno of torched homes, slaughtered or
missing relatives, possessions destroyed or stolen, livestock
killed, a country without infrastructure where they will need
massive world aid to rebuild from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we are going back to the Sahara. It will make Saddam
Hussein's looting of Kuwait look like child's play,'' said Ibrahim
B., a 30-year-old student and refugee from the Kosovo capital,
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going back to? Hell...'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: Story stands in 900 words. Total uncut is 1,050.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WARY-REFUGEES-900&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MILOSEVIC WAVES WHITE FLAG, ACCEPTS NATO'S DEMANDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MARCUS TANNER, ANDREW GRICE AND ANDREW MARSHALL &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS AND WASHINGTON _ Slobodan Milosevic came to power on a
pledge to keep Kosovo inside Serbia. Thursday he appeared to sign
it away as his parliament voted to accept the G8 proposals to end
the conflict with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The deal demands the total withdrawal of Serbian forces from
Kosovo within seven days and the deployment of a NATO-led peace
force. It is a bitter pill for Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was cautious, however. ``This is not a time for
popping champagne corks,'' said State Department spokesman James
Rubin. ``What we are going to be looking for is implementation,
implementation and implementation...'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SLOBBO-SURRENDER?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TONY BLAIR: CRUSADER WHO BELIEVED IN `JUST WAR' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW GRICE &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, widely portrayed as ``NATO's
hawk'' during the Kosovo crisis, does not mind looking tough but
believes his label does not do him justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not about being a hawk _ it is about being right,'' one
of the prime minister's closest aides said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   British cabinet ministers believe Blair has come into his own
during the Kosovo crisis, seeing his ``just war'' as a moral as
well as military crusade... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (350 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BLAIR'S-`JUST-WAR'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATO: FLAWED ALLIANCE HELD TOGETHER IN CRISIS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The war in Kosovo has shown both the strengths and
weaknesses of NATO, and they are the reverse of what might have
been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatically, the alliance has kept together well through
months of crisis. But the price has been a lack of military
effectiveness... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (325 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NATO-GLUE-WORKED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES RECEIVE NEWS OF PEACE DEAL WITH MIXED EMOTIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By KIM SENGUPTA, The Independent of London &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SKOPJE _ It began in urgent whispers; within minutes it had
turned into an excited murmur which seemed to fill the camp.
Serbian President and ethnic cleanser Slobodan Milosevic had
accepted the peace deal, they may at last be going home to their
beloved Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For some in the camp there was a bitter edge to the rejoicing.
They had lost members of their family as they were routed out of
Kosovo, and they are still missing. The agonizing search for them
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   As a U.N. official observed, ``the details of this peace plan
will have to be carefully worked out. We have a lot of very nervous
people here...'' &QL;
</P>
