A4849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX     06-06 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OK, you tell us; what do we call decade to come?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Barrels of ink cling to our fingers as we sweat
out the impending drama. What will our computers do at the stroke
of 00?
</P>
<P>
   Not to denigrate a good crisis, but it seems no one has fretted
another matter sufficiently: When the century's clock strikes none,
what to call the decade begun?
</P>
<P>
   I posed this question to my 11-year-old the other day.
</P>
<P>
   It came after one of those typical father-son exchanges showing
how out-of-touch with a decade a father can be. It had to do with
Korn, one of the musical groups my son cited as hot these days.
(Rolling Stone describes it as an ``angsty rap-metal quintet.''
Whah?)
</P>
<P>
   When I asked whether Korn started with a K or a C, he reacted
with, ``Dad, get with it. It's the Nineties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't be able to say that to me much longer,'' I said.
``What are you going to tell me to do when it's the 2000s?''
</P>
<P>
   That put the clamps on him for a second.
</P>
<P>
   Just what do we call the '00s? I've heard no candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Do we call them the Zeroes? Do we call them the Zips? The
Zilches? The Cheeri-Ohs? The Ooohs?
</P>
<P>
   Do we call them the Oughts? The Naughts? Shuddering thought. We
go from the Nineties to the Naughties (as if the Nineties aren't
naughty enough.)
</P>
<P>
   ``How about the Nothings?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diddly Squats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I think that has potential. The Diddlies. The Squats.
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``What of significance happened in the decade of the
Diddlies?''
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Squat.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late to come to a definitive term for the decade to
come. Ross Perot could chair it. If anyone knows Diddly, it's H.
Ross.
</P>
<P>
   If you think about it, this is the real Y2K crisis. This has far
more consequence. After all, even with crashes and black-outs and
calves' blood flowing from our taps, eventually all those
high-priced geeks are going to fix our 00 computer problem. But
what if we go through the next decade without a name for it?
</P>
<P>
   We've already seen amateurish attempts to label decades. Someone
somewhere tried to call the '70s the Me Decade. They were close,
only 10 years off. That was OK, because we could name the '80s
(which trickle-down economics made sure was even more about Me) the
Me II Decade, the Me-Me Decade, or Me Too, or Me Times 2.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, maybe we'd better wait for the decade to happen
before nicknaming it. We've conditioned ourselves somehow to
believe the worst about the future, and to fear the worst about
succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
   What became of the optimism of the New Frontier?
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd like to assume that the next generation to take
the baton will be OK, indeed, better than that.
</P>
<P>
   So should we still be alarmed? You bet we should.
</P>
<P>
   We should all be on alert _ stockpiling food, water, batteries,
copies of National Geographic (to remind us of what the world
looked like before) _ for our want of any inkling of what to call
the decade to come.
</P>
<P>
   What did they call the 1900s? We know all about the '20s, the
'30s and so on. That was easy. Naming this decade is going to
challenge humanity. As economist Ray Perryman recently pointed out
in discussing the 2000 computer barrier, like Alexander the Great's
troops, we are approaching the edge of our map and don't know what
to make of it.
</P>
<P>
   And we're supposed to march bravely now into the Diddly Squats?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor for the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
