<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LIONBRIDGE _ ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. _ One person's treasured
historic landmark is another person's dangerous traffic bottleneck
in St. Augustine, where the graceful Bridge of Lions may soon be
torn down. Preservationists plan to make last-ditch pleas at a June
7 (Monday) public hearing before the Florida Department of
Transportation, which will decide later this year whether to
refurbish or demolish the 73-year-old structure, which is graced by
turrets, arches and stately lion statues. Both the DOT and the
Coast Guard say the two-lane drawbridge is a problem, tying up both
car and boat traffic. Thousands of residents who face daily long
waits to cross it agree, saying safety is more important than
history. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
