<P>
   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Blace, Macedonia) _ NATO and Yugoslav military
officials continue talks on the withdrawal from Kosovo of Serb
forces. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright is on her way to the Balkans to help sort out details of
the Serbian withdrawal. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ What the Pentagon has to say
about what's holding up the talks on the border of Kosovo. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO headquarters says it will
continue air strikes until an agreement between military officials
is reached. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On the Serb refugees
from other parts of the Balkans. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Blace, Macedonia) _ In an indication of what
Serbs in Kosovo may face when Albanian refugees return, a gypsy
family is nearly beaten to death in a refugee camp after Albanian
refugees accuse them of having burned down their house. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Datelie TK) _ Shelling continues along the
border with Kosovo. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALBOTT (Washington) _ A profile of Strobe Talbott; a
look at his role in helping resolve the Kosovo conflict. By David
E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (Dateline TK) _ Developments at the war-crimes
tribunal. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REACT (Undated) _ What the American people think
about an end to the fighting. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta) _ Indonesia has it first free
national elections in 40 years. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-POLAND (Pelplin, Poland) Standing on Bishop's Hill, a
sacred site that was forced into the German Reich during World War
II, John Paul II reminded Poles that Christian martyrdom continued
well into this century. The 79-year-old pope, who arrived in nearby
Gdansk on Saturday for a 13-day visit to his homeland, is seeking
to tend to his Polish flock ten years after the fall of communism,
and also to underline the themes of his papacy as he prepares to
usher the Roman Catholic Church into the third millennium. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Johannesburg) _ One of the startling things
about the recent election here is how well the African National
Congress did not just at the national level, but in all 9
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.N.-RIGHTS (United Nations) _ Ten years to the day after
the massacre around Tiananmen Square, China has blocked granting
special U.N. status to a New York-based human rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   CORSICA-FRANCE (Ajaccio) _ On the tensions between Corsica and
Paris. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LAW-REFORM (Houston) _ Over the last decade, sweeping
changes have transformed the legal system here in Texas and in many
other states. Under the banner of lawsuit reform, Texas has helped
lead the way, embracing one of the nation's most ambitious attempts
to hold down the cost of civil suits and limit the size of jury
awards. For years, Texas had a reputation as the ``lawsuit capital
of America'' because its juries in injury cases were said to be
overly generous. But starting in the late 1980s, the state began
adding restrictions, like limits on punitive damage awards, and
provisions that make it harder for injured workers to sue. Now
Texas is seen as one of the most aggressive states in efforts to
curb civil suits under the banner of ``tort reform.'' By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   BIKES-EXTINCT (Hannibal, Mo.) _ These are exquisite days to ride
a bike in this all-American, middle-American boyhood home of Mark
Twain. Kids can ride to school, to the Tom Sawyer Cave three miles
south, to fish on the banks of the Mississippi, to play pitch and
catch in a park. They can and they did, but they don't anymore.
Hannibal's parks, river banks and schools are all but barren of
bikes. And as Hannibal goes, so goes the nation. In the shadow of a
long, slow decline in cycling generally, the bicycle as a
century-old symbol of childhood freedom and transportation is
nearly extinct. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-GUNS-REACT (Washington) _ School-sponsored rifle teams
and officer-training programs have come under scrutiny in recent
weeks as administrators redouble efforts to rid their schools of
guns in the wake of the Columbine High School killings.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CONNERLY (Miami) _ Ward Connerly, the man who campaigned
successfully to end affirmative action in government hiring and
school admissions in California and Washington state, has now aimed
his crusade at Florida, to the sound of slamming doors. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-RDP (Cape Canaveral) _ Seven astronauts were getting
their Earth legs back on Sunday after an unusual
middle-of-the-night space-shuttle landing capped their 10-day
mission to stock cupboards aboard the new international space
station. By William Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   MRSGORE-PROFILE (Washington) _ A profile of Tipper Gore. Mrs.
Gore, defined constantly in opposition to her husband, is supposed
to be the earthy, unguarded, effervescent one. Seemingly everyone
who knows her describes her this way, and the conventional wisdom
is that, in the coming campaign, she will serve as an essential
antidote to Al, the unlabored warmth to his unyielding chill. But
in a brief, stilted conversation late last week, Mrs. Gore seemed
ill prepared for that assignment. Her answers were fuzzy, cautious,
and, in a few instances, incredible. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-POLITICS (Washington) _ A bill sailing through Congress
that would expand federal health benefits for disabled people who
work illustrates the political strength of the disabled. By David
E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
