<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSPAPER-STRATEGIES-     06-06 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-STRATEGIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NARROWING THE ELECTRONIC NEWS GULF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was noontime on the East Coast on Thursday, and in one office
after another, workers headed to their usual lunch spots on the
World Wide Web _ abcnews.com, cnn.com, msnbc.com, nytimes.com,
usatoday.com, washingtonpost.com, yahoo.com. The special on all
these menus was peace.
</P>
<P>
   But the news that the Serbian leader, Slobodan Milosevic, and
the Serbian Parliament had accepted NATO's terms was being served
up very differently. On CNN Interactive and msnbc.com, articles
with original material were offered, along with the promise of live
video and audio coverage of President Clinton's comments on the
agreement. On The Washington Post's site, posted at 11:42 a.m., was
an article by Candice Hughes, the Associated Press correspondent in
Belgrade. The New York Times on the Web also offered Ms. Hughes'
report.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, wire service dispatches are still the main
ingredient of 24-hour news coverage on the World Wide Web, as far
as newspapers are concerned. The television sites, meanwhile, have
become their own wire services, mixing wire material with their own
reporters' information, putting one report after another on the
counter, sometimes with audio and video on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, however, that great divide _ between the once-a-day
multicourse meal of original material served up by newspapers on
the Web and the quickly changing menus of original fare of the
cable and broadcast sites _ is beginning to narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are beefing up their staffs of online journalists and
getting into the multimedia business; on Thursday afternoon, The
New York Times on the Web featured audio clips from key spokesmen.
And they retain their goal of depth. The Web sites of newspapers
like The Times, The Washington Post, The San Jose Mercury News
(with its ``Kosovo Watch'') and The Star Tribune of Minneapolis
(with links to other news and Balkan-related sites and a plethora
of multimedia material, including a snapshot of the key weapons
involved) had large packages available to those who had the time to
explore them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the television sites are trying to provide the
depth that is the newspapers' stock in trade; CNN.com, MSNBC.com
and ABCNews.com all featured full packages with graphics, maps and
extensive background material on the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Joining them in the hunt for online news fanatics are wire
services like The Associated Press, Reuters and Bloomberg News, the
financial news service that has gradually added general fare. Of
all the news organizations, they can best adapt to the
instantaneousness of the medium and its 24-hour cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to be at Bloomberg is a hybrid,'' said
Matthew Winkler, editor in chief of Bloomberg News, which feeds its
dispatches onto the Web site bloomberg.com. ``The appetite for
information on a real-time basis is growing. So there has to be
something esthetically that appeals to the reader of a great
newspaper or magazine but needs the staccato delivery of a
real-time news service. That is the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Television news organizations, particularly 24-hour news
channels, are well suited to the business of staccato delivery.
``What we do on the Internet is what we do on television,'' Mark
Bernstein, the general manager of CNN Interactive, said. ``That is
to pull the most appropriate, the most relevant, the most accurate
content from all the sources available to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same way we'll rely upon Christiane Amanpour,'' he
continued, ``we'll also rely on what we can get from AP and Reuters
and other CNN correspondents.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN has about 110 writers who contribute their material only to
cnn.com, he said, and they put in at least 100 updates a day. The
operation works 24 hours, but the staff is largest during regular
working hours _ the period when the site receives 75 percent of its
visits because people have high-speed access to the Internet
through office computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately,'' Bernstein said, ``we inherited a culture of
putting out the news when it happens. Newspapers continue to
struggle with what to do _ if they get the story at 2 in the
afternoon, do they put it on their Web site?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not. By early Thursday evening, The Wall Street
Journal's interactive edition was featuring the same article,
written by a Journal newspaper staffer, about the peace agreement
that would run, in substantially the same form, in Friday's
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The site of The Chicago Tribune has 30 news staffers, but it,
like most newspaper sites, was running with Ms. Hughes' Associated
Press story Thursday afternoon. It is not that The Tribune has
decided to be shy about putting original material on its site
during the day. Witt and his colleagues simply believe that _ even
though more than 50 percent of their visitors come from outside
their Midwest circulation area _ what they can do best is cover
breaking Chicago news because that is where their resources are
concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   So on Friday, a reporter for The Tribune's Web site went to the
meeting of the Chicago City Council along with a reporter for the
newspaper. The story was pure theater: Jerry Springer, the
television talk show host, was going head to head with elected
officials over the violence on his shows.
</P>
<P>
   That scene, Witt said, was superbly geared to the Internet. The
exchanges became increasingly quotable, so the Web reporter filed
two or three updates during the afternoon to a rewrite person back
at the office, who wrote the account that was posted and updated,
while technicians worked to put the audio recording of the event up
on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly back to the future,'' Witt said. ``The Chicago
Tribune used to have five or six editions. We had the classic
situation: `Hello, darling, get me rewrite.' All we're doing now is
putting this newspaper back in the business it used to be before it
became a one-edition newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   What do the readers want? Judging by the ratings compiled by
Media Metrix Inc., which measures Internet use, they prefer the
fast-food approach of the television sites. MSNBC.com and cnn.com
both have at least 80 percent more unique _ or different _ visitors
than usatoday.com, the most-visited newspaper site.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a story is developing,'' said Rich Jaroslavsky, managing
editor of The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition, the
principal interest of the visitor is, `` `Tell me what's happening.
Right now, I don't have the time to spend exploring all the bells
and whistles.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the perspective and depth that newspapers provide, he said,
do not necessarily have to wait until the middle of the night, when
many newspaper sites post much of the next day's paper.
</P>
<P>
   The once-a-day delivery of news, Jaroslavsky pointed out,
evolved after newspapers found they were unable to compete with
radio and television in the race to be the first to deliver
information. The publications then sought out a new niche, offering
depth, interpretation and context that broadcasters found hard to
match.
</P>
<P>
   The Web, he said, eliminates the rationale for that strategy.
``When newspapers ceased to be the source of actual news,'' they
sought depth, he said. ``The Web allows newspapers to do both _ to
be competitive on a time basis with television, and to provide
perspective as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
