<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `LABOR ASSISTER' AND OTHER ODDS AND ENDS FOR MOMS AND DADS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: China, Fla., Calif.)   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the first forceps were invented in the 17th century,
childbirth has been a fertile field for innovation. In this
century, pregnant women have been helped _ or, some have argued,
hindered _ by an explosion in new gadgets and procedures, ranging
from epidurals to contraptions for exercising the pelvic muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Novatrix, &UR;  &LR; a small company in Carlsbad, Calif., hopes that its
``labor assister'' will be the biggest thing in the hospital
delivery room since the advent of the fetal heart monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The labor assister, for which Novatrix recently received its
third patent, was initially conceived by Dr. Minying Gai, a Chinese
obstetrician who trained at Columbia University and who now
practices in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was looking for a way to reduce the incidence of
C-sections as well as births that require vacuum-extraction and
forceps,'' said John R. Bason, president of Novatrix.
</P>
<P>
   The device essentially mechanizes a practice that has been used
for centuries by midwives during the pushing stage of labor. Using
this technique, known as ``fundal pressure,'' the midwife presses
down on the top of the abdomen as the laboring woman begins a
contraction.
</P>
<P>
   The labor assister is essentially an inflatable plastic belt
that straps around the top of a mother's belly and plugs into a
tocotransducer, a machine that normally reads and graphs uterine
contractions and also monitors the fetal heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   When the laboring woman contracts, the transducer records a
change in pressure. This causes a valve to open so that a bladder
within the belt inflates for 30 seconds, exerting downward pressure
on the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bason, a study of 160 patients in China in 1992
showed that the device reduced the incidence of instrument-assisted
delivery by 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The device has not yet been approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration, but Bason contends that the potential market for
the device is $300 million a year in the United States, Canada and
Europe. Novatrix, which has $7.2 million in venture capital, is
currently conducting a patient study at five sites in the United
States and Britain. It hopes to submit data from that study to the
FDA next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company's patent for this device is 5,871,499. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Helping Eliminate Stretch Marks
</P>
<P>
   Are stretch marks inevitable? Dr. Kamran Ghodisian, an
obstetrician in Newport Beach, Calif., thinks not.
</P>
<P>
   Ghodisian's solution to postpartum seersucker skin is a thin
sheet of adhesive-backed, breathable polyurethane that is stretched
over the belly midway through the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   This membrane ``effectively neutralizes the forces of the
elastic and collagen fibers of the healthy dermis areas and
prevents the impaired areas from being stretched out,'' according
to the patent.
</P>
<P>
   After the baby is delivered, the membrane is peeled off,
supposedly revealing a striation-free stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Ghodisian is currently conducting tests with the membrane. He
received patent 5,755,680.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple Crib For Multiple Births
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of fertility treatments, multiple births are on
the rise. In response to this trend, Robert A. Butnick of Newport
Beach, Calif., has patented a crib for more than one infant.
</P>
<P>
   Butnick's larger-than-normal twin crib features a plexiglass
divider down the middle so that two babies may occupy it. A triplet
crib features two plexiglass dividers so that it may accommodate
three babies. The plexiglass allows the babies to see, but not
jostle, each other, according to the patent.
</P>
<P>
   Butnick received patent 5.787,524.
</P>
<P>
   A Gift Pack For Fathers-to-Be
</P>
<P>
   Not all childbirth inventions are for moms. Ashley Svopa, a
special education teacher in Coral Springs, Fla., patented an
``expectant father system'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``New fathers never get anything,'' Ms. Svopa said. ``After I
delivered, the baby and I got all the attention. My husband felt
left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Svopa's ``system'' is a kit, containing items both useful
and frivolous, that is meant to accompany the Dad-to-be to the
hospital. It includes such items as eye drops, fresh underwear, a
book for phone numbers of relatives and friends, a personalized
phone card, candy bars and cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Svopa has sold about 50 of her kits through word of mouth.
She is hoping to license patent 5,908,108.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
