<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hot and humid air will surge toward the northeast coast as winds
from the west become gusty at times. By afternoon, abundant
sunshine will boost temperatures to near record levels from eastern
Pennsylvania and New York to southern New England. Over the
Appalachians, some puffy cumulus clouds will help keep temperatures
a few degrees lower, but daytime readings will average 10 to 15
degrees above seasonal values.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will remain strong over the southeastern states,
helping to suppress the typical pattern of scattered afternoon
thundershowers over much of the region. Nevertheless, some
thunderstorms will form near the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico coasts
where converging winds from sea breezes help lift the sultry air.
Otherwise, most areas will have ample sun mixed with clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Heat and high humidity will persist from the southern Plains to
the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley ahead of a weak cool front.
Scattered thundershowers will develop as the front makes slow
progress to the east in the afternoon. A few potent thunderstorms
will develop over western Texas and Oklahoma late in the day. In
the wake of the front, less humid air will arrive in the northern
Plains and northern Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of unseasonably cool air masses will
spread over the northwestern states. Areas of clouds and showers
will be common especially near the coast and over the higher
terrain from the Cascades to the northern Rockies. Meanwhile, the
Southwest will be sunny with seasonal heat.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Positive Lightning
</P>
<P>
   All lightning is dangerous, but the first strokes in a storm may
be the most powerful of all. Lightning results when a difference in
electric charge in the atmosphere overcomes the resistance of the
air. Most thunderstorms have positive charges near the top and
negative charges at the bottom. Strong high-level winds can cause
the thunderstorm to tilt, with the positive charges drifting to the
front of the storm. Thus, the first strokes tend to lower positive
charges to the ground. Measurement of electric currents show that
these positive bolts can be twice as strong as negative lightning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
