<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGS-ADVENTURE-TRAGED     06-06 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGS-ADVENTURE-TRAGEDY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH IN THE GREAT OUTDOORS MAKES MONEY FOR MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When John Rasmus, the editor in chief of National Geographic
Adventure, introduced his magazine this spring, he was pleased to
include an article titled ``Trouble in Shangri-La'' about a
kayaking expedition in Tibet that ended in the death of a research
chemist from Salt Lake City. In the second issue, Rasmus had an
article investigating the deaths of cave-diving enthusiasts in
Florida. And in the coming issue, he hopes to have an article about
George Mallory, the explorer whose body was found on Mount Everest
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the literature of adventure tragedy, or the art of the
yuppie expedition gone wrong. Whatever it is called, this brand of
nonfiction writing not only makes writers happy _ because many of
the articles are transformed into books or movies, with concomitant
advances and options often accumulating into the millions of
dollars _ but it also sells magazines, publishers acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Now, mainstream magazines like Vanity Fair and even a spinoff of
Maxim magazine, Stuff, are taking a cue from their adventuresome
colleagues like Mariah Media's Outside, and Men's Journal, which is
published by Wenner Media, and are featuring more stories from the
pantheon of high-end tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Vanity Fair, which is published by the Conde Nast
Publications unit of Advance Publications, ran Bryan Burroughs'
``Death at Sea: Behind the Scenes at an Ocean-Sailing Race Gone
Terribly Wrong,'' while Dennis Publishing's Stuff magazine carried
a feature by a hiker titled ``Reality Bites: I Saw My Wife Get
Killed By a Bear'' in its second issue, which came out two weeks
ago. (The article reads in part: ``When its stomach was cut open,
they only found bits of Christine's clothing; he hadn't begun
eating her.'')
</P>
<P>
   The literature of the adventure-gone-wrong has been a popular
genre with readers since Homer, and was carried on by Jack London
and Hemingway, but in its contemporary incarnation it picked up
steam in 1996, the year that seven people died on Mount Everest.
The same year, Sebastian Junger, a then-struggling free-lance
writer in the East Village, decided to get book publishers
interested in his manuscript about a swordfishing boat that sank
with a crew of six in 1991 by selling it first as an article to
Outside magazine. A year later, the resulting book was on the
best-seller lists and Junger was on the ``Oprah Winfrey Show.''
Since then, a month rarely goes by when consumers cannot spot a
headline like ``Avalanche: A Survivor's Story'' or ``Murder of a
Mountain Man,'' both from recent issues of Men's Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Why are American readers suddenly so voyeuristic, and so eager
to participate in the extreme-sports version of highway
rubbernecking? The answer, Junger said, is the fat-cat American
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a culture, we're bridling at the amount of safety and
luxury we have,'' Junger said. ``The 1980s was about all this
wealth and opulence, and it seems we're sated with that. Now
there's a whole new esthetic of being fit and adventuresome and
everyone has to canoe down something.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Lapham, the editor of Harper's magazine and a longtime
cultural observer of the magazine industry, says that the
fascination with disaster sells magazines. Witnessing a tragedy
befalling another human being ``is traditional tabloid fare,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sells,'' Lapham said. ``And the glossier magazines are just
taking the tabloid notion and dressing it up in better product.''
</P>
<P>
   Sell it does. When Outside magazine published a long-hyped
article by Jon Krakauer about the deaths on Mount Everest, the
magazine doubled its average newsstands sales: The October 1996
cover featuring Krakauer's piece sold 150,000 copies on the
newsstand, compared with an average of about 80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Terry McDonnell, editor of Men's Journal, says sales jump when
the magazine runs a particularly chilling adventure article. For
example, the December/January cover featured ``Avalanche: A
Survivor's Story''; it sold 99,000 copies on the newsstand, about
12,000 more than the average of 87,820 for the preceding six
months, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus of National Geographic Adventure said: ``We are going to
do as many of those stories as we can.'' He added that the Tibet
piece generated a ``tremendous response.''
</P>
<P>
   And not only did readers respond to the article, but so did
other outlets: The writer, Michael McRae, signed a deal with Random
House's Broadway Books division, to write a book based in part on
the article. One of the expedition's survivors, Ian Baker, also
signed a book deal with Random House for $500,000. And ``National
Geographic Explorer,'' a companion television program to the
National Geographic Society magazines, ran a segment on the death
of the kayaker, showing the soul-chilling videotaped footage of the
moment he sank beneath the rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus of National Geographic Adventure sees the growing body of
literature not as voyeurism, but as a kind of warning device.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are important stories, and we try to make them
instructive in terms of what went wrong, what could have been
prevented,'' Rasmus said. ``Every time someone dies, there's an
automatic response: It was a freak accident. There's an
institutional form of denial about risk that we need to be aware
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see the growing trend as a degeneration of a once-great
art form. Mark Bryant, the former editor of Outside, said, ``I see
a lot of would-be adventure stories that are being published right
now that might not have ever been published if not for the success
of authors like Krakauer and Junger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure that we don't become ambulance chasers,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the ambulance chasing is evident. Earlier this year,
adventure-travel agencies across the country received phone calls
from a researcher at Outside magazine who was trying to unearth
unreported stories of tragedy on the adventure trail. Hal Espen,
the editor of Outside, explained that the researcher was asked at
the behest of an editor no longer employed by Outside to find a
guide who had dealt with some form of tragedy on a trip he or she
was leading. The article, which never materialized, would have been
a psychological profile of a guide who had led clients to their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a subject we're wrestling with,'' Espen said. ``We have
to measure the almost voyeuristic view of tragedy against our
obligation to be authoritative and a genuine voice and a genuine
source of reference for people.''
</P>
<P>
   And new outdoor-enthusiast magazines continue to appear. This
year alone, new titles include National Geographic Adventure, Women
Outside and Outdoor Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Madden, the editor in chief of Outdoor Explorer
magazine, which is published by Times Mirror Magazines, said that
the genre was already overextended and that for that reason he
would not run articles that end in death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fond of saying that nothing dies in Outdoor Explorer,''
he said. ``Fish don't die. Deer don't die. Climbers don't die. That
end of the category is incredibly crowded. There are way too many
of those stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about the mellower, more fun aspect of adventure. We're
not about the death march.''
</P>
<P>
   And Espen of Outside predicted that the trend would soon reverse
itself. ``Watch the sales of sports utility vehicles as an index to
when it will cease,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
