<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-ACER-ART-NYT &LR;      06-06 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-ACER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM EXPANDS ITS MARKETING OF TECHNOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM plans to announce an $8 billion technology sales agreement
Saturday with the Acer Group of Taiwan, representing another big
step in IBM's accelerating effort to market its leading-edge
technology to companies that are often its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Acer, spanning seven years, is the fourth
large computer parts deal for IBM in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo Inc. said last month that it would purchase $1 billion
worth of IBM's Power PC microprocessors to run its next generation
of video game machines. In March, the EMC Corp., an IBM rival in
storage systems for big computers, announced it would purchase $3
billion of IBM disk drives over five years. Also in March, the Dell
Computer Corp. said it planned to buy $16 billion of technology
components from IBM over the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of recent deals are the result of the strategy
pursued by Louis V. Gerstner Jr., IBM's chairman, of increasingly
marketing the company's technology to other companies in the
computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, IBM's famed research laboratories and its vast
network of manufacturing plants were dedicated to the single
mission of supplying Big Blue.
</P>
<P>
   But that tight vertical integration tended to make IBM insular
and slow-moving. Even before Gerstner arrived in 1993, the company
had taken some tentative steps to market its technology outside its
walls. But the push began in earnest in 1995 with the disk drive
business and then became a key element in IBM's plan for growth
last year, after Gerstner ordered a high-level rethinking of the
company's approach to outside technology sales.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-person task force spent six weeks on the study, which
was submitted to Gerstner last June. It concluded that IBM had a
``fantastic growth opportunity selling technology,'' but it also
cautioned that IBM should be selective as a technology supplier to
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, the study said, must focus on sizable markets in which the
company has a clear technological advantage and where IBM's lead is
judged to be sustainable, to insure fairly high profit margins.
Such technologies, the study noted, include specialized disk drives
able to store more data in a smaller area; fast microchips that
consume less power; and advanced liquid-crystal displays used in
notebook computers.
</P>
<P>
   This approach to the technology supply market has been called
``IBM Inside,'' a nod to the ``Intel Inside'' campaign and a
recognition that supplying crucial technology can be a lucrative
business _ as it has been for the Intel Corp., whose
microprocessors are the electronic brains of most personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, industry analysts say that IBM earns more profit from an
Apple Powerbook _ equipped with a disk, display screen and Power PC
chip from IBM _ than Apple earns from the same product.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, to step up the pace of technology sales, Gerstner
placed a handful of IBM's business divisions into what he called
the Technology Group and put James T. Vanderslice, former head of
the disk drive unit, in charge. Under the reorganization,
Vanderslice oversees the company's disk drive, semiconductor,
networking hardware, printers and display businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The technology group's mandate includes working closely with
IBM's research division to tap its know-how and quickly
commercialize innovations. ``The whole idea is to put IBM's
technology portfolio into the marketplace as soon as we can,''
Vanderslice, a senior vice president, said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Even before last year's reorganization and this year's deals,
the emphasis on selling the company's technology to outsiders had
helped fuel growth in those businesses. Since 1995, the businesses
now in IBM's technology group have grown 22 percent a year. And
Gerstner has said that the technology group, along with services
and software, is expected to be one of the engines of IBM's growth
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the technology supply deals is IBM's continuing
investment in research. The technologies that other companies are
buying today were nurtured in IBM's labs for years. Its pioneering
disk drive technology, for example, dates back to research on
``giant magnetoresistance,'' a phenomenon first discovered in 1988
by French scientists at Universite Paris-Sud in Orsay.
</P>
<P>
   But the phenomenon was thought to be mainly a scientific
curiosity, observed only at very low temperatures, until
researchers at IBM Almaden labs in San Jose, Calif., figured out
how to commercialize the technology to pack far more data on disk
drives than previously thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paradox is that to be good at bringing industry-leading
technology to market you need long-term research programs to pick
up new ideas,'' Paul M. Horn, senior vice president for research,
said recently. ``And then the speed comes from fuzzing the
boundaries between your labs and your business.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying ahead technologically is essential if its strategy is to
succeed. ``As long as IBM can be at or close to the leading edge,
the strategy makes sense,'' said David Yoffie, a professor at the
Harvard Business School, ``because it spreads its comparatively
high fixed costs of research and manufacturing over a much larger
customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Dell agreement, the Acer deal covers a broad set of
technologies including disk drives, liquid-crystal displays and
specialized microprocessors. IBM and Acer, a major PC maker,
already have an existing supply relationship, but the new pact
expands their arrangement considerably. In addition to the $8
billion in components that Acer is expected to purchase from IBM
over seven years, IBM will likely buy $1 billion in displays from
Acer, using technology licensed from IBM last year.
</P>
<P>
   Acer plans to use IBM's Power PC microprocessor to develop
Internet appliances, like handheld devices and set-top boxes, to be
marketed mainly in Asia during the next few years, according to
Acer executives.
</P>
<P>
   Such a broad technology supply deal with IBM, a rival in the PC
business, would have been unthinkable a few years ago, Acer
executives say. ``The mindset of IBM has really changed,'' said
Stan Shih, chairman of Acer. ``It is much more open-minded and
easier to partner with than it used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
