<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORSICA-FRANCE-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENCE MOVEMENT IN CORSICA MAKES FRANCE UNEASY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AJACCIO, Corsica _ A gentle breeze from the Mediterranean cools
the cafes along Napoleon Boulevard, which is named, of course, for
the island's most famous son. People are heading for the unspoiled
beaches. A happy springtime scene, perhaps, were it not for the
angry graffiti on Ajaccio's historic walls.
</P>
<P>
   They are code words left by separatists who are fighting to gain
independence or greater autonomy from France. For all the beauty of
its wild mountains and ravishing bays, the island gets more
attention in Paris for its bombings and killings.
</P>
<P>
   Corsica, France's most uneasy spot, is a place of
contradictions. Proud of their culture, the young people often
migrate to the mainland. With Corsicans largely dependent on
tourist income, the rebels regularly blow up villas and hotels
owned by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   And while 85 percent of Corsicans say in polls that they want to
remain part of France, the island's tumultuous politics are
dominated by the nationalists. Old Corsica had pirates, men with
bandannas and daggers. New Corsica has guns and firebombs. Its
unruly ways have exasperated France off and on since 1768, when it
bought the island from the city-state of Genoa.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the 25-year old nationalist violence has turned
particularly ugly. In February 1998, rebels killed Claude Erignac,
who as prefect was the French government's top official on the
island. Bernard Bonnet, his successor, was sent by Paris to impose
law and order. But in early May he was dismissed and arrested after
police under his authority burned down an illegally built beach
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corsica can drive people crazy,'' an official from mainland
France said. As Bonnet was jailed in Paris pending an
investigation, the French establishment was stunned. This was the
first arrest of a serving prefect, and for three weeks fights over
Corsica policy dominated the National Assembly. Such was the
atmosphere of crisis that Corsica was even overshadowing Kosovo in
national newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The cases involving the two prefects seem to have deepened the
distrust between Corsicans and most other French people. It has
convinced many Corsicans that France has lost all respect for them.
And it has tested the patience of mainland French citizens, whose
tax money seems to pour endlessly into Corsica without bringing the
island any closer to peace.
</P>
<P>
   But the mainland French also remain fascinated by that ``curious
mix of shepherds and bomb throwers,'' as the writer Jean d'Ormesson
called the islanders. The mainlanders love the island's haunting
music and medieval villages. But they rarely buy an island home or
business these days for fear of the nationalist bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Most Corsicans do not appreciate the image that a few militants
have created for them. ``We are not the savage hordes Paris makes
us out to be,'' said Jean-Guy Talimoni, a leader of Corsica
Nazione, an alliance of nationalist groups. ``The problem is that
the French haven't understood Corsicans. They just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``it'' varies, depending on who is articulating local
demands _ or throwing explosives. For the 250,000 inhabitants,
there are no fewer than 14 political parties or movements and at
least three clandestine armed factions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these groups agree that France should formally recognize
Corsica as a separate people, with its own culture and language, a
dialect of Italian. Some want the weak regional parliament to gain
more powers, including the right to adopt its own laws and spend
its own taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a mountain in the middle of the Mediterranean,'' said
Cesar Filippi, a hotel owner. ``So we need our own rules and our
own special tools to develop. But Paris wants to keep us poor, to
make sure we stay French.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not how the French government sees it. France's
centralized political system does disapprove of regional
aspirations. Even now, it lags behind the rest of Western Europe in
recognizing minority rights. But it has made some exceptions for
Corsica.
</P>
<P>
   To placate the nationalists, France has offered tax breaks and
sent more subsidies to the island than to any other region. But it
also asserts that much of this aid vanishes into the pockets of
corrupt politicians.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bonnet's mission at the time of his appointment last year was
not only to find Erignac's killers but also to clean up corruption
and to restore the rule of law. More than $100 million of bad loans
were outstanding at a local government bank.
</P>
<P>
   There was evidence that organized crime was growing and hiding
behind so-called political and separatist attacks. Bonnet's orders
from Paris were to be tough.
</P>
<P>
   His hard-line approach quickly brought results: Bomb attacks
last year dropped to 96 from the recent totals of 200 to 400 a
year. Armed robberies were cut by more than half. Bonnet uncovered
close to 80 corruption scandals and had dozens of local politicians
and notables placed under investigation. With confidence returning,
the economy and tourism picked up.
</P>
<P>
   But the cleanup caused much resentment, even among the local
police. Operating on the premise that Corsica is a tight web of
clans and interest groups, Bonnet trusted few people and was
working with a specially created elite squad of security police.
</P>
<P>
   Five members of this squad have confessed to setting the fire in
April that burned down the illegally built restaurant. Such illegal
restaurants, of which there are a number, have regularly ignored
court orders to close.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, Corsica made new headlines when six men were
arrested and charged with killing the former prefect. They
apparently belonged to a new faction of hard-liners who say that
other nationalists have sold out. A seventh man, Yvan Colonna, the
suspected trigger man, is believed to be hiding in the wild
mountains that rise up behind his village of Cargese, some 30 miles
north of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad if this murder is solved, but there are many
others,'' said Fernande Pintrel, a member of a women's peace
movement. She was referring to the more than 100 unsolved political
killings of the last decade, among them that of her nephew, who was
shot dead while riding his motorcycle in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corsica cannot calm down,'' she said. ``We cannot have peace
until all the murders are investigated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
