<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      06-06 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(HLW)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Monday, June 7, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service day
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Kumonovo, Macedonia) _ Developments concerning the
talks on the Kosovo crisis. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   (With map; photo.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Ablright flew to Europe Sunday night for something of a victory
lap: to meet with her fellow foreign ministers on Kosovo, confer
with ethnic Albanian leaders, and perhaps visit several of the
countries affected by the misery of the war. But the victory lap
could be a risky mission and rather muted. The peace pact was not
yet a done deal by the time she left. (News analysis.) By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ What the Pentagon has to say
about what's holding up the talks on the border of Kosovo. By
Steven Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ With fighting still continuing
on Sunday between Serb forces and the ethnic Albanian Kosovo
Liberation Army on the border with Albania, NATO kept up its
bombing campaign and warned again that it would not stop until the
Serbs actually started moving troops out of the province. By Craig
R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On the Serb refugees
from parts of the Balkans. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Blace, Macedonia) _ In an indication of what
Serbs in Kosovo may face when Albanian refugees return, a gypsy
family is nearly beaten to death in a refugee camp after Albanian
refugees accuse them of having burned down their house. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Morini, Albania) _ The intention may be peace,
but war is raging as fiercely as ever along the rugged border of
Kosovo and Albania, forcing some 1,000 people from a northern
Albanian town on Sunday, many of them refugees fleeing from
fighting yet again. Military and aid officials said the surge in
fighting seemed not to endanger any peace plan but appeared to be
motivated by a simple logic for all three warring parties, NATO,
the Serbs, and the rebel group, the Kosovo Liberation Army. That
logic: to destroy as much as possible before a peace agreement is
signed. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALBOTT (Washington) _ A profile of Strobe Talbott; a
look at his role in helping to resolve the Kosovo conflict. By
David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (Paris) _ Investigators of the international
tribunal in The Hague are preparing to enter Kosovo together with
the multinational peace-keeping force to insure that they can
gather the freshest possible evidence of war crimes, tribunal and
Western officials said. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REACT (Undated) _ What the American people think
about an end to the fighting. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 or (212) 556-1927: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night supervisor is Sam Weiss.
</P>
