<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS WILL GLADLY TRADE `SCONES BOWL' FOR THAT CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hockey protocol being what it is, after the ear-throbbing cheers
and the hugs and the handshakes, there was a trophy to be presented
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Clarence S. Campbell Bowl looks like something the queen
would use to keep her day-old scones in. But as newly crowned
Western Conference champions, it now belongs to the Stars, and
captain Derian Hatcher had to report back to the ice to pose for
photos with it.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher did. The Reunion Arena crowd roared appropriately. But
then Hatch did an odd and very un-90s thing.
</P>
<P>
   He turned and skated off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't skate a victory lap with the big silver prize hoisted
high over his blonde locks. He didn't even hoist the thing and
shout, ``We da man!''
</P>
<P>
   At least somebody remembered to bring the Campbell Bowl into the
Stars' locker room. But once there, it was placed on a table
normally reserved for the Gatorade and went conspicuously
unnoticed. The ugliest girl at the party.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs and on the sidewalks around Reunion, there was a Mardi
Gras breaking out. But the Stars' quarters were oddly quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go into that dressing room, their focus is four more
games,'' head coach Ken Hitchcock had promised after the Game-7
victory over Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The journey is not done, the Stars were reminding us. When a kid
in Canada or upper Michigan is on a pond, dreaming about the day he
wins a hockey championship, he isn't skating around the ice with an
imaginary Clarence S. Campbell Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was such an stark contrast to the first time the
baseball Rangers clinched their first division title in 1996.
Champagne flowed in the Rangers clubhouse that night. Players broke
out foot-long cigars.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, thanks to the Yankees, the season was over and
Rangers management was wondering where all the champagne stains
came from.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano was right when he said that the Stanley Cup may be
the most difficult trophy to win in team sports. There are four
rounds to survive, for one thing. The winner will play for more
than two months. In the NHL's West, at least, there are time zones
to cross and long late-night flights to squirm through.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it was an arresting series. Seven intriguingly contested
games. Great players, making great plays, on both sides.
Game-saving goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   If the world didn't know as much as it should about the Stars'
Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk or Jere Lehtinen, it does now. The
series proved to be a baptism, of sorts, for a rising star named
Jamie Langenbrunner _ and an absolution for the veteran Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team deserved to lose. By Game 7, though, and with their
frequent flier mileage at Defcon Five, the Avalanche finally seemed
to run out of legs. Their nearly shotless second period Friday
night suggested that they were weary of the battle in the neutral
zone.
</P>
<P>
   The series with the Avs left Stars fans limp. The contrast of
styles and clash of wills had produced enchanting hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the hockey literati did not seem to be overly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   In writing why Hitchcock should not be the next coach of Team
Canada, Chris Young of the Toronto Star wrote, ``The Stars are like
the baseball manager who walks Mark McGwire with the bases empty .
. . They're a lay-up on a par five . . . Yes, the Stars are the
straitjackets of this Stanley Cup semifinal. Next to them, the Avs
look like one of \RPat\S Riley's Armani suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh. That tired argument again. One last time, therefore, for the
Toe Blake-impaired:
</P>
<P>
   The Stars finished eighth in the NHL in scoring this season (236
goals) and scored just nine goals less than that acknowledged
red-light machine, the Detroit Red Wings. The Maple Leafs scored an
NHL-high 268, yet only posted the Eastern Conference's fourth-best
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored 68 more goals than they allowed. They kill
penalties. They seize opportunities. They don't take foolish
chances, except perhaps in Game Fives of conference-final series,
in which case even a 7-5 result is entirely possible.
</P>
<P>
   They may have seemed a joyless lot to the Canadian and Eastern
media, but you probably wouldn't be giddy, either, if the door
prize was the queen's scones bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The journey is not done, the Stars reminded us last Friday night
in mid-Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   The next trophy is a dreamboat.
</P>
</TEXT>
