<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACING-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING RISKS PACKAGE 
AUTO RACING COMMUNITY WEIGH SPEED, SAFETY AND RISKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The list is as chilling as it is detailed,
and Steve Fried is fortunate that his name will not be added to it.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-six people have died at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
since 1909, a list divided into various categories: drivers (39),
mechanics (14), racing personnel (4), spectators (8) and
miscellaneous (1).
</P>
<P>
   Fried, the chief mechanic and right front tire-changer on the
pit crew of Indianapolis 500 rookie of the year Robby McGehee,
suffered head and chest injuries when struck by the wheel of a car
tossed back into his team's pit stall during last Sunday's race.
While awaiting word of Fried's condition, officials of the Pep Boys
Indy Racing League collectively held their breaths. And prayed some
more.
</P>
<P>
   IRL officials have been praying a lot since May 1, when a wheel
and other debris from a three-car crash flew over a 15-foot-high
fence into the grandstands during the VisionAire 500 at Lowe's
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C. Three spectators were killed and
eight injured, including a 9-year-old girl. The tragedy occurred
only nine months after three spectators were killed and six injured
by a wheel that flew off a car after it had struck a wall during
the Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series' U.S. 500 at
Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Either mishap by itself might have been dismissed as a fluke but
together they placed all of open-wheeled racing under a heightened
level of security heading into Texas Motor Speedway for the
Longhorn 500 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freak things happen,'' said Billy Boat, winner of the IRL
night race here a year ago. ``Racing has never been 100 percent
safe. The problem is that we saw a bit of a pattern developing, and
we had to do something to fix that.''
</P>
<P>
   All motorsports sanctioning bodies _ from the IRL and CART to
NASCAR to the National Hot Rod Association _ are locked in an
ongoing debate: how to balance the need for speed vs. driver and
fan safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took 30 horsepower from them now, and they'll get it
back,'' said IRL executive director Leo Mehl after announcing a
serieswide engine revs reduction last week. ``And I'll get 'em for
50 \Rhorsepower\S next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have basically in racing ... most people are obsessed
with this thing \Rspeed\S. If your job is to make the race car go
faster, and you've got a guy working 8-to-5, you'll fire him and
get somebody who won't sleep until he makes it go faster. That's
their job. At the same time, it's our job to think about the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL driver Greg Ray said, ``You want to be safe for the fans.
But there has to be some edge you can walk up to and balance on _
or even go beyond and come back to _ to differentiate yourself from
other teams and drivers. Speed is the easiest way to do that. I
race because I love the speed. There's no such a thing as `too
fast.' That's a driver's prerogative.''
</P>
<P>
   Technological advances have made today's varied race cars safer
than ever for the drivers, despite the advances in speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back at the cars I drove 15 years ago, I must have
been out of my mind,'' said Eddie Cheever, the 1996 Indy 500
champion who also has raced in CART and Formula One. ``And yet at
that point, that was the safest car you could get into.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers voluntarily assume a degree of risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't expect to hurt fans,'' said Houston's A.J.
Foyt, the first four-time winner of the Indy 500. ``A race driver,
we're no different than the people that sit up there. But none of
the race drivers ever want to see where they hurt a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehl said the IRL has been operating in a goldfish bowl since it
ran its first race in January 1996. Many of the major issues facing
founder Tony George's all-oval series have dealt with driver
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crisis situation in Charlotte was different than previous
situations,'' Mehl said, ``where the driver was the one being
hurt.''
REACTING EN MASSE
</P>
<P>
   In the five weeks since the incident at LMS, sanctioning body
officials and track managements swiftly implemented a series of
improvements designed to protect drivers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   CART's teams were required to compete with tethered suspensions
and front wheels for the first time during the Motorola 300 at
Gateway International Raceway on May 29. On Friday, CART announced
it will require tethers on the rear wheels of its Champ Cars before
the July 25 U.S. 500 at Michigan Speedway, the next oval race on
the CART schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The 83rd Indy 500 last week saw the debut of the IRL's
``suspension-and-wheel energy-management system'' that uses
restraining cables made with Zylon _ a high-tech fiber reportedly
with the strength of five tons. The system costs approximately
$2,500 per car.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the race in Fort Worth, IRL engine revs will be
limited to 10,000 RPM, down from 10,300 RPM. The reduction is
expected to trim 25 to 30 horsepower and approximately 3 mph off
speeds around the 1.5-mile quad-oval.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials _ mindful of their position as the nation's
fastest-growing spectator sport _ reacted by making ``cable
restraints'' available for the front wheels of its Winston Cup and
Busch Grand National cars at LMS last weekend. Made of braided
steel cable, the restraints are the sanctioning body's equivalent
of tethers. The entire 43-car field in the BGN Carquest 300
voluntarily used the restraints on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Speedway Motorsports Inc. are raising the front
stretch grandstand fencing at each of its four tracks that play
host to IRL events. The fences at Lowe's, Texas Motor Speedway,
Atlanta Motor Speedway and Las Vegas Motor Speedway are being
raised from 15 to 21 feet. Overhangs at the top of the fences also
are being increased from three feet to six feet to better contain
debris.
</P>
<P>
   For first time in the track's three-year history, TMS management
has decided not to sell seats in the first 10 rows during the IRL
race. ``It probably is a terribly conservative, cautious approach
to take,'' said Eddie Gossage, TMS' executive vice president and
general manager. ``But particularly for this event, we need to be
ultra-careful.'' The seating ban will be in effect whenever IRL
cars are on the track.
</P>
<P>
   The spectator deaths at Lowe's, formerly known as Charlotte
Motor Speedway, were the first in the 40-year history of the
1.5-mile track, owned by Bruton Smith and run with flair by
president H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really has been a tough thing for our company
emotionally, the moral obligation that you feel,'' Gossage said.
``We wanted to do everything we could possibly do, and then call on
the IRL to make changes to the cars. Combined, we feel like that
makes these cars very safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to reduce engine revs is a prelude to the IRL's
downsized 3.5-liter engine program scheduled to debut in 2000. It
will feature a loss of approximately 50 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, speed is a result of tires, aerodynamics and
horsepower,'' Mehl said. ``The engine companies started looking at
the situation right away. Our goal was to have our
suspension-energy-management system in place for the Indy 500, in
addition to an engine \Rrev\S reduction by the Texas race.''
WHAT ABOUT FENDERS?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in what would rank as a radical departure, Mehl said
the IRL is studying the viability of putting fenders on Indy cars.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, who must decide if the IRL will return to LMS next
season, was a proponent of such a change long before the crash at
his track. But even as a safety device, the notion largely has been
met by skepticism from open-wheel traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fenders? Why? What are you going to gain?'' said Mario
Andretti, a former Indy 500, CART and Formula One World Driving
Champion. ``The Indy-car is a single-seater, open-wheel car. It's
the purest form of a race car. You shouldn't deviate from that.
This thing about wheels flying around, I think it'll be handled by
the tethers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Rahal, a three-time CART champion and current team owner,
said he believes talk about adding fenders bordered on the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cars really can't be much safer than they are,'' said
Rahal, the 1986 Indy 500 winner. ``The gains that you're going to
make are infinitesimal. I mean, they may not look it, but they're
far safer than a Winston Cup car or anything else because of the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   John Menard, who fields Ray's IRL team and is part-owner of
Robby Gordon's CART team, said one of the obvious results of adding
fenders to Indy cars is increased speed via aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest aerodynamic drag on these cars is the wheels,''
said Menard, who lost top driver Scott Brayton to a fatal crash
during practice at Indy in May 1996. ``If we put fenders on them,
we would pick up I don't know, 30 mph. I think tethers go a long
ways to serving the same purpose as fenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehl said one of the considerations on fenders is increased
downforce. Another is increased debris after a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in any of these things, you've got to be extremely careful
you don't make the situation worse,'' said Mehl, who has been
involved in major-league motorsports since 1965. ``Covering the
wheels up in some manner to retain them, it's probably not going to
work for our form of racing. What we're trying to offer is a
different form of racing. The skills required to drive an
open-wheeled car 20 or 30 mph faster are different than the skills
required to run a stock car. We certainly would be reluctant to
give up that tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, the embodiment of open-wheel tradition, scored his first
Indy 500 victory in 1961, the year Tony Bettenhausen was killed in
a crash on the front stretch during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt scored his second Indy 500 victory in 1964, a race marred
by a fiery, front stretch crash that killed popular veteran Eddie
Sachs and rookie Dave MacDonald at the end of Lap 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Victory Lane photo from that day shows Foyt standing next to
his wife, Lucy, and the Borg-Warner Trophy. He is holding a dummy
newspaper with the headline, ``Foyt Winner in 500; Sachs, MacDonald
Die.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt said death in a race car apparently was more accepted in
that era, when the event was restarted and run to its conclusion.
And A.J. wound up celebrating in Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said after the race, it's not the kind of win I like,'' said
Foyt, 64. ``It was a sad deal, and I expressed my sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a good friend of mine once told me, `A.J., there's no
guarantee in life. The only square deal you got on earth is ``He
put us here, and He can come and take us.'' ' Stop and think about
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
