<SLUG> BC-CAR-WALL-RISKS-RACING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIO ANDRETTI ENDORSES SAFETY PRECAUTION THAT GOES WALL-TO-WALL 
RISKS OF RACING PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of drastically altering open-wheeled cars via the
addition of fenders, Mario Andretti suggests that available
technology be directed at another element of the speed vs. safety
equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the 21st century, maybe it's time for the \Rtrack\S
operators to look for energy-absorbing walls,'' said Andretti,
former Championship Auto Racing Teams and Formula One World Driving
Champion. ``By that, I mean you don't get rid of the concrete walls
that you have, but you put something in front of them. We've been
talking about that for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil they have it, and I assure you that can be so
beneficial to stock cars and open-wheel cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a system is in its second year of development at the
2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Last Sunday's 83rd Indy 500
was the first race run with the new PEDS-2 Barrier, an enhanced
version of the revolutionary energy-aborbing system installed last
May.
</P>
<P>
   The new Polyethylene Energy Dissipating System (PEDS-2) Barrier
is located on the inside of Turn 4 at the Speedway, the same site
as the original. Two-time Indy 500 champion Arie Luyendyk struck
the original PEDS Barrier with a stock-car style Pontiac Firebird
during the inaugural International Race of Champions event at IMS
last August. Luyendyk suffered a concussion in the heavy crash, but
credited the system with preventing more severe injury.
</P>
<P>
   Since that crash, a new, 12-inch-diameter secondary polyethylene
cylinder has been placed inside each of the existing 16-inch
cylinders in the barrier modules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wall will now better accommodate the safety needs of all
the vehicles that compete at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway,''
said designer John Pierce, retired engineer from GM Motorsports who
serves as a safety consultant to the Pep Boys Indy Racing League.
In addition to Indy-cars, IMS also will play host this year to
NASCAR's Winston Cup stock cars and the IROC machines. In September
2000, Formula One cars also will race counter-clockwise on a
portion of the front stretch at IMS _ near the barrier system.
</P>
<P>
   Each module contains overlapping polyethylene impact plates
fastened to 16-inch-diameter cylinders, with the new 12-inch
cylinders inside each of the larger cylinders. The upper portion of
the impact plate is folded over the top of the cylinders. Each
module is anchored to the concrete wall with the original vertical
steel cables and new horizontal cables.
</P>
<P>
   When the system was introduced last year, Speedway officials
said they were confident it might someday be applied around the
walls of entire racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the oval track operators put their minds to it,'' said
Andretti, the 1969 Indy 500 champion, ``I assure you they'll come
up with something that will be relatively inexpensive and will help
not only open-wheel cars but stock cars. We've got to look at
making those walls more painless. There's a way to do it that makes
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't we figure this out?''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
