A4948 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-CARS-RISKS-T     06-06 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-CARS-RISKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING INDY-CARS ON BANKED OVALS QUESTIONED 
RISKS OF RACING PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 24-degree banked turns at Texas Motor Speedway admittedly
were designed to accommodate full-fendered stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   But the best racing around the 1.5-mile quad-oval in Fort Worth
arguably has been put on by the open-wheeled cars of the Pep Boys
Indy Racing League the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've run very, very competitively at 220-plus mph here,''
said Eddie Gossage, executive vice president and general manager of
TMS. ``That's a show you don't want to take your eyes off of. I
kind of feel guilty selling fans a seat because they're standing up
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the wisdom of racing Indy-cars on high-banked ovals has
come into question since the tragedy at Lowe's Motor Speedway, TMS'
sister track in Concord, N.C., on May 1. Three fans were killed and
six injured when a wheel and assorted debris flew over a
15-foot-high catch fence and into the grandstands in the Turn 4
area after a three-car crash.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL is limiting engine revs to 10,000 RPM beginning with the
Longhorn 500 at TMS on Saturday night. That is expected to delete
approximately 25 to 30 horsepower from the normally aspirated
Oldsmobile Aurora and Nissan Infiniti V-8 engines.
</P>
<P>
   But should Indy-cars continue to compete on high-banked tracks?
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel icon Mario Andretti and three-time NASCAR Winston Cup
champion Darrell Waltrip were among the most prominent figures to
raise that question in the Lowe's aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a big difference racing on this racetrack \RTMS\S
vs. any other racetrack,'' said IRL driver Greg Ray of Plano. ``If
you have an impact and a piece flies off the car, why does it
matter if it's a banked track or not. ... Somebody's going to have
to show me a calculator with scientific measurements and physics to
say what's the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti is a former Championship Auto Racing Teams champion
whose son, Michael, won an active-series-leading 38th race on the
Gateway International Raceway oval in Madison, Ill., on May 29.
Mario Andretti said there that his comments immediately after the
Lowe's tragedy were misinterpreted. He said he was not targeting
IRL facilities. Andretti also has a problem racing Indy-type cars
at Brooklyn, Mich., and Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the speeds there _ 240 mph,'' Andretti said. ``I mean,
incredible. And they're still lifting \Rthe accelerator\S. On a
high-banked track \Rlike TMS\S, they'd run 250 mph. That's the part
that seems to be unreasonable. We're almost victims of the
technology that we know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have seen those tracks, where they spent
so much money, to have been a flat track where it could have been
so viable and so versatile going into the 21st century. We'd
\RCART\S love to be in Dallas-Fort Worth. It makes your heart bleed
that we're not there. It really does. But the tracks are built, the
money's been spent _ and nobody wants to hear some realities.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
