r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-RISKS-SAFETY-TEX     06-06 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RISKS-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY CHANGES FOLLOW DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at some of the most notorious accidents in racing
history, and changes that resulted: June 11, 1955: 24 Hours of Le
Mans, France
</P>
<P>
   Pierre-Bouillion Levegh's Mercedes 300 SLR, racing at
approximately 130 mph, hits another car, becomes engulfed in flames
and launches over a barrier into the crowd. More than 80 people are
killed and more than 100 injured. Race organizers refuse to cancel
the race, saying a mass exit of fans would have hindered rescue
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the wreck, several races were canceled around
Europe. An international outcry went out against auto racing, with
some politicians calling for its outright ban. Slight modifications
of the track and pit areas were made the following year.
May 24, 1964: Charlotte Motor Speedway
</P>
<P>
   Glenn ``Fireball'' Roberts is seriously injured in a fire when
his car hits the wall and the fuel tank explodes. Fellow drivers
pull him out of his car. He dies in July as a result of injuries
suffered in the crash. In the wake of the accident, the fuel cell
becomes commonplace in stock cars. Ironically, Roberts' car had a
more sturdy lining around the gas tank earlier in the season,
designed by car owner Ralph Moody. But NASCAR officials told him to
remove it because it was not an approved part. The tank held 22
gallons, was oval and made of fiberglass. After the wreck, NASCAR
permitted Moody to use the fuel cell.
May 24, 1964: Indianapolis Motor Speedway
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Sachs and Dave MacDonald are killed in a fiery fourth-turn
crash on the second lap of the Indianapolis 500. The wreck prompts
several changes in Indy-car racing, including:
</P>
<P>
   Firestone creates a fuel cell with an outside casing of either
steel or aluminum that has a thick rubber bladder and a low-density
plastic foam. The fuel tank capacity is also limited to 75 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Auto Club bans the use of gasoline in race
cars and switches to methanol, the same fuel used today. Methanol
is cleaner burning and does not ignite as quickly as gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   USAC also institutes a minimum weight rule of 1,250 pounds for
Indy cars. Today, IRL cars must weigh at least 1,585 pounds.
Fall of 1970: Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Drag racer Don Garlits loses part of his foot during an accident
with his front-engine Top Fuel Dragster. While recuperating,
Garlits designs the first rear-engine Top Fuel machine. He
introduced the design late in the 1970 season. Early in 1971, he
became the first driver to use a rear-engine car and win a National
Hot Rod Association event. All professional Top Fuel dragsters now
have their engine mounted in the rear of the chassis.
May 28, 1973: Indianapolis Motor Speedway
</P>
<P>
   Salt Walther is badly burned, 11 spectators are injured and 11
other cars damaged when Walther crashes down the front straight at
the start of the race. Rain red-flags the race until a restart on
May 30, when more tragedy occurs. On Lap 58, Swede Savage crashes
in Turn 4 after leaving the pits. Blazing fuel brings out a red
flag for 1:15. On July 2, Savage dies of injuries suffered in the
wreck.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the crashes, rule changes were made that
decreased the amount of fuel. Also, fuel tanks were switched to the
left side of the race cars, away from the retaining wall.
</P>
<P>
   Changes to the track included removing seats that were at track
level, with a second safety fence put up in front of the new first
row of grandstands. The inside and outside retaining walls were
raised to a uniform height of 32 inches, and the pit lane was
widened.
</P>
<P>
   1980-1982: Knoxville (Iowa) Raceway
</P>
<P>
   The half-mile dirt track known as the ``Capital of Sprint Car
Racing'' witnesses five fatalities in non-winged Sprint Car
competition during a three-year span. After the fifth fatality in
1982, Knoxville officials mandate the use of a 25-square-foot wing
on all sprint cars. The wing helps the cars ``stick'' to the track
and, if the car flips, acts as a shock absorber and preventing the
car from rolling.
May 1987: Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Allison's Buick becomes airborne and flies into the catch
fence at the 2.66-mile banked superspeedway. Allison escapes
unharmed. This was the same event where Bill Elliott set a one-lap
record for a stock car at faster than 212 mph. Allison's wreck
prompts NASCAR officials to slow the speeds of the cars on the
series' two superspeedways _ Talladega and the Daytona
International Speedway _ with the introduction of a carburetor
restrictor plate. The plate is placed in between the intake
manifold and carburetor. By restricting the amount of air taken
into the engine, it reduces horsepower from more than 700 to
approximately 420.
November 18, 1990: Atlanta Motor Speedway
</P>
<P>
   A crewman for Bill Elliott is hit and killed on pit road at the
Georgia track. Another crewman is injured in the same incident. For
the 1991 season, NASCAR mandates a maximum speed limit on pit road,
which varies with each track. That speed typically is at 55 mph.
July 1993: Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bonnett's car becomes airborne and hits the catch fence.
This incident, combined with other similar crashes, results in
NASCAR making roof flaps mandatory on stock cars.
Sept. 1, 1996: Indianapolis Raceway Park, Indianapolis, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Talented Top Fuel driver Blaine Johnson is killed in a wreck at
the quarter-mile asphalt dragstrip during the U.S. Nationals. In
the wake of the wreck, the National Hot Rod Association mandates
that all entrances and exits must be closed and flush all the way
down the drag strip. The height of the concrete barrier is raised
to 48 inches.
</P>
<P>
   July 26, 1998: Michigan Speedway, Brooklyn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Three spectators are killed and six injured after a tire off of
Adrian Fernandez's Champ Car launches into the stands over the
catch fence during the Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series'
U.S. 500. Later in the year, the fencing from the fourth turn to
the first and second turns in front of the main grandstand is
raised from 141/2 feet to 17 feet. The overhang on the fence is
also extended by four feet.
</P>
<P>
   May 1, 1999: Lowe's Motor Speedway, Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Three spectators are killed and eight injured after a wheel and
suspension pieces created by a three-car crash clear a 15-foot-high
fence and enter the grandstands during a Pep Boys Indy Racing
League event. An investigation of the incident by IRL and track
officials determined that a wheel off the car of Stan Wattles was
punted into the grandstands by the car of John Paul Jr. The
management of Speedway Motorsports Inc. subsequently announces that
the fences at SMI tracks playing host to IRL events, including
Texas Motor Speedway, will be raised to 21 feet and the overhang
increased from 3 to 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Also, both the IRL and CART mandate the use of tethers to keep
wheels and suspension parts connected to the open-wheeled cars
during a crash.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
