<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-RISKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR SAFETY RECORD NOTEWORTHY 
RISKS OF RACING PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rookie Casey Atwood was traveling 180 mph down the front stretch
at Daytona International Speedway in his Busch Grand National car
when he was tapped from behind. The car of Atwood, 18, went
sideways. Air began rushing under his car, and lifted it up. It
went airborne, landing on its roof. The car slid upside down for
about 200 yards in front of the main grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   Then he hit the grass, and the car began to flip. Once, twice,
three times, four times he barrel-rolled before coming to a rest on
the roof.
</P>
<P>
   It was a frightening crash, and spectators gathered for the
season-opening NAPA Auto Parts 300 feared the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, though, climbed out of his Chevrolet Monte Carlo, waved
to the crowd and walked to a waiting ambulance. At the infield care
center, he was treated for superficial bumps and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   He raced the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Wrecks are a part of virtually every NASCAR race. That's part of
racing in close quarters at speeds approaching 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Stock-car drivers know the risks, and still don't hesitate to
climb behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought about it, you wouldn't do it,'' said Ron
Hornaday, reigning champion of the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
that comes to Texas Motor Speedway this week for a race Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the inherent danger of the sport, NASCAR's safety
record is noteworthy. Major injuries happen but are rare. In
Winston Cup, stock-car racing's top series, there hasn't been a
fatality since 1994, when Neil Bonnett wrecked at Daytona
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main focus is to protect the drivers,'' NASCAR
representative Tim Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   That's primarily done with the welded steel rollcage that
surrounds the driver. The rollcage protects drivers when cars flip
out of control, as Atwood's did.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike open-wheel cars, which are built to break upon impact to
disperse energy, stock cars are designed with crumple zones that
cave and protect the integrity of the rollcage.
</P>
<P>
   Although safety measures lessen the risks of stock-car racing,
they don't eliminate them. Most serious injuries occur when a car
crashes into a concrete wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going faster and faster, and the walls aren't getting
any softer,'' said two-time Busch Grand National Series champion
Randy LaJoie.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
