r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DRAG-RACING-RISKS     06-06 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DRAG-RACING-RISKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAG RACING'S RAW POWER POSES OWN HAZARDS 
RISKS OF RACING PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An amazing number of things can happen during a four-second pass
down a quarter-mile drag strip, some of it out of control of even
the most experienced or bravest professional driver.
</P>
<P>
   That's because nowhere in motorsports is the release of raw
horsepower more instantaneous and more violent than in drag
racing's premier classes _ Top Fuel and Funny Car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have many crashes in our sport, obviously, because
we're racing in a straight line,'' said Kenny Bernstein, the only
driver to have won National Hot Rod Association Top Fuel and Funny
Car championships. ``If you're going to crash at any speed, it's
bad. At 320 mph, it's of a pretty good magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern, rear-engined Top Fuel Dragster and front-engined
Funny Car are powered by nitromethane-burning, 500-cubic-inch
engines that produce 6,000 horsepower. Top Fuel cars, which weigh a
minimum of 2,100 pounds, are the quickest-accelerating vehicles on
the planet _ capable of traveling from 0 to 100 mph in 0.8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each car has its own, what I call, hiccups,'' said Bernstein,
the winner of four Funny Car titles and in his 10th season of
wheeling the Budweiser King Top Fuel car. ``In Top Fuel, if the
front wings don't work right, the car has a tendency to fly over.
The Funny Car has a problem with fire. And both have problems when
they, at speed, hit the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of a drag race _ when all that horsepower is unleashed
through the transmission and drive line to the rear end and wheels
_ is a critical moment. A loss of traction off the line _
accompanied by the wrong split-second decision by the driver with
the throttle _ can send him or her into the wall or across the lane
into the path of the competing car.
</P>
<P>
   Top Fuel cars also get into trouble when the engine or
supercharger blows and stray metal cuts into the huge rear slick
tires like shrapnel. A flat rear tire on a Top Fuel car almost
invariably sends it into the wall. The same problem can occur if
the rear wing collapses under pressure, causing a loss of downforce
and steering control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Top Fuel car looks flimsy, but it's made that way to
transfer the power to the rear tires. It can't be stiff,''
Bernstein said. ``In a crash, these cars are built to absorb a lot
of impact. They keep the driver in the shell, the cocoon, to keep
him safe. The front end is capable of folding up and tearing away,
and the rear end is made to come apart and break away from the
driver.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
