<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-PECA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PECA IS HEART AND SOUL OF HARD-WORKING SABRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is what you need to know about Michael Peca:
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11, 181-pound Buffalo Sabres captain might well be,
pound for pound, the toughest player in the NHL. And last week, he
refused to carry around the Prince of Wales Trophy, the prize that
went to the Sabres for winning the Eastern Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't grow up working as a kid to hold the conference
trophy over your head,'' Peca said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   And for just about everything you need to know about the Buffalo
Sabres, who will be at Reunion Arena on Tuesday night to start the
Stanley Cup finals with the Stars, you can find in Peca.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the hero of the Sabres is Dominik Hasek, the all-star
goalie whom Wayne Gretzky called the greatest player in the world
this season. Hasek, the two-time defending league MVP will get the
chance to square off against his old Chicago Blackhawks teammate Ed
Belfour as both fight for their first Stanley Cup championship.
Indeed, the battle of goaltenders will loom large as experts try to
dissect the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Hasek is the Sabres' poster boy, Peca is their
conscience. Peca is the work behind the flash. Peca is the
blue-collar captain. In fact, the Sabres have built a team of Pecas
_ players who are tougher than they should be, who work harder than
opponent, who continue to surprise the NHL with every game of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They're even surprising their coach a little as they find
themselves with an NHL-best 12-3 record in the postseason despite
being the seventh seed in the East at the start of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see more grit, more speed and more determination, that's the
big difference in our team,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said. ``Last
year, I didn't think there were a lot of times when we dominated.
Throughout the playoffs \Rthis year\S, there have been periods
where we have dominated play. Last year, we survived. Now, we just
keep coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock has noticed the change and said his
team already has an idea of what the Sabres can do. Yes, Buffalo
finished with a 37-28-17 and 91 points _ 23 behind the Stars _ but
Hitchcock said that was due more to injuries than to lack of
talent. In the past two playoffs, the Sabres have gone 22-8,
advancing to the Eastern Conference finals last season before
bowing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got kicked really hard in Buffalo \Rduring the regular
season\S, and we left there thinking that they're basically a
younger version of ourselves,'' Hitchcock said of a 2-1 loss to the
Sabres on March 5. ``Of all the teams we played against in the
East, the two best teams, we felt, were New Jersey and Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres proved that by sweeping the second-place Ottawa
Senators in the first round of the playoffs, overcoming a groin
injury to Hasek in the second round against the Boston Bruins and
taking out the Toronto Maple Leafs in five games in the Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   While talk of Western Conference domination already has started
_ the West has swept the past three Stanley Cup finals _ Eastern
Conference coaches are warning the Stars that the Sabres are no
patsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in first place in January and then they had a lot of
injures,'' Maple Leafs coach Pat Quinn said. ``I think they were
underestimated by a lot of people, but they're playing great
hockey. The Joe Juneaus, the Geoff Sandersons, they've never
finished a check in their lives. But they're doing it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Juneau and Sanderson, skilled forwards with the Capitals and
Hurricanes, respectively, were late-season adds. But while they
were asked to bring in their goal-scoring skills, they were told
they couldn't do it in a soft manner.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Stars have turned Brett Hull and Mike Modano into
tough checking forwards, the Sabres have created a crew of
aggressive forecheckers. That's paid off in the playoffs, where the
Sabres average 3.3 goals per game and have an army of players who
can put the puck in the net. Curtis Brown has seven goals, Dixon
Ward six, Vaclav Varada five and Peca and Stu Barnes four apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view Buffalo as a carbon copy of us,'' Hitchcock said.
``They do a lot of the same things we do. And for us to be
effective, we need to be able to play four lines 5-on-5 and
forecheck well.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Stars will try to follow a similar game plan
that beat the Avalanche. The Stars want to avoid penalties, get the
puck deep, work it behind the Sabres' net, and play team defense by
not letting the talented players get possession of the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of quickness, a lot of guys who can scoot
around,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``That, and they've got
a great power play. What we have to do to combat that is stay
disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   And the first part of that discipline seems to be the mental
preparation to take on a Sabres team that will paint itself a huge
underdog. Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy said he thought the
Stars-Avalanche series might have been the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up in Buffalo, they're going to be reading a lot of statements
from players that they don't have a chance,'' Modano said. ``And
I'm sure they'll be using that as motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Modano said the Stars have time to get ready for the Sabres
and their sneak attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's no better team that prepares better for a game
than us and our coaches,'' Modano said. ``The way it's broken down
to minute details, there will be no overlooking anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Start with Michael Peca.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
