<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4955 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-76     06-06 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING CONTINUES ALONG BORDER OF KOSOVO AND ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ The intention may be peace, but war raged as
fiercely as ever Sunday along the rugged border of Kosovo and
Albania, forcing some 1,000 people from a northern Albanian town _
many of them refugees fleeing from fighting for at least the second
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that maybe the fighting would end'' with the
declared peace agreement between NATO countries and Yugoslav
leaders, said Xhavit Ibrahim, 46, as he packed his wife, parents
and seven children into a tractor wagon to escape the shelled town
of Krume. ``But we're still waiting _ just waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Military and aid officials said the surge in fighting seemed not
so much to endanger any peace plan but was driven by a simple logic
for all three warring parties _ NATO, the Serbs and the rebel
group, the Kosovo Liberation Army. That logic: to destroy as much
as possible before a final peace agreement is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, NATO B-52 bombers dropped what appeared to be
cluster bombs along hillside Serb positions near the border
crossing here. The bombs exploded with such force that curtains
fluttered in a cafe several hundred yards away.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombs fell _ along with thousands of propaganda
leaflets _ amid the roar of continued fighting between Yugoslav
soldiers and the Kosovo Liberation Army, whose members are massing
along the border waiting to enter Kosovo once Yugoslav forces
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Serbian soldiers stepped up their shelling of
Albanian border towns, dropping at least 10 shells into the town of
Krume, where hundreds of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo have
been living. The shelling, just before midnight, prompted a mass
exodus Sunday of scared refugees to the town of Kukes, some 10
miles from the border.
</P>
<P>
   Bjoern Kuehne, head of the Krume office of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, which monitors fighting along
the border, said Serbian shells had started falling now on
settlements not known to harbor any KLA fighters, such as Golaj,
Perollaj and Nikoliq, where two 14-year-old girls were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Before, he said, the shelling was contained to towns, like
Krume, where the guerrilla army is active.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much more indiscriminate than anything we ever had
before,'' Kuehne said. ``They seem to be trying to do as much
damage as possible as long as they are there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO officials warned the Serbs not to continue the
shelling, even as NATO has promised to continue its own air
campaign until there is hard evidence that Yugoslav forces are
withdrawing from Kosovo. Officials also reported looting in some
Kosovo towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, officials with the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe said they had no evidence that Serbian
soldiers were withdrawing from their border positions.
</P>
<P>
   But an official with the KLA, Masar Shala, said that five buses,
with mostly Serb civilians on board, left from the southern city of
Prizren toward Kosovo's capital, Pristina. Other trucks, some of
them military, left on the road toward Brezovica, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO planes appeared to strike the Kosovo border town of
Gorozhupe, which the Kosovar Albanian rebels claim to occupy in
part. The town was burning through much of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The planes also dropped leaflets with a photograph of the son of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, saying in Serbian that
he was sunbathing and ``dancing in his own disco'' as regular
Serbian troops suffered in the ``dust and blood of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fighting, the number of refugees crossing from Kosovo
through this border post, where the shelling is in plain sight,
slowed to only 82 people Sunday, according to the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees. The men said they had been held prisoner
and interrogated in the northern Kosovo town of Smrekovnica, near
Mitrovica. In the past two weeks, nearly 3,000 men who have said
they were held there have crossed into Albania here.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of deaths in any of the shelling in
Albania, though several houses were destroyed. But the refugees
left Krume all the same, stacking up mattresses and suitcases in
wagons as they fled for a second or third time to what they hoped
would finally be safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running just to save my life,'' said Zize Bozhdari, 74,
who was leaving Krume with her 29-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   An aid official said that some of the men leaving Krume faced
another obstacle: rebels from the KLA ``harassing'' them to join
the guerrilla force. In recent weeks, there have been several
reports of aggressive recruiting among the refugees.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the fighting is expected to die down in the coming
days, many refugees express a more long-term uncertainty about
NATO's plans to send them home.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that most of the NATO and other foreign troops
entering Kosovo will do so from Macedonia, rather than from
Albania, where the border with the Serbian province is mountainous
and roads narrow and poor.
</P>
<P>
   Military and aid officials are wondering what exactly that might
mean for the orderly flow of refugees back home, where they face
dangers from land mines, booby traps and a rough life with houses
and all amenities, including water supplies, destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   One major worry is that if few NATO troops arrive in Albania,
there will be little to stop the refugees from picking up and
leaving any time they deem it safe.
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials say they are planning education campaigns to
dissuade refugees from leaving early, but many worry that once NATO
is in Kosovo very little will hold people back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go alone if I know NATO is there,'' said one refugee,
Emine Berisha, 31, who left her 11-year-old daughter in Kosovo and
is worried about her safety. ``I will not wait for anyone to say,
`OK, you can go now.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
