<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTEBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' HITCHCOCK PLANNING TO CHANGE THE PRACTICE PACE BETWEEN
GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars made a mistake by giving players too
many days off between Games 6 and 7 of the Western Conference
finals, coach Ken Hitchcock said, and they've learned a lesson from
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one mistake we made is our players were really achy
because we gave two skates off for a lot of the players,''
Hitchcock said of not skating either Wednesday or Friday. ``We
didn't get rid of \Rthe lactic acid\S, so we're going to skate at
least twice before Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have scheduled practice today and tomorrow, and
Hitchcock will probably again make Tuesday's morning skate
optional. Ironically, only three regulars participated in the
morning skater _ Mike Keane, Joe Nieuwendyk and Blake Sloan. Keane
and Nieuwendyk were two of the Stars' best players Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres coach Lindy Ruff, whose team has been resting since
defeating the Toronto Maple Leafs in Game 5 on May 31, said he
doesn't expect the Stars to be tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into the finals, I don't think anybody is
tired,'' Ruff said. ``They're going to have three days to recover,
the excitement is going to be there. I don't think you can even use
having played a seven-game series to say that they are going to be
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will have home ice advantage because of their best
record (51-19-12) in the NHL during the regular season. The Stars
are 7-2 on home ice in the playoffs. The Sabres are 5-3 on the
road.
PICTURE PERFECT
</P>
<P>
   When Stars general manager Bob Gainey made the trade-deadline
deal that shipped Todd Harvey and Bob Errey to the New York Rangers
for Mike Keane and Brian Skrudland, Gainey knew that he was getting
playoff toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is a competitive player,'' Gainey said of Keane, who had
three goals in the Conference finals, including two in Game 7.
``When you get into a tug-of-war, like we have in this series, I
think you could use his play as a good instructional video. Not
only that he scored goals, but his shot blocking, his penalty
killing and his play along the boards. He had a terrific series,
his competiveness is clear for everyone to see.''
CENTER ICE
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said the battle of the Stanley Cup finals could
come down to a war at center ice. The Sabres' quartet of Mike Peca,
Curtis Brown, Brian Holzinger and Keith Primeau is as competitive
as the Stars have played, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as deep at center ice as any team we've seen,''
Hitchcock said. ``We never felt that we started with the puck the
last time we played them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Stars answer with a tough quartet of their own in
Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk, Guy Carbonneau and Brian Skrudland.
And Hitchcock said he will study the option of using the speedier
Tony Hrkac or Derek Plante to possibly replace Skrudland.
\Nsubheds:Special event
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said he felt best for Brett Hull after watching
the Stars celebrate the Western Conference championship Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a kid in a candy store,'' Hitchcock said. ``I've
never seen a guy with such genuine excitement in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who signed with the Stars as a free agent in the summer,
played his first two games as a rookie in the 1986 Stanley Cup
finals with the Calgary Flames. In 11 years with the St. Louis
Blues, however, he had not advanced past the second round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes you reach a mental state where you don't
believe anymore,'' Hitchcock said. ``You think you do, but in your
heart you really don't. But when this happened, I've never seen
anyone so happy in all my life.''
NOT SO BORING
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano kind of likes this role he's adjusted
to as a two-way forward. While critics have said the Stars are
boring for sapping the offensive light out of players like Modano,
he said yesterday that he's getting more and more used to defensive
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of exciting being out there killing penalties or
being out there for the last minute of the game taking faceoffs,''
Modano said. ``I think I get a lot more out of that nowadays.''
ALL'S FAIR
</P>
<P>
   During the final handshake with the Avalanche, Stars center Guy
Carbonneau made peace with Peter Forsberg and Sandis Ozolinsh _ two
of his most heated opponents in the series. Carbonneau said both
teams had yelled at each other and taken some liberties with sticks
and elbows.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I battled hard and I expect them to do the same, but
it's all in the heat of battle,'' he said. ``After the game is
over, you have respect.''
HAPPY BIRTHDAY
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher celebrated his 27th birthday in
Game 7 of the Western Conference finals. Stars center Mike Modano
will celebrate his 29th on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Other birthdays during the finals include: Rob Ray of the Sabres
on Tuesday at Game 1, Grant Marshall of the Stars on June 9
(Wednesday) and Darryl Shannon of the Sabres on June 21.
OLD PALS
</P>
<P>
   Stars goalie Ed Belfour and Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek each
were members of the Chicago Blackhawks from 1990-92 and even played
together in the 1992 Stanley Cup Finals. That's the only finals
experience for either goalie.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the only connection between the two teams. Stars
defenseman Darryl Sydor and Sabres defensemen Alexei Zhitnik each
were members of the LA Kings from 1992-95. Both were members of the
1993 Kings team that lost in the Stanley Cup finals to the Montreal
Canadiens. Ironically, Zhitnik and Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov
(Sydor's partner) also were teammates, but that was on CSKA in
Russia in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Pat Verbeek and Sabres winger Geoff Sanderson were
teammates on the Hartford Whalers 1990-95. Stars center Brian
Skrudland and Sabres defensemen Jason Woolley and Rhett Warrener
were teammates on the Florida Panthers team that lost in the 1996
Stanley Cup finals. Sabres defenseman James Patrick and Stars
defenseman Craig Ludwig were on the 1982 NCAA championship team at
the University of North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sabres winger Paul Kruse was coached by Ken
Hitchcock on the Kamloops Blazers in 1988-89 and Stars winger Grant
Marshall and Sabres center Mike Peca were teammates on the Ottawa
67s from 1991-93.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
