<HEADLINE>
A FANTASY BLUEPRINT, IF YOU DARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Wednesday night, the Los Angeles Dodgers plan to
walk out 3-year-old Rex Sjpute to sing the national anthem, which
will supposedly earn him a place in the Guinness Book of World
Records.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if Rex can actually walk the walk. Then there's the
chance day care might not wake him up from his nap in time.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's a fit end to the ``Think Blue'' week, the Dodgers'
attempt to make people forget about the other Fantasyland run by
the Disney competitors down the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you wanna drag the infield or take a drag off Kevin
Malone's cigar, the Dodgers can accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, almost.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfortunate that the homestand isn't any longer. Otherwise,
some of the good ideas that got passed over could have been added
to this year's list of activities. Ones like:
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy clean-up crew: Stay up with the gang until 3 a.m. as
they first sweep up, then hose down, all the stands. Learn the
secret of scraping nacho cheese off the bottom of the plastic
seats. Don't tip over that cup that looks like there's still some
beer left in it. And remember to turn into lost and found all the
loose change you collect _ wink, wink.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hurry down to the dugout and pick up each sunflower seed
shell. By hand.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy organ donor: As part of Fox's move to play more recorded
music, you rent a U-Haul and take Nancy Bea Heffley's prized organ
down to Goodwill for a donation _ and a nice tax write-off for
Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy member of Kevin Brown's family: Fly in on the jet from
Georgia, have ``Dad'' show you how to bust up a locker room toilet
after he ignores the media, then let him take you on a Toys R Us
shopping spree after the game. (Two special fans get to light $100
bills on fire with Brown in a pregame ceremony).
</P>
<P>
   Smell your favorite Dodger's game-used sliding pants: No
explanation necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy official scorer: A grounder to third goes off Adrian
Beltre's glove. So call it a hit. Except that'll mean Darren
Dreifort is charged with an earned run. So now what do you do?
Experience the dilemma that faces the Dodger Stadium official
scorekeeper each night.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy sportscaster: Sit in the Dodger Stadium working press
box with Stu Nahan, who'll show you how to openly root without
getting ejected. (See: Fantasy freeloader).
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy parking-lot attendant: Direct cars to the full lot way
down the Pasadena Freeway instead of that empty one right behind
the left-field pavilion held for season-ticket holders who aren't
coming anyway. Call in the tow truck for those double-parked morons
along the beltway. And if you want, start your own ``valet
service'' and see how many actually leave their prized car with
you.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy construction worker: When the season ends, you and five
friends get to help rip out a bunch of the blue seats on the
reserve level behind home plate and build a new press box for those
overworked sports writers. (Please bring proof of health
insurance).
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy translator: Listen closely to a postgame interview as
Rick Monday quizzes Chan Ho Park about the latest grand slam he's
given up _ then do your best to let the rest of us know what the
heck was just said.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy clubhouse kid: No worry about sorting out uniforms or
scraping mud off cleats or handing out canteens of creatine. The
most important task: Learn how to forge the entire team's autograph
on a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy umpire: Forget about working that fantasy softball game.
You put on the mask and chest protector and get to work an actual
inning of an actual game. Determine the strike zone. Feel free to
use the rule book as a reference.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy freeloader: Spend the day eating with Tommy Lasorda _
breakfast, lunch and dinner, plus a late-night snack. And you'll
never see the bill!
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy footrub: While you fill out the Dodgers lineup card,
Davey Johnson files down your corns.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy Farmer John pitchman: Can you convince us as well as Vin
Scully that a shank and butt portion of a pig is really succulent?
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy concessionaire: A little kid comes up and asks how much
for that Dodgers inflatable bat. Five bucks? 150 bucks? You make up
the price as you go along.
</P>
<P>
   Just go easy if it's Rex Sjpute trying to score one of those
dope blue caps with the silver bill. He'll probably be spent from
missing his nap to sing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
