<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA HOLDS FIRST FREE ELECTION IN 4 DECADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The world's fourth most populous country,
freed from the grip of its longtime dictator, marked a new era of
political freedom Monday with its first free election in four
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Across the 13,000 islands of this Southeast Asian archipelago,
some 130 million people cast their votes in a parliamentary
election that will start a complicated, months-long process of
choosing a new president.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the stage-managed elections of President Suharto,
who was forced to resign one year ago after 32 years in power, the
outcome of Monday's vote is utterly unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is an experiment, from the electoral laws to the
competitive campaign to the formation of coalitions to the voting
process itself, and the watchword among optimists is that Indonesia
may manage to ``muddle through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to bear with us,'' said Smita Notosusanto, who heads
a leading poll-watching group called Unfrel. ``This is our first
so-called free and fair election. We have never experienced this
before. We are like a little kid who just started their first day
in school.''
</P>
<P>
   At 300,000 polling places, from high-tech cities to remote
jungles, voters are electing 462 representatives who will join 38
military delegates to form a 500-member Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In August that Parliament will join 200 unelected members chosen
by provincial parliaments and by social and professional groups to
form an electoral assembly. Unless the timetable is shortened, the
assembly will choose the next president in November.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the parliamentary vote is only the start of a long struggle
for power in which closed-door deal making and money politics will
supplant democratic openness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indonesian election is really a five-month process, a
five-month continuous election day with ups and downs, with some
parts more public and some parts more private,'' said Adam Schwarz,
the author of ``A Nation in Waiting'' (1994), a political history
of modern Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   For many people here this messy process, with all its unknowns,
amounts to a battle over the soul of a future Indonesia, pitting
what are known as the forces of reform against the forces of the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The status quo is represented by Suharto's party, Golkar, which
still holds power and is fielding his former vice president, and
interim successor, B.J. Habibie, as its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The leading symbol of reform is Megawati Sukarnoputri, the
daughter of Suharto's predecessor, Sukarno. She is the candidate of
the conservative, nationalist Indonesian Democratic Party of
Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Her party seems prepared to form a coalition with the moderate
Islamic party of Abdurrahman Wahid. A secular party with a large
Islamic base, headed by Amien Rais, could emerge as a swing group.
</P>
<P>
   But around these big-name players, the country's politics, with
its 48 competing parties, swirls and surges with factions,
rivalries and hidden agendas.
</P>
<P>
   With Indonesia suddenly free to redefine itself after the
stultifying rule of Suharto, who took power after a military coup,
old struggles and suppressed conflicts are boiling to the surface,
sometimes dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among them is the role of Islam, here in the world's
largest Muslim country, with a population of more than 200 million.
On the eve of the vote, Muslim preachers around the country called
on their followers to reject ``secular'' parties, notably that of
Mrs. Megawati.
</P>
<P>
   If her party manages to form a winning coalition that excludes
the less-moderate Muslim groups, it may be sowing the seeds of
future tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the military will, as always, be key in Indonesia.
Since Suharto's resignation it has agreed, under reformist
pressure, to reduce its bloc in Parliament by half and is in the
process of redefining its place in the political scene.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear which way it will throw its weight in the
post-election coalition-building. It is also unclear to what degree
it will continue to withdraw from politics, particularly at this
time of national instability.
</P>
<P>
   The new government also will face the task of building a real
democracy that goes beyond an election into the construction of
working, independent legislative and judicial branches and
nongovernmental institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts agree that the country's loose and
outdated Constitution must be revised. There is talk of instituting
direct presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia must also address increasingly intense questions about
the relationship between the central government in Java and the
distant, sometimes resource-rich provinces. Since Suharto departed,
separatist movements in East Timor, Aceh and Irian Jaya have become
newly demanding and violent.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins power, the question will remain as to whether the
momentum of reform that has been transforming the country in the
last year will continue or stall.
</P>
<P>
   There is still no firm legal foundation for the newly open
press, no guarantee that freed political prisoners will not be
replaced by newly arrested ones and no assurance that the many
contentious new political parties will remain free to jostle and
shout.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how differently a new power structure may behave
from the old one. The battle cry of the reformist students who
helped bring down Suharto was an end to ``corruption, collusion and
nepotism.''
</P>
<P>
   After decades of one-man rule, these are ingrained traits in the
Indonesian power structure that will not disappear simply with a
change of personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the power groups realigning themselves, the temptations
for graft for the new government will be intense,'' a Western
diplomat said. ``It will take a pretty principled group to resist
them.''
</P>
<P>
   It will also be up to the new government to decide how
vigorously to pursue the hidden billions of Suharto and whether to
put him or any of his six wealthy children on trial for their
financial abuses.
</P>
<P>
   This urgent demand of student demonstrators and other reformists
is a particular challenge for any government because of the large
number of prominent Indonesians who are tainted by their corrupt
ties to the old regime.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying all the challenges and pitfalls for the country's
next leaders is Indonesia's debilitating economic collapse in the
last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is in for continued difficult times,'' said Jack
Bresnan, an expert on Indonesia at Columbia University, who is
observing the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of categories of data in which there has
been a modest upturn in the last couple of months,'' he said, ``but
a tick does not make a trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just so many structural problems that were
unattended to last year. The destruction of the banking system is
by far the most serious. I ask myself whether Indonesia will ever
return to the level of social and economic welfare it had in
1996.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
