<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FIELDING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRIDGET JONES' STRIKES A UNIVERSAL CHORD, SURPRISING WRITER A
BIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Helen Fielding, best-selling British author, was
ensconced on a couch in the Four Seasons Olympic Hotel in Seattle,
chatting amiably about her comic creation, Bridget Jones, the
desperately single thirty-something who is an international
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   And Fielding was the very picture of relaxed confidence, in
stark contrast to the mass insecurities and foibles that bedevil
her heroine. Until the writer's hand happened to toy with the top
of her black crew-neck sweater.
</P>
<P>
   And what should Fielding discover as her fingers ran along the
sweater's front neckline but the tags of the manufacturer. Yes, she
had her sweater on backward. And yes, this was the day after she
had appeared on American television wearing a T-shirt that she
later discovered had been inside out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones,'' Fielding finally conceded Friday, ``does
reflect a part of me.''
</P>
<P>
   And a part of millions of other women around the globe, as
Fielding has discovered firsthand while promoting the paperback
release of her book. ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' (Penguin, 271 pages,
$12.95) has become a beloved compatriot of single women everywhere
who fight daily, often losing, battles with their weight, their
habits, their aloneness and their self images.
</P>
<P>
   As Bridget catalogs in one of the daily entries in her diary:
``123 lbs., thigh circumference 18 inches (honestly, what is bloody
point), alcohol units 0, cigarettes 25 (excellent, considering),
negative thoughts: approx. 445 per hour, positive thoughts 0.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielding has met women who claim to be ``just like Bridget'' in
Britain, America, Sweden, France, Italy and Japan. And Fielding has
met women who claim to be ``just like Bridget'' despite being women
of considerable accomplishment and social aplomb, television
anchors, attorneys, teachers, artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that women who have achieved a huge amount
are still haunted by images of perfection,'' Fielding observed.
``We are all expecting to look like swimsuit models who have been
airbrushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Bridget muses: ``I am a child of `Cosmopolitan' culture,
have been traumatized by supermodels and too many quizzes and know
that neither my personality nor my body is up to it if left to its
own devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielding's book, at first glance, might seem merely a Xerox copy
of a year in a single woman's real life with its acutely observed
minutiae, the useless pantyhose crumpled in drawers, the late-night
snacks devoured amid guilt pangs, the annoying ``Smug Marrieds''
who think nothing of inquiring, ``How's your love life?''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' is actually a careful literary
construct, exaggerated for effect, laced with high-octane irony and
zeroing in on painful life truths amid the host of hilarious
one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   As Bridget observes, ``When someone leaves you, apart from
missing them, apart from the fact that the whole little world
you've created collapses, and that everything you see or do reminds
you of them, the worst is the thought that they tried you out and,
in the end, the whole sum of parts adds up to you got stamped
REJECT by the one you love.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Jones began life as the subject of an unsigned weekly
column in a London newspaper, which started slowly and built a
loyal following over three years. Fielding's modest goal was for
every column to have two or three lines to make her laugh out loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing,'' the former Oxford University student
recalled, ``was not so much making it funny as battling fears that
it was such light fare that I often wondered: Why would anyone want
to read this?''
</P>
<P>
   Any such thoughts now seem eons away. The 40-year-old Fielding
has been subject of a media frenzy (from writing Amazon.com's
``favorite book of 1998'' to being named one of People magazine's
``most intriguing'' newcomers). She has gone on to become a Bridget
Jones Factory.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding has turned reported millionaire on the strength of the
book's million-plus sales, an upcoming film version (which she also
wrote) and a much-delayed book sequel in which the quirky, yet
resilient ``singleton'' heroine finds herself confronting the
challenges of actually being in a relationship with a man and later
perhaps even in (although still uncertain now) a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Jones' life may be an open book, but not Fielding's. The
former BBC journalist is a charming interview subject who instantly
turns insistent whenever asked personal questions. She declines to
confirm her age, declines to provide details of her social life
(other than to say she is still ``not married''), declines to pose
for any more newspaper photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep a fence around my life,'' Fielding explained.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding had long dreamed about being a writer, had dreamed
about having a best seller, had dreamed even of being interviewed
on TV about her book. All that has now happened, and more, which
makes every morning feel like Christmas for Fielding except there
still remains an undercurrent of disbelief and wariness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I can't believe this happened _ that it was my book
and that so many people liked it,'' Fielding said. ``It has been a
wonderful thing to have happened, but very strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
