<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC `WILL BE FINE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Charismatic got on the road to recovery _ and a
future at stud _ in a white-and-blue horse ambulance that backed up
to within 30 feet of his Belmont Park stall late Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   With two of trainer D. Wayne Lukas' assistants guiding him, with
a pained expression about his eyes, Charismatic walked haltingly
into the van, which flashed its yellow roof light as it made the
slow five-minute drive along tree-lined lanes to the Belmont Equine
Surgical Clinic at the corner of Affirmed Road and Secretariat
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Greeted there by a man in green surgical garb and another who
sponged off the three hooves that weren't encased in a plastic
``air cast,'' Charismatic took a few more ginger steps up a short
incline and through double doors to the operating room.
</P>
<P>
   In the next 2{ hours, Dr. Stephen Selway inserted four screws in
the left front cannon bone, one of two bones Charismatic fractured
as he finished third in the Belmont Stakes while chasing a Triple
Crown on Saturday in a race won by 29-1 shot Lemon Drop Kid.
</P>
<P>
   After the surgery, Selway said the injury ``was not the worst of
this kind I've ever seen, but it was a nasty one. He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Selway said Charismatic's left leg was fitted with a cast, and
if he is shipped by airplane, he should be ready to travel in a few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas left no doubt the 3-year-old colt, a son of 1990 Preakness
winner Summer Squall and a great-grandson of Secretariat, would be
retired to a lucrative career in the breeding shed. Owners Bob and
Beverly Lewis have made no announcement about his destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not thinking about (racing),'' Lukas said. ``He wouldn't
come back at the same level as what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   So ends an unusual career for Charismatic, who was purchased
privately as a yearling for $200,000 and went on to earn $2,038,064
by winning 5 of 17 races. Along the way, he won twice in his first
13 starts, the second victory coming by disqualification in a
$62,500 claiming race at Santa Anita, before blossoming to win the
Kentucky Derby (at 31-1) and Preakness (at 8-1) during a hot
stretch of five races in nine weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was thriving on the way he was raced,'' said Dr. Larry
Bramlage, acting as spokesman for the American Association of
Equine Practitioners, trying to deflect speculation the heavy
schedule led to the injury.
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Charismatic became evident when he bobbled while
running third a couple of strides from the end of the 1{-mile
Belmont and jockey Chris Antley pulled him to a stop yards past the
wire. The disappointment of the record crowd of 85,818 at not
seeing a Triple Crown winner turned to hushed concern for the colt.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries were not unusual for racehorses, although Bramlage
said serious injuries are not as common as the 1990s' spate of
breakdowns in major televised events might lead some to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Bramlage said a study at Kentucky racetracks concluded that the
incidence of injury serious enough to require an ambulance is about
1 in 1,000 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was asked what he'd say to people who were upset by what
they saw Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to animal-rights ``purists,'' Lukas said: ``These
horses are probably getting more care than their own children. They
get more upset when a horse like this gets hurt, or when we have a
Go for Wand (break down in the 1990 Breeders' Cup Distaff), than
when a guy hits the wall at Indy and he's killed. You can only
educate them that we're doing all we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
