<HEADLINE>
HBO'S `THE SOPRANOS': WHERE `GOODFELLAS' MEETS `THE SIMPSONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Few television series manage to hit a high note
consistently without getting a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   Even the long-running ``Law &AMP; Order,'' which routinely delivers
taut, believable drama, checks in with the occasional clunker.
(Case in point: This season's May-sweeps publicity grabber
featuring Julia Roberts.) And the recently canceled ``Homicide:
Life on the Street,'' possibly the best dramatic TV series of the
`90s, was straining a bit as it struggled to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, there's just no telling where a quality show might end
up after a promising first season. For me, ``Ally McBeal'' quickly
went south in its sophomore year, while ``The Practice,'' now three
seasons old, seems to get better and better, with richly drawn
characters who defy David E. Kelley's penchant for silliness.
</P>
<P>
   So, take this with a dash of caution, but in the glee club of
life there may never be anything quite like ``The Sopranos.'' Many
critics already consider it the best thing since individually
wrapped cheese slices. But, since it airs on HBO, the audience is
limited to those with enough discretionary income to afford extra
cellophane with their cheese and extra lines on their cable bill.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have HBO and you don't have a
friend/relative/neighbor who has HBO and you're just waiting for a
legitimate reason to have HBO, ``The Sopranos'' is probably it.
Shoot, the performance of James Gandolfini alone is worth the cost
of subscribing.
</P>
<P>
   Gandolfini plays the fleshy, flashy Tony Soprano: husband,
father, mob boss. And not always in that order, which is what makes
``The Sopranos'' so special. It's about a wise-guy crime figure
who's got the same middle-class problems that none of us bothered
to read in the fine print of the American Dream contract.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Tony is probably upper middle class, though it's hard
to quantify because most of his assets weren't earned the Dean
Witter way.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Tony Soprano is a fascinating specimen worthy of
further research, and HBO this week graciously begins a reprise of
the first season of ``The Sopranos'' (9 p.m. Wednesdays, 12:30 a.m.
Saturdays).
</P>
<P>
   Launched in January and played out over 13 weeks of winter, the
continuing story arc of the Soprano family _ make that families _
was as irresistible as a shot of hot fudge on anything. Think of
``Goodfellas'' meeting ``The Simpsons.'' Violent, funny, profane,
funny, poignant, funny.
</P>
<P>
   For many Americans, Tony's problems are eminently relatable: His
wife is restless, his teenage daughter is insolent, his son is a
chip off the old delinquent. And then there's his other family. He
and his uncle are in a power struggle for control of organized
crime in northern New Jersey, one of his lower-echelon gofers
(Michael Imperioli) an inveterate idiot, and his mother _ widow of
the recently deceased head of the family _ is, well, a real mother.
</P>
<P>
   If Nancy Marchand doesn't win an Emmy Award as the mother of all
mob madres, we may have to convene a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' is the creation of David Chase, whose writing
resume includes such noteworthy fare as ``Northern Exposure'' and
``I'll Fly Away.'' If the first 13 weeks of his latest project are
any indicator, Chase has nothing to worry about in the area of
future employment. But let's hope he doesn't kill off too many of
the Sopranos prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Fabulous characterization is what makes ``The Sopranos'' work,
and there's so much more to know about Tony's wife, Carmela (Edie
Falco), and his uncle, Junior (Dominic Chianese). And let's not
forget his psychiatrist, Jennifer Melfi, played with exquisite
understatement by Lorraine Bracco. (Billy Crystal played a
mobster's analyst for laughs in ``Analyze This''; Bracco plays it
for keeps.)
</P>
<P>
   There's still no telling if the second season of ``The
Sopranos,'' due in January, will be spectacular or hopelessly
off-key, but for the next three months anyway, it's reason to sing
the praises of HBO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
