<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-     06-06 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN NATIONAL CONGRESS DRAWING MIXED-RACE SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ It was just an Election Day spat between a drunk
who was harassing voters and a cranky fruit-juice seller, but it
encapsulated the split in the ``colored'' vote, the crucial bloc in
the Western Cape province, which contains lovely, touristy Cape
Town, its vast suffering townships and dozens of fishing and
farming villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're voting ANC?'' shouted the drunken New National Party
supporter. ``The ANC's going to throw you out of your house and put
a black man in it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aah, go back to work for the white man,'' retorted the juice
seller, a supporter of the African National Congress. ``He threw
you out here in these bushes with all this sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument, conducted in Afrikaans, took place in Mitchell's
Plain, home to 800,000 descendants of a fabled colored, or mixed
race, neighborhood in Cape Town that was bulldozed in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Results still trickling in from last Wednesday's elections show
that the mixed-race voters of the Western Cape are no longer a
bulwark of the Afrikaner-dominated New National Party, formerly the
National Party. One startling outcome of the election is how well
the African National Congress fared in all nine of South Africa's
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   The Nats, as they are commonly known here, got 53 percent of the
Western Cape vote in South Africa's first free elections in 1994
and ruled the province. This time, they got only 39 percent, while
the ANC climbed to 42 percent from 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Voting patterns are still being analyzed, and no figures are yet
final, but it's obvious that the congress, which preaches
multiracialism but gets almost all its votes from black South
Africans, picked up support from the mixed-race people who mostly
speak Afrikaans. In 1994, those of mixed race tended to vote for
the National Party, which created apartheid, apparently reasoning
that while white government treated them badly, black government
would treat them worse.
</P>
<P>
   In Western Cape, the switch in mixed-race votes seems to have
been sufficient to drain away the National Party's majority.
Elsewhere, too, the African National Congress fared spectacularly
well.
</P>
<P>
   It got 85 percent of the vote in Mpumalanga, which contains
Kruger Park, up from 81 percent, even though local government is
riddled with scandal and its popular premier was ousted by the
central party.
</P>
<P>
   It got 67 percent in Gauteng, which contains both Johannesburg
and Pretoria, up from 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It got 65 percent in the Northern Cape, a large, desolate area
with a few rich diamond mines, up from 50 percent. (The Nats had
boasted that they would win there, and polls had predicted a dead
heat; they faded to 24 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   More important, in the two provinces the congress failed to win
in 1994, the Western Cape and KwaZulu/Natal, it did well enough to
force everyone to seek coalition rule.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the African National Congress lost KwaZulu/Natal to the
Inkatha Freedom Party. Inkatha had 50 percent of the vote to the
ANC's 32 percent. This year, the ANC got 39 percent while Inkatha's
lead was whittled to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said it appeared that Inkatha, the Zulu
nationalist party dominated by Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi, had hung
onto its rural supporters, who generally vote as their chiefs
instruct. But it lost ground in districts bordering Xhosa territory
and in cities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, urban whites were drawn by Inkatha's conservative
stance, support or free enterprise over what was seen as ANC
socialism and a certain respect for Zulus among the British who
fought a bitter war with them in 1870s. However, some of
Buthelezi's chief white supporters have since quit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite peace talks that had cooled the political killings for
which the province was famous, KwaZulu/Natal was poorly run and
Inkatha itself was riven by infighting.
</P>
<P>
   Several Sunday newspapers, quoting anonymous sources in the
African National Congress, reported Sunday that a grand deal was in
the works under which Buthelezi would be offered the deputy
president's job, the same one president-elect Thabo Mbeki held
under President Nelson Mandela. In return, the reports said, the
congress would get to name KwaZulu/Natal's premier, the equivalent
of governor.
</P>
<P>
   Joint government ``will help stability,'' said Shaun MacKay, a
political analyst at the Center for Policy Studies, a think tank.
``The violence will settle down more.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Cape, the Nats had assumed they would hang on to
their lead. A pillar of the Nats' national campaign, besides their
demand for the return of the death penalty, was their claim that
the Western Cape was the country's best-run province.
</P>
<P>
   They said that 80 percent of 12th graders graduated, as opposed
to a national average of 50 percent; that crime was lower except in
neighborhoods where drug gangs and Muslim vigilantes were battling
and that tourism was up. In reply, their opponents pointed out that
they had a head start _ most working class and poor people in the
Cape are mixed race, and the old government always treated them
slightly better.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to push either the African National Congress or the
New National Party over 50 percent resides in the Democratic Party,
which got 12 percent of the vote. That party, once a small white
liberal voice, quadrupled its support this year, mostly from
Afrikaners.
</P>
<P>
   Hennie Bester, its provincial leader, was talking with the Nats
and refusing to form a coalition with the ANC, saying, ``We're
suspicious of too much power being in any one hand.''
</P>
<P>
   District results suggest that the mixed-race vote deserted the
Nats in droves, voting ANC in areas where white farmers still
oppress farm workers, and voting Democratic Party in cities where
black government is in effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of a monolithic `colored vote' bothers me,''
said Sipho Maseko, an analyst from the University of the Western
Cape. ``The colored community now votes any party that meets its
interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
