<HEADER>
A5004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DOVER-COX     06-06 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DOVER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte fuels 'em at Dover
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Bobby Labonte topped off a remarkable weekend at
Dover International Speedway on Sunday by winning the gas mileage
war and, consequently, the MBNA Platinum 400.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was running sixth when he made a pit stop under caution
to top off his fuel on lap 293 of the 400-lap event. The only
contender to pit at the time, Labonte fell to eighth after getting
gas, but it proved to be a decisive stop.
</P>
<P>
   He was still running strong the final 107 miles, and when race
leader Jeff Gordon pitted for a 2.34-second splash of gas with six
laps to go, Labonte cruised to the front for his first victory of
the season, by 22.071 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin was a distant third. Labonte's teammate, Tony
Stewart, turned in another strong performance by leading for 127
laps and had the third fourth-place finish in his last four races.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, the pole-sitter, led only five times for 44 laps,
including the final six. ``But I led the most important ones,'' he
said. ``The first one, the middle one and the last. I really don't
care about the rest of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Jimmy Makar made the critical call, bringing Labonte
in twice during the six-lap caution period (laps 290-295) after
Kenny Wallace smacked into the backstretch wall in the No. 55
Chevrolet. The last time was for the fuel top-off.
</P>
<P>
   The extra gas enabled Labonte to stay out on the track when
Martin had to pit for fuel with 12 laps to go and Gordon pulled in
with six remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're wrong, you're looking for a rock to hide under,''
Makar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good top five car, that was obvious, and we could
have come in with everybody else and finish in the top five,''
Makar said. ``Sometimes you just get a hunch and you decide, well,
we're here to win the race, we're not here to just finish. We took
a small gamble, it wasn't a huge gamble. It was something we
thought we could do and capitalize on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never look at them gauges, anyway,'' Labonte joked. ``Right
there, I had to look at that. It was down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, rebounding from three finishes of 31st or worse in the
last five races, may have had the strongest car at the end. But
communication problems with crew chief Ray Evernham frustrated his
decision to pit for fuel or not to pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the heat of the moment, you don't know exactly
what the strategy is,'' Gordon said. ``I was having a lot of
trouble with the radio. Ray told me to ease up. I thought he meant
to ease up to stretch it.
</P>
<P>
   We pretty much knew 18 (Labonte) could go all the way. We were
just going to hope for a caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a driver, you just want to just stretch it. But when you
look at all the numbers, we couldn't have made it. I would have
looked like an idiot if I had tried to make it and run out of
gas.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bum radio connection made it all the more frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray was having to talk and my spotter was have to relay it to
me,'' Gordon said. ``I asked several times, `can we make it, can we
make it?'
</P>
<P>
   I kept getting this total fuzz and the radio breaking up. I kept
going a little bit further. Finally, Ray said something and the
spotter relayed to me, no we can not.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin seemed frustrated in trying to explain fuel efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, you don't understand racing,'' Martin said to a reporter.
``If you can't run that many laps, then you can't run that many
laps whether it's 108 or whatever it was. If you can only run 100,
and it's 108 to go. There's no gambling to it. Man, you're eight
miles short. That's the way it is. Bobby Labonte could run that
far. And we could run a couple laps less than Jeff Gordon, and Jeff
Gordon couldn't make it. It wasn't close.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Labonte's first win of the season, though he'd put
together two seconds and four thirds. And he was chagrined that he
could win on a day his car wasn't the best while he's lost some
with a better machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd had been second on the race track, if we'd had a
better car, we might not have been able to win,'' Labonte said.
``We wouldn't have pitted if we were running second or third.
Instead, we were sixth or seventh on that restart and decided to
come in.''
</P>
<P>
   MBNA PLATINUM 400 TOP 5
</P>
<P>
   1. Bobby Labonte, Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jeff Gordon, Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mark Martin, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   4. Tony Stewart, Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   5. Dale Jarrett, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
