<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY AGREE TO BRIEF EXTENSION FOR YUGOSLAV WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States might be willing to agree to a
brief extension in the timetable for the withdrawal of Yugoslav
forces from Kosovo as part of a peace deal with Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic, military officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, indicated that Washington
would consider a Yugoslav request made in the ongoing talks with
NATO to take 10 days to pull out their troops, rather than the
seven demanded by NATO leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials stressed that the NATO bombing campaign would
continue until there was concrete evidence that Yugoslav forces
were moving north out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on ABC's ``This Week'' news program on Sunday, Cohen
said the ``time frame'' requested by the Yugoslavs was ``not
significant.'' Yet he cautioned that ``what we have to be concerned
about is, no slow rolling here. We're not going to allow a kind of
deliberate policy of delaying day by day.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same show, Shelton agreed that the three-day extension
requested by the Yugoslavs might be so insignificant that NATO
could accept it. ``But we in fact want to make sure that the extra
time is for a good reason. We want to get the Kosovars back in as
soon as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The statements came as the United States and its NATO allies
were scrambling to prepare for a postwar period that seemed to be
nearing much more quickly than they had anticipated. Even though
talks between NATO and Yugoslav military leaders at the
Macedonia-Kosovo border dragged on and seemed to turn sour on
Sunday, American and allied officials acknowledged that the shape
of NATO's involvement in a postwar Kosovo _ and its relationship
with Milosevic and his government _ remained unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   With the military plans stalled, NATO bombing of Yugoslav forces
in the field in Kosovo continued Sunday. The Pentagon said
warplanes hit an anti-aircraft site, 14 armored personnel carriers,
13 artillery pieces, a battalion-size staging area, five mortars
and several fixed positions, including ammunition dumps and
early-warning radar sites.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing campaign, which had shown such little promise of
achieving NATO's goals in its first few weeks, became far more
successful once the Yugoslav army was forced to come out into the
open to fight the Kosovo Liberation Army, Shelton and other
officials said Sunday. By cooperating with NATO's air armada, the
KLA in effect acted as the ground force that NATO itself had been
reluctant to insert into the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Yugoslav forces massed to do battle with the KLA,
``that requires you to come out of hiding, move your tanks out and
get your artillery in position,'' Shelton noted. ``Whenever that
happens, needless to say, they make better targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton and Cohen also echoed the sentiments of European
leaders, who again Sunday called for the prosecution of Milosevic
for war crimes. Milosevic is now indicted as a war criminal.
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Sunday that Yugoslavia had
no future with Milosevic at the helm. ``It must be in the interests
of people in Serbia to have him go,'' he told BBC Television's
David Frost.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana agreed. ``It's not NATO's
aim to depose Milosevic, it never has been, but I think all
citizens of good faith, not only in Europe but all over the world,
would like Milosevic to give up power in Serbia,'' he told the
Spanish television station Telecinco.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached with the Yugoslav government, however,
does not give Kosovo independence from Yugoslavia, but autonomy
with a civil administration _ even under a Milosevic-led
government. That leaves the KLA short of its goal.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the peace agreement also requires the KLA to
lay down at least some of its arms, and NATO officials have not yet
explained how they plan to accomplish that. Several rebel leaders
have said they do not trust the peace agreement or the Serbs'
compliance with it, and some have suggested that the guerrillas
will not disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton was careful to note Sunday that the peace deal would not
require NATO forces to disarm the KLA, but only to ``demilitarize''
the rebel force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said that we're going to disarm the KLA,'' Shelton
said. He added that demilitarization means ``no longer having
organized units, getting rid of the uniforms, the heavy weapons,
things of this type. To our knowledge today, they (the KLA) still
intend to comply with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russia's role in a Kosovo peacekeeping mission also
remained unclear Sunday. Russia, Yugoslavia's most important ally,
played a critical role in forcing Milosevic to accept a deal, but
Washington is now resisting Moscow's efforts to play a peacekeeping
role in Kosovo independent of NATO control. Cohen insisted Sunday
that the Russians would have to serve under a NATO-led command.
``Ultimately, NATO has to be in charge,'' Cohen noted.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton conceded Sunday that the situation was in such an
uncertain state that it was almost impossible to tell what kind of
conditions the NATO peacekeeping force will face inside Kosovo.
``Given the type of environment that they are going into, the
hazards will abound,'' Shelton said on CNN's ``Late Edition.
</P>
</TEXT>
