<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCHOPEN-NYT &LR;      06-06 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCHOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI MAKES HISTORY IN WINNING FIRST FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Andre Agassi played the first two sets of the most
important match of his life like a petrified pretender Sunday.
Then, when the shock and embarrassment failed to destroy him, he
gathered his wits about him and played like someone who deserved to
be in the company of Rod Laver, Fred Perry, Roy Emerson and Don
Budge.
</P>
<P>
   By capturing the French Open singles title with a 1-6, 2-6, 6-4,
6-3, 6-4 victory over Andre Medvedev, Agassi became the fifth man
in tennis history to win all four Grand Slam events and completed
the latest and most significant turnaround in a career marked by
occasional flashes of brilliance amid unfilled promise.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 1 in the world for 30 weeks in 1995, Agassi went into
a spiral that saw his ranking fall as low as 141st in November
1997. He took a 70-day hiatus that year, during which he married
the actress Brooke Shields, and began to resurrect his career,
returning to the top 10 last year.
</P>
<P>
   His personal life hit a bump in March, when his marriage to
Shields ended. But after his victory Sunday, his tennis ranking
will rise from No. 14 to No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost feels like it was just sheer destiny,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   But this was destiny abetted by will and mobility. When he puts
his mind to it, there are few hurdles in tennis that the
29-year-old Agassi, a professional since 1986, cannot clear.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first Grand Slam tournament at Wimbledon in 1992,
even though he has never had the serve-and-volley power game that
that tournament favors. When he won the 1994 U.S. Open, he was
unseeded. And he collected his third Grand Slam title, at the 1995
Australian Open, on his first visit there.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi is the only man to win the four Grand Slam events on
three different surfaces. When Laver, Perry, Emerson and Budge
captured the tournaments, the French Open was played on the clay of
Roland Garros and the other three were played on grass. Now the
Australian and U.S. Opens are on hardcourts while Wimbledon remains
on grass.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent Sunday, the No. 100-ranked Medvedev of the Ukraine,
was the lowest-ranked man to play for the French Open championship.
He played the most inspired tennis of his life to gain his first
Grand Slam final, defeating second-seeded Pete Sampras along the
way, but ultimately gave way to a force beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm human,'' Medvedev said. ``I left my heart and soul on the
court, I played 110 percent of my human abilities. But you have to
remember on the other side of the net is Andre Agassi.''
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev added: ``When we went to the third set, he wasn't yet
the greatest player of our decade. Now he has an argument to be the
best player. He's making the history; he has the right to say now
that he's a greater player than, let's say, Pete, by winning all
four Grand Slams.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the 29-year-old Steffi Graf's comeback victory over Martina
Hingis in the women's final on Saturday, Sunday's theatrics by
Agassi, a loser in French Open finals in 1990 and 1991, seemed the
stuff of fairy tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a proven war dog,'' Agassi said after extricating himself
from a two-sets-to-none deficit for the third time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Although I could have lived with it, losing would
have been devastating to me. The truth of it is that anything can
happen if you keep working, but you also fear the worst. That's the
nature of competition. There's always battles in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Apprehensive but optimistic, that was the Agassi who strutted
onto center court and, dwarfed by the 6-foot-4-inch Medvedev and
the power tennis clinic he conducted, lost the first set in 19
minutes and surrendered the second 33 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   With flashbacks of his failed voyages in his first three Grand
Slam finals, two of them in Paris, forcing him onward, Agassi
buckled down. Spurred by some terse advice from his coach, Brad
Gilbert, during a 20-minute rain delay after the first game of the
second set that interrupted the final, he stopped playing out of
panic and began pacing himself like a pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pulling triggers I shouldn't have pulled in some
cases,'' Agassi said. ``He assured me that he felt shot for shot I
was better, if I would just work hard, hustle, move my feet, and
strike the ball effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   While his fans exhorted him with the wave, Agassi finally began
to make inroads on Medvedev's serve in the third set. He broke him
with a forehand line drive for 4-2 and then, with rain sprinkling
the court, immediately gave back the break with a love game. After
double-faulting to break point at 4-4, he held for 5-4 and broke
Medvedev at love for the set with a perfectly timed backhand drop
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Greedy about maintaining his momentum, Agassi broke for a 2-0
lead in the fourth set and never let Medvedev back into it. By the
final set it was the 24-year-old Ukrainian who was doubting himself
and rushing his shots. Agassi, a veteran of some 30 five-setters,
closed in like a bloodhound and broke for a 3-2 lead. Medvedev
saved 3 match points, the first of them with his 23rd and final ace
of the 2 hour 55 minute match, when he served at 3-5. But when
Agassi secured a fourth match point as he served at 5-4, Medvedev
sailed a forehand return long.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi immediately dropped his racquet as if it had burned him
and mouthed, ``I won,'' in the direction of Gilbert and Gil Reyes,
the fitness trainer and spiritual guru Agassi has called a best
friend for the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   From somewhere in the stands, a French fan shouted, ``The king
is back!'' And then Agassi, whose honed-down physique has earned
him the nickname Rock from his entourage, ascended the podium to
receive his fourth career Grand Slam trophy from Laver, the man
known as the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed I would see this day,'' said Agassi. ``This
was the greatest thing I could ever do, but I certainly have a lot
more belief that if I can do it here, I can do it again in a few
other places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
