<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE LANDS AFTER CREW REPAIRS SPACE STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Seven astronauts were getting their earth
legs back on Sunday after an unusual night space-shuttle landing
capped their 10-day mission to stock the new international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   For only the 11th time in 94 flights, a shuttle swooped out of a
star-filled sky to land. The black-bellied spaceship was visible
only seconds before its wheels touched pavement at 2:03 a.m., but
it announced its presence four minutes earlier with a pair of sonic
booms that rousted sleepers, rattled windows and activated car
alarms in and around Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness was no challenge for Discovery's commander, Kent
Rominger, who found the space center's marsh-bound 15,000-foot
runway bathed in bright xenon light as he glided the shuttle to a
touchdown after 153 orbits.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle, with a crew of four men and three women from the
United States, Canada and Russia, spent six days docked at the
space station. Astronauts unloaded two tons of supplies for the
first permanent occupants, due next year.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the station, the crew fixed a communications system,
replaced defective battery packs and installed foam mufflers around
noisy fans. Outside, two astronauts made a seven-hour 55-minute
space walk, the second-longest space walk in the shuttle program to
mount American and Russian construction cranes.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the astronauts released a 19-inch mirrored
educational satellite called Starshine. It is designed to twinkle
from space so student volunteers can track its motion to learn
principles of physics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a flawless mission,'' NASA administrator Daniel
Goldin told reporters on the shuttle runway.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts skipped a traditional walk around the shuttle on
the runway, bypassed a microphone set up for a statement and
departed about two hours after touchdown in their crew transport
vehicle _ a modified airport people-mover equipped like an
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   The flight director, Linda Ham, and other NASA officials at
Mission Control in Houston referred questions about the astronauts'
health to public affairs officers at Kennedy, who said they had no
information, but added that the astronauts would appear at a news
conference at Kennedy on Monday morning before returning to their
training base in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Robert Cabana, deputy director of flight crew operations
at the Johnson Space Center in Houston, said that the ``crew is in
great spirits and doing fine'' and had decided to forgo the walk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
