<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-SCHOOL-WORKSHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CITY'S BALLET'S FOOTSTEPS, STUDENTS EXHIBIT THE JOY OF DANCING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Young dancers who can surmount the pressures of the
annual School of American Ballet Workshop Performances can probably
survive anything. The highly competitive atmosphere of what is a
combination graduation, audition and professional performing
experience can show in somewhat grim, stiff, do-or-die dancing.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood was mostly joyous and even playful in workshop
programs on Saturday afternoon and evening at the Juilliard
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The four ballets, an inspired selection, came from the repertory
of the New York City Ballet, with which the school is affiliated.
These young dancers came surprisingly close to matching the level
of dancing in the senior company.
</P>
<P>
   The accent was on graciousness of manner in George Balanchine's
``Tombeau de Couperin,'' which opened the programs. Kiyon Gaines
stood out at the matinee in this luminous homage to the classical
corps de ballet for the warmth and stylishness of his dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Amar Ramasar and Megan Pepin were a well matched couple in the
matinee performance of the Balanchine-Glinka ``Valse Fantaisie,''
lyrical yet full of daring appetite for space and for technical
challenge. Ramasar, who popped up in nearly everything on both
programs, was the great find of the day, a comfortable blend of
long-limbed prince and endearing goof and a dancer who seems
refreshingly aware at all times of his ballerina and of others on
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Ricard was the evening's ballerina, dancing with charm and
polish. A nervous-looking Andrew Veyette pushed very hard,
diminishing the impact of his strong technique and neglecting his
ballerina. Both men need to land more softly. The cast was
completed by Elizabeth Ford, Danielle Giordano, Davena Scott Gross
and Abi Stafford in the afternoon and by the extra-stylish quartet
of Gwyneth Muller, Lisa Platt, Lauren Toole and Amy Watson in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Wheeldon's ``Scenes de Ballet,'' set to the
Stravinsky score, is a knowing, delicately rapturous celebration of
ballet itself and of child dancers at all levels. Ms. Ricard was
the radiant matinee ballerina. Faye Arthurs danced the ballerina
role in the evening with the exciting quality of a sleek racehorse
that may bolt at any moment. Craig Hall, an elegantly finished
classical dancer and a gifted partner, was their cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   The programs ended with impressively authoritative, amusing
performances of Jerome Robbins' ``Fanfare,'' set to Benjamin
Britten's ``Young Persons' Guide to the Orchestra.'' Ramasar,
Philip J. Spencer and Jonathan Porretta (matinee) and Sean Suozzi
(evening) nearly stole the show in the percussion trio, with Igor
Burlak just as funny as the doleful matinee tuba. Other standout
performers included Ms. Giordano, Jordan Pacitti, Carla Korbes,
Seth Orza and Veyette at the matinee and Charlene Cohen, Mary Glenn
Keenan and Ms. Pepin in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The fine lead casts were completed by Jung-Min Lee, Chiaki
Yasukawa, Katherine Daines, Ms. Gross, Orlando Canova, David
Schneider, Ms. Ford, Hall, Ms. Arthurs, Ms. Stafford, Ms. Ricard,
and Gaines. Richard Moredock conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUKE-BALLET-REVIEW-NY     06-06 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKE-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ AND CLASSICAL FLIRT BUT GET SERIOUS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``A Tribute to Duke Ellington,'' the New York City
Ballet's latest collaboration with Jazz at Lincoln Center, swings.
</P>
<P>
   The program's three works, with two world premieres performed
over the weekend at the New York State Theater, gave the company a
chance to let its hair down. Never mind that most of the women wear
their hair up, either in 1940s upsweeps or in ballet chignons.
</P>
<P>
   The not so irreconcilable gap between jazz and classical ballet
becomes, eventually, the unannounced theme of the evening. There is
even a bodice-ripping finale in which Maria Kowroski as a Degas
ballet girl and hilarious odd woman out among flappers, tears off
her tutu and joins the party in Susan Stroman's choreography in
``Duke!'' That work also has two equally inspired sections by two
other choreographers, Robert La Fosse and Garth Fagan.
</P>
<P>
   It may be startling to see how feverishly the wonderful City
Ballet men throw themselves to the floor in Ms. Stroman's zoot-suit
finale. But the real surprise is ``Them Twos,'' a new ballet by
Peter Martins and Wynton Marsalis.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to expectations, the music Marsalis has written for
Martins is not, strictly speaking, a jazz composition; it is his
first orchestral score to be performed publicly, and at the
program's premiere on Thursday night the music was played by the
City Ballet orchestra under Robert Sadin's baton while the music
for ``Duke!'' the other premiere, as well as the opening piece, the
1993 ``Jazz,'' had music provided by the Lincoln Center Jazz
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Them Twos'' Martins has choreographed a neo-classical
ballet about the uneven course of love. Serene, witty and
pugnacious, it builds toward a supremely haunting image of loss: A
blind lover carries his angelic beloved at a tilt across his
shoulder as her tresses stream down to one side.
</P>
<P>
   Darci Kistler and Jock Soto gave this strange, surreal image an
evocative power in all its asymmetry and finality. Marsalis has
titled this last of six movements in his score ``Loss'' and he and
Martins are, in their second joint venture, more than ever on the
same esthetic and emotional level.
</P>
<P>
   Consisting of an overture and five duets, ``Them Twos'' is
sophisticated and subtle, with the quirky choreographic image
meshing perfectly into a score of symphonic aspirations that knows
how to keep its commissioned dance pulse in the forefront. In
short, a great success.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan and Ms. Stroman, the guest choreographers, and La Fosse,
of City Ballet, are no slouches. They have produced the crowd
pleaser on this three-part program, to be repeated on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them Twos'' will be performed on other mixed bills on Thursday
night and at two matinees, on Saturday and on June 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them Twos'' continues Martins' serious and pioneering
collaboration with major American composers. The ballet is
presented jointly by two member organizations of Lincoln Center.
Martins is City Ballet's artistic director, and Marsalis is the
artistic director of Jazz at Lincoln Center, which is devoting its
entire season to the Ellington centenary.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see this program _ with Ellington music in
``Duke!'' and Marsalis music in ``Jazz,'' the first
Marsalis-Martins collaboration, and ``Them Twos'' _ as still
another ploy to attract new audiences.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more accurate to see Marsalis as an American
composer commissioned by Martins. The ballet world has been slow to
recognize the significance of Martins' choices, but the music world
knows that he has selected leading American composers (Charles
Wuorinen, John Adams and Michael Torke). Marsalis' score lends
itself less to the leotard-ballet abstraction that the other
composers inspire. But its lyricism, as Marsalis has shown in the
past, does not exclude dissonant bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   The overture is a light waltz for strings and flute, invaded by
brass. The rhythm turns lickety-split in a shift of sound that has
a wide range of intensity. ``Forever,'' as the overture is titled,
yields to ``First Love,'' a title that embodies the first danced
section. Janie Taylor is the fresh young thing in a frilly tunic
who emerges with Sebastien Marcovici from between the pillarlike
panels that Alain Vaes has designed as a simple, effective set that
Mark Stanley's lighting codes with emotional effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The music is quiet, and the choreography is deceptively simple
but packed full of steps. Marcovici's dynamically executed brises
voles, a series of flying leg beats to each side, superbly
telegraph his puppy love exuberance. Ms. Taylor is refined and
pure, with legs flicked back or swung around her partner. Like the
couples to follow, this pair separates, but dances mainly together;
they are playful but deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost'' introduces Nilas Martins as a partner to a sensual
Miranda Weese in one of Vaes' idiosyncratic costumes. Martins was
superb in the one-armed partnering and Ms. Weese, spooling out from
his arms, had a touch of mystery. Ms. Kowroski, in long black slit
dress, showed plenty of leg as Charles Askegard, in brown street
clothes, made ``Horror,'' the next duet, a witty battle of the
sexes. Marsalis added a frequent whistle, but no one cried foul.
The dancers gave their ingeniously updated apache dance a
contemporary thrust: yanks and splits, lifts and twists told the
story.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Borree, in black bikini, and Nikolaj Hubbe, somewhat
Tarzan-like in a red wrap top, gave ``Sex'' a genteel eroticism in
a wraparound duet ending in an embrace. The music moved aptly from
oozing strings and brass to a buzzing sound that died down. The
choreography is intricate and inventive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loss'' is the dramatic climax. Ms. Kistler, in long gown and
loose hair, bourrees out from behind the panels, a vision
accompanied by a violin. Soto, groping like a blind man or
sleepwalker, finds her rarely in his grasp although they link arms.
She glides along with the music. Like a fugitive from one of George
Balanchine's ballets of the 1930's, Ms. Kistler is here to visit,
not to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them Twos'' is danced behind a scrim, which makes the action
look dim onstage. But ``Duke!'' is as bright as its costumes by
William Ivey Long.
</P>
<P>
   The first segment, ``Rockin' in Rhythm,'' is a spiffy parade of
swing dancing, stylized but close to the real thing. La Fosse has
created the equivalent of a cakewalk led by the jiving Askegard and
Helene Alexopoulos, strongly seconded by Jenifer Ringer and Arch
Higgins. With its basic Lindy hop for an ensemble, the whole thing
has the welcome bounce of a distilled movie musical. David Berger
conducted the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra seated onstage
throughout the ballet. La Fosse's Ellington selections were the
title piece, ``Old King Dooji'' and ``Echoes of Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, whose ``Griot'' with Marsalis was one of modern dance's
best pieces in recent years, won a Tony for his choreography in
``The Lion King.'' Unsurprisingly, his segment, ``Ellington
Elation,'' is the most original and subtle. His women are on toe
and the men wear gold jazz shoes with their blue outfits. The
ensemble's five couples are led by Kathleen Tracey and Albert Evans
and Ms. Weese and Nilas Martins. Ellington's ``Ad Lib on Nippon''
from his ``Far East Suite'' has drops of sound and fast tempos to
which Fagan adds his own dimension.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers are like night birds in the sky. Entrances and
exits, with lifts and arabesques and fast turns, make for a
changing spatial composition. The two main couples swap partners,
and for all the flexed feet, the partnering is classical, ending in
lifts. A ballet to see again.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blossom Got Kissed,'' Ms. Stroman, who has won her laurels
on Broadway, has given us a perfect balleticized musical in
miniature. The music is ``It Don't Mean a Thing if It Ain't Got
that Swing'' and ``Lotus Blossom.'' She uses toe for her flappers
and Ms. Kowroski, who can't get groovy until taught by La Fosse,
portraying a musician. (He plays the triangle.) The conceit is slim
but sensationally realized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
