<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY CREW ENDS 10-DAY TRIP TO SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shuttle Discovery and its multinational crew of seven swept
to a rare nighttime landing in Florida early Sunday, ending a
successful 10-day flight to the fledgling international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle touched down at Kennedy Space Center at 2:02 a.m
EDT, only the 11th time in 94 missions that a shuttle has landed in
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The crew members were to fly back to Houston on Monday. The
arrival of the astronauts was tentatively scheduled for 2:30 p.m.
EDT at Ellington Field, and NASA has scheduled a brief public
welcoming ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew spent most of its flight docked to the first
components of the new space station. The astronauts left two tons
of supplies for the first resident crew that is scheduled to arrive
in March. The astronauts also made minor repairs to the satellite
communications and power systems.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASA planned to transport the shuttle Columbia to a
coastal launching pad at Kennedy for a possible July 20 liftoff
with the $1.5 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory. The Chandra
mission has been delayed for nearly a year by a succession of
difficulties with the spacecraft and its propulsion system.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent setback involved the failure of a Boeing booster
on an Air Force Titan launched April 9 with a Department of Defense
satellite. The massive Chandra observatory is fitted atop a similar
booster that will be carried into orbit in Columbia's cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   NASA is hopeful that a Pentagon probe into the April failure
will conclude there is no reason to believe the Chandra booster is
flawed as well, said space agency shuttle program manager Ron
Dittemore.
</P>
<P>
   If Chandra cannot be launched by mid-August, it will face
another lengthy postponement.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of the shuttles, Columbia is scheduled for major
refurbishments and structural inspections at its California
production plant. None of the other shuttles is configured to
launch the large observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's commander for the five-day mission is Eileen Collins,
a veteran astronaut and the first woman to command a space flight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
