<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO-060     06-06 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO-0607-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    HOPES FADE FOR QUICK PEACE AS KOSOVO WITHDRAWAL TALKS NEAR
COLLAPSE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ Hopes for a quick withdrawal of Serb-led
forces from Kosovo faded Sunday after Yugoslav military commanders
refused to sign an agreement putting the peace plan into action.
</P>
<P>
   As marathon talks edged into a third day early Monday in a
camouflage tent at this hot and dusty air field, NATO officials
were uncertain when _ or even if _ a so-called ``military technical
agreement'' would be signed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Yugoslav military commanders had agreed to
only six of the 20 conditions in the 6-page document, which lays
out conditions for the withdrawal of Serb military and police units
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do not sign the documents in their entirety, the air
campaign continues,'' said Maj. Trey Cate, a spokesman for the
American delegation to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the talks became snagged Sunday, NATO used U.S. B-52
bombers to pound Serb troops along Kosovo's border with Albania.
And early Monday morning, air raid sirens sounded in Belgrade,
warning of possible resumed NATO attacks in the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the Yugoslavs' reluctance
to sign the agreement was a stalling tactic. Pentagon officials
have said in recent days that Serb forces may want more time to
cover up evidence of atrocities before they are forced to withdraw
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There also were NATO reports Sunday of Serb forces looting the
towns of Prizren and Pristina inside Kosovo. Meanwhile, Serb forces
and pro-independence Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas engaged in
heavy fighting Sunday along the Kosovo-Albania border.
</P>
<P>
   The snag in the Kumanovo talks came as a surprise because the
Serb parliament had overwhelmingly approved the peace settlement
last Thursday. When the talks on implementing the settlement began
Saturday, NATO officials assumed Yugoslav military commanders would
quickly sign the agreement specifying the timetable and routes for
the rapid withdrawal of Serb-led forces.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after the talks resumed Sunday morning, it became
apparent there were problems. After several breaks requested by the
Yugoslav delegation, Cate told reporters they had made ``very
little progress.'' About the same time, Col. Carmine di Pascale,
head of the Italian delegation, reported ``all kinds of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Finnish President Marti Ahtisaari, who had brokered the
peace plan, abruptly cancelled a planned trip to discuss it with
Chinese leaders in Beijing amid speculation he might be asked to
resume his negotiating role.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and other allied officials said late Sunday that the
Yugoslav military commanders raised a number of objections to the
agreement. Among them, they:
</P>
<P>
   _ Could not withdraw all of their estimated 40,000 forces within
the specified 7-day period because they didn't have enough gas and
many of their vehicles were damaged. They reportedly wanted up to
ten days. They also reportedly said that many of their forces could
not quickly reach the three NATO-designated withdrawal routes from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Opposed withdrawing their forces from a 15-mile buffer zone
between Serbia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were unwilling to withdraw Serb police officers who are
residents of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Objected to the virtual simultaneous entry of NATO troops into
Kosovo at the same time that Serb-led forces were withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday in Washington, Army Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said on ABC-TV that the withdrawal
deadline could be extended a few days, but only for ``good
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, also appearing on ABC, warned:
``We're not going to allow any deliberate policy of delay day by
day.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was confusion Sunday about whether the KLA would
disarm, as called for in the peace plan. Shinasi Rama, a KLA
spokesman, told CNN that ``we see no reason'' to totally disarm,
arguing that guerrilla fighters should be permitted to retain small
arms like those Americans ``can buy in a K-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, aid workers at the main Stankovec refugee center in
Macedonia on Sunday attributed a near-riot and bloody attack on
five ethnic Roma, or gypsy, refugees three of them children to
mounting tensions over the talks. They also worried the incident
previewed how ugly relations may become in Kosovo among ethnic
Albanians, Serbs and other minority groups once the refugees do get
home again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad sign for any kind of ethnic tolerance inside Kosovo
when they go back,'' said Nancy Shalala, spokesperson for the
Catholic Relief Services. ``People are looking for some face to be
responsible for what happened inside Kosovo. This time the face was
the Romas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic agency's volunteers and international staff dragged
a Roma father and son from a crowd that was battering them Saturday
night around 7:30 p.m. Some ethnic Albanian refugees believed the
two men had been collaborators with Serb forces and were
responsible for killing some Albanians, Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers took the Romas, who are also considered gypsies, to
an agency office for protection. But the crowd built until some
angry refugees stormed the office and beat the two men nearly
senseless.
</P>
<P>
   The attacking refugees finally were driven outside, but then set
upon three Roma children and tried ``to rip them limb from limb,''
Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   All five were rescued and taken for medical treatment, but only
after U.S. Ambassador Christopher Hill came to the scene and
quieted the teeming crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more tense now,'' said refugee Musa Govori, 32, who
said he witnessed part of the melee and Hill's intervention.
``These people have already learned a lot from the Milosevic's past
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees not only are afraid the talks may not bear fruit, but
also now must confront the uncertainty of what destruction and loss
they will find at home if the talks do succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
