<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CONNERLY-2TAKES-A     06-06 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CONNERLY-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST COAST CHAMPION OF ENDING AFFIRMATIVE ACTION AIMS AT FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash.)   (ART ADV: A photo was sent Thursday, June 3. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (DW) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI, Fla. _ Ward Connerly, who campaigned successfully to end
affirmative action in government hiring and school admissions in
California and Washington State, has now aimed his crusade at
Florida, to the sound of slamming doors.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders here, Democrats and Republicans, blacks,
whites and Hispanic, do not want Connerly, a conservative black
businessman, in Florida, and they definitely do not want his
initiative on the ballot in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who has managed to draw together the political elite
in this racially diverse and often discordant state, said Florida
political leaders were behaving like ostriches, ``with their heads
in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Black political leaders and many Hispanic ones around the
country see Connerly as a pariah, a traitor who plans to amend the
Florida Constitution to stop preference programs based on race, sex
or ethnicity in government hiring and contracts and college
admissions, robbing them of one of the spoils of the civil rights
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders, in Florida and elsewhere in the country,
have another reason for turning their backs to him. Connerly has
brought his divisive issue to the doorstep of Gov. Jeb Bush just as
his older brother, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is preparing to
enter the race for the Republican Presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The issue could, political experts say, create cracks in the
national Republican Party's ranks, just as the Bush brothers are
working to unify them, and hamper efforts to draw in disaffected
Democrats in time for the election.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of his campaign was no coincidence, concedes
Connerly, 60, the chairman of the American Civil Rights Institute
and a regent of the University of California system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can bring Florida into the win column, we will have
brought a major player in the national scene into the family,''
Connerly said in a recent telephone interview from his office in
Sacramento, Calif., ``and will be well on our way to declaring
victory in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no better forum'' for debating affirmative action, he
said, ``than a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who ignored pleas from Republican leaders and black
officials to keep his crusade out of Florida, said that he needed
the street-level voters, not their leadership, to pass his
initiative, and that he was confident that working people in
Florida would vote for it as they did in his home state,
California, four years ago and, a year later, in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, pollsters and political experts agree that he has a
good chance of getting his initiative approved, if he succeeds in
getting the question on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, Connerly must gather the signatures of about 430,000
registered voters. Political experts in Florida say the effort can
cost $1 to $2 a name, money that would probably come from
supporters of the proposition. The battle against affirmative
action in California cost about $6 million, with the Republican
Party putting up $2.5 million and other backers raising $3.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it gets on there, it will pass,'' said Dario Moreno, a
professor of political science at Florida International University
who has studied this state's political makeup.
</P>
<P>
   But at stake in the battle, Moreno said, may be more than a
program that has opened doors for minorities and women in business,
government work and universities.
</P>
<P>
   While it would certainly not be the deciding issue in the 2000
campaign, the initiative could create political problems for the
Bush brothers, say political experts and Connerly himself.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers ran campaigns that ``reached out to people'' other
than to the white, conservative Republicans, even as they tried to
retain the party's core supporters, Moreno said. If the proposition
gets onto the ballot in Florida, he said, it would ``undermine the
Bush message, by both brothers, at the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   But Connerly said: ``I want this to be part of the presidential
debate. It scares the hell out of Jeb Bush, because he doesn't want
it on the ballot when his brother runs for office.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the brothers are snubbing Connerly. But Jeb Bush, who
counts on conservatives as a major pillar of support, has written
Connerly, saying: ``Dear Ward, I oppose rigid quotas and
set-asides.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush went on to say that ``a bitter political campaign that
divides Florida by race or ethnicity'' would keep the state
political leadership from focusing on ``more pressing issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said that he expected to battle the state's black
leadership but also asserted that the Republican leadership was
being hypocritical, accusing it of playing politics while ignoring
many Republican voters' opposition to affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why that is controversial,'' he said of his
position.
</P>
<P>
   But affirmative action is an issue that people argue from the
head, and heart, and he has become its lightning rod.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, perhaps one of the best-known black conservatives in
the United States, besides Justice Clarence Thomas of the Supreme
Court, has provoked the disdain and outright dislike of many blacks
and political leaders by asserting that affirmative action has gone
too far. He has been called an Uncle Tom and had rocks hurled by
protesters at his office. Instead of correcting the prejudices of
the past, he says, affirmative action has become just another form
of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly has the support of Florida's builders' associations,
which are weary of rigid affirmative action requirements in Florida
contracts, but there was no grass-roots anti-affirmative-action
movement in Florida, political experts say, until he began his
drive for an initiative just a few weeks ago. Since then, he has
been featured in newspapers and television programs, and black
newspaper columnists have criticized his plans.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the opposition Connerly has found among the
political leadership and others, polls in Florida have shown that
many voters believe that affirmative action has crossed the line
from an advantage to reverse discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kane, editor in chief of The Florida Voter, a polling
service based in Fort Lauderdale, said a recent poll showed that 84
percent of more than 600 voters surveyed by telephone would vote
for a ban on affirmative action similar to the measure that was
passed in California in 1996, Proposition 209, if it was worded
similarly. The survey had a margin of sampling error of plus or
minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The California initiative said ``the state shall not
discriminate against or grant preferential treatment to'' anyone
based on race or sex.
</P>
<P>
   But the Florida survey found that when residents were asked
whether they would support an initiative that would ``prohibit
affirmative action'' for women and minorities, only 42 percent said
they would vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   There seemed to be stronger support in the state for another
statement in The Florida Voter poll. The poll said: ``Irish,
Italians, Jewish and many other minorities overcame prejudice and
worked their way up. Blacks should do the same without any special
favors.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked for a response, 52 percent strongly agreed and 29
percent somewhat agreed.
nn
</P>
<P>
   Countering the arguments of his opponents, Connerly says
affirmative action creates a society in which those who get an
unfair advantage will live their lives doomed to feelings of
inferiority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got 30 percent of the black vote on 209,'' he said. ``I
want black kids and Latino kids to believe they are 10 feet tall
and made out of steel, believing that they can navigate this system
and come out on top. If you walk around believing that everybody is
a racist who knocks you down, it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly is ignoring the realities of racism, his critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minority communities across the nation are reeling in poverty,
disinvestment and red-lining, and racism is still deeply imbedded
in our minds and manifested through a lack of educational and
professional opportunities,'' said Alicia Hughes, a second-year law
student at the University of Miami and president of the Black Law
Student Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is a slanted scale,'' Ms. Hughes added ``it
is necessary that there are programs like affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Another second-year law school student there, Dolly Hernandez,
said she wanted to feel as if she could compete equally, regardless
of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's race, religion, sex or creed should be the deciding
factor,'' Ms. Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly expects more hurdles to get his proposition on the
ballot, including state election guidelines that insist that such
initiatives be on a single subject. Calling for an end to
affirmative action on the basis of race and sex, for instance,
could violate that guideline.
</P>
<P>
   But those are just details, for a true believer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
