<HEADLINE>
TEXAS POLICE LOOK FOR POSSIBLE LINK IN RECENT KILLINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ky.) 
 
By STEPHEN JOHNSON 
and LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The bludgeoning deaths of a southeast Houston woman
and an elderly woman in Fayette County over the weekend were under
investigation Sunday by officials trying to determine if they are
related to recent slayings in West University Place and Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   In each instance, authorities suspect the victims were killed by
intruders who broke into their homes after possibly arriving in the
area by freight train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking into that (the similarities),'' Houston homicide
Lt. Ronald Walker said. ``There are some slight similarities in
those cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But Walker would not go into details, saying only that they had
not ruled out anything.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent slaying is that of Noemi Dominguez who
authorities would only say was struck a fatal blow to the head. Her
body was found by her brother Saturday in the bedroom of her
southeast Houston home, but investigators believe she had been dead
since late Thursday or early Friday. A Houston Belt and Terminal
Railway Co. line runs behind her home.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he believed Dominguez was an inner-city school
teacher and a graduate of Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   Police also are looking for Dominguez's missing 1993 white Honda
Civic, Texas license JJH 57N, with a black and white bumper sticker
printed with Japanese writing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fayette County Sheriff's Department investigators,
assisted by Fort Bend County deputies and the Texas Rangers, are
working to determine who killed 73-year-old Josephine Konvicka, who
was found bludgeoned to death Friday in her Weimar-area home.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar is about 90 miles west of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Someone attempted to steal Konvicka's car but failed to locate
the keys that Konvicka left in a drawer, according to Sheriff Rick
Vandel. The killer and would-be car thief had cut the electrical
connection to the car's dome light to keep it from coming on while
he was inside the car, Vandel said.
</P>
<P>
   Vandel said he was told by Texas Rangers of the Dominguez
slaying and that efforts were being made to determine if the
Konvicka and Dominguez slayings could be linked since both women
were bludgeoned to death and the homes of both were located near
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   A mere 3 1/2 miles east of Konvicka's home was the residence of
the Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife Karen 47, who
were both discovered bludgeoned to death May 2. Their killer
apparently had used a sledgehammer on the couple after entering the
rear of their home behind the Weimar Church of Christ, where Sirnic
was pastor. A car belonging to the Sirnics was also taken.
</P>
<P>
   Similarities between the killings of the Sirnics and the Dec.
17, 1998, slaying of Dr. Claudia Benton at her West University home
prompted the Weimar Police Department and West University police to
compare notes on the crimes in their respective cities. Benton also
lived near railroad tracks and a car was taken from her residence.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Benton and Sirnic cars were located in San Antonio
after being abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   A suspect in the slaying of Benton is Rafael Resendez-Rameriz
whose criminal history spans two decades. A transient, Rameriz is
suspected of riding freight trains and is described as 5-foot-7 and
weighing 150 pounds. Resendez-Rameriz's fingerprints were found
inside a Jeep Cherokee stolen from Benton's home.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is also considered a possible suspect by
Lexington, Ky., officials in the unsolved 1997 slaying there of
University of Kentucky student, Christopher Maier. Maier, 21, was
beaten to death and his girlfriend was assaulted as the couple
walked along railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
