<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDSOX07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez delivers late again
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Safe to say the Fenway faithful had about enough of
Javy Lopez for one weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Lopez mustered a game-winning hit
to spoil another sunny afternoon for a sold-out Red Sox crowd. This
one was a two-out single in the 10th inning Sunday. It came after
he fouled off a couple two-strike pitches and lined a Jim Corsi
curve into left-center to score Otis Nixon from second for a 3-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``A (curveball) was the only thing I was looking for,'' said
Lopez, who yanked a Tom Gordon curve down the third-base line in
the ninth on Saturday to drive in two runs for a 6-5 victory. ``I
told myself if I'm ready for the curveball, I can make an
adjustment to hit the fastball in. That's what he'd been throwing
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves managed only four hits in the first nine innings and
two runs, both knocked in by designated hitter Keith Lockhart.
After failing to manufacture a run in the ninth after a leadoff hit
by Andruw Jones, the Braves buckled down an inning later. Walt
Weiss singled, Bret Boone moved pinch-runner Nixon over with a
sacrifice, and Chipper Jones was intentionally walked. A Brian
Jordan flyout brought up Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   After they were dominated by Pedro Martinez Friday, the Braves
scraped together back-to-back wins and headed home up 2-1 in
interleague play after facing the top team in the American League
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good, especially the way we did it,'' Boone said. ``We're
not hitting on all cylinders. Fact is Milly (Kevin Millwood)
pitched a great game again. That's six or seven in a row now. Only
one pitch hurt him all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood had a no-hitter going into the seventh before Boston
took care of that, along with the shutout and the Braves' 2-0 lead.
John Valentin singled sharply to left on the first pitch of the
seventh, and then with two outs, Troy O'Leary drove a fastball for
a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   That's the pitch that had been working for Millwood most of the
day, but he left it over the plate instead of off the plate inside
like he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a lot sharper,'' said Millwood, who failed to get a
win for the first time in five starts. ``But that's what pitching
is all about, you have to make adjustments and find ways to get
people out. I was able to locate (my fastball) in and out. Got away
with all but one.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
