<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More homers, less stress for Jordan in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With two home runs in the past four games, Brian Jordan
has 13 home runs, which is tied with Chipper Jones for the Braves'
lead, and well on the way to making this quite a year for the
club's new cleanup hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan hit a career-high 25 home runs with the Cardinals last
season. If he maintains this season's pace, he has a shot a 40.
Last year at the all-star break, Jordan had 15 home runs and 56
RBIs. Currently, he has 13 home runs and 52 RBIs and the all-star
break is still more than five weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relaxing, having fun,'' Jordan said. ``It was more
stressful last year because of the pressure of being the No. 4
hitter behind Mark McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 32, has been playing baseball only for the past six
years. He said he's still learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take more chances now because I'm learning the game, more
experienced,'' he said. ``I don't know what my potential is. I just
go out, play hard and hopefully get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The `playing hard' part has been evidenced by Jordan's bumps and
bruises _ starting with his left hamstring strain, left ankle
strain, a sore left abdomen from sliding into first last Wednesday
and then a sore left knee from running into the right-field wall
trying to catch a foul ball on Saturday. Through it all, he's only
missed one game.
</P>
<P>
   With numbers like these, Jordan has made a case to be a National
League all-star though he was disappointed last year when NL
all-star manager Jim Leyland didn't choose him despite his
league-leading .339 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has plans to spend the all-star break with his family at
their vacation home in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go to the All-Star Game,'' Jordan said. ``To get
that experience, just to say I've been.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart's chance
</P>
<P>
   The at-bats have been few and far between for backup second
baseman Keith Lockhart this season, so Sunday's return to the
lineup as the Braves designated hitter was welcome. He came through
with a hit and two RBIs in four at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Lockhart's fifth start of the season through 56
games. His 49 at-bats is the lowest total of any position player
for the Braves. He is hitting .222, ahead of only Gerald Williams
(.195), Otis Nixon (.171) and Ozzie Guillen (.151).
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no rhythm, there is no flow _ you just don't play
enough,'' Lockhart said. ``I thought I'd be in there a little bit
more. I just kind of go with the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Grab that baseball
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz needs one strikeout in today's start against the
Devil Rays to reach 2,000 for his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two thousand will be neat,'' he said. ``Not a ton of people
have achieved it. It's like a feather in your cap.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will stop long enough for the Braves to retrieve the
ball.Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
