<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSING-WORKERS-SPI &LR;      06-06 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-WORKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S COSTLY HOUSING MAKING IT HARDER FOR EMPLOYERS TO LURE
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN AND TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Joe Soroka survived the move from the moderately
priced and stable housing market of Cleveland to the increasingly
pricey housing market in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was a ``sizable salary increase to be motivated to
come out here,'' the banker says _ and a willingness to commute 30
miles each day from North Bend to downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew prior to coming out here it was going to be more
expensive,'' says Soroka, vice president of international banking
at KeyBank. ``It was more than I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's too expensive. Soroka knows of one colleague who
declined a transfer to Seattle because of the cost of housing here.
</P>
<P>
   Other employers are hearing the same thing. A handful of recent
Lake Washington School District job offers were met with the reply
``I'd love to work there, but I can't afford to live there,'' says
Sharon Weston, employment coordinator for the Kirkland and Redmond
district.
</P>
<P>
   High prices, especially for housing, don't stop people from
coming. The vibrancy of the economy, the companies here that lead
their respective industries, the cultural life, the scenery and
even the weather are irresistible lures to many.
</P>
<P>
   But costly housing is making it increasingly difficult to
recruit employees to the region, employers say. Recruits who turn
down job offers here cite the cost of housing almost as often as
impacts on family, adds Shari Blackwood, relocation director for
the real estate firm Coldwell Banker Bain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be addressed, but it's tougher and tougher,'' says
Gayle Glew, president of Windermere Relocation, which handles about
500 transfers a month.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are using signing bonuses, cost-of-living adjustments
and other incentives where they can. But ``sticker shock is here
with us,'' says Glew.
</P>
<P>
   Sticker shock is biting both newcomers and those already here.
The median price of home and condominium sales in King County was
$208,975 in April, up 8.9 percent from the same month a year ago
and up 28 percent from April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But people still come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fall in love with the area; if they're married and have
kids, it's even worse,'' says Key Bank Vice Chairman Luke Helms.
The area's lures make them overlook or compensate for a lot of
drawbacks, like the cost of housing. Helms says they get a look at
the area and say ``Forget the rain, forget the traffic, I'm still
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   High housing prices aren't likely to choke the region's economy
because employers can't get the people they want. One reason is
that prices aren't uniform across the region. While the squeeze is
the worst in Seattle and the Eastside, a recruit to a company in
Federal Way, for example, can still find plenty of reasonably
priced houses in South King County or in Pierce County.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Seattle is by no means the least affordable housing
market in the country. San Francisco and Silicon Valley are far
worse. And as Helms notes, ``The Bay Area is booming, this one is
booming.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that high housing prices don't provoke a lot of grumbling
from those who move here. ``If they're in a 3,000-square-foot house
in Denver, Kansas City or Minneapolis, either they have to
downscale if they want to keep the payments the same,'' or they
have to pay more than they were expecting, Glew says. ``To many of
them, it's depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Soroka sold a 55-year-old, 1,950-square-foot house about 12
miles from the office in Cleveland for a 3-year-old,
2,200-square-foot house in North Bend. The North Bend house cost
twice as much as the one he sold in Cleveland. And the North Bend
home probably cost a third more than a comparable recently built
home in the Cleveland area.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Williams moved the opposite direction, from Seattle to
Cleveland. An assistant vice president of executive communications
at KeyBank, Williams sold a small two-bedroom house in Shoreline _
``kind of a classic Seattle starter home'' _ for a three-bedroom,
two-bath home in Bay Village, a suburb 12 miles west of downtown
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get twice as much home for 10 percent more''
than what he had sold his Shoreline home for, Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   For that extra 10 percent, Williams not only got a house with
double the space (not counting the full basement) but private beach
rights to a neighborhood park, complete with benches and barbecue
pit, along Lake Erie. While utility costs are higher _ both because
of the winters and because Seattle has the lowest electric rates in
the country _ on the whole, he says, ``We did very very well.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact this was the second move Williams has made to a more
affordable market. In 1988 he moved from Los Angeles to Seattle
because ``we thought we might be able to afford a house in
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Those moving to Seattle today start with the notion of looking
for a reasonably priced home within a reasonable commute of where
they work, Helms says. ``That's out.''
</P>
<P>
   So buyers adjust. One way is to accept a longer commute (which
helps accentuate the region's traffic snarls, but that's another
issue). Soroka was wary of living north or south of downtown
because of clogged Interstate-5, but finds the traffic on
Interstate-90 comparable to what he encountered in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers may think they're moving to Seattle, and that may be
where the job is. But ``if they actually end up buying in Puyallup,
that's perfectly acceptable to them,'' Glew says.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond police Officer Craig Shanks' traffic-snarled commute
from Renton takes at least 30 minutes each day. He'd like to move
closer, but houses in Redmond were way out of his price range when
he moved from South Dakota in August.
</P>
<P>
   A Northwest native, Shanks had only been away in South Dakota
for four years. When he moved back, he was astounded by hefty
Eastside house prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the money we wanted to spend, it was horrible,'' he says
of rickety fixer-uppers selling for upwards of $200,000. ``Hence,
we live in Renton.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Seattle-area housing market looks quite different to
roughly a dozen new deputies hired by the King County Sheriff's
office this year. They were recruited from Hawaii, where the
salaries are lower and house prices are higher.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's office recruiters have actively looked toward Honolulu
and surrounding areas, knowing many police officers there have both
the talent and the desire to move to a place where salaries and the
cost of living aren't so far apart, according to King County
sheriff's spokesman John Urquhart.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers also console themselves with the notion of price
appreciation: Whatever they paid, they'll probably be able to sell
for more. Given the economic prospects of the region, a meltdown in
housing prices is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly important for buyers who expect to be
transferred out of this market by their employers in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are helping too. ``We've seen some significant
cost-of-living adjustments extrapolated into recruiting
proposals,'' Windermere's Glew says.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood, of Coldwell Banker Bain's relocation services, says
some employers will help recruits with the sale of their old house,
or cover closing costs and points on a new property.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't help directly with the cost of housing, employers
and relocation experts may offer other assistance. Blackwood says
employers will offer job-placement help to spouses of recruits. She
has even seen employers help recruits with relocation of elderly
parents for whom they're caring.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the companies, relocation is an expensive proposition,''
Blackwood says.
</P>
<P>
   But in a tight labor market, ``It's a cost of doing business,''
and businesses figure the cost is worth it if it helps retain those
employees, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a sign-on bonus has helped Bellevue's Overlake Hospital
hire nurses. There's been a shortage of candidates, and the area's
cost of living has only compounded the problem of bringing in
people, said Lori Vocca, the hospital's employment and employee
relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   The private hospital used to pay only top-level recruits for the
expense of relocating to this area. These days, the hospital gets _
and grants _ more and more requests to help people with moving
costs, Vocca said.
</P>
<P>
   Those options aren't available to all employers though. A public
school system like Lake Washington can't offer pay incentives,
bonuses or help with moving expenses, Weston says.
</P>
<P>
   It has cost the district some candidates who were ``highly
qualified and would have been a good asset for our district,'' she
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2TAKE     06-06 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYPSIES ATTACKED BY REFUGEES, SPARKING FEARS OF CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANKOVEC I REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ For a moment, it seemed as
if the mob of Albanian refugees would literally tear the 7-year-old
Gypsy boy apart, limb from limb, said three aid workers who saw the
attack on Saturday night. Minutes earlier, 15 to 20 enraged Kosovo
Albanian refugees had beaten the boy's older brother and father,
whom they accused of collaborating with the Serbs and killing
Albanians inside Kosovo last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The look in their eyes when they tried to tear this boy's arms
out _ there was just fire in their eyes,'' said Ed Joseph, of the
Catholic Relief Service, one of the aid workers who pulled the boy
from the mob. ``I was just grabbing them and shouting `No! No! You
won't!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The attack was part of a chaotic and terrifying four-hour siege
here as a mob of several thousand Kosovo Albanian refugees tried to
seize and beat the Gypsy family.
</P>
<P>
   The attack illustrated both the chaos NATO forces could face in
Kosovo when hundreds of thousands of Albanian refugees return home
to the shattered province _ and NATO's reluctance to get involved
in such conflicts. Many of the Albanians could arrive home intent
on exacting revenge on former Serbian and Gypsy neighbors who
attacked Kosovo Albanians or destroyed their homes.
</P>
<P>
   While most Serbs, and Gypsies have who allied themselves with
the Serbs, are expected to flee the province before any Kosovo
Albanians return, some elderly people could remain. Before the NATO
bombing campaign, Serbs made up roughly 10 percent of Kosovo's
population and Gypsies about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Gypsies attacked on Saturday had been in the camp for weeks
after crossing the border from Kosovo. While refugees have reported
that Gypsies in some Kosovo cities have allied themselves with the
Serbs, it was unclear whether this family was among them.
</P>
<P>
   In the attack, the refugees, chanting and screaming for blood,
tore down the fence surrounding the Catholic Relief Service's main
office here, kicked in the front door, tore bars from its windows
and used a metal gutter as a battering ram.
</P>
<P>
   The violence was only defused after hundreds of Macedonian riot
police arrived, and Christopher Hill, the U.S. ambassador to
Macedonia, addressed the mob at midnight and promised that justice
would be done in the case. Relief workers spirited the Gypsy family
and other Gypsies out of the camp and took the men who were beaten
to a Skopje hospital, where they remained hospitalized Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man's face was the color of an eggplant and his eyes were
swollen shut,'' said Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees. ``The other had been beaten with a stick
and had a very large wound on his head. It was very clear that if
they had been caught they would have been killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has been tense since refugees started pouring in from
neighboring Kosovo after NATO began its bombing in late March. But
it was the worst violence in Macedonia since Serbian protesters
ransacked the American Embassy at the outset of the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary authority NATO carries with the refugees and
the political sensitivity of its mission was shown during the
siege. The mob repeatedly demanded that NATO troops come to take
the Gypsies away to be held as war criminals. But officials of the
U.N . High Commissioner for Refugees, in consultation with NATO
officials, decided it was not part of NATO's mission in Macedonia
to carry out such an operation.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how NATO troops respond to similar situations inside
Kosovo could be crucial in their success. NATO officials are
already emphasizing that they will enforce any peace accord
``evenhandedly.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Trey Cate, a NATO spokesman, said that if they fire their
weapons, for instance, Serbian soldiers, as well as members of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the separatist Kosovo Albanian rebel group,
could potentially be fired on by NATO soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, NATO's only other peacekeeping mission, whether or
how NATO troops would intervene in such situations was the focus of
fierce debate. At the outset of that mission in 1996, NATO
commanders insisted they would not be involved in carrying out what
they saw as ``local police actions'' and instead delegated much
responsibility to local police forces controlled by Bosnia's three
ethnic factions. NATO officers feared being progressively drawn
into a larger and larger role in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Critics assailed the approach, saying it undermined NATO's
authority and allowed local Muslim, Serb and Croat authorities to
act in the sectors they controlled to thwart efforts by refugees
from other ethnic groups to return to the homes from which they
were expelled from during the war. Most refugees in Bosnia have not
returned to their homes more than two years after the Dayton Peace
Accord guaranteed that they could.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo represents a vastly different mission, but NATO is also
likely to face difficult decisions over the scope of its mission.
After NATO forces enter Kosovo, refugees now in the sweltering
camps here may grow tired of waiting for an organized return to
their homes and simply decide to head into Kosovo on their own.
</P>
<P>
   A chaotic scenario could develop in which NATO forces would be
in the awkward position of potentially blocking refugees from
returning to their country, a right they are guaranteed under
international law.
</P>
<P>
   A far larger problem could be revenge attacks. The Saturday
night attack here illustrates how intense the desire for vengeance
may prove.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, who was still shaken by the attack Sunday, said the
attack seemed to him to be a grim omen for what could happen in
Kosovo when the refugees return. ``I think it's a very bad
harbinger for any kind of reconciliation or easy peace,'' he said.
``Any Serb still there has to be packing his bags.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the refugee camps here are sweltering cauldrons of
hate, where increasingly frustrated Kosovo Albanians can
commiserate about their mutual victimization at the hands of the
Serbs. As might be expected, peer pressure is exerted in the camps
to hate Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cegrane camp here, which holds 40,000 refugees, children
recited poems to a crowd of refugees last Thursday that glorified
the Kosovo Albanian rebel soldiers and listed massacre after
massacre believed to have been committed by Serbs as their Albanian
teachers looked on approvingly. And most refugees interviewed here
Sunday said they believed the Gypsies who were attacked did commit
war crimes and applauded the mob's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the Hague for them,'' said Afrim Ademi, an Albanian
refugee, referring to the international war crimes tribunal in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of what sparked the attack on the Gypsies were already
rampant Sunday. Nancy A. Shalala, a spokeswoman for the Catholic
Relief Service who was trying to piece together what occurred
Saturday night, said that she repeatedly heard that a newly arrived
ethnic Albanian refugee said he recognized the Gypsy teen-ager
because he was wearing a piece of jewelry stolen from the refugee's
mother. The refugee reportedly said the Gypsy had killed his father
and then robbed his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The Gypsy teen-ager and his father were then beaten in separate
attacks and brought at about 7:30 p.m. to the Catholic Relief
building by Kosovo Albanians who work for the aid agency. A group
of 15 to 20 Albanian refugees stormed the building an hour later
and beat them two men even more fiercely. The aid agency's staff
staff finally pushed the group out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   A large crowd then began forming around the building, led by a
group of 150 to 200 men, Ms. Shalala said. The badly beaten father
and son were moved to the building's bathroom to prevent them from
being seen by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Aid agency workers also went to the family's tent to try to
retrieve the mother and three younger children before they too were
set upon by the Albanian refugees. When they arrived at the relief
agency's building, the 7-year-old boy was grabbed by the mob, but
then wrestled free by aid workers. With other Gypsies in the camp
being ``hunted like dogs,'' aid workers said, the aid workers tried
to hide them to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   The mob continued to grow. Efforts by Joseph and other aid
workers to use megaphones to get them to disperse failed. The crowd
repeatedly rushed the building, ripping bars from the windows. At
one point, Joseph said, he stood on a window ledge, imploring the
crowd to stop. At other times panicked aid workers stacked cots
against the chain link fence surrounding the building to prevent it
from giving way. They failed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ghedini, the refugee agency spokeswoman, said that at one
point her agency considered evacuating all foreigners from the
area. But when it became clear that the refugees' real hostility
was toward the Gypsies, she said, 17 Gypsies were evacuated from
the camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
