<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      06-06 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK TRYING TO ASSEMBLE DIVERSE GOVERNING COALITION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak appears ready to
form a midsize coalition government comprising the traditional
Israeli left, the new Israeli center, the settlers, the Russian
immigrants and the ultra-Orthodox of European descent.
</P>
<P>
   That would give him a 66-seat majority bloc in the 120-member
parliament, which is to be sworn in on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It would leave the conservative Likud Party and the Sephardic
ultra-Orthodox Shas Party in the opposition, at least at the start.
Intensive negotiations in the three weeks since Barak was elected
on May 17 have not paved the way to what he had hoped would be a
broad consensus government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now working toward a 66 government,'' Barak, the Labor
Party leader, said in a television interview Sunday night, his
first since election day. ``But the doors are open to Shas and the
Likud.''
</P>
<P>
   Policy differences _ on Jewish settlements in the West Bank and
the drafting of Orthodox yeshiva students into the military, for
instance _ remain to be ironed out within the 66-member bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has until July 8 to cobble together a Cabinet. The
negotiations have yet to begin. Although rumors about who will get
what post are rampant, Barak has been holding his cards close to
the vest.
</P>
<P>
   Only one position seems certain: Barak, a highly decorated
former general, is likely to serve as his own defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at a hotel in the seaside city of Herzliya, Barak's
negotiating team has been hammering out the coalition's principles,
broad enough to appeal to a motley group but not so broad that they
paralyze a new prime minister intent on making changes.
</P>
<P>
   They have been seeking common ground between wildly disparate
groups: how to reconcile Shinui, a new centrist party elected on an
anti-Orthodox platform, and United Torah Judaism, an ultra-Orthodox
party; how to find an acceptable middle road between Meretz, the
traditional leftist party that opposes the building of Jewish
settlements in the West Bank, and the Jewish settlers themselves,
represented by the rightist National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers on Sunday published the basic policy guidelines
outlined in the draft coalition agreement. They reported that
Barak's government would not establish any new settlements but
would not dismantle any existing ones. A clause refers to a review
of ``prior authorized decisions,'' leaving unclear the fate of
several projects recently approved by the departing government of
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Also, settlers would lose tax advantages and other benefits that
they have long enjoyed for establishing residence in the West Bank.
That section of the guidelines is under attack by the settlers and
by the leadership of Yisrael B'Aliya, the Russian immigrant party,
which strongly supports settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Navigating a path between the secular and religious parties, the
draft suggests that the government will work to prevent religious
legislation and either religious or anti-religious coercion.
</P>
<P>
   It also states relatively mildly that the government will ask
for legislation dealing with the drafting of yeshiva students, who
now are entitled to a deferment to study the Torah _ but not mildly
enough for the United Torah Judaism leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't agree to a situation in which a single soul that
thirsts for Torah will not be able to study,'' Meir Porush, a party
leader, was quoted by the newspaper Maariv as saying.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting Sunday between Barak and Ariel Sharon, the outgoing
foreign minister and temporary chairman of the Likud Party, ended
without any agreement. Sharon has reportedly been pressing to
retain his post as foreign minister, which is considered unlikely.
He also reportedly wants to shape a peace policy that sounds like
his own rather than Barak's.
</P>
<P>
   The draft guidelines call for accelerating negotiations with the
Palestinians and submitting a final-status agreement to a national
referendum. They suggest resuming talks with Syria based on
international agreements presuming the trading of land for peace _
that is, the return of part of the Golan Heights to Syria. And they
propose a withdrawal of Israeli troops from southern Lebanon but do
not repeat Barak's campaign promise to do so within a year.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-member coalition would include eight parties: Labor, now
called One Israel; Meretz; Shinui; the Center Party; Yisrael
B'Aliya; the National Religious Party; United Torah Judaism, and
One People, a workers' party that broke off from Labor.
</P>
<P>
   While Barak won an overwhelming victory in the vote for prime
minister, his party lost seats in parliament, as did Likud. Shas,
which represents Sephardic Jews whose families came to Israel from
Middle Eastern countries, won big, siphoning votes from Likud and
earning a place as a third major party.
</P>
</TEXT>
