</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-WORKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S COSTLY HOUSING MAKING IT HARDER FOR EMPLOYERS TO LURE
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN AND TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Joe Soroka survived the move from the moderately
priced and stable housing market of Cleveland to the increasingly
pricey housing market in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was a ``sizable salary increase to be motivated to
come out here,'' the banker says _ and a willingness to commute 30
miles each day from North Bend to downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew prior to coming out here it was going to be more
expensive,'' says Soroka, vice president of international banking
at KeyBank. ``It was more than I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's too expensive. Soroka knows of one colleague who
declined a transfer to Seattle because of the cost of housing here.
</P>
<P>
   Other employers are hearing the same thing. A handful of recent
Lake Washington School District job offers were met with the reply
``I'd love to work there, but I can't afford to live there,'' says
Sharon Weston, employment coordinator for the Kirkland and Redmond
district.
</P>
<P>
   High prices, especially for housing, don't stop people from
coming. The vibrancy of the economy, the companies here that lead
their respective industries, the cultural life, the scenery and
even the weather are irresistible lures to many.
</P>
<P>
   But costly housing is making it increasingly difficult to
recruit employees to the region, employers say. Recruits who turn
down job offers here cite the cost of housing almost as often as
impacts on family, adds Shari Blackwood, relocation director for
the real estate firm Coldwell Banker Bain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be addressed, but it's tougher and tougher,'' says
Gayle Glew, president of Windermere Relocation, which handles about
500 transfers a month.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are using signing bonuses, cost-of-living adjustments
and other incentives where they can. But ``sticker shock is here
with us,'' says Glew.
</P>
<P>
   Sticker shock is biting both newcomers and those already here.
The median price of home and condominium sales in King County was
$208,975 in April, up 8.9 percent from the same month a year ago
and up 28 percent from April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But people still come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fall in love with the area; if they're married and have
kids, it's even worse,'' says Key Bank Vice Chairman Luke Helms.
The area's lures make them overlook or compensate for a lot of
drawbacks, like the cost of housing. Helms says they get a look at
the area and say ``Forget the rain, forget the traffic, I'm still
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   High housing prices aren't likely to choke the region's economy
because employers can't get the people they want. One reason is
that prices aren't uniform across the region. While the squeeze is
the worst in Seattle and the Eastside, a recruit to a company in
Federal Way, for example, can still find plenty of reasonably
priced houses in South King County or in Pierce County.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Seattle is by no means the least affordable housing
market in the country. San Francisco and Silicon Valley are far
worse. And as Helms notes, ``The Bay Area is booming, this one is
booming.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that high housing prices don't provoke a lot of grumbling
from those who move here. ``If they're in a 3,000-square-foot house
in Denver, Kansas City or Minneapolis, either they have to
downscale if they want to keep the payments the same,'' or they
have to pay more than they were expecting, Glew says. ``To many of
them, it's depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Soroka sold a 55-year-old, 1,950-square-foot house about 12
miles from the office in Cleveland for a 3-year-old,
2,200-square-foot house in North Bend. The North Bend house cost
twice as much as the one he sold in Cleveland. And the North Bend
home probably cost a third more than a comparable recently built
home in the Cleveland area.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Williams moved the opposite direction, from Seattle to
Cleveland. An assistant vice president of executive communications
at KeyBank, Williams sold a small two-bedroom house in Shoreline _
``kind of a classic Seattle starter home'' _ for a three-bedroom,
two-bath home in Bay Village, a suburb 12 miles west of downtown
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get twice as much home for 10 percent more''
than what he had sold his Shoreline home for, Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   For that extra 10 percent, Williams not only got a house with
double the space (not counting the full basement) but private beach
rights to a neighborhood park, complete with benches and barbecue
pit, along Lake Erie. While utility costs are higher _ both because
of the winters and because Seattle has the lowest electric rates in
the country _ on the whole, he says, ``We did very very well.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact this was the second move Williams has made to a more
affordable market. In 1988 he moved from Los Angeles to Seattle
because ``we thought we might be able to afford a house in
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Those moving to Seattle today start with the notion of looking
for a reasonably priced home within a reasonable commute of where
they work, Helms says. ``That's out.''
</P>
<P>
   So buyers adjust. One way is to accept a longer commute (which
helps accentuate the region's traffic snarls, but that's another
issue). Soroka was wary of living north or south of downtown
because of clogged Interstate-5, but finds the traffic on
Interstate-90 comparable to what he encountered in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers may think they're moving to Seattle, and that may be
where the job is. But ``if they actually end up buying in Puyallup,
that's perfectly acceptable to them,'' Glew says.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond police Officer Craig Shanks' traffic-snarled commute
from Renton takes at least 30 minutes each day. He'd like to move
closer, but houses in Redmond were way out of his price range when
he moved from South Dakota in August.
</P>
<P>
   A Northwest native, Shanks had only been away in South Dakota
for four years. When he moved back, he was astounded by hefty
Eastside house prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the money we wanted to spend, it was horrible,'' he says
of rickety fixer-uppers selling for upwards of $200,000. ``Hence,
we live in Renton.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Seattle-area housing market looks quite different to
roughly a dozen new deputies hired by the King County Sheriff's
office this year. They were recruited from Hawaii, where the
salaries are lower and house prices are higher.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's office recruiters have actively looked toward Honolulu
and surrounding areas, knowing many police officers there have both
the talent and the desire to move to a place where salaries and the
cost of living aren't so far apart, according to King County
sheriff's spokesman John Urquhart.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers also console themselves with the notion of price
appreciation: Whatever they paid, they'll probably be able to sell
for more. Given the economic prospects of the region, a meltdown in
housing prices is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly important for buyers who expect to be
transferred out of this market by their employers in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are helping too. ``We've seen some significant
cost-of-living adjustments extrapolated into recruiting
proposals,'' Windermere's Glew says.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood, of Coldwell Banker Bain's relocation services, says
some employers will help recruits with the sale of their old house,
or cover closing costs and points on a new property.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't help directly with the cost of housing, employers
and relocation experts may offer other assistance. Blackwood says
employers will offer job-placement help to spouses of recruits. She
has even seen employers help recruits with relocation of elderly
parents for whom they're caring.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the companies, relocation is an expensive proposition,''
Blackwood says.
</P>
<P>
   But in a tight labor market, ``It's a cost of doing business,''
and businesses figure the cost is worth it if it helps retain those
employees, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a sign-on bonus has helped Bellevue's Overlake Hospital
hire nurses. There's been a shortage of candidates, and the area's
cost of living has only compounded the problem of bringing in
people, said Lori Vocca, the hospital's employment and employee
relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   The private hospital used to pay only top-level recruits for the
expense of relocating to this area. These days, the hospital gets _
and grants _ more and more requests to help people with moving
costs, Vocca said.
</P>
<P>
   Those options aren't available to all employers though. A public
school system like Lake Washington can't offer pay incentives,
bonuses or help with moving expenses, Weston says.
</P>
<P>
   It has cost the district some candidates who were ``highly
qualified and would have been a good asset for our district,'' she
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSGORE-PROFILE-ART-6     06-06 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSGORE-PROFILE-ART-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPPER GORE REACHES SOME MILESTONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tipper Gore was tense.
</P>
<P>
   The question before her _ about whether her husband's designs on
the presidency had to be weighed before her recent disclosure of
her struggle with depression _ did not hew to the script she had
been following.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand at all,'' she said in a chiding, deeply
disappointed voice. Her revelation, she made clear, had nothing to
do with politics.
</P>
<P>
   That was surely true. That was also not the question. It was
recast: Given the ambitions of her husband, Vice President Al Gore,
did she not consult him about the timing and impact of what she
intended to say? Did they not talk about that?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Mrs. Gore said slowly, disbelievingly. ``No. No.''
</P>
<P>
   It was late one afternoon last week, and Mrs. Gore was giving
another interview to promote the first-ever White House Conference
on Mental Health, which will be held on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It is an event that she, as President Clinton's mental-health
policy adviser, was integral in planning and making happen. It is
also an event to which Mrs. Gore feels an intense personal
connection, and as it neared, she began talking publicly about her
own experience with mental illness, but in carefully chosen venues,
and on very strict terms.
</P>
<P>
   She would not say precisely when depression struck. She would
not say how long ago it lifted, or all the symptoms she exhibited,
or what medication she took.
</P>
<P>
   She would not even divulge these details to Oprah Winfrey, the
empress of empathy, who made do with assuring Mrs. Gore that
choosing mates who were dull but dutiful was the way to go. (``Give
me boring, honey,'' Ms. Winfrey had hooted. Mrs. Gore had laughed.)
</P>
<P>
   There was less laughter this time around, in a conversation that
lasted 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the first question came, she all but flinched. ``Oh,'' Mrs.
Gore said. ``Are we going to start right now?''
</P>
<P>
   When she was asked about the difficulty of being raised an only
child by a divorced mother who had had her own bouts of severe
depression, her answer was interrupted by her spokeswoman, Camille
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you do want to dispute the fact that you had a
difficult childhood,'' Ms. Johnston told Mrs. Gore, who was silent
for several beats, and then agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' Mrs. Gore said. ``I had a great childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she had told a television reporter recently that she
was one of her husband's closest advisers, she now said that she
could not remember that comment. Ms. Johnston piped up to clarify
that it had been ``a flip remark.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, defined constantly in relation to her husband, is
supposed to be the earthy, unguarded, effervescent one. Seemingly
everyone who knows her describes her this way, and the conventional
wisdom is that in the coming campaign, she will serve as an
essential antidote to Al, the unlabored warmth to his unyielding
chill.
</P>
<P>
   But on this occasion, Mrs. Gore seemed unprepared for that
assignment. Her answers were fuzzy, cautious, aloof.
</P>
<P>
   She was asked why, on the December day when the House impeached
Clinton, she was absent from the Democratic pep rally at which her
husband proclaimed that Clinton ``will be regarded in the history
books as one of our greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even remember when that was or what I might have been
doing that day,'' Mrs. Gore said. ``I may have been with my kids or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's expulsion from office would have made Gore the leader
of the free world, but Mrs. Gore said she paid limited heed to the
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went on with my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that life, especially in the last decade, has been
devoted to advocacy for the mentally ill and for an enlightened
attitude toward mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the last great stigmas of the 20th
century, really, to do away with,'' she said, ``and I think that we
can educate the American public, answer questions that they have
about mental health and illnesses and dispel fear, hopefully, by
replacing it with knowledge.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That concern carries over from her childhood, no matter how
those years are described.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was hospitalized twice for depression, leaving little
Mary Elizabeth Aitcheson _ the nickname Tipper came from a favorite
lullaby, ``Tippy Tippy Tin'' _ in her grandparents' care. Her
parents broke up when Tipper was just 4, and she has said that she
felt the stigma of that at school.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was a pivotal juncture in her life, she said, it
was marrying Al Gore. She said that his political career, along
with the couple's decision to have four children, derailed the
possibility of her becoming a professional therapist. She has a
master's degree in psychology from Vanderbilt University in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The mental-health conference is one of several milestones in her
life right now. Mrs. Gore, 50, will welcome her first grandchild
into the world in about a month. The formal kickoff for her
husband's campaign is next week.
</P>
<P>
   She was rushing off after this interview to record the
president's weekly radio address with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way for people to understand me the best,'' she
said before leaving, ``is for you to understand that I'm not really
of the political milieu.''
</P>
<P>
   If that was ever true, it is not anymore. Mrs. Gore is in the
swim, and the water will only get deeper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
