<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY: C'mon, Grandmama, let's see you hit that trey again _ this
time when you're really fouled. NBA Eastern Conference finals Game
4: Indiana at New York, Channel 4, 6 p.m. (NBC has Game 5 Wednesday
at 6 p.m. and, if necessary, Game 6 Friday and Game 7 Sunday, TBA) 
TUESDAY: Our scouting report says Darth Hasek has had plenty of
rest, while the Stars come out of a seven-game headbanger with Ed
Belfour's bell run. The Dominator, who used to be Belfour's backup
in Chicago, wants the Cup worse than Brett Hull, and he'll get it
in five. Stanley Cup Finals Game 1: Buffalo at Dallas, Channel 11,
5 p.m. (Fox Channel 11 also has Game 2 Thursday at 5 p.m.; ESPN has
Game 3 from Buffalo on Saturday at 5 p.m.) 
WEDNESDAY: Thanks to the Angels' Spanish-language TV friends,
there's beisbol en la tarde. You know Giants fans will watch.
Angels at San Francisco, Channel 52, 12:30 p.m. 
THURSDAY: Instead of another very special rerun of ``Golden
Girls,'' Lifetime breaks out the hoop chicks. But while the Lakers
were national TV's regular-season NBA darlings, the Sparks aren't.
Their first of 32 WNBA games, against Sacramento from the Forum,
doesn't make the tube. In fact, Lisa Leslie and her lady friends
get only six national exposures. Instead, the opening-night
spotlight is reserved for the defending champion Comets, who have
almost a third of their games on either ESPN, NBC or Lifetime.
WNBA: Houston at Orlando, Lifetime, 5 p.m. (Saturday, NBC has
Washington at Houston, 1 p.m.) 
FRIDAY: The Dodgers can help the Angels by cooling off the
Athletics; the Angels can help the Dodgers by tripping up the
Diamondbacks. The whole tank wins. But how does USC get a spot in
the College World Series? Dodgers at Oakland, Channel 5, 7 p.m.;
Arizona at Angels, Fox Sports West, 7 p.m.; College World Series
tournament, ESPN, 12:30 p.m. and 5 p.m. 
SATURDAY: Tough enough to gear up a ride for a 24-hour-long race?
How about broadcasting it that long? Speedvision almost does it,
with 20 hours of live coverage from the classic from Le Mans with
four Le Broadcasters. Gentlemen, start your No-Doz. 24 Hours of
LeMans, Speedvision, 6:30 a.m. 
SUNDAY: The NBA Finals could heat up today if the East series wraps
up by Friday. Otherwise, check out who's hot heading into next
week's U.S. Open golf championship or how hot tempers will be when
we face Iran again on the soccer field. NBA Finals Game 1, Channel
4, 1:30 p.m.; PGA's St. Jude Classic final round, Channel 7, noon;
U.S. men's soccer vs. Iran, Channel 7, 10 a.m.
