<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart 4th, still stalking win as rookie
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ A rookie hasn't won a Winston Cup race since 1987
_ when the late Davey Allison won in his 14th start _ or finished
in the top 10 in points since 1980. But 13 races into the season,
Tony Stewart appears ready to change all that.
</P>
<P>
   The former Indy League champion finished fourth in Sunday's MBNA
Platinum 400 in the No. 20 Pontiac, his third fourth-place finish.
He led the most laps, 127. And he remained fifth in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't pay for the first three-quarters of a race,''
Stewart said of his early-race dominance. ``We're gaining ground
and we're learning. Two or three top-fours in a row. I can't be
griping about this. I'm very happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was running second to Jeff Gordon after a four-tire pit stop
on lap 368 but fell to fourth seven laps later and never got
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told 'em I thought it was time to come in,'' Stewart said.
``I felt like my tires were gone at that time. We thought it was a
little bit of a gamble, but we went for it. (Gordon) was pulling
away from us a little bit, so we thought the only chance we had to
stay close to him was to put on four tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing his four-tire strategy to teammate Bobby Labonte's
topping-off fuel stop that determined the outcome of the race,
Stewart said, ``We're one race team at the shop and two race teams
at the track. They did what they thought was best for them. We were
getting as good fuel mileage as he was but we couldn't go as long
as Bobby could go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett still leads
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett finished fifth, leading once for 21 laps, to
maintain his Winston Cup points lead. He's 51 points ahead of Jeff
Burton and 69 ahead of Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is kind of the story of our season,'' Jarrett said. ``We
work hard and get better toward the end (of a race), but it's not
quite all together. If we keep coming out with top-fives we'll be
OK. It would be nice to have a day where we didn't make these
adjustments every single stop, and come out on one side or the
other where the car would be either too tight or too loose. But
that's not happening right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Earliest exit
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader, who started 16th, saw his day pretty much
destroyed on the seventh lap of the 400-lap race when his No. 33
Chevy was severely damaged by a crash into the front-stretch wall.
By the time the front end was cut off the car and patched together,
Schrader was 261 laps down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 28 car (Kenny Irwin) got into the back of me,'' Schrader
said. ``Everybody checked up (when Dick Trickle's No. 91 Chevy got
loose) and he didn't. With the banking here, you get little help.
You're not going to get it gathered back up.Pit accident
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Tracey, the gasman-truck driver for Rusty Wallace, injured
his left ankle in a pit mishap just before the third caution
period. According to team officials, Tracey was hit by an airgun
and a lugnut that spun off a tire as Wallace was leaving the pits.
He went to a local hospital to check for a possible hairline
fracture. Someone else had to drive Wallace's hauler home.
</P>
<P>
   Job swap at Sabco
</P>
<P>
   The two struggling Chevrolets of Team Sabco swapped crew chiefs
this weekend to try to change their luck. Scott Eggleston became
crew chief for Sabco's No. 40 Chevrolet and driver Sterling Marlin.
He moved the 20 feet or so in the team garage from where he was
crew chief for the No. 42 Chevy driven by Joe Nemechek. Team
manager Tony Glover will serve as interim crew chief for Nemechek.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin is 18th in Winston Cup points with one top-10 finish in
10 starts; Nemechek is 35th in points with one top 10. Nemechek
finished 25th after starting 27th Sunday; Marlin was 29th after
starting 33rd.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
