<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD'S LESSON TO MILLER: HOW TO BE A SUPERSTAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Bird always incorporated his Boston teammates
into the Celtics' offense, even encouraging them to shoot more when
they, too, became flammable. But if a crucial game was still
undecided in the final two minutes, well, the ball was going to
Bird; he had no qualms about phasing everyone else out.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Sunday if he ever deferred to Kevin McHale in that type of
situation, the coach of the Indiana Pacers curtly said, ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to get his behind out there and stand, and I'll go
in the post for a while,'' he said. ``Jordan is the same way.
Scottie could score six or eight points, but when it came down to
the last two minutes of the game, you knew who was going to have
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we have to do with Reggie. Reggie's got to have
the ball in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day the Pacers were recovering psychologically from Larry
Johnson's devastating four-point play that stole Game 3, Bird
challenged his best player to return to his clutch ways. His words
were spare, his demeanor matter-of-fact. But the message was clear:
from one superstar to another _ behave like one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go get the ball,'' Bird said, referring to Indiana's last
ill-fated possession that ended with Mark Jackson's fumbling in the
lane and releasing a difficult turnaround jump shot that fell a few
inches short. ``If you have to run out there and take it out of
Mark's hands, go get the ball. That's the way it is. Superstars are
supposed to go and get the basketball. Reggie didn't do it last
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller hit two free throws with two seconds left to win Game 2
on Tuesday in Indianapolis, but his late-game heroics have
dissipated almost as much as his numbers have for most of the
Eastern Conference finals. He has made less than 43 percent of his
shots and is averaging 15.6 points a game in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing statistic for Bird was Miller's scoring
total in the final 16 minutes 38 seconds of Game 3: 0. It is
baffling to Bird that Miller, a fabled Knick assassin, became
another role player in the final seconds on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bird put some of the onus on himself for failing to free Miller
for shots, and he gave credit to a stingy and menacing Knicks
defense that double-teams Miller on nearly every pick-and-roll
opportunity. Yet Bird's overriding theme focused on Miller's
mind-set; how the sinewy shooting guard needed to revert to being
the player who has haunted New York for much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, Reggie gets in this mind-set: `Well, they're
playing well, they're moving the ball well. I come off the pick,
they're going to double-team me, so let's let them play and go
ahead and finish this game out,''' Bird said. ``But you don't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller graciously took his lumps Sunday after the Pacers'
practice at Madison Square Garden, vowing to come out firing Monday
night. ``No question, I've got to be more aggressive,'' he said,
sitting casually in the Garden stands. ``I've got to shoot more, 15
to 20, sometimes even 25 shots. I think that's going to be the case
in Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that he and Allan Houston were essentially canceling
each other out and that he had to do a better job of trying to make
Houston guard him one-on-one. But ultimately he came back to Bird's
point about seizing the moment, saying, ``I think I'll just be a
ball hog and just run to the ball and shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, the Pacers are an extension of Bird, the Hall
of Fame player. Chris Mullin, the slow-footed forward with the
deadeye shot and deceptively quick hands. Jackson, with his
unparalleled ability to see a play before it develops. And Miller,
the money player unafraid to hoist a game-winning 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when one of those parts does not work correctly, the
Pacers look nothing like Bird; Miller and the rest resemble any
malfunctioning team that draws its coach's ire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember back when they were in the Eastern Conference
finals, when I wasn't coaching,'' Bird said. ``I'd watch and look
in the paper and say: `Wow, Miller just shot 12 times. You can't
win games with Miller shooting 12 times.' Well, now I'm in it and
he's shooting nine. So it shows what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird spoke to Miller privately Sunday about exerting more
influence on the series, which the Knicks lead 2-1 . But it's
unclear whether the message got through. After all, they had the
same type of talk about two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can ask him,'' Bird said. ``I said: `Reggie, there's times
during a game when you got to be selfish. All superstars are.'''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has brought many crazy, surreal moments to this rivalry
over the past seven years, and it speaks to his greatness in the
clutch that Bird and others now expect it from him. Maybe his tank
is emptying with all those fresh bodies the Knicks are throwing at
him. Maybe he's merely a spot-up jump shooter who is very human
with a hand in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Miller is about to add cruelly to New York's
post-season misery, waiting as always for the proper moment to
deliver his team and demoralize Spike Lee's.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, before he ever makes another game-winning shot, a
more immediate task awaits: Reggie Miller must first find a way to
get open and take one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
