u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-GUNS-REACT-NY     06-06 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-GUNS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT SHOOTINGS PUT SCHOOL RIFLE TEAMS UNDER MORE SCRUTINY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ga., Tenn., Ky, Miss. Ark., Colo.)   By RENWICK McLEAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some school-sponsored rifle teams and officer
training programs have come under scrutiny in recent weeks as
administrators redouble efforts to rid their schools of guns in the
wake of the Columbine High School shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Those schools with shooting ranges where competitive rifle teams
practice, are a particular concern for parents, administrators and
advocates of school safety who are uneasy about the proximity of
guns to classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, Va., for example, members of the rifle team for
Yorktown High School have been honing their shooting skills in the
dusty basement of the main school building for years. But now the
shooting range is drawing passionate opposition from parents and
may be turned into storage space as part of a plan to make room for
extra classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposal to ease crowding by abandoning the range
space predates the recent school shooting, the Arlington School
Board is now examining the issue through the lens of school
violence and gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the whole concept of whether it's appropriate to
have a rifle range in the school has become a consideration, even
though it wasn't originally,'' said Lisa Farbstein, spokeswoman for
Arlington Public Schools. Safety ``will be a factor in the school
board's decision,'' Ms. Farbstein said.
</P>
<P>
   For some parents, keeping guns out of schools has become
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I detest guns, and I don't think they belong in our schools,''
said Martha Rutter, whose daughter, Katie, is a junior at Yorktown.
``I am completely against the range.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of high school rifle teams nationwide is difficult to
determine because most operate outside the auspices of state
athletic associations. Gary L. Anderson, a two-time target-shooting
Olympic gold medalist in the 300-meter rifle and the director of
the Wolf Creek Olympic Shooting Complex in Atlanta, Ga., estimated
that the total is 800 to 900. The vast majority of them use only
air rifles, he said, but several use the more powerful .22-caliber
rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps sponsor 2,587
Junior Reserve Officer Training Corps programs at high schools in
all 50 states, reaching hundreds of thousands of youngsters. Rifle
training is a frequent _ but not mandatory _ part of the
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the Clinton administration has advocated ``zero
tolerance'' for guns in schools, and the Department of Education
reported in its most recent Annual Report on School Safety that in
1996-97, 91 percent of public schools in the United States had
adopted such policies.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Secondary School Principals, has no
policy about rifle teams training on school grounds. It promotes a
``zero-tolerance policy concerning weapons in school,'' and says
school weapons policies must be ``blindly enforced across the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of school safety point to what they view as a
contradiction between those policies and school-sponsored rifle
training. They say concerns about violence have prompted more and
more school districts to reexamine such sports and training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a double standard,'' said Ronald D. Stephens, the
Executive Director of the National School Safety Center. ``What are
school administrators supposed to do when students are carrying
weapons on campus in connection with JROTC and other rifle training
programs?''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hetler, a training technician for the JROTC Directorate at
U.S. Army Cadet Command, dismissed the suggestion that rifle
training by the program presents any threat to students. ``None of
these kids are ever without adult supervision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash against rifle shooting on campus has affected
schools with a strong tradition in the sport, like Montgomery Bell
Academy in Nashville, Tenn. The school's rifle coach, Leo Lujan,
fears that his proposal for a new shooting facility on school
grounds will be doomed. ``If this continues, I am sure it will
affect our ability to raise funds for the range,'' Lujan said. The
new range would cost about $250,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Gioia, the academy's headmaster, said that if the project
is approved, ``we will have to do a really good job articulating
why we want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery Bell rifle team, which has been a part of the
academy's extracurricular life for several decades, uses a room at
the school for practice. But while Gioia praised the rifle coach's
commitment to safety, he said the Littleton killings have made him
anxious about holding rifle practice in the school. ``I would put
more controls on it now than ever before,'' he said. ``Anyone
following the news would have concerns, as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of high school rifle teams say the sport is being
unfairly maligned in response to the school shootings in Littleton
and those in in West Paducah, Ky.; Pearl, Miss., and Springfield,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a bit disappointed that some people associate school
violence with a legitimate team sport,'' said Keith Dowling, a
sophomore marksman on the rifle team at Yorktown High School who
hopes to continue competitive shooting in college. ``It's a great
sport, and just like any other, it teaches you sportsmanship,
responsibility, and cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the gold medal winner, echoed the student's concerns
and called the scrutiny an overreaction.'' If anything, he
contended, ``people that are taught marksmanship are even less
likely do anything dangerous with a gun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
