A5075 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIREDSIDE-SFCHRON &LR;      06-06 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIREDSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Co-Founder Talks About Life After Wired  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Louis Rossetto turned 50 yesterday.
<P>
   He's got a 2-year-old son and a 10-day-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   He's investing in high-brow online smut.
</P>
<P>
   And he refuses to talk about Wired.
</P>
<P>
   As painful as it was for the pioneering publisher to leave the
company he founded, he said in a phone interview that it's not his
place to critique the new management's stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should be making comments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rossetto and his wife and business partner, Jane Metcalfe, live
in Berkeley and spend much of their time raising their kids, Orson
and Zoe. While Rossetto is thinking about his next venture, that's
probably not coming any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably have lots of other businesses,'' he said. ``The
question is, do I have anything to prove? Do I have a passion like
I had a passion for Wired?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wired was an all-consuming, 24-7 commitment that Jane and I
were on since 1991,'' he said. ``After that, it's time to take a
sabbatical and get reconnected to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blessed,'' he said. ``I don't know how many fathers have
the opportunity to spend as much time with their children as I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also blessed with riches from his days at Wired. The
magazine was sold to Advance Publications for $90 million, and the
Web business he built, Wired Digital, should wrap up its sale to
Lycos for more than $300 million later this month. While Rossetto
and Metcalfe will see only a fraction of that money, they certainly
will realize a gain of millions. In the Wired Digital deal alone,
each received $1 million in severance pay and $500,000 in exchange
for uncashed stock options.
</P>
<P>
   They also will end up holding about 270,000 shares apiece of
Lycos stock. Lycos stock closed Friday at $91, valuing Rossetto and
Metcalfe's stakes at nearly $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go into it to become wealthy,'' Rossetto said. ``I'm
astounded at what an editor ended up with.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already dabbling in investments; one is Nerve.com, the New
York proprietor of what he calls ``intelligent smut.'' He likened
the erotica on the Web site to Henry Miller's writings, calling it
``sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm helping people who have vision and passion, and they're
also smart and have a good idea,'' Rossetto said.
</P>
<P>
   Rossetto's story is a remarkable one, and it has yet to be fully
told: how a long-haired expatriate returned to the United States,
founded a magazine and built a $60 million company and then lost
control as the digital revolution he heralded engulfed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much material success that I got out of it, there's the
life lesson it taught me,'' he said. ``People can make lots of
money and not necessarily learn the things that I learned.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Learning comes from success as well as failure and
adversity,'' he said. ``I've had my share of all of those, and in
very intense quantities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
