<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEATTLE-FESTIVAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF QUALITY TO GO AROUND AT 25TH SEATTLE INTERNATIONAL FILM
FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``Run Lola Run,'' an exhilarating German film about a
woman frantically trying to raise money to pay off her boyfriend's
debt to gangsters, received the Golden Space Needle award for best
picture Sunday in the closing ceremonies of the 25th Seattle
International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Everett was voted best actor for his performance in ``An
Ideal Husband;'' Piper Laurie was named best actress for her
performance in ``The Mao Game;'' John Sayles was selected best
director for `Limbo;'' and ``Buena Vista Social Club'' was honored
as the best documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The two American Independent Awards went to ``Dead Dogs'' and
Laurie (her second prize of the day); and the three awards in the
New Director's Showcase competition were divided among Belgium's
``Rosie,'' the Czech Republic's ``The Bed'' and Norway's ``Only
Clouds Move the Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards and the official closing night presentation, ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' capped 25 days of frantic film
activity in the city and screenings of some 206 films _ SIFF's
largest lineup ever _ and, once again, a figure no other American
film festival can come close to matching.
</P>
<P>
   It was the best-attended festival ever (up 8 percent from last
year, with a projected attendance of 142,560), and, to my mind, the
best festival of the '90s in terms of quality. Festival director
Darryl Macdonald said going in that this 25th SIFF would be
``something special,'' and he more than made good on the promise.
</P>
<P>
   It was the festival that had something for everyone, and a bit
more: five filmmaker tributes, 25 classic revivals, 20
documentaries, appearances by literally hundreds of filmmaker
guests _ climaxing with a spectacular, goosebump-inducing
presentation of the 1925 ``Battleship Potemkin'' (accompanied by
the full Bellevue Philharmonic Orchestra) that is sure to go down
as one of the greatest moments in SIFF history.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there were the usual flub-ups and no-shows that
invariably plague any film festival (the much-advertised, 25th
anniversary souvenir booklet, for instance, somehow didn't get
printed, and is now scheduled to come out for next year's 26th). I
also didn't attend a single event that started on time.
</P>
<P>
   But these annoyances were barely noticed, the vibes were
exceedingly good, and less complaining was heard in the queues than
in any festival of recent memory _ largely, I think, because the
films were overwhelmingly good. Out of the 80-plus entries I
managed to see, I can count the stinkers on one hand, and thus will
have to forgo my usual ritual of revenge: a festival ten-worst
list.
</P>
<P>
   The number of low-budget American independent films _ a figure
that has grown astronomically in the '90s _ was significantly
slashed for the 25th, and, clearly, a much tougher selection
process was exercised. Many of the films that made the cut still
were forgettable, but most justified their presence in the lineup
with a stand-out performance, an intriguing storyline or a flash of
embryonic talent somewhere in the credits.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, SIFF '99 lived up to the ``I'' in its initials by
delivering its strongest slate of foreign films in many years: a
testament both to the programmers' determination to make the 25th
festival a landmark edition and to the fact that the international
cinema genuinely seems to be in the first stages on a badly needed
creative renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this may have been the first SIFF in which I caught at
least one memorable film from each of 30 countries, and from every
region of the world: such happy surprises as the Czech Republic's
``Sekal Must Die,'' Ireland's ``Sweety Barrett,'' Tunisia's ``Bent
Familia,'' Russia's ``Day of the Full Moon,'' Taiwan's ``Jam,'' and
Australia's ``The Castle.''
</P>
<P>
   There were almost as many foreign films that, because of the
daunting 206-film lineup, I missed, but which generated
enthusiastic reviews and audience word-of-mouth, including
Yugoslavia's ``Black Cat, White Cat,'' Greece's ``Shores of
Twilight,'' France's ``Lautrec,'' and Italy's ``Besieged.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is my list of 10 festival discoveries that are definitely
worth catching when (and if) they come back to town for a
theatrical run:
</P>
<P>
   Earth _ Incorrectly labeled a Canadian film in the SIFF program,
this heartbreaking Indian drama set in Lahore just before and
during the partition of India in 1947 is a stunning historic epic,
and a profound examination of the 20th century's seminal and
still-bloodiest outbreak of communal violence. Opens in September.
</P>
<P>
   An Ideal Husband _ This British comedy is arguably the movies'
best adaptation of an Oscar Wilde play: a witty, stylish character
piece and delicious slice of late-Victorian London society, with
Rupert Everett at his scene-stealing best muttering Wildean
epigrams from the corner of his mouth. Opens June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Adrenaline Drive _ Shinonu Yaguchi demonstrates once again why
he is considered Japan's hottest comedy director with this uniquely
charming and frequently hilarious farce about a timid rental-car
clerk and a meek nurse who fall in love while on the run with a bag
of the Yakuza's money. No opening scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Last Night _ This offbeat Canadian ensemble tragicomedy,
directed by actor Don McKellar and set in a Toronto counting down
the final hours before the end of the Planet Earth is a funny,
scary and surprisingly emotionally powerful examination of a human
species in a strange state of denial. Opens in September.
</P>
<P>
   Return With Honor _ This absorbing, sobering documentary about
the U.S. POWs in Hanoi during the Vietnam War (which incorporates
recently released footage from the Vietnamese government) is an
epic story of prison survival comparable to such classics in the
genre as ``Papillon'' and ``Birdman of Alcatraz.'' Opens July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Run Lola Run _ Incorporating animation, rock-video techniques
and director Tom Tykwer's unique story-telling style, this German
celebration of speed _ showing three alternate plot-lines as its
heroine has 20 minutes to raise 100,000 marks to save her
boyfriend's life _ powers along like a truck on the Autobahn. Opens
June 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Contract _ It's not quite ``The French Connection'' or
``Day of the Jackal,'' but this what-if, Swedish nail-biter about a
maverick cop who stumbles on the 1986 conspiracy to assassinate
Prime Minister Olaf Palme is an irresistible paranoid thriller that
proves Hollywood no longer has a monopoly on the genre. No opening
date scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates of Silicon Valley _ This made-for-cable, dual biopic
which chronicles the rise of Microsoft's Bill Gates and Apple
Computer's Steve Jobs in the '70s and '80s _ and basically contends
the two tycoons stole the ideas that made them so fabulously
wealthy _ is fast, wildly irreverent, outrageous fun. Airs on TNT,
beginning June 20.
</P>
<P>
   Jinnah _ British actor Christoper Lee plays Mohammed Ali Jinnah,
the Father of Pakistan, in this absorbing biography that sugarcoats
some aspects of his life, but is mostly an eye-filling and
fair-minded epic designed to boost Jinnah's legacy as an
alternative to the Taliban-like Muslim extremists now trying to
take over that country. No opening date scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   To Walk With Lions _ This superb British/South African drama,
roughly a sequel to 1966's ``Born Free,'' is a passionate
environmental plea, a extraordinary character study (with a
towering performance by Richard Harris), and a disturbing,
mournful, poignant ode to the passing of the African wilderness in
our lifetime. No opening date scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
