<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Microsoft To Push Office 2000  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Microsoft Corp., looking to maintain its stranglehold on the
business software market, officially will launch its new Office
2000 before about 600 invited guests today at the Sony Metreon
center in San Francisco.
<P>
   Office 2000 will hit retail shelves Thursday. It is the first
major upgrade in two and a half years to Microsoft's Office 97
package of word-processing, spreadsheet and e-mail programs.
</P>
<P>
   Today's formal launch, starting with a 1 p.m. keynote speech by
Microsoft President Steve Ballmer, is expected mainly to be a
promotional event for selected customers and computer trade
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Redmond, Wash., software giant actually began
shipping the final version of Office 2000 to new computer
manufacturers on March 25. The product already is in the hands of
about 1 million corporate customers that were involved in testing.
</P>
<P>
   Napa Valley's Robert Mondavi Winery began installing the program
in its 1,000 desktop computers in 20 locations around the world in
early April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it: It's stable, it's fast, and it has great new
features,'' said Brian Shelden, director of information services
for the Oakville winery.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it's crucial for Microsoft to persuade customers
like Mondavi to upgrade to Office 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Office 97, used by about 100 million customers worldwide,
generated about $4.8 billion in sales last year, about one-third of
Microsoft's $14.5 billion in revenues for fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry estimates, Office holds 85 to 95 percent
of the market for business productivity software, easily dominating
competitors like Corel Corp., which released its new WordPerfect
2000 on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   J.P Morgan analyst William Epifanio &UR;  &LR; projects that Office 2000
will generate about $5.8 billion in revenue for 1999 and $6.3
billion for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Office 2000 represents Microsoft's single biggest product,''
Epifanio said. ``Given that Microsoft has about 95 percent market
share, Microsoft's key competitor is itself. The critical thing is
to get people to upgrade, and Office will succeed at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 packages the latest versions of Microsoft's Word for
word processing, Excel for spreadsheets, PowerPoint for
presentations and Outlook for e-mail. Prices will range from $209
for a small business version to $799 for the full premium version
for new users.
</P>
<P>
   The new Office is easier to install and maintain, said Microsoft
group product manager Andrew Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Office can install individual programs automatically only when
needed, so they're not hogging space on a hard drive. For example,
Dixon said, if a PC user never uses spreadsheets but gets one in
e-mail, Office automatically will install the Excel program or
access it from a network server so the user can read the document.
If the user doesn't expect to use Excel again, it can be deleted
from the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Office automatically can replace a file needed to run
a program if it accidentally is deleted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Reducing maintenance costs should be a big selling point for
corporate computer system managers, said Dwight Davis, a Microsoft
analyst for the technology research firm Summit Strategies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to set up a standard configuration and distribute it
across all desktops electronically as opposed to going to each
desktop,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Other new features will let users cut and paste up to 12
different items in Word, instead of only one at a time, and make it
easier to put together group mailing lists in Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Also, documents can be saved in the HTML format, which is
designed to make creating Web pages and sharing documents through
the Internet simpler.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not enamored with Web publishing and Web
integration, there might not be any compelling reason to upgrade
immediately,'' Davis said. And the new Office is ``very demanding
on system resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 computer problem also may slow Office sales as
companies halt new software purchases until after the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because Office 97 is already in widespread use, ``I
wouldn't sell Office 2000 short,'' Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
