<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIDCO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Device Does E-Mail Without a PC  &HT;       
 By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Cidco Inc. last week began selling a new $99 device designed to
get Grandma online _ without a PC.
</P>
<P>
   The MailStation is dedicated to one purpose: sending and
receiving e-mail. The narrow focus, Cidco officials said, let them
make the MailStation inexpensive and simple enough for customers to
master quickly, even if they have no computer experience.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The machine plugs into a standard phone jack. Service from
Cidco costs $99 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Once it's hooked up, users can check to see if they have mail at
any time, just by pushing a button labeled ``Get e-mail,'' or they
can have the MailStation do it for them automatically every every
four, eight, 12 or 24 hours. When mail has been downloaded but not
yet read, a small light on top of the unit flashes.
</P>
<P>
   No setup will be required, Cidco said, because it will configure
each unit at its factory with an e-mail address and local access
number.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a Morgan Hill telecommunications equipment
manufacturer best known for its Caller ID devices, said seniors
looking for a way to communicate with family and friends are likely
to be the largest market for the MailStation. The company also aims
to market the product to ``boomers without PCs.''
</P>
<P>
   The MailStation is about the size of a hardcover book. It
includes a laptop-style keyboard with keys about 85 percent of
normal size, plus an adjustable-angle screen that's 6 inches wide
and 2.25 inches high. A modem that runs at 33.6 kilobits per second
and a 20,000-word spelling checker are built in.
</P>
<P>
   The MailStation comes with an AC adapter, but it will also work
for three to six weeks on three AA batteries, according to Cidco.
It connects to any phone jack via a standard phone line, and
there's an extra connector on the back so buyers can keep a phone,
answering machine and the device all connected to the same jack.
</P>
<P>
   The device has enough memory _ 384 kilobytes _ to store 300 to
400 typical e-mail messages. There's no way to save messages to
disk, but they can be printed out on Hewlett-Packard, Canon or
compatible inkjet or laser printers. The MailStation keeps a log of
outgoing messages that have been sent, but doesn't save their
contents.
</P>
<P>
   MailStation buyers are entitled to up to five e-mail addresses.
Messages are limited to 1,000 words, graphics and sound can't be
included, and any attached files _ even Word documents _ are
removed when the MailStation retrieves a message. But users who
have access to a PC will have the option of getting their mail
complete with attached files on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who don't want to sign up for a full year's service
can buy the MailStation for $149 and pay $9.95 per month for
service.
</P>
<P>
   Cidco's Web site,  &LR; www.cidco.com,  &LR; currently refers potential
buyers to a toll-free number, but online sales are scheduled to
begin next month. Eventually, the device will also be available
through retail outlets and selected Internet service providers and
local phone companies, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
