<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: UC Berkeley Students Ticked Off at Idea of Online Charges  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It seems like old times at the University of California at
Berkeley.
<P>
   Whistle-blowing graduate students are howling in outrage at a
hush-hush plan by school administrators to begin charging students
and faculty for Internet access. Rebellion is thick in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A university committee on computing is hashing out several
options to defray online connection costs _ including Internet
surcharges for individual departments _ and could implement a
pay-to-surf plan next year, faculty and staff fear. Thousands of
on-campus personal computers would be saddled with an undetermined
online fee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  That is particularly galling at Berkeley, which _ like most
colleges _ provides free, high-speed Internet access to students,
staff and faculty. A standard UC connection is 10 Megabits per
second _ or up to 350 times faster than a standard Internet account
(28.8 kilobits per second) that costs about $20 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some accounting guy must have come up with the idea to
generate revenues,'' said Ray Cranfill, a graduate student in
integrated biology. ``I pay $2,240 a semester for tuition. To do
this at a state-run university, it doesn't make any sense and it
isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Poppycock, counters Jack McCredie, associate vice chancellor of
information systems and technology for the University of California
system and chairman of the network funding committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while the university has offered dial-in access for
off-campus students for $10 per month since 1997, there are no
immediate plans to charge their on-campus counterparts for Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
   However, the committee is mulling several options for the
2000-01 academic year to generate additional money to pay for its
campus network, which costs $12.1 million and serves 37,000 people.
One possibility is docking departments $6 per PC per month for
network access. If imposed, department heads would be notified in
March 2000 as part of the campuswide budget process. McCredie
emphatically said there are no plans to charge students for
Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large user fee may disenfranchise some faculty or
students,'' the commission said in an August report. ``Such a
consequence should be unacceptable in a modern university.''
</P>
<P>
   But Berkeley students might want to get used to the idea of
paying more for online connections in the future, as on-campus
networking costs escalate and more data-rich information is
transmitted.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, U.S. universities and colleges are increasingly charging
students for on-campus use of the Internet. Stanford University,
Harvard University, Cornell University, University of Michigan and
Yale University, for example, charge students $25 to $30 per month
for high-speed Net access. That's still a bargain compared with
what people in the real world pay: Most standard 56K Net
connections cost about $20 monthly for unlimited use; high-speed
Net access usually is $50 a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   But a small group of Berkeley grad students aren't buying into
the idea of paying for access to the Net, whose roots are in
higher-education research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the cusp of a millennium where the Internet is the
door for information dissemination,'' Cranfill said. ``I fear the
wealthy sector of society will be able to manipulate its
infrastructure by charging for access and controlling vast amounts
of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Try explaining that to cost-conscious network administrators at
American universities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CRASH COURSE &LR; : On the other hand, college life may never be easier
_ or slothful _ in the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in late June, a free, new online service
( &LR; www.campuspipeline.com &LR; ) will let students enroll, register for
classes, view grades, request transcripts, obtain reading lists,
buy and auction books and engage in interactive chats with
professors _ without leaving their dorm rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to eliminate some of the daily hassles that coeds
encounter waiting in line at the campus bookstore or the admissions
and records office,'' said Chad Muir, co-chief executive of Campus
Pipeline in Salt Lake City. ``Our motto is, `Get out of line by
going online.'''
</P>
<P>
   Campus Pipeline _ which fancies itself as a higher-education
portal based on e-commerce agreements with Amazon.com and Sun
Microsystems to hawk books, apparel and auction services online _
has signed up more than 170 colleges and universities nationwide,
including the University of San Francisco and Mills College in
Oakland. It initially will reach about 1.2 million students.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It's a big time-saver,'' said Breeana ``Breezy'' Borghetti,
21, a marketing major at Clemson University in Clemson, S.C., who
tested Campus Pipeline. ``Other colleges offer courses over the
Internet, but this program lets you do a lot more without trudging
to campus and finding faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WAR OF THE PICKUP ARTISTS: &LR;  The Speed Seduction guru versus
Steelballs sounds more like the &UR;  &LR; titillating title of an NC-17
movie than the nicknames for combatants in a libel lawsuit with
implications for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ross, aka Ross Jefferies _ whose Web site, newsletter and
seminars promote a behavioral approach to picking up women called
``speed seduction'' &UR;  &LR; _ is suing R. Don Steele, aka John J. White,
whose Steelballs Web site hawks books such as ``How to Date Younger
Women,'' ``Sexpectations'' and ``How to Dump Your Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in late April in Los Angeles County Superior
Court, alleges that White called rival Ross a ``fraud, ex-felon,
crack addict and psychotic'' among other things in numerous online
postings since March 1997. It seeks unspecified damages and a
restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   White claims that Ross is attempting to ``chill'' his free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can call it a classic Internet pissing match,''
said San Francisco attorney Karl Olson, who represents White.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' attorney, William E. Harris of Brentwood, said White has
attacked Ross online for two years. At one point, Steelballs
allegedly broke into a private newsgroup on Ross' Web site and
libeled him. He then posted that confrontation on his own
commercial home page.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The guy wants to ruin Ross like a company would put a rival
out of business with vicious rumors and distorted ads,'' Harris
said. ``This is a case about how far you can go with freedom of
speech. The constitution doesn't protect libel _ especially on the
World Wide Web.''
</P>
<P>
   White said he is merely trying to expose Ross, whom he
repeatedly called a ``thief and crook'' in a phone interview last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who has received favorable coverage in Rolling Stone and
Playboy, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Free computer assistance is only a mouse click away at
 &LR; www.techpointer.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got any interesting or quirky Web sites you'd like to share? If so,
drop me an e-mail at jswartz(AT SIGN)sfgate.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
