<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5084 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIRED-SFCHRON &LR;      06-06 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wired Shifts Its Focus   By Dan Fost  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In the year since Conde Nast took over Wired, editor Katrina Heron
has heard criticism that the magazine now features too many
celebrities, too little of what readers used to love and too much
of the Conde Nast influence.
<P>
   Heron heard it all before, when she was an editor at Tina
Brown's New Yorker, also owned by Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   There's a big difference, though. At The New Yorker, Brown was
tinkering with an intellectual institution, a general interest
magazine founded in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Wired is a mere 6-year-old. But Wired cultists
are every bit as rabid as dyed-in-the-wool New Yorker readers, and
many of them are griping about the changes in their beloved
techno-bible.
</P>
<P>
   When founders Louis Rossetto and Jane Metcalfe brought Wired to
life in 1993, they invented a new genre of computer magazine _ and
in the process made it hip to be geek.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's cluttered, neon-colored layouts were so copied by
advertisers that before long, you could barely tell the stories
from the ads.
</P>
<P>
   It published long, philosophical essays about technology and its
impact on politics, culture, society and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Under Conde Nast, which acquired Wired on June 15, 1998, the
magazine is edging away from big thoughts and placing more emphasis
on business in the Internet age. The June cover story is on ``The
Wired Index: 40 Companies Driving the New Economy,'' and next month
features author Po Bronson's chronicle of life at a high-tech
startup.
</P>
<P>
   Readers who felt part of something hip and unorthodox fear that
Wired is becoming more like the myriad techno-business publications
that are flooding the market.
</P>
<P>
   Wired, while still looking smart, also appears cleaner and more
mature. Less MTV and more CNBC. It's got new editors, designers and
writers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most infuriating to the old guard: The changes are
successful. Wired's circulation, advertising pages and revenues are
all on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended May 31, Wired's advertising revenues rose 9
percent, to $36.2 million, according to Competitive Media
Reporting, a New York ad-tracking firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of last year, Wired's subscriptions grew 55
percent, to 423,157, and its overall paid circulation, including
newsstand sales, grew 36 percent, to 511,478, according to the
Audit Bureau of Circulation
</P>
<P>
   The numbers seem to validate Heron's new direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to be crazy not to recognize that business and
finance are an integral part of the Internet, of the Wired
culture,'' Heron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `Whatever happened to Cyber Rights Now?''' she
said, referring to a popular column she discontinued. The debate
over free speech on the Internet ``has gone mainstream. Wired used
to be the only voice. ... We no longer need to rattle the sabres
and shout from the rooftops.''
</P>
<P>
   The top names on the masthead are all Heron hires, and many
share her New York publishing background. Executive editor Alex
Heard came from The New York Times Magazine. Design director Daniel
Carter came back to Wired after helping launch The Industry
Standard. Business editor Michael Noer hailed from Forbes Digital.
New writers include Warren St. John from the New York Observer and
Randall Rothenberg, who had written for New York and Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   Heron, 44, had worked for Conde Nast at both Vanity Fair and The
New Yorker. In 1994, she moved to the West Coast for a journalism
fellowship at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   She started working as an editor-at-large at Wired in 1995, took
a leave in 1997 when her twins were born, returned at the end of
the year and was named editor in December.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time, Rossetto and Metcalfe were under intense
pressure from their board of directors. The company had failed to
go public, losses from its online division were mounting, and
investors were getting impatient.
</P>
<P>
   By spring of 1998, Rossetto was out entirely and Heron started
making her changes.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes continue to stir debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conde Nast has Conde Nastied Wired,'' said Lewis Perdue, a
free-lance writer and longtime reader. He thinks it's lost its
edge, and he adds, ``There's so little time, so much to read, and
at least for me, Wired has moved off the desktop and into the
recycle bin.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Katz, a media critic who once wrote for Wired and now
contributes to Rolling Stone, said Rossetto's Wired covered the
political and cultural aspects of technology, not just the business
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 15 years of working in journalism, I never heard a reporter
mention the word freedom, but at Wired and Hot Wired, they talked
about it all the time. They relished it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One source inside the magazine put it differently. ``There were
people who wanted to sit around and think about big ideas and go to
long lunches and conferences.'' None are there anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff O'Brien, the editor of the trade magazine Marketing
Computers, said Heron is raising the quality of journalism at
Wired.
</P>
<P>
   He said recent articles like science fiction writer William
Gibson's piece on eBay and Rothenberg's article about NBC are the
kind of stories that could put Wired back on the map, as opposed to
what he called ``the crazy visionaries of yesteryear espousing the
future of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Leyden, a former managing editor, said that during the
transition between Rossetto and Heron, the was a huge internal
debate about the magazine's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the original crowd wanted to stay more in
line with the original Wired,'' said Leyden. ``I was saying, cede
the digital economy story. There are so many people in that turf,
we should go into a more global story, into more politics, into
more culture.''
</P>
<P>
   As a ``new economy'' magazine, Wired does face plenty of
competition, from upstarts such as Fast Company, Upside, Red
Herring, Business 2.0 and The Industry Standard to bigger business
publications with beefed-up tech coverage, like Fortune, Business
Week and Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   With Wired's quirky blend of business, culture and technology,
``they don't have any direct competition, which is good and bad,''
said O'Brien. It's nice to be unique, but ``it would be really good
for them if Hearst came out with a book like Wired. It's easier for
two magazines to drive a market, to validate a market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Wired's niche seems to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Adscope, a Eugene, Ore., firm that tracks high-tech advertising,
reports that Wired's paid ad pages rose 18 percent, from a total of
189 in April and May of 1998 to 223 in the same months this year.
Wired publisher Dana Lyon said ad page year-over-year increases are
14 percent for June, 46 percent for July and 43 percent for August.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wired maintains its own ad sales force, Conde Nast also
sells Wired as part of a package with its other magazines. Conde
Nast ``does give them more credibility from a publishing
standpoint,'' said Laura Bracken, senior vice president and media
director in ad agency Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi's San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast brought other changes. Rossetto's Wired never ran
cigarette ads. Wired does now though that could end as governments
negotiate deals with the tobacco industry to stop advertising in
magazines, newspapers and billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Another big difference: Wired, the magazine that led the digital
revolution, no longer has its own Web site. Advance bought only the
magazine, leaving the online properties _ including the valuable
 &LR; www.wired.com &LR;  domain name _ in a separate company, Wired Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Wired Digital posts the magazine's content and subscription
information on its Web site under a cross-promotional deal. At the
end of the month, Wired Digital will be sold to Lycos, a
Massachusetts Internet company, putting the magazine's long-term
access to the domain name in question.
</P>
<P>
   But its biggest long-term challenge ``will be keeping it fresh,
unique and distinctive,'' said John Battelle, who was Wired's
managing editor and left to found The Industry Standard, a weekly
Internet-economy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wired proved something that needed to be proven, which is that
there are new markets out there and new ways of thinking about
publishing,'' Battelle said. ``There's been something of a
renaissance in publishing since the emergence of Wired. The rest of
the world woke up to that story after Wired paid attention to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5085 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORG-SFCHRON &LR;      06-06 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Designing With Women in Mind  &HT;       
 By Terry Nagel 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Anita Borg snorts at a photo of a woman smiling at her
``ScreenFridge.'' The picture is part of a press kit from ICL, a
British tech company that developed the prototype refrigerator in
partnership with Frigidaire Home Appliances.
<P>
   Before you throw out an empty milk carton or bread wrapper,
you're supposed to wave the package past a scanner built into the
refrigerator so that it can create a shopping list for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every woman is going to tell you, `I don't need one more
step,''' she says. ``Something like this would have to be voice
activated. Women complain that too many so-called labor-saving
devices add extra work.''
</P>
<P>
   Borg founded the Institute for Women and Technology in Palo Alto
to persuade companies to consider the female perspective when
designing new products, and to get more women involved in creating
them. Her one-and-a-half-year-old organization runs workshops in
which women brainstorm about how new products might help run their
homes and improve family life.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to open ``virtual development centers'' where female
college &UR;  &LR; students work with faculty members and engineers from
sponsoring companies to develop prototypes of some of the products.
</P>
<P>
   Borg says women are seldom consulted about product design. When
they are, it's usually after a prototype has been made and it would
be too expensive to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   She gives the example of a French company that designed a new
stove, then invited in a female consultant. ``The woman said, `It's
a beautiful stove, but you can't clean it.' No one who cooks would
have designed that stove,'' Borg recalls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  She winces at American inventions, too. The PalmPilot, for
example, was shaped to fit in a man's breast pocket. &UR;  &LR; And she's
discovered that most calendar software programs are designed to
track one person's life. ``How many women do you know who keep
track of one life?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, women in her workshops, who range from teenagers to
octogenarians, have suggested a layered calendar program that would
let the user track several family members' schedules
simultaneously. They also have proposed:
</P>
<P>
   _``Smart Pipes'' that warn homeowners when a pipe is about to
leak, clog or freeze.
</P>
<P>
   _A security device that lets children summon help when they're
in danger.
</P>
<P>
   _Seats in cars that swivel for easier access by handicapped
people.
</P>
<P>
   _A ``virtual wall'' that would let grandparents in a different
state ``sit'' in the same room with their grandchildren and watch
them play.
</P>
<P>
   Borg is convinced that there won't be many products like these
until more women are involved in creating them. Right now, she
points out, technology is being shaped by a narrow slice of the
world's population: young, Western, white male engineers, venture
capitalists and executives who often are more interested in making
gadgets than things that serve a human need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is,'' she says, ``do we want a bunch of 18-to
30-year-old guys making all the decisions about the technical
future of the world?
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't necessarily bad people,'' she adds, ``but other
perspectives are not being heard.'' What's lacking from the brain
pool, she argues, are diverse viewpoints _ in gender, age and race
_ that would help create products of value to more of the world's
population.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Institute's goals is to interest more women in
becoming engineers and computer scientists. Before the passage in
1972 of Title IX, which bans gender discrimination in any school
receiving federal funds, only 2 percent of engineers in the United
States were women. The National Research Council reports that 9.8
percent of working engineers in the United States in 1997 were
female.
</P>
<P>
   That's still not enough, says the Chicago-born Borg, 50, who
seldom encountered other women during her ascent from data
processor at an insurance company to research scientist at Digital
Equipment Corp. in Palo Alto. ``I worked directly with only two or
three women in 20 years,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   Borg has a doctorate in computer science and is proudest of her
work in memory-system performance analysis and fault-tolerant
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   She's not shy about speaking her mind. ``I've learned the boys'
rules,'' she said during a recent talk to a women's group in San
Francisco. ``I'm always thinking of how I am going to interrupt
someone else and get my idea out there.'' But she's always reached
out to other women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, she founded the Systers List, an Internet community of
women in technology that now has 2,500 members in 25 countries. In
1994, she organized a conference called the Grace Hopper
Celebration of Women in Computing.
</P>
<P>
   Then she read ``The Futures of Women: Scenarios for the 21st
Century,'' by Pamela McCorduck and Nancy Ramsey. The book predicts
the future of civilization with and without women involved, and it
stresses that females are not an inevitable part of technology.
After reading it, Borg says, ``I decided this could no longer be a
part-time activity,'' and she founded the Institute for Women and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she has raised $3 million in personnel, hardware and
cash from Xerox, Sun Microsystems and Hewlett-Packard that has let
her sponsor four brainstorming workshops and travel around the
world, talking up the Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Borg has enough seed money to start the virtual development
centers, but she needs another $1 million to operate them. The
centers will be located at Santa Clara University, Texas A&AMP;M
University, Carnegie-Mellon University and, possibly, Smith College
in Northampton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan is to have women students run community workshops to
gather ideas for female-friendly products, then work with faculty
and engineers from sponsoring companies to make prototypes. During
the process, the women will be able to explore the idea of becoming
engineers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Borg's enthusiasm is winning converts; as she explains it, some
of the men running technology firms are beginning to ``get it.''
</P>
<P>
   One is Greg Papadopoulos, chief technology officer at Sun
Microsystems in Mountain View. ``Invariably, with the folks in the
Valley and elsewhere that are off building the next technology, the
habit has been to build it first for ourselves,'' he says. ``It
takes things like what Anita is doing to cause a sea change. We
need another set of people coming into technology businesses with
new and different perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   But just when Borg feels that she's making progress, along comes
another new invention that brings her back to reality _ like
Eureka's prototype Robot Vac vacuum cleaner. Measuring 15 inches in
diameter and 6 inches high, the self-propelled device can't get
under couches or into corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perfect for some guy who lives in an apartment and
doesn't care what's underneath the bed,'' Borg says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Institute for Women and Technology is located at 3333 Coyote
Hill Road, Palo Alto, Calif. 94304; telephone: (650) 812-4496; Web
site: &LR;  www.iwt.org. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
