<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT BEGINS SHIPPING
</P>
<P>
   Revamped Office Software Microsoft will announce Monday that it
has begun retail shipments of a new version of its office
productivity ``suite,'' Office 2000, that all but eliminates the
distinctions between a PC document and Internet data.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000, which includes word processing, spreadsheet,
database, e-mail, scheduling and other software functions, has new
features, almost all of which are intended to give PC users a set
of software tools that deeply integrate Internet capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In its antitrust trial, Microsoft is expected to introduce
documents intended to contradict testimony by an IBM executive who
said Microsoft would offer the computer maker a favorable price on
its Windows operating system only if IBM agreed to drop its
competing operating system, OS/2.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN STANLEY'S ADVERSARY
</P>
<P>
   Christian Curry, the man at the center of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's legal trouble, was raised to blend fluidly into social and
business elites. But he did not fit in at the Wall Street
powerhouse, and the events that led to his dismissal,
discrimination suit and government inquiry into Morgan Stanley's
response raise the question of whether he is a victim, a rogue or a
little of both.
</P>
<P>
   DOW JONES JOURNALISTS PROTEST CUTS
</P>
<P>
   Some journalists who work for Dow Jones, which publishes The
Wall Street Journal, have stopped appearing as volunteers on CNBC
to express their dismay over proposed cutbacks in their pension
benefits. The quasi-boycott began after one Journal reporter was
instructed to keep his union button out of sight on CNBC, which has
contracted with Dow Jones for voluntary appearances by staff
members. Since then, the number of volunteers has dropped.
</P>
<P>
   $5.9 BILLION BANKING DEAL IN WEST
</P>
<P>
   Trying to establish banking supremacy in the West, Zions
Bancorp. is buying First Security, its longtime rival in regional
consumer banking, in a deal valued at $5.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY CONSIDERS INTERNET SPINOFF
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney is considering a spinoff of its Internet-related
operations, several people close to the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   BOSCH WIRELESS UNIT TO BE SOLD
</P>
<P>
   Trying to deliver high-speed Internet links without wires, Cisco
Systems and Motorola plan to announce Monday that they have agreed
to acquire a unit of Robert Bosch of Germany that is developing
wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   INSIGHTS INTO MCI WORLDCOM
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MCI Worldcom convened its first meeting for analysts
and investors in more than two years, and three points emerged: The
company's rivalry with AT&AMP;T is in decline; former Worldcom
executives, not those from MCI, are running the show and setting
strategy; and speculation abounds that the company ought to buy
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   CONCEPT OF FREE E-MAIL EXPANDED
</P>
<P>
   A small start-up company called Onebox.com plans to start a new
service on the Web on Monday that combines free e-mail with free
voice mail and free incoming faxes. If the company, founded in part
by Bill Nguyen, can iron out some bugs in its service, if its
business model holds up and if the technology can handle thousands
of users, the company could find itself at the front of a new wave
of Internet messaging.
</P>
<P>
   BANK CANCELS DEAL WITH ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland said that it had canceled a proposed joint
banking venture with the television evangelist Pat Robertson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
