<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRI     06-06 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SERBS HESITATE ON PEACE, NATO ISSUES WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Inserts 2 grafs, beginning ``On Sunday.'' Inserts 1 graf beginning
``In addition.'' Inserts 2 grafs beginning ``Prime Minister'' and
deletes graf that would have followed.)  (lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ As Yugoslav military negotiators raised new
objections Sunday night to a NATO peacekeeping mission in Kosovo,
the alliance warned that it would intensify the bombing, now in its
75th day.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic agreed in principle last Thursday
to withdraw his 40,000 troops from Kosovo and to let in an
international peacekeeping force, when the Serbs approved a
two-page draft agreement. But an allied diplomat said that Yugoslav
commanders meeting with NATO officers in Macedonia were objecting
to letting in peacekeepers unless the U.N. Security Council
authorized them first, a condition that some allies view as
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air campaign will continue,'' a senior NATO official said,
as the Yugoslav officers met into the night with the British
officer who would command the international peacekeeping force, Lt.
Gen. Sir Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we don't come to a conclusion down there,'' Maj.
Gen. Walter Jertz, the spokesman for the allied military command,
said, ``the operations will be intensified.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The aircraft are in the area, the pilots are still
there and all the assets are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the bombing would not stop until the Serbs
started moving troops out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to explain why Yugoslav and Serb commanders could take
more than two days to accept withdrawal terms that Milosevic had
appeared to agree to, a senior diplomat here said, ``They were
trying to water down what they agreed to last week.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said that allied field commanders
were refusing to negotiate the terms, which officials said require
the Serbs to shut down their anti-aircraft defenses within 48
hours, to pull all of their military, police, and paramilitary
forces out of Kosovo by designated routes within seven days, and to
let in 45,000 international peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   If those terms are met, the allies then expect about 1.5 million
ethnic Albanians to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to bar the peacekeeping force without express
Security Council approval strikes at the weakest link in the recent
chain of events that the allies are counting on to result in a
diplomatic and military victory.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain agree with France, Germany and
other European allies that the peacekeeping force should have the
Security Council's authorization. But they are concerned that if
approval were delayed for some reason, and if the Serbs were
withdrawing troops, NATO should be ready to move in to prevent a
vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   France and most of the European allies do not see things that
way, and neither does Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats hope that Russia would be willing to approve a
Security Council resolution sending in peacekeepers whether
Milosevic wanted them or not, under Chapter Seven of the U.N.
Charter. Russia might also join the peacekeeping force on its own
terms, but Russia would certainly not approve of NATO troops
entering Kosovo without a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, in remarks televised in Moscow, the Russian prime
minister, Sergei Stepashin, made clear that Russia was not pleased
with NATO's terms for ending the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many questions are being solved with NATO calling the
tune,'' Reuters quoted him as saying. ``Our task is to prepare a
serious resolution on Yugoslavia for the Security Council. We have
to treat it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   So Milosevic's military negotiators have raised a thorny issue
just at the time when the foreign ministers of Russia and the seven
largest industrial democracies, the United States, Britain, France,
Germany, Italy, Canada and Japan, are about to meet near Bonn to
discuss a draft resolution on Kosovo, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been insisting that the allies stop the bombing
before the Security Council votes, but the weekend snags appeared
to put off any pause in the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is to continue, Shea said on Sunday, ``until the Serbs accept
the detailed military agreement that has been outlined to them by
NATO commanders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get it right, we want to pin down all of the
detail, we want to make it watertight, and if that takes two extra
hours, it will save us many days of agony subsequently,'' Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the dispute over a resolution, the Serb commanders
are reportedly pressing NATO to keep the ethnic Albanian Kosovo
Liberation Army from attacking the withdrawing Serb forces.
Fighting between them continued Sunday along the border with
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Jertz, of the allied command, said that most of the bombing runs
among the 431 missions that NATO planes flew from Saturday to early
Sunday, had targeted Serb forces battling the ethnic Albanian
rebels there. That number was more than a hundred below that of the
previous day.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs know that one of the most dangerous moves for any
military force is disengagement and retreat from battle.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have long said they did not want to become the Kosovo
Liberation Army's air force, and they still insist that NATO has no
direct contact with the rebels. But for the past few weeks, allied
planes have been bombing Serb tanks and artillery positions that
were firing at the rebels along the Albanian border. NATO planes
hit 14 Serb tanks and artillery pieces at the border from Saturday
to early Sunday, the allied military command said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Pentagon said 13 artillery pieces, a
battalion-size staging area, five mortars, and several fixed
positions, including ammunition dumps and early-warning radar
sites, were struck Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering Kosovo, NATO peacekeepers would have to see to it
that the Kosovo Liberation Army, now believed to have between 6,000
and 10,000 fighters in the Balkans, is disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate that we are going to have a lot of trouble
with the KLA,'' Jertz said. ``The KLA want their people to go back
home to their own country, and that is one of the reasons why we
think that they will be following the guidance which they will get
from us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the allies have been surprised by the Kosovo Liberation Army
before. Last winter its leadership balked at the terms of a
proposed peace agreement during talks at Rambouillet Castle outside
Paris. At the end of the talks in February, the Albanian side
insisted that its field commanders would have to be consulted
before it could agree to the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, on March 14, the Albanian side signed an
accord that would have required all the Kosovo forces to disarm and
disband, provided that Milosevic also accepted the accord and that
NATO peacekeepers would move in to ensure that all fighting
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Milosevic refused, and the allies started bombing on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serb forces do carry out Jackson's terms, the allies seem
to be disposed still to see no problems on the Kosovo Albanian
side. Shea said, ``As the Serb forces pull out and the NATO forces
move into Kosovo, we expect the KLA to exercise restraint and not
to attempt to take advantage of the situation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
