<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.N.-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. DENIES STATUS TO RIGHTS GROUP CRITICAL OF '89 MASSACRE IN
CHINA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Ten years to the day after the massacre around
Tiananmen Square, special U.N. status has been denied to a New
York-based human rights organization that has been helping victims'
families in a campaign to bring criminal charges against Chinese
leaders responsible for the 1989 killings.
</P>
<P>
   After China spoke against the measure, the U.N. Committee on
Nongovernmental Organizations refused, by a vote of 13 to 3, to
grant nongovernmental organization status to Human Rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the group announced that it helped the families file
a petition with the government in Beijing last month seeking a
criminal investigation into the 1989 military crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators. Hundreds of civilians are believed to
have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   As an accredited nongovernmental organization, Human Rights in
China would have been able to attend certain U.N. meetings and to
present evidence to panels like the Human Rights Commission and the
Commission on the Status of Women. China opposed accreditation,
contending that the group is a political organization, most of
whose leaders live outside of China.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, France and Ireland were the only members of
the 19- nation committee that voted in favor of giving the group
official status, but France and Ireland made clear that their
position is shared by all 15 members of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Those opposed were Algeria, Bolivia, China, Colombia, Cuba,
Ethiopia, India, Pakistan, Lebanon, Russia, Sudan, Tunisia and
Turkey. Chile and Romania abstained, while Senegal was absent from
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights in China's chairman, Lie Qing, served 11 years in
prison after his arrest in 1979 for involvement in the ``Democracy
Wall'' movement in Beijing. Several other board members had to flee
China after the Tiananmen crackdown or were released from prison
into exile.
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions from committee members, Liu and Human Rights
in China's executive director, Xiao Qiang, said their organization
sought to support all who favored human rights and democracy in
China. While supporting every people's right to self-determination,
they said they had taken no position on such questions as the
independence of Taiwan and Tibet, which China opposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5113 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-1STLD-WR     06-06 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SOME ISSUES STILL NOT RESOLVED IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes ``what she hopes is'' to ``what she hoped would be''
in 1st graf. Inserts ``a breakdown in the talks and'' in 2nd
graf.)  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright flew to
Europe on Sunday night for what she hoped would be something of a
victory lap. In fact, it is a risky mission, and could be rather
muted.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo peace pact is not yet a done deal, with a breakdown
in the talks and several issues outstanding that Albright will
confront over the next few days as she meets her fellow foreign
ministers, confers with ethnic Albanian leaders and perhaps visits
several countries affected by the misery of the war.
</P>
<P>
   As Albright left Washington on Sunday night, the European allies
and Washington were still divided over the necessity of winning a
U.N. Security Council resolution that would give a mantle of
authority to the NATO security force and the civil administration
planned for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And it was unclear how the ethnic Albanian leaders, in
particular the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, whose representatives
Albright plans to meet in Germany, would accept the sketchy
document that is the basis of the pact with President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, beneath the buoyancy about the end of the war
appearing to be in sight, questions lingered about whether the
original goals of the air campaign had been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Some, both inside and outside the administration, recalled the
objectives set out by President Clinton in his televised Oval
Office speech on March 24, the first night of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said then that the mission was to show the ``seriousness
of NATO's purpose,'' to ``deter an even bloodier offensive against
innocent civilians in Kosovo,'' and to ``seriously damage the
Serbian military's capacity to harm the people of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the air campaign was intended to keep stability in
the fragile neighboring countries of Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Clinton's first goal of demonstrating the
seriousness of NATO's purpose was achieved: Under great strain and
differences of opinion, the alliance stayed together.
</P>
<P>
   But in essence, asserted Ivo Daalder, a former member of the
Clinton administration's National Security Council, NATO unity was
achieved at the expense of the other objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs were extraordinarily high to do this,'' Daalder
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first several weeks of the air campaign, Milosevic's
forces expelled hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians over the
border of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, more than 850,000 Kosovar Albanians, the population
NATO had wanted to protect, were squatting in tents or crammed into
the homes of relatives, friends and strangers in Macedonia and
Albania, with many of their identity papers destroyed, their homes
in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of others were left wandering around
homeless inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's goal of maintaining stability in the region also went
by the boards, Daalder said.
</P>
<P>
   The delicate ethnic situation in Macedonia between Macedonians
and ethnic Albanians was thrown out of balance by the huge influx
of Albanian refugees. The weak economy has been thrown into
disarray by the cutoff of trade with Yugoslavia and by the costly
burden of maintaining the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, a weak political equilibrium was unsettled by the
new refugees and the growing numbers of Kosovo Liberation Army
guerrillas training in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
   To try to reverse these outcomes, the United States and European
nations will be entrenched in Kosovo maintaining the peace for
years, administration officials and their critics said. The
financial costs could extend for a generation, Daalder predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of maintaining NATO credibility was achieved. The
alliance followed through on the threats to bomb, got Milosevic to
accept a deal on its terms and has not yet stopped bombing in the
absence of final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But that goal was not entirely cost-free, either.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the deal with Milosevic sank in at NATO headquarters,
a senior NATO official said the alliance had hung together by
stumbling along, rather than by smart decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful whether NATO will ever venture into another
Kosovo-style campaign, he said. After 50 years of drawing up white
papers, analyzing and preparing, NATO's first war may well be its
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``This showed the incredible difficulty of a
humanitarian-military action by an alliance,'' the official said,
speaking on condition that his name not be used. ``I personally
believe this is never to be repeated. NATO got in way over its
head, stumbled through, didn't know how to get out, was scared to
death by what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the internecine battles of the last 10 weeks, the
official said, ``This has left a bitter taste, of tilting within
governments, between governments, between NATO headquarters at
Brussels and the military headquarters at Mons. This has been a
searing experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those questions will come up as Albright visits Germany
and the devastated countries that adjoin Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Her first order of business is a meeting of the foreign
ministers of the seven richest industrial countries and Russia, in
Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Moscow suggested that the Russian foreign minister,
Igor Ivanov, might not come until the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia
stopped. The approval of Russia, as well as China, is needed for
passage of a Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were not counting on the
Russians and the Chinese to quickly agree to a resolution. Viktor
Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy who helped win Milosevic's
acquiescence to the pact, came under heavy criticism when he
arrived back in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government, embittered by the mistaken bombing of
their embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, was unlikely to veto a
resolution. But officials said the Chinese would probably delay
their approval to seek concessions from the United States on other
fronts in exchange for not vetoing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Washington puts much less stock in a U.N. blessing than
the Europeans do. First, the State Department argues that it would
be dangerous to leave a vacuum in Kosovo as Yugoslav forces
withdraw by waiting for a Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Second, these officials assert that planning for interim
administration and the future political landscape of Kosovo can go
ahead without a resolution. But the document Milosevic agreed to
stipulates that the ``interim administration'' for Kosovo will be
established within ``substantial autonomy'' of Yugoslavia ``to be
decided by the Security Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the detailed 44-page accord reached in Rambouillet,
France, that Milosevic rejected in March, provoking the NATO
bombing, the document he agreed to on Thursday leaves the future of
Kosovo vague.
</P>
<P>
   While the ethnic Albanians eventually signed the Rambouillet
pact after extracting a promise of a referendum on Kosovo's status
in three years, the present document does not make clear whether
Kosovo remains part of Yugoslavia, or eventually will have the
chance of becoming independent, as the ethnic Albanians want.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns have been raised that with protracted negotiations
among the United States, the Europeans and the Russians, these
political questions will be held hostage by the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Almost certainly the Russians will try to circumscribe Kosovo's
autonomy and will try to limit the chances for eventual
independence, a move that promises to antagonize the Kosovar
Albanians on whose behalf largely the war was fought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      06-06 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS STILL WEARING HEARTBREAK ON THEIR SLEEVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Indiana Pacers strode into Madison Square Garden
nearly a half-hour after their practice was scheduled to start
Sunday, and it was hard to say what had accounted for the delay _
city traffic or the players' slow, disappointed gaits.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief conference, they seemed even more despondent as
they trudged back to the court, the disaster in Game 3 of the
Eastern Conference finals replayed on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to hold on in the final minutes of a game was an
all-too-familiar scenario for the Pacers, who trail the New York
Knicks 2-1 after their 92-91 loss on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the regular season, Indiana lost 6 of 7 one-point games. In
this series the Pacers have been outscored by the Knicks over the
final two minutes of the three games by 25-9.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1 the Knicks pulled out a 93-90 victory; in Game 2, the
Pacers were able to hang on in the final seconds and win, 88-86.
And then in Game 3, it was an 11-2 Knicks run over the final 3
minutes 22 seconds, culminating in Larry Johnson's four-point play,
that turned around the game and possibly the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question a lot of breaks have gone New York's way,''
Indiana's Reggie Miller said. ``But one thing I am going to say is
that we've given them a lot of breaks as well. In the game of
basketball, a lot of times you have to make your own breaks. In a
few of these games, we've kind of handed it to them on a silver
platter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they've made plays down the stretch, but we've played
terrible in the last few minutes in just about each and every ball
game. We're lucky to win one of them. If you correct those things,
we could be here talking about a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   But the correction has not come yet, Pacers coach Larry Bird
said. ``We've been doing it all year,'' he said. ``We lost a lot of
games when we had the lead going down the fourth quarter and we
never really got out of it. The Knicks played some good defense
last night, but we just didn't score. We're suffering a little bit
today. Our pride's hurt. It's how we bounce back now. We feel that
we've got to put it aside and move ahead, but you never know what's
going to happen until you get out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird saw Sunday the same despair that his players displayed in
their eyes on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, I was a little concerned,'' Bird said. ``During a
time out, we had a three-point lead and we had the basketball and
we looked like we were down 20, just the facial expressions, the
way they were sitting there. I told them last night, `You can't
have a better situation. Time's running out, less than a minute to
go, we've got a three-point lead and the ball, and you guys look
like you're 20 points down. We've got to finish the ball game.'
Obviously, they were down.''
</P>
<P>
   They were familiar with what was happening. A veteran team with
a player like Miller would not expect to have last-minute lapses,
particularly not against the Knicks, who have had their own
problems late in games and have been hurt by Miller too many times
to count. But the regular-season failures seem to have depleted the
Pacers' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would probably have killed lesser teams,'' Pacers
point guard Mark Jackson said of Johnson's 3-point basket and free
throw with 5.7 seconds left in the game. ``But we still feel real
good. We'll come in here and take care of business tomorrow. Tough
loss, tough one to swallow. But so be it. It can affect a Portland
or a regular team. It's not going to affect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was not so sure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they had a lot of confidence coming in, but they don't
finish games,'' he said. ``We've had a lead in every game we lost
this year, especially down the stretch. For some reason we have a
spell in that four- or five-minute stretch at the end that we don't
get anything accomplished. It's turnovers. It's missed shots. Last
night we weren't taking any shots and it cost them.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
