u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY-NYT &LR;      06-06 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY AND CAMBY: PLAYOFF PALS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Maybe Jeff Van Gundy's method of making Marcus
Camby earn his time brought out the dominant side Camby has shown
in the playoffs. Or perhaps Van Gundy's unwillingness to trust
Camby initially hid the talent that was there all along.
</P>
<P>
   As that chicken-and-the-egg controversy began to unfold for the
Knicks this season, it resulted in organizational bickering, which
was at least part of the reason that the former team president
Ernie Grunfeld was demoted. But there is little doubt now that
Camby is the kind of player who can take over a game, the kind of
player Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach, has come to count on.
</P>
<P>
   This process has not been easy on Camby. He has bit his tongue
for the most part, except to say that he prefers steadier minutes,
but there is an iciness between Van Gundy and Camby after a
tumultuous first year together.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what I'm going to say, everyone is going to say
we're in a feud,'' Van Gundy said Sunday after practice. ``So,
write it how anybody wants to write it, but we haven't had any
problems all year. The disappointment he's had is that he hasn't
played as much as he wanted. That was my decision on what I thought
was best for the team. Now was it or not? I don't know. All I know
is now, when it counts the most, we're getting his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for whatever reason, it's worked out, whether it's him
sticking with it. And I'd say all the credit has to go to him for
perseverance. And he's gotten much, much better as the season has
gone along. I've always had faith in him, but obviously, watching
him play so well against different types of players at the highest
level of competition, there's no worry that there will be
up-and-down performances.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby has been as steady as any Knick in the playoffs. In the
second round, Camby shot 55.6 percent, scored 9 points and grabbed
6 rebounds a game in 20.8 minutes a night. In the first round,
Camby averaged 7.4 points and 5.2 rebounds a game. He also shot
68.2 percent and played 20.6 minutes a game. So far in the Eastern
Conference finals against Indiana, Camby is shooting a team-high
59.1 percent, and averaging 10.7 points, 9.3 rebounds and 27
minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, he was integral in making up for the absence of the
injured Patrick Ewing by scoring 21 points and adding 11 rebounds
off the bench. Still, he was stunned when Van Gundy told him he was
starting the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' Camby said. ``I'm not used to starting any
half. I was on the floor stretching and he came up to me and said
he wanted me to start with Chris Dudley having three fouls. So that
was a big adjustment I had to make in my mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going out and playing. I can't worry about if he's
going to play me or not. I'll go out there and make the most of my
time and minutes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller Not Getting His Shots
</P>
<P>
   By having their big men help by trapping, and with aggressive
chasing by Allan Houston, the Knicks have held Reggie Miller to
only 33 attempts in three games. But with Miller vowing to take a
more assertive role in Game 4, the Knicks were not ready to say
they had been successful in cutting off the Pacers' devastating
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lulled them into having Rik Smits score every time,'' Jeff
Van Gundy said with a heavy dose of sarcasm. ``Look, we don't
underestimate Reggie Miller at all. He's a dominant player even
when he's not putting up dominant numbers because a lot of your
attention goes to him. That opens up things for everyone else. We
have to be right with him. And even when we are, he can still put
up big numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's lack of impact has not been seized upon by either
Houston or Latrell Sprewell. Neither is having a good series
offensively, with Houston and Sprewell combining to shoot little
better than 35 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have success with Allan and Latrell
shooting that,'' Van Gundy said. ``We can't say what we've done so
far is good enough.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Praise for Johnson
</P>
<P>
   There was much-deserved praise for Larry Johnson Sunday after
his 26-point performance in Game 3, capped by his logic-defying
4-point play to win the game. Johnson has played the role of
wallflower since he arrived three years ago as a former All-Star
from Charlotte, but he has proven in the playoffs that he still has
that star quality about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's definitely an exception, not only in his
willingness to sacrifice but in his work ethic and vocal leadership
skills,'' Jeff Van Gundy said. ``When you find guys like him, you
just keep him. You never let them get away because they are so
rare.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
