<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-ELECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMORESE LOOKING AHEAD TO AUGUST REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, INDONESIA _ In stark contrast to the election fervor in
Indonesia's capital, Jakarta, voters in the troubled territory of
East Timor are cool about prospects for change as a result of this
Monday's historic election.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's people can vote to fill four seats in the national
parliament and for members in the two-tier district parliament.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of international observers has arrived to monitor
polling in the provincial capital, Dili, and in rural areas across
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But many East Timorese said they were far more excited about the
chance to vote for their territory's independence in a United
Nations-organized referendum scheduled for Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 23 years, we've been under the boot of the Indonesians,''
said a 32-year-old man who gave his name only as Alberto and said
he lost his right arm ``fighting Indonesians'' at the age of 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been killed and intimidated,'' he said. ``I'm not
going to participate'' on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sose Gusmao, a Dili street vendor, said he would vote on Monday
but did not think it would achieve much. ``I don't have much hope
because I'm just a small man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum on Aug. 8 will offer a choice between broad
autonomy within Indonesia and outright independence.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a United Nations-brokered agreement signed on May
5 and intended to resolve the long struggle over East Timor's
status.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials on the island said this weekend that they are
investigating apparent breaches of the accord by government
officials by exerting unspecified pressure to get votes for
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the East Timor accords, all militia groups are to be
disbanded before the August vote. A Dili-based human rights group
this weekend criticized the reorganization of at least three
pro-Indonesian militia groups into civil defense units working with
the police, saying it was ``legal nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   East Timor covers half an island and was first colonized by the
Portuguese in the 16th century. Indonesian forces invaded in 1975
and the following year incorporated the territory as the country's
27th province.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations never recognized the move and a fierce war
waged. During the first years of Indonesian control, tens of
thousands died _ some say up to 200,000 _ from massacres, disease
and starvation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
