<SLUG> BC-ZIONS-FIRST-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIONS TO BUY FIRST SECURITY, A RIVAL, FOR $5.9 BILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Calif., Idaho. and Nev.)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to establish banking supremacy in the Western United
States, the Zions Bancorporation said Sunday that it was buying the
First Security Corp., its longtime rival in regional consumer
banking, in a deal worth $5.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, Zions will exchange a little less
than half a share for every share of First Security. The price per
share is about $28.90, or a 55 percent premium to First Security's
closing price of $18.625 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks, based in Salt Lake City, trace their origins to
Brigham Young, the Mormon leader whose followers settled in Utah.
The combined assets of the two will be $40.5 billion, making Zions,
which is taking the First Security name, one of the largest banks
in the West and one of the 20 largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Simmons, 44, the chief executive of Zions, will become
co-chief executive, president and chief operating officer of the
new bank. Spencer Eccles, 64, the chief executive of First
Security, will be the other co-chief executive through 2002 and
will be chairman until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both banks have approved the deal, which is
subject to shareholder and regulatory approval. Some assets in
Utah, where both banks are most active, will have to be sold to
comply with antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Talks that led to the deal began in late March, Simmons said in
a telephone interview Sunday. ``We've certainly known each other
for a long time, and we've had a great deal of respect for each
other as competitors,'' he said. ``We saw this as a unique
opportunity to create a significant and very premier financial
services company located here in Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   While both banks, which are active in California, Idaho, Nevada
and several other states as well as Utah, have staked their
reputations on consumer service, they are also involved in
insurance, investment banking and Internet technology through
acquisitions and other investments. Zions in particular has been on
an acquisition binge lately, with three deals since the first of
the year alone. First Security now owns the Van Kasper investment
bank, based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Zions bought the Sumitomo Bank of California, now
known as the California Bank and Trust, for $546 million. ``It's
given us a wonderful foothold in the California market,'' Simmons
said, ``with a lot of room for additional expansion.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
