<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     06-06 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT RELYING ON MIRACLES, KNICKS CHANGE LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The pixie dust and magic beans have served the
Knicks well in their enchanted tour through the playoffs, but the
team's realistic coach has decided that the trouble with miracles
is they are too unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   So against his structured nature, coach Jeff Van Gundy will
shake up his starting lineup even though his team leads the Pacers
by two games to one in the Eastern Conference finals. To combat the
matchup problems that could doom their supernatural ride through
the postseason, he will insert Latrell Sprewell into the starting
lineup for Game 4 Monday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell's spirits were popping like champagne after he had
campaigned for a starting role during the bulk of the season, he
didn't let it show in his subdued response to Van Gundy's decision
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal now,'' Sprewell said after the Knicks
practiced at SUNY-Purchase. ``We're so close.''
</P>
<P>
   Too close to a National Basketball Association championship
series to worry about whose name is called out as a starter. But as
fate would have it, Sprewell had just convinced himself that his
bench role was irrevocable for this season _ an issue he would take
up in the off season _ when Patrick Ewing went down with a
season-ending injury after Game 2. As a result, the matchups swung
dramatically in the Pacers' favor for Game 3 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the elated crowd nor the score revealed it _ not after a
wild 4-point play by Larry Johnson won the game, 92-91 _ but Van
Gundy saw his team dominated from the start and decided to tinker
at the risk of breaking good karma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's a gamble right now,'' he said, ``but this is the
one thing _ and it's not about winning just one game _ I know I
would have changed if the miracles wouldn't have happened. The
miracles happened, and it doesn't change what I think we need to do
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   They need to win without needing a fantasy finish. Each time the
Pacers threatened to tear away from the Knicks, Johnson came up
with shots diagramed by commercial choreographers. To close the
first quarter, Johnson hit a 30-footer at the buzzer. To beat the
shot-clock early in the fourth, he launched a 3-pointer that banked
off the glass. To win the game, he head-faked Antonio Davis, let go
of a 26-foot 3-pointer and drew a foul to create the dramatic
ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Indiana looked at the tape, they'd say, `We kicked their
butt,''' Van Gundy said. ``We made three miracle shots. That was
the difference in the game. You need those type of things when
you're outplayed. We got some unbelievably great performances by
individuals, but we can't kid ourselves, either. If we play like
that again, we're going to rely on miracles? I don't think that's
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Sprewell will get his fifth start of the season, and
first of the playoffs, to balance the Knicks without Ewing. Kurt
Thomas will come off the bench, with Johnson moving over to power
forward, next to Chris Dudley at center.
</P>
<P>
   To open Game 3, the Pacers put a vulnerable Chris Mullin on the
offensively challenged Dudley and played Dale Davis on Johnson
while the 7-foot-4-inch Rik Smits guarded Thomas. By the end of the
first half, Dudley had three fouls, Thomas had two, Johnson had two
and the Pacers had a 47-42 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were cross-matched all over the place,'' Van Gundy said.
``So in transition, we were all screwed up. Instead of being able
to go at Mullin, we couldn't. And so it really got us, I thought,
off to a bad start. And I think against this team, it would
continue to get us off to a bad start. Plus, with Kurt and Dud
together, boom, quick foul trouble and then we're too small in the
second quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Pacers had Jalen Rose on the floor to push around
Sprewell, and the foul-prone big men were unable to aggressively
guard Smits, who scored 15 consecutive points at the end of the
second quarter. For Sprewell, this is also a chance to get off to a
better start and exploit any matchup he has with the slow-footed
Mullin. So far, Sprewell has had a miserable series in the
halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the fast-break points that have grown harder to get
as the series has progressed, Sprewell would be scoring in single
digits each night. As it is, he is shooting 34 percent for the
series. He was just 6 for 19 in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was just missing shots,'' Sprewell said. ``I had a
lot of great looks, but the ball was just not going down for me. A
couple of times, they were there, and contested the shot. But
mostly, I just didn't make shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Sprewell has the chance to attack from the start, to pour
out the energy he has had to contain on the bench for the first
four to six minutes of every game. That energy has meant so much to
the success of the second unit. What now? Thomas will be the one
coming off the bench with the lively Marcus Camby and Chris Childs.
Any one of them could argue a good case to be in the starting
lineup, but they seemed at ease with Van Gundy's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latrell is going to start, and that's fine with me,'' Camby
said. ``It's something he's wanted, so you just have to rock 'n'
roll from there.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps win a game without using up their apportioned ration
of miracles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
