<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 20TH TRY, INKSTER GETS THE U.S. TITLE SHE CHERISHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Juli Inkster made it look so easy because
her play was so excellent.
</P>
<P>
   In her 20th attempt to win the U.S. Women's Open, Inkster left
nothing to chance, and overwhelmed the competition. At the age of
38, and in record-shattering fashion, she won the most prestigious
championship in women's golf Sunday, bringing her experience and
talent together on a vulnerable golf course that played to her
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Inkster reached the 16th tee at Old Waverly Golf
Club, she had a five-stroke lead, the gallery was showering her
with ovations and it was safe to start working on a victory speech.
While young talents like Kelli Kuehne and Grace Park proved they
have the talent to win future Opens, this moment _ and a $315,000
winner's check _ clearly belonged to Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting an Open-record 16-under-par 272 for the tournament, and
winning the fourth major title of her splendid career, Inkster
cruised to a five-stroke victory over Sherri Turner, who finished
at 277. Kuehne, a 22-year-old two-time U.S. Amateur champion, was
third at 279 after shooting a 74.
</P>
<P>
   For Inkster, a three-time U.S. Amateur champion, her first U.S.
Open championship was worth the wait. A native of Santa Cruz,
Calif., she became the first American to win the women's Open since
Patty Sheehan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   After a restless night, Inkster started the round Sunday morning
holding a four-stroke lead. In 1992, she had led the Open by two
strokes with two holes to play, only to lose to Sheehan in a
playoff. It was a loss that Inkster could never forget, and before
this weekend, she wondered if her best chance to win the Open had
already passed.
</P>
<P>
   But Inkster was rock-solid Sunday, shooting a one-under 71, and
she never led by fewer than three strokes. And after sinking her
final putt, Inkster, whose victory was her third of the year, spoke
freely about winning the championship that she wanted so badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told myself I've got to have the heart to win this
thing,'' said Inkster, who played the most consistent golf of her
career. ``To lose it again, I don't know if I could have gone
through another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my tournament to lose. No one had the pressure on
except me. That's the hardest part. I've played a lot of years, and
'92 was a heartbreak. But to come back to win today, no one can
take that away from me. I'm a U.S. Open champion, and I always will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster will try for the modern career grand slam later this
month when she plays in the McDonald's LPGA Championship, the only
major tournament she hasn't won.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster now has 24 Hall of Fame points, three shy of gaining
entrance into the LPGA Hall of Fame. Players are awarded two points
for winning a major, and one point for winning any other Ladies
Professional Golf Association event. Inkster has 20 career
victories, including four majors. But this tournament will be
remembered not only for her play, but also for the numerous scoring
records that fell:
</P>
<P>
   _ With scores of 65-69-67-71, Inkster's 16 under par easily
surpassed the previous women's Open record of 10 under, set by
Alison Nicholas in 1997 at Pumpkin Ridge Golf Club in North Plains,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   _ There were 135 under-par rounds during the tournament,
smashing the previous record of 89, also in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   _ In tying for eighth, Park, the reigning U.S. amateur champion
who will turn professional on Monday, set a low-scoring record for
an amateur (five-under-par 283), breaking Jenny Chuasiriporn's 290
last year. If not for a two-stroke penalty when her caddie
accidentally stepped on her buried ball at No. 8, Park's score
would have been even lower.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turner's 277 was the best score on record for a runner-up.
After winning just $12,017 last year, and without a top-three
finish since 1995, she was one of the happiest second-place
finishers ever, winning $185,000, more than she had won in the last
three years combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win, but in my mind, I got over a hump,'' said
Turner, who had the most spectacular shot of the day when she
eagled No. 11, sinking a 7-wood shot from 216 yards. ``The last 10
years has been a struggle. There have been times when I've felt
like quitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Turner nor anyone else could threaten Inkster. At No. 7,
she saved par with a marvelous bunker shot from a buried lie from
about 35 feet, the ball stopping less than two feet from the cup.
Kuehne, who was paired in the final group with Inkster, could sense
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked at Juli and said, `That's an amazing shot,'''
said Kuehne, who has finished seventh, first and third in her last
three events. ``She was playing way too consistently to have any
sort of meltdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Inkster was embraced by her husband, Brian, on the
18th green and surrounded by players offering congratulations.
There were times Inkster wondered if she could juggle her family
life _ she also has two children _ and her career. Today was
further proof that she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every tournament has a special place,'' Inkster said.
``But this is the ultimate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
