A5149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-COACH-535&AMP;AD     06-06 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-COACH-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGER SAYS HE'LL GO IF METS DON'T GET BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day after three of his coaches were dismissed,
New York Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said he deserved to follow
them if the team did not improve within the next third of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about my job,'' Valentine said at the end of a
long and uncomfortable news conference at Yankee Stadium that he
shared with General Manager Steve Phillips, who dismissed the
coaches Saturday evening against Valentine's strong objections. ``I
believe within the next 55 games if we're not better, I shouldn't
be the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said that consideration of the first 55 games,
approximately one-third of the 162-game season, was enough to
decide it was time for a change. He replaced Bob Apodaca with Dave
Wallace as pitching coach, Randy Niemann with Al Jackson as bullpen
coach, and Tom Robson with Mickey Brantley as hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips acted after the Mets had lost their eighth straight
game and had fallen to a record of 27-28. The last time the Mets
lost eight in a row was in 1996; Valentine became manager in the
midst of that one.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was asked if he felt he would be gone if the team
didn't improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would be an absolute foregone conclusion,''
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Would he resign?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say that,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine expressed some optimism that the team would stay
in the pennant race. ``Within the next 55 to 75 games we'll be in
touch with the leaders of our division,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during batting practice, as Valentine discussed Bobby
Bonilla's hitting mechanics with Brantley, Valentine was asked if
he had considered quitting his job in protest against the dismissal
of three coaches who also happen to be his good friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand quitting,'' Valentine said. ``I don't know
what it is to quit. And to my coaches' credit, they know that about
me and they made it absolutely clear what we've got to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, during the news conference, Valentine squirmed often in
his seat and appeared to have trouble controlling his reactions to
certain questions directed at Phillips. Later, Valentine admitted
that the last two days had been extremely tough on him and that he
had spent Saturday night in a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was finding me last night,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   He had just endured another galling defeat on Saturday, only to
ride a team bus back to Shea Stadium to meet with Phillips for more
than an hour. Valentine delivered his arguments to Phillips about
why he should not replace the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   So far as Phillips was concerned, however, there was nothing
Valentine could say to change his mind. The two met again Sunday
afternoon before making the trip from Shea. And one member of the
organization said that where an already strained relationship could
have become irreparably lost, it was surprising, considering the
growing animosity between Phillips and Valentine, how well things
went.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Sunday to describe his relationship with Phillips,
who was sitting right next to him, Valentine said: ``It was
emotional last night and very professional today. We've had some
situations in the past and we came out stronger afterwards.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Could there be a worse place in America to hold this news
conference than Yankee Stadium, one questioner asked. Phillips did
not answer. But Valentine smiled inside the home of the team that
always steals the headlines from his team and said, ``I don't think
it could be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Valentine's players were dealing with questions about
their relationships with the three coaches who had just been
deposed. Almost all noted that it was they and not the coaches who
threw or hit the balls.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was that it was not the coaches' fault that the Mets
were already six games back in the loss column in the National
League wild-card race. John Olerud, for one, appeared to be taken
aback that Robson had been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, who set the club record in batting average last season
when he hit .354, credited Robson with helping him turn around a
career that had gone stale in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best hitting instructor that I've worked with,''
Olerud said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the Mets' front office felt the same about
Apodaca's work with the team's pitchers. But the Mets, who opened
the season with a $63.5 million payroll, are built to win now.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Valentine's job was in jeopardy, Phillips said,
``It is still my opinion that Bobby is the guy who will lead us out
of the slump we're in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
