<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WIZARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S WIN IS A STRUGGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With the way his luck has gone lately,
nothing has been a sure thing for Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   He's missed more chances and hit more posts than he could count
this season, which made his can't-miss, empty-net goal tougher than
it should have been in the Los Angeles Galaxy's 1-0 victory over
Kansas City in front of 6,871 at the Rose Bowl on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a game pitting the two lowest-scoring teams in Major League
Soccer, the Galaxy's Cobi Jones narrowly beat an off-side trap down
the left side on a pass from Mauricio Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   Clear of the defense, Jones drew Wizards goalkeeper Chris Snitko
away from his line, leaving Mathis clear in front of the net. Jones
dropped his pass in front of the goal for Mathis, but what seemed
like an easy tap-in barely caught the right side of the net in the
64th minute.
</P>
<P>
   That's just how it's gone for the Galaxy (6-6) this season.
Nothing comes easy, not when you've scored only eight goals in 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City dropped to a league-worst 1-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the goal) was definitely harder than I thought it was
going to be,'' said Mathis of his third goal of the season. ``It
was a little bumpy in front of the goal. They just sodded that area
and it took a funny bounce. It went in, though. That's the most
important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and Jones (two goals this season) have taken most of the
heat for the Galaxy's lack of scoring. Jones hit the post twice
Sunday and Mathis missed an earlier opportunity that would have put
the Wizards away much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis admitted he had several chances to score last week in a
2-1 shootout loss at Columbus. He said his confidence isn't
rattled, but it's definitely on the shaky side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, sometimes it is,'' said Mathis. ``Right now it seems
like nothing's going to go my way. In practice, I've been working
on (finishing). I've been getting a lot of confidence there, but it
was good to actually get one in the back of the net during a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid was hoping his team could use this game
to notch its first multiple-scoring outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going through this a long time,'' said Schmid.
``The goal seems so small right now or maybe it's just wrapped in
cellophane.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Los Angeles received another solid effort from
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman, who recorded his MLS-leading sixth
shutout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
