u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALBOTT-1STLD-     06-06 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALBOTT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PEACE NEGOTIATOR WAS ALWAYS A DIPLOMAT AT HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to modify the 4th graf to reflect the newly uncertain state
of the peace deal.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1967, when Yale, like many other universities,
was in ferment over the war in Vietnam, James Reston, the columnist
for The New York Times, was in New Haven and ran into a 21-year-old
junior named Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   When Reston asked Talbott where he stood on the war, Reston
wrote in his column, this is the response he got: ``I do not want
to help pillory the present administration. I am interested to see
if there are new means and attitudes by which this university, and
hence the university community in general, can make discussion less
polemical and more meaningful and at the same time help the search
for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Talbott, now 53 years old and the deputy secretary
of state, spent his entire career as a journalist before he joined
the Clinton administration, he obviously thought and spoke like a
diplomat even as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   His diplomatic skills served him well last week during
negotiations to end the war in Yugoslavia with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic; the Russian envoy on Kosovo, former Prime
Minister Victor Chernomyrdin, and President Martii Ahtisaari of
Finland.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Saturday, Talbott, who arrived home
Friday night, was wary of saying anything that might jinx the
endgame in the Balkans. ``The talks at the border are still going
on, and this isn't over,'' he said. ``I want to make sure my
comments aren't ahead of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the negotiations as ``a very complex example of
diplomacy and force coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth week out of the last seven that Talbott (he
pronounces it TALL-but) has been in Europe. On weekends, he flew
home to meet with President Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very intense,'' he said. ``It's had its ups and
downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said that becoming a diplomat was never his ambition.
``Journalism is the only profession I ever aspired to,'' he said.
``It was a biographical fluke that presented me with this
extraordinary opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The fluke was that he and Bill Clinton were roommates at Oxford
when they were Rhodes Scholars, and they remained close friends
afterward. When Clinton became president in 1993, he made Talbott
ambassador-at-large with responsibility for countries of the former
Soviet Union. The next year, he became deputy secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations over the war in Yugoslavia allowed ``a couple
of aspects of my life to come together,'' Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   One was his interest in Russia. He majored in Russian studies at
Yale, is fluent in Russian and translated and edited two volumes of
Nikita Khrushchev's memoirs in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   He and Chernomyrdin spoke Russian when they talked one on one,
aides said. When all three negotiators were at the table, the talks
were in English, and they were translated into Russian for
Chernomyrdin,
</P>
<P>
   The other aspect Talbott mentioned was his interest in
Yugoslavia. His first job after he and his wife were married in
1971 was as Eastern European correspondent for Time magazine, based
in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he turned on the television in his room in
Bonn, Germany, this week and saw the Yugoslav Parliament meeting on
the peace agreement, he recalled that the first apartment he and
his wife had in Belgrade was only three blocks away from the
Parliament building.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Strobridge Talbott III was born in Dayton, Ohio, on April
25, 1946. His father was an investment banker. He began learning
Russian in prep school at Hotchkiss in Connecticut and wrote his
thesis at Yale on the 19th century Russian lyric poet Fyodor
Tyuchev.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Time magazine after his years as a Rhodes Scholar and
never worked anywhere else until he entered the government. He
began as an intern in the Moscow bureau and rose to become
diplomatic correspondent, White House correspondent, Washington
bureau chief and editor at large.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bosnia peace negotiations were under way in Dayton in
1995, he pointed out to the participants some landmarks of his
youth, and he was host of a dinner at the Dayton Racquet Club, to
which his parents had belonged when he was a child.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott's wife, Brooke Shearer, has long been a friend of the
Clintons. She worked on the 1992 campaign and is now an official at
the Department of Interior, where she helps developing countries
set up park systems. They have two sons, Devin, 22, who is entering
law school in the fall, and Adrian, 18, who just finished his
freshman year at Amherst College.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at Amherst dedicating a Russian culture center last
year, Talbott described how he had been fascinated by Russia ever
since the Soviet Union launched the Sputnik satellite when he was
11 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found it useful,'' he declared, ``to have, programmed
into the software of my thinking and puzzling about Russia, a sense
of what a mixed bag that proud and insecure, rich and deprived,
confused and confusing country has been, what it is today and what
it can be someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
