<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SPINOFF FROM DISNEY IS CONSIDERED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Walt Disney Co. is considering a spinoff of its
Internet-related operations, several people close to the
discussions said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The details of any plan were not clear, but Disney has stakes in
several Internet businesses that could become part of any spinoff.
A Disney spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts say that Disney is under pressure to raise its
sagging stock price, which has been hurt recently by weak earnings
from its television and film operations. For the second quarter,
Disney said its profit fell 30 percent because of weaker home video
and merchandising sales and higher costs at ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those figures, shares of Disney rose $1.625, or 5.6
percent, on Friday, to $30.625, amid reports that Disney might
either spin off some of its Internet operations or possibly buy
back some stock. Disney's stock had been as high as $40.313 last
July and had fallen to $22.50 by October.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Disney acquired 43 percent of the Infoseek Corp., a
service that helps guide users on the World Wide Web, in a deal
valued at $900 million. Disney put up $90 million in cash and its
ownership of Starwave, a company that creates elaborate Web sites.
Disney had previously acquired Starwave in several phases from Paul
Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The company's biggest venture is the sports site it operates on
behalf of ESPN. Several of Disney's other businesses, including
ABC, ABC News and Disney itself, have established Web sites, and
one analyst speculated Sunday that Disney might swap those assets
into Infoseek in exchange for a larger stake in the company.
Infoseek executives could not be reached for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Disney already has the right to raise its stake in Infoseek to
as much as 50.1 percent as part of an agreement to lend Infoseek up
to $139 million over the first five years of the deal. Infoseek and
Disney have also created the Go Network, Disney's answer to Yahoo,
and other portals to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Disney could theoretically spin off some of its assets into a
tracking stock, where underlying assets are owned by the parent
company but the stock itself is publicly traded. But a spinoff
might not be met as favorably on Wall Street as a stock buyback
because Internet stocks have weakened and new offerings have lost
some of their allure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO-1st     06-06 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    HOPES FADE FOR QUICK PEACE AS KOSOVO WITHDRAWAL TALKS COLLAPSE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Updates with collapse of talks and fresh material
throughout 
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ NATO pledged to ``intensify the air
campaign `` against Yugoslavia after marathon talks on implementing
a peace plan collapsed early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav military commanders had made a proposal ``that would
not guarantee the safe return of all'' ethnic Albanian refugees who
fled Kosovo or ``the full withdrawal of Yugoslav forces'' from the
embattled province, said Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, the NATO
commander in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav proposal was ``inconsistent'' with terms of a peace
plan accepted Thursday by the Yugoslav federal government and
approved overwhelmingly by the Serb parliament, he said. Serbia is
the dominant republic in the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   Reading a statement to reporters in the pre-dawn darkness,
Jackson said NATO now has ``no alternative'' but to ``intensify the
air campaign until such time as the Yugoslav side (is) prepared to
agree to implement the agreement fully and without ambiguity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Jackson's announcement, air raid sirens sounded in
Belgrade, warning of possible resumed NATO attacks in the Yugoslav
capital.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear when, of if, talks would resume on
the so-called ``military technical agreement'' that lays out the
conditions for the withdrawal of Serb-led military and police units
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson indicated the NATO commanders were willing to meet
again. Yugoslav Foreign Ministry spokesman Nebojsa Vujovic, who
participated in the talks, told reporters the same thing as he
demanded a halt to any further bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's reference to a Yugoslav ``proposal'' indicated the
talks had gone seriously off track. When they began Saturday at a
cafe in Blace on the Macedonian border, NATO officials had
envisioned no negotiations and swift Yugoslav acceptance of the
alliance withdrawal plan.
</P>
<P>
   But snags developed early Sunday when the talks shifted to a
camouflage tent at a hot and dusty airfield in Kumanovo, northwest
of the Macedonian capital of Skopje. The Yugoslav commanders took
issue with plans for the simultaneous entry of NATO-led
peacekeeping forces as Serb-led forces were withdrawing from
Kosovo. As the talks edged into Monday morning, it became apparent
they were at an impasse on this and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Yugoslav military commanders had agreed to
only six of the 20 conditions in the 6-page withdrawal document.
</P>
<P>
   Hinting at the seriousness of the ruptured talks, Finnish
President Marti Ahtisaari, who had brokered the peace plan,
abruptly cancelled a planned trip to discuss it with Chinese
leaders in Beijing amid speculation he might be asked to resume his
negotiating role.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the talks collapsed, NATO used U.S. B-52 bombers to
pound Serb troops along Kosovo's border with Albania. Yugoslavia's
state-run Tanjug news agency reported late Sunday that NATO jets
also fired 30 missiles at Serb targets in western Kosovo, which is
a province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the Yugoslavs' refusal to sign the
agreement was a stalling tactic. Pentagon officials have said in
recent days that Serb forces may want more time to cover up
evidence of atrocities before they are forced to withdraw from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There also were NATO reports Sunday of Serb forces looting the
towns of Prizren and Pristina inside Kosovo. Meanwhile, Serb forces
and pro-independence Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas engaged in
heavy fighting Sunday along the Kosovo-Albania border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and other allied officials said late Sunday that the
Yugoslav military commanders raised a number of objections to the
agreement. Among them, they:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did not like the simultaneous entry of NATO-led peacekeeping
troops into Kosovo at the same time that Serb-led forces were
withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were unable to withdraw all of their 40,000 forces within the
specified 7-day period because they didn't have enough
</P>
<P>
   gas and many of their vehicles were damaged. They reportedly
wanted up to ten days. They also reportedly said that many of their
forces could not quickly reach the three NATO-designated withdrawal
routes from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Opposed withdrawing their forces from a 15-mile buffer zone
between Serbia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were unwilling to withdraw Serb police officers who are
residents of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Insisted the NATO-led peacekeeping effort could not begin
until the United Nations Security Council approved it.
</P>
<P>
   There also was confusion Sunday about whether the KLA would
disarm, as called for in the peace plan. Shinasi Rama, a KLA
spokesman, told CNN that ``we see no reason'' to totally disarm,
arguing that guerrilla fighters should be permitted to retain small
arms like those Americans ``can buy in a K-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, aid workers at the main Stankovec refugee center in
Macedonia on Sunday attributed a near-riot and bloody attack on
five ethnic Roma, or gypsy, refugees three of them children to
mounting tensions over the talks. They also worried the incident
previewed how ugly relations may become in Kosovo among ethnic
Albanians, Serbs and other minority groups once the refugees do get
home again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad sign for any kind of ethnic tolerance inside Kosovo
when they go back,'' said Nancy Shalala, spokesperson for the
Catholic Relief Services. ``People are looking for some face to be
responsible for what happened inside Kosovo. This time the face was
the Romas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic agency's volunteers and international staff dragged
a Roma father and son from a crowd that was battering them Saturday
night around 7:30 p.m. Some ethnic Albanian refugees believed the
two men had been collaborators with Serb forces and were
responsible for killing some Albanians, Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers took the Romas, who are also considered gypsies, to
an agency office for protection. But the crowd built until some
angry refugees stormed the office and beat the two men nearly
senseless.
</P>
<P>
   The attacking refugees finally were driven outside, but then set
upon three Roma children and tried ``to rip them limb from limb,''
Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   All five were rescued and taken for medical treatment, but only
after U.S. Ambassador Christopher Hill came to the scene and
quieted the teeming crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more tense now,'' said refugee Musa Govori, 32, who
said he witnessed part of the melee and Hill's intervention.
``These people have already learned a lot from the Milosevic's past
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees not only are afraid the talks may not bear fruit, but
also now must confront the uncertainty of what destruction and loss
they will find at home if the talks do succeed.
</P>
<P>
   (Albright reported from Kumanovo; Kunstel reported from Skopje.
The Associated Press contiobuted to this report).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
