<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY'S PET ISSUES COULD SHAPE SENATE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As she inches closer to running for senator from
New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton is preparing to build a campaign
around education, family and health care issues _ the areas where
she has the clearest record of accomplishment, and failure,
Democrats close to the first lady say.
</P>
<P>
   Those three areas would be a natural focus of Mrs. Clinton's
campaign, because she cares passionately about them and has become
a leading administration voice on all three. For someone who has
never run for office, Mrs. Clinton has also established a
remarkably long and detailed track record on the issues during two
decades of public life.
</P>
<P>
   That record _ established in leading an education commission in
Arkansas, in her much criticized handling of the 1993 health care
debate and in her more recent but less noticed role in negotiating
adoption and bankruptcy legislation _ is sure to be a target of
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton's advisers believe that there will be a clear
political payoff to constructing a campaign around her keenest
interests. For one thing, they say, she has developed an
encyclopedic expertise on the three subjects that enables her to
debate arcane policy and give seamless speeches without a text or
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also assert that New York voters have grown
increasingly concerned about the quality of their schools and the
availability of health care, while crime _ the issue on which
voters tend to give higher marks to Republicans _ has fallen
somewhat in importance in polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were other moments when Mrs. Clinton might not have been
the right candidate for New York state,'' a top adviser to Mrs.
Clinton said. ``But a happy confluence of events has made this an
ideal time for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, many prominent Democrats believe that Mrs. Clinton's
positions on education and health care will provide the sharpest
contrasts between her and the man they expect to be her Republican
rival, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible opponent is Rep. Rick A. Lazio, a Suffolk
County Republican, who has said he might enter the race. Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the three-term Democrat who holds the
seat, is retiring at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond policy, Mrs. Clinton's advisers also expect her to attack
Giuliani's hard-edged style, if he is the candidate. ``The
temperament to be a senator is very different from being a mayor,''
said State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a Democrat. ``Many people
will not see Giuliani as somebody with the ability to get along
with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding contrasts with Giuliani is important to many Democrats
because, even though Republicans have sought to paint Mrs. Clinton
as an extreme liberal, she and Giuliani agree on many of the issues
that have historically separated Republican and Democratic
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Both support the death penalty, abortion rights and homosexual
rights _ as does Lazio. She endorsed the welfare law that helped
Giuliani shrink the city's welfare rolls. And he broke with other
Republicans in endorsing the Clinton administration's crime bill of
1994, which included gun control provisions and money for hiring
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of contrast that I had with D'Amato on gun control
and choice will not be as stark,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, a
Democrat, referring to former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, whom he
unseated last year.
</P>
<P>
   But on education, there are clear differences. Giuliani has
clashed with New York City school officials over what he considers
their excessive spending, and has strongly advocated vouchers to
allow more students to attend private schools. Mrs. Clinton has
been an ardent supporter of increased spending on public schools
and an outspoken critic of vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   On health care, many Democrats say that Mrs. Clinton should
attack Giuliani for having tried to privatize the municipal
hospitals. Those Democrats assert that even though Mrs. Clinton's
highly publicized efforts to win sweeping health care changes in
1993 was a signal failure of her husband's first term, most New
Yorkers now support her goal of making health care coverage
available for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to say she was out there way ahead of her
time,'' said McCall, contrasting Mrs. Clinton with Giuliani.
``People see him as someone who tried to downsize and privatize
hospitals, not being an advocate for improving health care.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In recent New York appearances, Mrs. Clinton seems to have
tailored her speeches to draw distinctions between herself and
Giuliani, without mentioning his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never lift up our public schools, or the students they
serve, by tearing them down,'' she said to roaring applause at City
College last week, in what seemed a reference to Giuliani's feud
with Chancellor Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   And in an address at Teachers College at Columbia University in
April, Mrs. Clinton urged her audience not ``to be pulled off track
by false debates'' advanced by advocates of publicly financed
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have already begun attacking Mrs. Clinton by
depicting her as being out of the mainstream, and say they are
likely to use the health care debate as evidence that she is a
big-government liberal at heart. Her allies say she is more of a
pragmatist than the Republicans realize.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also say they are likely to try to cast Mrs. Clinton
as having grand but gauzy ideas on a few national subjects, but
little knowledge of regional issues like dairy prices or mass
transit. Giuliani has already repeatedly assailed Mrs. Clinton as
an out-of-stater who cannot find her way around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say she is well on her way to learning local issues.
Those Democrats say Mrs. Clinton's greater challenge, similar to
that facing Vice President Al Gore, will be to demonstrate that she
has been more than just a spokeswoman for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton can point to her own record on education,
family and health care issues, dating back to her Arkansas days.
During his second term as governor of Arkansas, Clinton appointed
his wife head of an education task force that helped write
legislation that set standards for class sizes and course
offerings, raised teachers' salaries and required teachers to pass
competency tests _ a step sharply criticized by teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
   On most issues, Mrs. Clinton's positions are indistinguishable
from her husband's _ which is not necessarily a bad thing in New
York state, where the president's policies have been widely
popular.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been some cracks between Mrs. Clinton's and the
administration's positions. For instance, Mrs. Clinton in 1998
endorsed the idea of a Palestinian state, a position not taken by
the administration. Giuliani has already begun criticizing her
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are also likely to attack those administration
policies that are viewed as harmful to the state, trying to force
Mrs. Clinton, who would be the first first lady to seek office, to
choose between criticizing her husband or defending unpopular
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Democrats have been the first to do that, urging
Mrs. Clinton to oppose the administration's efforts to cut
Medicare. In a sign of how difficult it may be to run for office
while living in the White House, 1199, the National Health and
Human Service Employees Union, which is reliably Democratic, has
begun an advertising campaign attacking the president's Medicare
cuts. Though the campaign does not mention Mrs. Clinton, its
message is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every reason to believe that Hillary Clinton will be
defending the interests of all New Yorkers, and one of them will be
defending the health care community of New York,'' said Dennis
Rivera, the union president and one of Mrs. Clinton's strongest
backers.
</P>
</TEXT>
