<HEADLINE>
EDWARD LUMBARD, 97, JUDGE AND PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Vt., N.Y., N.M., Mass., Wash.)  (lb) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge J. Edward Lumbard Jr., whose career as a lawyer,
prosecutor and jurist spanned eight decades, culminating in his
appointment by President Dwight Eisenhower in 1955 to the 2nd
Circuit Court of Appeals, died on Thursday at his home in
Fairfield, Conn. He was 97.
</P>
<P>
   As a young lawyer, he worked with William Donovan, the director
of the Office of Strategic Services, which was the precursor of the
CIA. He also worked with Thomas E. Dewey as chief assistant U.S.
attorney in New York City and investigated many scandals. He also
was an assistant campaign manager for Dewey's second unsuccessful
campaign for president in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most major figures in the long history of
the courts in the 2nd Circuit and the development of the body of
law in this circuit,'' said Judge Ralph Winter, the current chief
of the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals. The 2nd Circuit covers New
York, Connecticut and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Lumbard was born on Aug. 18, 1901, in the Harlem section of New
York City. He graduated from DeWitt Clinton High School in 1918,
Harvard College in 1922 and Harvard Law School in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to New York in 1925 as an assistant in the office of
the U.S. attorney for the Southern District, which includes eight
counties in the state. In 1928, Gov. Alfred E. Smith, responding to
allegations of sewerage-construction kickbacks in the borough of
Queens in New York City, named Emory Buckner as a special
prosecutor. Buckner named John Harlan as his chief assistant, and
Lumbard, in turn, became Harlan's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The highly publicized investigation led to numerous indictments,
including that of the Queens borough president. It also sparked a
close friendship between Lumbard and Harlan, who later became a
justice of the U.S. Supreme Court. Indeed, the two were men's
doubles champions at the Country Club of Fairfield in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Lumbard took Harlan's seat on the Court of Appeals in 1955, when
he was appointed to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   After the Queens sewer scandal, Lumbard, from 1931 to 1933, was
the chief of the criminal division for the U.S. attorney's office,
under Dewey. In 1933, he became a founding partner in the law firm
of Donovan, Leisure, Newton &AMP; Lumbard. In 1935, at the behest of
the American Civil Liberties Union, he took on, pro bono, a
well-publicized case and helped win acquittal of 10 Mexicans who
had been accused of murdering a sheriff in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he again left private practice to be the chief
assistant to Hiram Todd, who had been appointed by New York Gov.
Herbert Lehman to investigate the beating and strangling of Samuel
Drukman, a garage worker, and a Brooklyn grand jury's subsequent
refusal to indict three men linked to the killing. The men were
later convicted of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, Lumbard was a special assistant attorney general in
charge of a newly formed election-frauds bureau. He also took a
temporary appointment in 1947 as a state Supreme Court justice in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, he left private practice and for two years was
the U.S. attorney in Manhattan before being appointed to the Court
of Appeals in 1955. He became the chief judge there in 1959 and
remained in that capacity until 1971, when he became a senior
judge.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, he made many changes in the management and
administration of the court system. He was the first chief judge to
schedule appellate arguments on a specific date, a step that helped
ensure that judges who would be hearing the appeal were familiar
with the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an inspirational mentor to many of the most outstanding
judges and lawyers in the city,'' said Robert Fiske Jr., a former
U.S. attorney, who in 1954, while a student, worked in Lumbard's
office when he was the U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Chief Justice Warren Burger named Lumbard to the
Special Court of Appeals responsible for appointing independent
counsels. He resigned that position in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   From 1964 to 1968, Lumbard was chairman of the American Bar
Association's Committee to Develop Minimum Standards for Criminal
Justice. In 1968, he was awarded the ABA's Gold Medal for his
contributions to justice administration.
</P>
<P>
   He was an overseer of Harvard University from 1959 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Polly Poindexter, died in 1997. He is survived by a
daughter, Abigail Lumbard of Seattle; a son, Thomas, of Washington,
and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
