<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-RDP-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC HAS SURGERY, PAVING WAY FOR A PRODUCTIVE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no swelling in Charismatic's left front leg
Sunday morning, and veterinarians had no problems surgically
inserting four screws into that leg Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The chestnut, who was injured Saturday after running a game
third in the Belmont Stakes, is expected to recover fully and live
well as a high-priced stallion.
</P>
<P>
   But his racing career, brief and brilliant, is over.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time claiming horse whose unlikely ascent took him to
the doorstep of the Triple Crown underwent 2 1/2 hours of surgery
at the Belmont Equine Surgical Clinic to repair fractured left
front cannon and sesamoid bones. Dr. Stephen J. Selway led the
five-person surgical team to align and stabilize Charismatic's
fetlock joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the worst injury of this kind I've ever seen, but
it was a nasty one and certainly not an average one,'' Selway said
Sunday. ``What happens usually with these is that the fracture
spirals to the front _ this one spiraled to the back. The condylar
fracture happened first, and I believe Chris Antley knew something
was wrong inside the eight pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the horse went on, the damaged piece hit the sesamoids and
caused them to fracture. The sesamoids are the reason why this
horse won't race again.''
</P>
<P>
   The successful surgery was welcome news in the trainer D. Wayne
Lukas' barn. It came at the end of a harrowing 24 hours that began
with Charismatic a head from becoming the 12th Triple Crown winner
in history as he approached the stretch of the staggering 1 1/2
-mile race on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhilaration suddenly turned heart stopping when Antley,
Charismatic's jockey, leapt off the colt just past the finish line
and held up the horse's left leg.
</P>
<P>
   Antley was ashen and sobbing after the race, but his quick exit
from the saddle may very well have saved Charismatic's life.
According to Selway, Antley's action certainly prevented further
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Selway emphatically tried to remove any suspicion that Lukas or
Charismatic's owner's, Bob and Beverly Lewis, had made the horse
susceptible to injury by racing him five times _ including winning
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness _ in 64 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody deserved a Triple Crown, it was these people,'' he
said. ``And let me say that this joint was pristine. There was no
evidence of any pre-existing condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who is thoroughbred racing's most accomplished trainer,
began Sunday optimistic and ended the day elated. He said
Charismatic showed no signs of swelling overnight when the trainer
removed his compression boot. He was rambunctious in his stall and
lived up to his reputation as a hearty eater.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a son of a gun,'' Lukas said of the colt who he often
referred to affectionately as a big, fat horse. ``We've never had
so much as to run a hose on his leg or put ice on it. He's the
toughest horse I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The trainer was also unapologetic about the training and racing
regimen he had imposed on his horse as he vied to become the first
Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has won 12 Triple Crown races, has often been
criticized for pushing his horses too hard in his search for those
grueling victories. His integrity and horsemanship were savaged in
the mid-1990s when Union City, a horse some believed was not sound,
fractured a leg during the 1993 Preakness Stakes and did not
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Several other high-profile breakdowns followed, including that
of the 1995 Kentucky Derby and Belmont winner Thunder Gulch.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many horses as I train and at the level we compete, I'm
going to get criticized,'' Lukas said. ``The only critics I have to
worry about are my owners _ the Lewises. I can't worry about what
people say.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown of Charismatic perhaps overshadowed one of horse
racing's finest days and the Belmont's long-shot winner, Lemon Drop
Kid. A crowd of 85,818, some of them very lucky or knowledgeable or
both, watched a 30-1 shot win and a 55-1 shot, Vision and Verse,
finish second.
</P>
<P>
   In an even more improbable twist, the riders _ Jose Santos on
Lemon Drop Kid and Herb Castillo Jr. on Vision and Verse _ are
brothers-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize that he was on the inside of me until we got
past the wire and he gave me a high-five,'' said Santos, who is
married to Castillo's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid walked quietly around the track Sunday morning
and probably won't run until late summer in the Grade II Jim Dandy
at Saratoga. ``He's fine, but he's tired,'' said Randy Schulhofer,
who is the assistant trainer to his father, Scotty.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mile and a half is a long way to go. He ate all his feed
last night and this morning, and came out with no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone filly, Silverbulletday, also was in good shape Sunday
despite losing her first race after nine victories. She looked like
she might become only the third filly to win the Belmont after
leading for a mile, but ultimately was wrapped up by Jerry Bailey
and finished a disheartening seventh.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She will now be rested for a while. ``Jerry did just what we
asked him to do,'' said Mike Pegram, the filly's owner. ``When he
felt he didn't have a chance, he took it easy on her.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lukas nor the Lewises knew how much of a chance
Charismatic had when he rounded the first turn in the lead. Lukas
said veterinarian Robert Copelan, a respected horse doctor, called
him twice Saturday night after watching tape of the race and told
him it appeared Charismatic had first got hurt at the top of the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Antley believes it happened either before or after the wire.
Wherever it occurred, Lukas said, two things are certain:
Charismatic will go to stud and command a lucrative fee _ probably
about $40,000 _ and the injury stopped a potentially brilliant
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's speculation where it occurred and I'm not saying it cost
him the race,'' Lukas said. ``But that horse ran hard, gave it all
he had. He's a great one, and thank goodness we didn't lose him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REACT-1ST     06-06 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 NEIGHBORS, 3 VIEWS OF THE WAR IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to make selected deletions because of the newly uncertain
state of the peace deal: in 8th graf, beginning None has
relatives...; 17th graf, beginning I'm just fed up...; and 27th
graf, beginning So was it ...) (mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end of NATO's war on Yugoslavia seems to be in sight, but
among a group of Americans who discussed the news, there is little
exultation.
</P>
<P>
   Dilia Theodosakia, a retired secretary who long ago abandoned
her initial support for the bombing, sees no winners, only losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all criminals in their own way, not just Milosevic,''
she said, lumping in the leaders of NATO countries with Slobodan
Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia. ``They are all responsible
for escalating suffering. The Albanians in Kosovo had problems
before, but once the bombing started the killing got worse and the
Serbs suffered terribly, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Mrs. Theodosakia, Martha McCauley has remained steadfast
in her belief that only military force could stop Yugoslav violence
against the Albanian population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO cause is just, she said, but the bill will be high.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the refugees go back, and their houses are all gone, what
will we do?'' said Mrs. McCauley, a retired IBM employee and busy
grandmother. ``Who is going to pay for the rebuilding of that
country? I think Milosevic and Yugoslavia should pay for that. It's
their fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the NATO bombing campaign against the
Yugoslavs, Mrs. Theodosakia, Mrs. McCauley and several of their
neighbors in White Plains, N.Y., which is in Westchester County not
far from New York City, have been asked regularly to discuss their
impressions and opinions about the war.
</P>
<P>
   None has relatives or friends in the military. So without a
personal stake in the conflict, they have been paying less and less
attention to what has been happening in Yugoslavia, but they are
skeptical about whether NATO's aims have been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Theodosakia, who describes herself as a conservative, has
come full circle in her views about the war.
</P>
<P>
   At first mistrustful of President Clinton's motives, she came to
rally to the NATO cause, believing it a moral mission to save the
Kosovo Albanians. Then, as civilian casualties mounted in the NATO
bombing, so did her sympathies for the Yugoslavs as victims of
equal standing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mrs. Theodosakia, who at age 57 is about to start a new
career as a nutritionist, is once again deeply suspicious of the
motivations of NATO leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every war, there's something behind it _ politics or
selfishness on somebody's part _ and yet civilians are the ones who
suffer,'' she said. ``I'd really like to know the truth, why they
were doing this just in Yugoslavia when there are people suffering
all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   From reading several newspapers, listening to radio talk shows
and having discussions with relatives, Mrs. Theodosakia said she
had reached her own conclusions about what the situation in Kosovo
was before the NATO bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a holocaust in the making, as portrayed by President
Clinton, but a conflict between the Yugoslav government and the
Kosovo Albanian separatists, ``who used force and terror because
they wanted a piece of the country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO did not resolve that conflict by bombing. ``What did they
accomplish?'' she continued. ``What I say is this: Send the leaders
to war. Let them feel the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clark, an employee of the Westchester County Board of
Elections, tuned out weeks ago to the war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just fed up with it,'' he said. ``We have exhausted our
stay over there, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a trim 58-year-old, served in Vietnam as a Marine and
that experience still marks his views. He looks with a skeptic's
eye at any war, no matter how noble-sounding its goals, and
recalled his own war days as a time when he ``saw kids dying like
flies.''
</P>
<P>
   During the more than two months of the Kosovo war, he has had
very little patience with what he sees as the bombast of military
commanders, and a great deal of faith in the old adage that truth
is the first casualty of war.
</P>
<P>
   So when NATO missiles began occasionally to go astray, killing
Yugoslav civilians and in some cases Kosovo Albanians, Clark
considered his natural cynicism well founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so many civilian casualties,'' he said.
``Friendly fire _ I told you that was going to happen. Once you go
to war, even if you have all these high-tech weapons, as long as
you're human, you're going to have errors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the NATO bombing, Clark paid close
attention to the war news, almost in spite of himself. ``In the
beginning I was interested,'' he acknowledged. ``But after it got
so prolonged, I just wasn't interested anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way he could explain his indifference was, again, to
reach back to his own memories as a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what the outcome was going to be before it happened,''
Clark said. ``I knew no one would really win. I knew innocent
people were going to die. Been there. Done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCauley's interest, on the other hand, never flagged. An
avid reader before the war, she added an extra daily newspaper to
her morning regime to stay informed.
</P>
<P>
   At 69, she is old enough to remember her father serving in the
Army in World War II. Moved and angered by the Serbs' expulsion of
Kosovo Albanians, she saw the NATO war against Yugoslavia as an
echo of her father's good fight. And while the casualties and the
destruction wrought by NATO bombs saddened her, they never dented
her pride that the United States ``helps people.''
</P>
<P>
   So was it worth it? she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCauley did not like that question. ``It was war,'' she
said, ``and you never think of anything as being worth war. But I
just don't think Milosevic would have done anything without this
war. He would have just gone on with his ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
