<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-NKOREA-ART-550(2T     06-06 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NKOREA-ART-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NORTH KOREAN WOMEN'S SOCCER TEAM, PARADISE AND LUNCH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFFSIDE PARK, N.J. _ With a thaw in the frosty relations
between the two countries, North Korea has arrived to prepare for
the Women's World Cup and a first-round match against the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials sat in a restaurant here Saturday, wearing
identical blue blazers with the North Korean star flag etched on
the breast and lapel pins bearing the likeness of President Kim
Jong Il. They spoke as stiffly as they dressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please ask questions only related to soccer and sports,'' said
Ryu Song Il, secretary-general of the North Korean Olympic
Committee. ``Otherwise we will make no comments.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the United States faced Iran in the 1998 men's World Cup
during a time of political softening, North Korea has arrived days
after President Clinton offered to phase out American economic
sanctions if North Korea abandons its ambitions to manufacture
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States-North Korea game, scheduled for June 27 in
Foxboro, Mass., will be held on Fair Play day, which is meant to
honor sportsmanship, Ryu said. Beyond that, he tread lightly on the
idea that soccer could be used as diplomacy the way the United
States and China once used Ping-Pong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to see,'' he said. ``That's all I can say about
that match.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryu did express his gratitude to the U.S. Embassy in Beijing for
granting visas to the North Koreans without delay. There had been
uncertainty, given that the embassy had been closed over protests
of NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two countries have no normalized relations, so we were
very concerned, but we received them without any hitches,'' said
Ryu, who loosened up considerably after his early starchiness and
allowed reporters to mingle with players as they ate lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean team has arrived as one of the great unknowns
in the 16-team Women's World Cup. Sport is as closed as the rest of
the Communist society that has been wracked by the collapse of the
Soviet Union, international isolation and famine, which has killed
two million to three million people since 1995, according to
international aid groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans know only that North Korea finished second to
China in the Asian qualifying tournament and that the team plays
with speed and assertive tackling. The North Koreans say they have
not seen the Americans play. Only one of the players, Kim Sun Hui,
a former captain, has previously traveled to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But unknown does not mean unskilled. The North Korean men's
soccer team was unknown, too, when it made it to the 1966 World Cup
finals _ after African nations withdrew in protest _ and pulled off
one of the greatest upsets in the history of the sport, shocking
mighty Italy, 1-0, and advancing to the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   While the Italians returned home to be pelted with rotten fruit,
Pak Doo Ik, who scored the lone goal, was rewarded in Pyongyang,
the North Korean capital, with a Mercedes-Benz, a luxury apartment
and the titles of People's Athlete and Labor Hero of the Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was beyond all description,'' Ryu said of the celebration
that greeted the team. ``Everybody turned out to the streets to
celebrate them. There is no more important reward than that the
players are still in the minds of the people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta, 16-year-old Kye Sun Hi
of North Korea entered her first international event as a wild-card
entry and won a gold medal in the women's extra-lightweight judo
division. Her opponent, Ryoko Tamura of Japan, had not lost in 84
matches over four years. It was the first gold medal for a North
Korean woman, and Kye received an apartment and a car as a reward.
A movie was made of her life and is now being shown on North Korean
television, Ryu said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean women have won five other Olympic medals in
speed skating, table tennis and volleyball. And now they are
looking for a breakthrough in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea did not participate in the previous two Women's
World Cups, but it would be foolish for the American women to take
them lightly. Just ask the American men. The North Korean men's
soccer team came to the United States in October 1991 and defeated
the Americans, 2-1, in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each player and each team has come to win the match, not lose
the match,'' said Kim Kum Sil, who scored the goal in a 1-0 victory
over Japan that enabled North Korea to qualify for the Women's
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Since she scored that goal in December 1997, Kim said, she is
recognized on the streets. At 28, she was not yet born when Pak
scored his shocking goal against Italy in 1966 in Sunderland,
England. But she does remember, as an 11-year-old, asking her
father why he seemed to be so intensely interested in watching
soccer on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm very happy when I see our nation's flag at big
athletic events,''' Kim said. ``At that time, women's soccer was
beyond my imagination. But I was inspired by my father talking
about the importance of athletes in international matches and Pak
Doo Ik's events.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean women's team made its first international
appearance in 1989. Kim, who was on that first team, said that the
early teams possessed only rudimentary skills, ``just kicking the
ball randomly in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought that soccer was kicking the ball and running
after it,'' Kim said. ``Now we think about utilizing the space to
the maximum.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer participation is now mandatory at elementary schools in
North Korea, officials said, and each district has a sports school
to identify promising athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The women on the national team are all single. Most of them are
graduate students in physical education. Their World Cup matches
will be televised on state television. Kim Jong Il, the reclusive
president, is said to be a fan of soccer and basketball who follows
international matches with a satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, sports officials have acknowledged some
difficulty in preparing teams in North Korea, given the country's
isolation and withered economic state. Its top basketball player, a
7-foot-8-inch center named Ri Myong Hun, had his ambitions to play
in the NBA thwarted, in part, by international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Several days ago, it was announced that Yoon Myong Chan,
formerly the coach of the North Korean men's soccer team, had
sought asylum in South Korea. He is the first known North Korean
sports official to defect. Myong Tong Chan, coach of the women's
team, did not accompany a group of players when they met with
reporters Saturday. No reason was given.
</P>
<P>
   Ryu, of the North Korean Olympic Committee, addressed his
country's struggles obliquely. ``It is true we are suffering
natural disasters the last couple years and also under economic
sanctions and other forces,'' he said. ``I think these temporary
difficulties can be overcome by the people's concentrated
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Kwak of Iowa City, president of the Korean Businessmen's
Federation in America, who is accompanying the soccer team and has
made 50 visits to North Korea, said the players did not appear to
be suffering any deprivation in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Kim Jong Il pays special attention to the team and
supplies good things to them,'' Kwak said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
