<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NFL-CADILLAC-NYT &LR;      06-06 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NFL-CADILLAC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOYLE BEATS THE FIELD AFTER BEATING BACK PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ When the spasms flared in Allen Doyle's back
during Saturday's third round of the Cadillac NFL Golf Classic, he
was asked if he thought the pain and discomfort could ever be bad
enough that he would withdraw from the tournament's final round on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, a hockey star at Norwich University in Vermont 30 years
ago, flashed a look of indignation. He may be a golfer now but he
was a hockey player first, and not surprisingly, his attitude
toward injuries remains rooted in the hockey culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to crawl around the course, I would finish,'' Doyle
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not crawl, but he limped and repeatedly grabbed at the
pang he felt in his lower back after most every swing. He stumbled
and played conservatively. But in the end, though it took 22 holes,
he also won.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, playing full time on the Senior PGA Tour for the first
time, continued his remarkable rookie run with his third victory
this year, a streak that has the once-unknown Georgia driving-range
owner a contender for the tour's player-of-the-year honors.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle defeated Joe Inman on Sunday on the fourth hole of a
two-man playoff after the two golfers tied at 12-under-par 204 at
the conclusion of Sunday's final round. It was the third
consecutive playoff at the Cadillac NFL Golf Classic, and though
both golfers played somewhat unsteadily in the playoff, Doyle sank
a nervy, 5-foot par putt on the fourth playoff hole to win, just
after Inman's 8-foot par putt lipped out.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Trevino was third, never seriously threatening after two
early bogeys, completing the tournament at 10 under par.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, 50, awoke Sunday without pain in his back, visited a
chiropractor who was a member of the tournament's host club, Upper
Montclair Country Club, and took megadoses of an over-the-counter
anti-inflammatory. But by the ninth hole, it was clear his back was
inhibiting his swing, which is normally abbreviated and unorthodox
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as Inman was sinking a birdie putt on the ninth hole to
briefly take the tournament lead, Doyle was back on the ninth
fairway, touching his toes, trying to stretch his back.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle hit his approach shot within 8 feet of the ninth hole,
grabbing at his back after his follow-through. He then limped to
the green and made his only birdie putt of the day to tie Inman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang in there, Mr. Doyle,'' a spectator yelled from the
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying,'' Doyle responded.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Doyle acknowledged that he was only chasing par on each
hole, afraid to ask too much of his back with an aggressive swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to play through it,'' said Doyle, who didn't turn
professional until 1995 and a year later was the oldest rookie in
the history of the PGA Tour. ``I kept telling myself par was my
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle and Inman remained tied through much of the back nine on
Sunday and each player had a chance to win the tournament on the
final hole of regulation play. But neither could make a birdie
despite good early positioning.
</P>
<P>
   There was more bumpy play from there, although for Doyle it was
ultimately more of the same _ four pars. He did not bogey any of
the 22 holes he played Sunday, shooting 71 for the first 18, while
Inman had a 66.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle has now won the Ace Group Classic and PGA Seniors
Championship, after entering just six Senior Tour events last year
and never finishing higher than fourth. With $1,036,364 earned this
year, he tops the tour's money list, vaulting over Bruce Fleisher,
the tour's other sensation, who has also won three events this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Once somewhat of a curiosity on the Senior Tour for his unusual
swing _ which may have evolved from his hockey slap shot _ Doyle
conceded that he may have to raise his original goal for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to win once and finish in the top 30,'' Doyle
said. ``I would have never thought of being the money leader. I
guess it's a thought I have to entertain now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
