<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990606.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-06 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-ART-NYT &LR;      06-06 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MORE HOPE THAN RUIN AT BELMONT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horse racing is often pictured as a troubled sport, sinking from
sight. But the throng of 85,818 at Belmont Park on Saturday, and
the threads of the drama of this year's Triple Crown, should offer
it much more hope than despair.
</P>
<P>
   The only part of the story that suggests the worst of times
would be the injury suffered by Charismatic as he struggled to
complete his sweep of the Triple Crown. It always seems that horses
break down on great stages _ before full crowds at Belmont Park on
network television.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic may have actually been injured farther up the
homestretch than people saw, but he kept racing to the finish line.
Then he felt the damage from the two broken bones in his left leg,
Chris Antley jumped off his back to comfort and calm him on the
track, and the record crowd suddenly grew hushed.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened before at Belmont Park. It happened to the
undefeated superfilly Ruffian in the great _ (but useless) _ match
race with Foolish Pleasure in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   It happened cruelly to the champion filly Go for Wand in the
Breeders' Cup in 1990. It happened just as tragically to Prairie
Bayou in the 1993 Belmont Stakes. It happened to Charismatic when
he was trying to complete his Triple Crown sweep in the Belmont
Stakes, with all those fairy-tale angles enhancing his career:
ignored as a claiming horse twice in the last seven months, winner
of the Kentucky Derby at odds of 31-1, winner of the Preakness at
8-1, a horse who ran in five major stakes on both coasts in two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Is that part of the worst of times in this horse's lifetime? He
ran fourth in the Santa Anita Derby on April 3, first in record
time in the Lexington Stakes on April 18, first in the Kentucky
Derby on May 1, first in the Preakness on May 15 and then third in
the fateful Belmont on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Racing records will report that the winner of the 1999 Belmont
Stakes was Lemon Drop Kid at 29-1, with Vision and Verse second at
54-1, which is dramatic enough. But the people who saw it happen
will remember it as an afternoon of dramatic complexity, of dreams
within reach but doomed to be lost, of a bunch of weary veterans of
the Derby and the Preakness at last surrendering to the demands
placed on them in the Belmont _ and of the favorite not
surrendering anything but eventually losing everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people would call me foolish for saying so,'' his owner,
Bob Lewis, reflected, ``but I tell you, he is just an iron horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not. But his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, had been
praising him as ``a two-week horse,'' meaning that he could run
every two weeks. And he did, but was that too much too often? A
generation or two ago, horses used to be raced more often than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Citation ran 20 times as a 3-year-old, and won 19 times. Between
the Preakness and the Belmont, he even took a detour and won the
Jersey Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' his illustrious trainer, Jimmy Jones, said. ``He
needed a workout anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, horses take the workout and aim for the race, or
wait for the $1 million purse. Charismatic ran the races, and may
have paid the price. They say that fast horses are the ones most
likely to get hurt because they are the ones straining to win.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic was a fast horse straining the most to win the
ultimate prize in racing, he was doing it before 85,818 screaming
spectators, he was the star of a day to remember in New York
sports. And he was running his fifth major race in two months.
</P>
<P>
   But his fate has to be placed in perspective. Race horses are
the warriors of sport. All race horses run at risk; all Triple
Crown horses run at escalating risk. It is an issue that won't be
solved here and now, or by Charismatic's loss of his youth, or by
Lukas and his relentless drive to turn 2-year-old horses into
3-year-old champions.
</P>
<P>
   It is a philosophical issue that goes beyond the Belmont, which
is more vulnerable to sad endings because it is the final,
exhausting goal in the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Belmont also sets the stage for the best
of times in racing. The race track is spacious, orderly and
beautiful, and it may have solved racing's ``identity'' problem
with three straight years of Triple Crown showdowns (and misses).
That is the piece de resistance: the very chance that a horse might
complete the sweep, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont Day has become a force in the industry, more than any of
the marketing strategies announced by the National Thoroughbred
Racing Association, which has had little to do with the success of
the Triple Crown or the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The show's the thing. Belmont Park on its day of days is the
thing. Noble Charismatic is the thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
