<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 06/06/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Attention editors: Please note that the photo with a an earlier
story slugged ``BIKES-EXTINCT'' has been killed.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ELMONT, N.Y. -- June 6, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT, 6-6 --
Charismatic, his front left leg in a cast, being led to an
ambulance before his surgery on Sunday morning. Racing records will
report that the winner of the 1999 Belmont Stakes was Lemon Drop
Kid at 29-1, with Vision and Verse second at 54-1, which is
dramatic enough. But the people who saw it happen will remember it
as an afternoon of dramatic complexity for the race favorite, not
surrendering anything but eventually losing everything. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CLIFFSIDE PARK, N.J. -- June 6, 1999 -- SOC-NKOREA, 6-6
-- With a thaw in the frosty relations between North Korea and the
United States, the North Korean womens soccer team has arrived with
seven members of its national team, to play the U.S. squad on June
27 in the first round of the Women's World Cup in Foxboro, Mass.
The United States-North Korea game, scheduled will be held on Fair
Play day, which is meant to honor sportsmanship. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 6, 1999 -- HARE-PLAYWRIGHT-PROFILE, 6-6
-- The playwright David Hare turned actor for his play ``Via
Dolorosa,'' at the Booth Theater. Hare is considered in the top
rank of British playwrights today. He says that he drew inspiration
for his play from visits to Israel. ``Via Dolorosa,'' is a one-act
monologue by the author, who takes the part of people encountered
on a trip to Israel and explores the Arab-Israeli conflict and
other issues. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- June 6, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S.-REACT,
6-6 -- Dilia Theodosakia, a retired secretary living in White
Plains, who long ago abandoned her initial support for the bombing
of Yugoslavia. Mrs. Theodosakia and several of her neighbors
express little joy as the end of the Kosovo war seems likely,
saying they see no winners, only losers. ``They are all criminals
in their own way,'' she says, lumping in the leaders of NATO
countries with Slobodan Milosevic. ``They are all responsible for
escalating suffering.'' (Richard L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KRUME, Albania -- June 6, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 6-6 --
As Serbian forces stepped up artillery fire on Albanian border
towns like Krume, which was hit by at least 10 shells, many
Albanians fled by truck on Sunday. The intention may be peace, but
war raged as fiercely as ever Sunday along the rugged border of
Kosovo and Albania, forcing some 1,000 people, many of them
refugees fleeing from fighting for at least the second time. (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- June 6, 1999 -- MRSGORE-PROFILE, 6-6 -- As
President Clinton's mental-health policy adviser, Tipper Gore, 50,
has been integral in planning the first-ever White House Conference
on Mental Health, which will be held on Monday. It is an issue that
Mrs. Gore, who has a master's degree in psychology from Vanderbilt
University in Nashville, has been devoted to in the last decade, as
an advocate for the mentally ill and for an enlightened attitude
toward mental illness. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BERKELEY, Calif. -- June 6, 1999 -- DISABLED-POLITICS-2,
6-6 -- Under current federal law, Alana Theriault, 32, must weigh
her desire to earn a living against the loss of Medicaid, the
federal-state medical insurance program for the indigent. Ms.
Theriault, who has a condition called spinal muscular atrophy,
earns less than $1,000 a month working part time as a benefits
counselor in Berkeley. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BERKELEY, Calif. -- June 6, 1999 -- DISABLED-POLITICS-1,
6-6 -- Alana Theriault, 32, who has a condition called spinal
muscular atrophy, earns less than $1,000 a month working part time
as a benefits counselor in Berkeley. ``As things stand now, I can't
take a job. I can't have any investments. I can't even really have
a savings account,'' says Theriault. Under current federal law, Ms.
Theriault must weigh her desire to work against the loss of
Medicaid, the federal-state medical insurance program for the
indigent. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 6, 1999 -- MORGANSTANLEY-CURRY, 6-6 --
Christian Leigh Curry, 25, with his fiancee Marissa Wheeler. Nine
months after joining the Wall Street powerhouse Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in 1997, Curry was abruptly fired. Curry has struck back
with a discrimination suit, claiming that racism and homophobia run
rampant at Morgan Stanley. Curry's dismissal came just days after
an issue of Playguy, a gay pornographic magazine, hit the
newsstands with Curry featured in an eight-page photo spread.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) YORKTOWN HEIGHTS, N.Y. -- June 6, 1999 -- IBM-ACER, 6-6
-- Two IBM executives, James Vanderslice, right, and Paul Horn,
examine a tool that is used to electroplate copper wafers at IBM's
research center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y. IBM plans to announce an
$8 billion technology sales agreement Saturday with the Acer Group
of Taiwan, representing another big step in IBM's accelerating
effort to market its leading-edge technology to companies that are
often its competitors. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HERNDON, Va. -- June 6, 1999 -- INTERNET-OVERSIGHT-2, 6-6
-- Donald L. Telage, senior vice president of Network Solutions is
a critic of the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers
interim board, or Icann. Network Solutions argues that the interim
board should be doing nothing more than setting minimum technical
standards for the competing registries. ``They have turned what is
supposed to be a standards-setting body into a regulatory
commission,'' says Telage. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 6, 1999 -- INTERNET-OVERSIGHT-1, 6-6 --
Esther Dyson, a well-known Internet entrepreneur, who leads the
Internet oversight body's interim board, the Internet Corporation
for Assigned Names and Numbers, says it is caught between
special-interest groups. ``It's frustrating to hear 'Let's go slow;
let's go fast,''' she says. ``I just want to hear legitimate
criticism of what we may or may not do. Let's argue it on the
merits.'' (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
