<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN NIEUWENDYK SOLVE HASEK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ TV camera lights flashed on, finding Stars
leading playoff scorer Joe Nieuwendyk with a microphone in his face
and bait dangling before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Joe,'' the challenge began, ``what's the key to beating
Dominik Hasek, probably the world's greatest goalie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' Nieuwendyk said, shrugging his shoulders, unwilling
to concede words like ``best'' and ``greatest'' before revealing
the blueprint to beat Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   A single Stanley Cup Finals game has yet to be played, and
Nieuwendyk simply refused to bite on any talk of Hasek's being an
intimidating presence for Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just faced a very good goaltender in Patrick Roy, and we
got a lot of pucks on him,'' Nieuwendyk reminded. ``This guy isn't
going to be able to stop everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Well ...
</P>
<P>
   Hasek has spent this playoffs trying to prove otherwise. He has
a 1.82 goals-against average and many believe he single-handedly
propelled a No. 7-seeded Sabres bunch to a Finals series that
begins with Game 1 scheduled for 6:30 p.m. tomorrow at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   So, back to the original question: How do the Stars beat the
great and powerful Dominik Hasek? Or better yet, whom do the Stars
have to beat him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Nieuwendyk's a start,'' said Stars winger Dave Reid, a
linemate of Nieuwendyk and Jamie Langenbrunner. ``He's playing
fantastic. He's got a lot of jump in him, a lot of enthusiasm.
Playoffs tend to bring out the best in players. It's definitely
brought out the best in Joe and Jamie.''
</P>
<P>
   In 17 postseason games, Nieuwendyk has 18 points, half from
goals and half from assists, ranking him No. 3 among 1999 playoff
scorers. Only Joe Sakic and Peter Forsberg are ahead of him, and
the Stars bounced out Colorado with a resounding 4-1 victory in
Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk started that ball rolling, his perfectly timed pass
leading to an easy Langenbrunner goal and a first-period lead that
Stars' players simply added to until a Finals berth had been
secured. To finish off Roy, the Stars got 23 pucks past him, an
average of 3.2 per game and better than what they had been scoring
in previous playoff rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's playing ... ,'' Stars usual playmaker Mike Modano
began, searching for a way to describe Nieuwendyk's impact. ``He's
got the whole line playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Well? Try unbelievably, amazing well?
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's a scorer; his goals were expected. He had the
winning goals in Games 2 and 3 against Colorado and assisted on
Langebrunner's in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   But nine goals, including three game-winners, from
Langenbrunner? He had a single goal in last season's playoffs. Or
what about eight points in 17 games from the usual fourth-liner,
role player Reid? In his 60 playoff games before this season, he
had 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it usually is the playoffs,'' Reid said. ``The
top lines are going to wash each other out with the same output. So
it's important for everybody else to contribute on the third and
fourth lines.''
</P>
<P>
   With Selke Trophy-candidate Michael Peca of the Sabres likely to
act as Modano's shadow, the Stars probably are going to need a lot
of other players scoring if they are going to solve Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk says the search for players to chip away at Hasek
should probably begin with Langenbrunner and Reid. He also likes
Mike Keane's chances and Brett Hull's and Guy Carbonneau's and Pat
Verbeek's ...
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk named just about every guy on the Tom Hicks' payroll
except for the Zamboni driver, and he's not counting him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those deals where we need offense from
everybody,'' Verbeek said. ``Playing on this team, there is never
the pressure on any one individual to have to do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, Hull and Jere Lehtinen have been good so far as the No.
1 line, scoring 17 goals and getting 19 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need them scoring goals,'' Keane said of Modano and Co.
``But every playoffs, you also need somebody new to step up. I
think everyone gets their chance when the playoffs start. Anyone
could be a hero. He's a hero for the night, and the next night it's
someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane had his ``hero'' moment in Game 7 against Colorado,
scoring two goals, including the game-winner and the back-breaker.
Hull had his ``hero'' moment in Game 6 against St. Louis, assisting
on both goals. Nieuwendyk's entire playoff run has been one
``hero'' moment after another.
</P>
<P>
   So the question now becomes: Who is going to have the ``hero''
moments against Hasek? Or is Hasek going to be the hero once again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``... He's obviously a
world-class goalie. We're going to have our hands full, but I think
we've proven that we can create offensive chances and put the puck
in the net.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
