<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLANTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEREK PLANTE COULD BE STARS' SECRET WEAPON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Former Blues player Brett Hull assisted on both
goals in Game 6 as the Stars eliminated St. Louis in the Western
Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Former Avalanche player Mike Keane scored two goals in Game 7 as
the Stars eliminated Colorado, 4-1, in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, if the Stanley Cup Finals come to a deciding game the
Stars can count on a big game from former Sabres player Derek
Plante, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``There you go,'' Plante said. ``There's no pressure there.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante could be the Stars' secret weapon in the Finals. He
played in Buffalo from his rookie season in 1993 until he was dealt
to the Stars at the trading deadline on March 23.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, he can provide inside information on his former
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll be asked some questions,'' Stars forward Brian
Skrudland said.
</P>
<P>
   Plante, a center, would be happy to contribute in any way he
can. Thus far in the postseason he has been more of a stealth
weapon than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars got him to inject speed and a left-handed shot into
the lineup, but it's hard to help when you're not on the ice.
Plante played in 10 of 11 regular-season games after joining the
team, but was a healthy scratch in 11 of the 17 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a matter of matchups, I don't know,'' he said.
``They haven't really talked about it. I hope I get to play. It's
out of my control, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante scored one of the Stars' biggest goals in their run to
the Cup, the game-tying tally late in the third period of Game 6
against the Blues. He hasn't played since.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, who values the familiarity factor, is
toying with giving him some playing time in the Finals, although
Plante didn't skate with one of the regular lines in practice
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plante is a player who is expected to play sometime in the
series,'' Hitchcock said. ``That's something we're going to have to
play by ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante has been a key player in the postseason before. He led
Buffalo in assists (6), game-winning goals (2) and points (10) and
was tied for second in goals (4) during the 1997 playoffs, and
played in 11 of the Sabres' 15 playoff games last year.
</P>
<P>
   But if he's frustrated about his lack of playing time this time,
he's hiding it well.
</P>
<P>
   He remains ready to answer teammates' questions, ready to give a
scouting report, ready to do whatever he can. With his team four
victories away from winning the big prize, he's not about to stir
up trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking the approach be positive, and whatever it takes for
this team to win the Stanley Cup, that's what we'll do,'' he said.
``If I'm not in there, I'm not going to have sour apples or get
frustrated. If I get the chance to help out, I'll try to do the
best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante continues to play hard in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to stay focused,'' he said. ``You can't think
you're not going to play and just go through the motions. You've
got to stay ready to play and stay sharp and in shape, and have the
best legs you can. That's what I'm trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he doesn't get the chance to emulate Hull and Keane and
be the Stars' secret weapon, he's still ready to enjoy the series
between his new team and the one he played for the better part of
six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty cool,'' Plante said. ``A lot of those guys are my
friends, so it's kind of neat. It should be a fun series.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
