<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT OF IRVIN, LETT DOESN'T ADD UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Back in early spring, when he was calling
``major press conferences'' to announce the signing of
asterisk-laden free agents, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones was easy to
find.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, Owner Jones is taking the Fifth. As well as the
6th, 7th, 12th or any other day when anyone in the media wants to
ask him about Leon Lett.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys say they are bound by rules of confidentiality,
which is good. The continuing saga of Leon Lett deserves no real
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Lett has a problem. But whether the problem is drugs, drug tests
or signing the roll sheet at drug-abuse meetings, his problem has
crept into the workplace. His employer can no longer depend upon
him.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many games the defensive tackle will miss with
this third and latest suspension for violating the NFL's
substance-abuse policy. Four? Ten? An entire season?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what the terms of Lett's reinstatement, if any,
will be. Will he now be tested hourly? Will he have to write an
essay for the commissioner? Will he have to relinquish his VIP
parking space at the Iguana Mirage?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the terms, there is fervent hope here that Owner Jones
isn't keeping the porch light on for old lost Leon. The Cowboys
have things to do and places in January to see, and the time to do
and see them is getting preciously thin with each passing season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if history has told us anything, it is that Jones holds a
fond place in his heart for his star Cowboys, especially the ones
who are signed at less than market value, as Lett is.
</P>
<P>
   With free-agent defensive linemen being signed around the league
for $4-5 million per season, Lett qualifies as a $2 million
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   There are business decisions, apparently, and then there are
business decisions.
</P>
<P>
   While Jones feels compelled to wait on Lett, he
uncharacteristically lets Michael Irvin twist in the June wind. Go
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Irvin's fast and breezy lifestyle.
Argue, if you must, about how Irvin let his off-field antics
scuttle the Cowboys' season in 1996. The fact is that Irvin bleeds
Cowboy blue.
</P>
<P>
   Trade him? Whose fool idea was that?
</P>
<P>
   Irvin did not have a prominent season last year, though he did
catch 74 passes for 1,057 yards. Left unanswered in the Cowboys'
late-season swoon is how the football never did seem to find
Michael after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Cowboys find the win column much. So please _ if
you're going to argue that the new offense just isn't suited for
Irvin, maybe the harder questions should be directed at the
architect of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Irvin? Somebody tell me why Owner Jones ever allowed that
to leak. It had to rip out the heart of the always passionate
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Steve Endicott, now says, sure, his client would
accept a trade. But it doesn't make sense. That's not Irvin, who
justifiably could have _ maybe should have _ demanded such a trade
at the height of his troubles three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody at Valley Ranch has decided that they don't need
Michael Irvin anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the head coach? Interesting. Especially for a coach whose
team slid miserably and then couldn't beat the Cardinals in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is loyalty. Jones owes Irvin some and Lett none. Yet
Irvin is the one on the very public trading block.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, before he hurt his knee during a scrimmage against
New Orleans, Lett's trade value was as high as it was ever going to
get. Yet Jones resisted. He had faith in Lett's ability to be one
of the cornerstones of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months later, what does Jones have for his blind faith? He
even let the April draft go by without finding Lett's possible
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows, of course. Lett might be back in October. He may
never come back at all.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the point _ the uncertainty should be damning enough,
as far as the Cowboys' future plans are concerned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
