<HEADER>
A5292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARE-PLAYWRIGHT-PROFI     06-06 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARE-PLAYWRIGHT-PROFILE-ART-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYWRIGHT LAYS CLAIM TO PARTS OF HARE'S `VIA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Los Angeles actor and playwright has charged in a
federal lawsuit that David Hare's latest play, ``Via Dolorosa,''
which features the author as performer and has enjoyed critically
acclaimed runs in London and New York, misappropriated its ideas,
structure and some dialogue from a play written by the plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit, filed last month in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan by Steven Greenstein, charged that the Royal Court
Theater in London rejected his one-act play ``Voices From the Holy
... and Not So Holy Land'' in 1997 and then usurped many of its
elements for Hare's play last year.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which asked for unspecified damages, named only the
Royal Court as the defendant and not Hare. It did not use the word
``plagiarism,'' and did not accuse Hare of wrongdoing. But it noted
that Stephen Daldry, who directed ``Via Dolorosa,'' was the
artistic director of the Royal Court when Greenstein submitted his
script in late 1996, and implied that he may have been a conduit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know to what extent Hare knew what was being given to
him,'' Richard Crisona, Greenstein's lawyer in New York, said
Sunday. ``We only know that Greenstein sent the Royal Court a
script, they rejected it, and subsequently Hare's play came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikki Heywood, executive director of the Royal Court, insisted
that the suit would be dismissed as groundless. ``It has absolutely
no merit at all,'' she said. ``The Greenstein play was submitted to
us after we had already begun discussions with David. The play has
not been read by Stephen Daldry or David Hare, and they had no
knowledge of this play until this spurious case was brought.''
</P>
<P>
   Hare, who performed a matinee of his play on Sunday at the Booth
Theater in New York and presented an award at the Tony ceremonies
Sunday night, declined through a spokesman to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hare, with Harold Pinter and Tom Stoppard, is considered in the
top rank of British playwrights today. Hare has said frequently
that he drew inspiration for his play from visits to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Like Greenstein's play, the suit said, ``Via Dolorosa,'' which
opened last September at the Royal Court and has been at the Booth
since March 18, is a one-act monologue by the author, who takes the
part of people encountered on a trip to Israel _ Jews, Arabs,
politicians and others _ and explores the Arab-Israeli conflict and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Court, the suit said, commissioned a play by Hare that
``incorporated central elements, ideas, themes, structures and even
some dialogue from plaintiff's play.'' It said both plays were solo
one-act works performed by their authors, and both open in settings
outside Israel, explore Middle East issues from the visitor's
standpoint, incorporate the voices of similar characters and close
in settings far from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing dialogue, the suit said that an American Jewish
visitor in ``Voices'' says, ``It's like we the Jews are the rulers,
the occupier, and these Arabs, these Palestinians, are our
occupied,'' while in ``Via Dolorosa'' a Jewish character says,
``When you begin to see yourself as the occupier and them as the
occupied.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit said both plays incorporate themes of a yuppie culture
in which young Israelis turn away from hard work, sacrifice and
military service, and both express concern about Jewish
assimilation, restrictions on Palestinians and the struggle of
living in Israel as opposed to living in the diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   Greenstein, 39, said in an interview that he wrote his play in
1995 and 1996, submitted it to the Royal Court in late 1996 and
received a rejection letter from Graham Whybrow, the theater's
literary manager. His suit said he had received no credit or
compensation for the use of his script, which was copyrighted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying who's the culprit,'' he said. ``I'm just saying
they had my play and Daldry was the artistic director when my play
was there, and he later directed David Hare's play. The Royal Court
was the inspiration and the originators. They commissioned Hare to
go to Israel and write this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenstein said his play was inspired by his experiences living
in Israel from 1992 to 1995. He said he had performed it many times
at theaters in San Diego, Los Angeles and Antwerp, Belgium, and at
Rutgers University and Bloomfield College in New Jersey. He filed
his suit on May 19 after discovering what he called similarities in
Hare's work; he sent a copy to The New York Times on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
