<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CUNY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FUTURE OF CUNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 7:
</P>
<P>
   Benno Schmidt's task-force report on the City University of New
York documents the failures of an urban education system that badly
needs a clearer mission and more coherent management. Often called
the ``gateway'' to a better life for immigrants and those who
cannot afford private college, CUNY is described as being
``adrift'' or caught in a ``spiral of decline.'' Some of this drift
has a political undercurrent as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov.
George Pataki have criticized CUNY and cut its budget. However,
Schmidt's ambitious report ducks the hazards of New York politics
and instead offers thought-provoking suggestions of ways CUNY could
become the model for a public urban university system.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial debate at CUNY has been how to maintain
open admissions while shoring up the value of a degree. The task
force proposes an admission policy that would have different
standards for four-year colleges and for community colleges, much
like the widely admired university system in California. At least 2
of the 11 four-year colleges should evolve into schools rivaling
the nation's better universities, Schmidt, the former president of
Yale, argues persuasively. Such elite public colleges, however,
must not diminish the opportunity for all New Yorkers who have
completed high school to attain a college education in some part of
the CUNY system.
</P>
<P>
   This issue leads to the tumultuous question of the remedial
classes that have become the norm at CUNY. Currently, 87 percent of
first-year students at community colleges and 72 percent of those
at the four-year colleges need remedial help to continue. This
abysmally high rate means that CUNY has been trying to fill in the
gaps left by New York City schools. Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew is
right to seize on the report as a catalyst to reinvent the public
schools, which send a third of their graduates to CUNY and also
employ many CUNY graduates as teachers. But meanwhile, the task
force argues wisely that CUNY must not end remediation. Rather, the
report proposes updating the tests and evaluating different
approaches to remediation to see what works. Some proposals, like
limiting remediation to community colleges and using vouchers to
foster competition among remedial programs, clearly need more
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the report advises CUNY to organize itself as a system
rather than treat its 17 campuses as separate city states.
Similarly, in a section on financial planning, the report suggests
that the ``passivity'' at the central administration should be
replaced with strategic planning and accountability that rewards
those educational functions that work and revamps those that are
failing.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and the governor have indicated they like what they
know of this weighty report. A spokesman for Governor Pataki called
it ``an important blueprint'' for improving standards. While CUNY
has pockets of success, its failures are now catalogd, with
concrete solutions proposed. The Schmidt report should be used not
merely to denounce CUNY, but to rebuild it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
